<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SUMMER OF EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: also see NY-SONOFSAM-SCENE)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York City that brims with health and vibrancy today
seemed destined for a different ending in 1977. The city went broke
and grew steadily dirtier and more disheveled. A blackout plunged
millions of people into a darkness punctuated by fiery riots and
the screeching voices of looters. While televising baseball from
Yankee Stadium, cameras panned the horizon for the flame-tinged
columns of smoke spawned by arsonists who single-mindedly torched
the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Life in a city that seemed to be terminally breaking down was
tense enough. But a serial killer whom the tabloids had dubbed the
``Son of Sam'' was stalking the streets, killing at random,
taunting the police with handwritten notes. Parents feared for
their children as the corpses mounted. Neighbor suspected neighbor.
Fearful of being outside after dark, New Yorkers were driven into
cramped, airless apartments during one of the hottest summers ever
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   New York was being stalked by what seemed like an evil of
biblical proportions _ a killer whose malevolence was almost
without limit. But like most murderers, David Berkowitz turned out
to be a flesh-and-blood human being who made mistakes, the most
fateful of which was getting a parking ticket in an area where his
car was identified and eventually traced back to him.
</P>
<P>
   Cities, like human beings, tend to repress horrific memories in
favor of pleasant ones. When Berkowitz went to jail, New York
caught its breath and went back to a slightly milder version of its
heightened reality. People who had lost loved ones to the killer
were never the same. But for the rest of the city, the summer of
1977 was soon like a nightmare that might never have happened at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The opening this week of Spike Lee's new film ``Summer of Sam''
brings that harrowing summer back from the mental depths to which
most New Yorkers had cast it. For those who experienced the real
thing, the movie will summon up the chaos and paranoia of one of
the most difficult periods in the city's history. It will also
remind them yet again that evil does indeed exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
