<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES THRASH METS IN LAUGHER, 16-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the clubhouse, after a 16-0 shellacking brushed on
by the bats of the National League East-leading Atlanta Braves,
manager Bobby Valentine of the New York Mets mustered a sheepish
smile. ``Well, that was interesting, wasn't it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, what occurred in the ninth inning Friday night did
get intriguing in a terribly farcical way.
</P>
<P>
   What up to that point had been a merely miserable showing before
a bored crowd of 51,979 _ the team's second sellout of the year _
was enlivened by the appearance of backup infielder/outfielder Matt
Franco on the pitcher's mound with two on and two out.
</P>
<P>
   But to get him there, Valentine had to move right fielder Roger
Cedeno to second base and Luis Lopez from second to third base, and
insert a starting pitcher, Rick Reed, into right field on his day
off. None of this was a stunt. On a night the Braves banged an
overworked Mets pitching staff for five home runs, Valentine
anticipated that Franco, who had pitched two innings in the minor
leagues, might get some work from the rubber.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the third inning, I told him we might need him,'' said
Valentine, whose team trailed Greg Maddux by 8-0 at that point.
</P>
<P>
   More worrisome in the ninth inning, as well as after the game,
was the reason Franco was needed to pitch _ because the other
Franco, the closer, John, felt something pop in his right middle
finger after starting the inning and getting two men out. With John
Franco on his way to the clubhouse for X-rays, Matt Franco faced
Gerald Williams with two on.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing overhand meatballs clocked at 84 mph, Franco worked
Williams to a 1-1 count. But the third pitch was knocked far out of
the field. ``I was just throwing batting practice,'' said Franco,
who says he pitched two innings in Triple-A in 1995. ``And they hit
it like it was batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   After Williams' long ball, Franco gave up a double to Ozzie
Guillen, but recovered his dignity in time to strike out Andruw
Jones _ much to the delight of a crowd that had become distracted
watching the Braves bat around while awaiting a post-game fireworks
display.
</P>
<P>
   But he could hardly be blamed on a night when the Braves got 15
hits off six bonafide Mets' pitchers and Franco for their third
victory over the Mets in four games in the span of a week. The
crowd expected a low-hit, high-strike pitchers' game between the
steely, four-time Cy Young Award winner Maddux and Masato Yoshi,
who tested him last week in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Yoshi and Maddux impersonated a couple of doctors trying
to get to the golf course on a Friday afternoon. They worked fast
and precisely in a downright fleeting 2 hour, 6 minute game won by
the Braves, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux held up his end Friday night. He took a no-hitter to the
fifth inning before Lopez got a one-out single. And he raised his
record to 8-5 by striking out one, walking two and holding the Mets
to just two hits over six innings.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoshi didn't hold up his end and heard about it from the
crowd, which was grumbling about his performance after the Braves
scored three runs in the first inning, two of them on a 412-foot
blast by Chipper Jones, the first of two home runs he hit on his
way to a 2 for 2, four-runs-batted-in night.
</P>
</TEXT>
