<BODY>
 NURSES FACE REVIEW FOR EXPLICIT WEB BUSINESS  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A husband-wife team of critical-care nurses says a Scottsdale
hospi tal is trying to dump them because they star on an X-rated
Web site they say has 22,000 paid subscrib ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing it to help pay for our kids' college
educations,'' said George Miller, 35, father of a 5-year-old
daughter and an 11-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   George said he and his wife, Tracy, 33, of northeast Phoenix,
did not tout their Web site during work hours at Scottsdale
Healthcare Os born. But word leaked out about a month ago and
employees began connecting to the steamy site on their work
computers.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the trouble started.
</P>
<P>
   George Miller said when he showed up for work as an on-call
nurse on Thursday, he was told by a supervisor she had ``forgotten
to cancel me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned home, he said, a supervisor called and told him
that ``because of the Web site, we were not to come to work until
further notice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the hospital has a prob lem with nudity, or they don't
want their image tarnished,'' he said. ``But no one would have ever
known at Scottsdale Healthcare if they had not brought this to
light. They created their own problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay Sperduti, hospital spokes woman, would not comment on the
Millers' case except to say, ``The matter is under review.'' She
said she did not know how long the review will take.
</P>
<P>
   She would say only that employ ees must sign a hospital policy
statement that says they can be disciplined for ``immoral or inde
cent conduct while on or off duty.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy does not spell out what is considered immoral or
indecent, Sperduti said.
</P>
<P>
   George says that the Web site, which shows his bare-breasted
wife sitting at a computer or in other sexually explicit poses, is
not im moral and is none of the hospital's business.
</P>
<P>
   He said the couple haven't de cided to sue, even though he is
convinced the hospital is ``invading our rights of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, says Terry Hall, a Phoenix attorney who represents
employees but is not involved in the Millers' case.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said state and federal work ers' rights to privacy are
guaranteed by the Constitution as long as their off-duty lives
don't affect their work.
</P>
<P>
   But he and another attorney said workers for private companies
don't have those broad constitutional guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Eleanor Eisenberg, an attor ney at the American Civil
Liberties Union, who is familiar with the case, said she is
concerned about ``employers invading employees' privacy and making
decisions based on facts unrelated to their job performance.''
</P>
<P>
   George said he and Tracy don't identify themselves as nurses or
hospital workers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, which the couple put up two months ago, features
Tracy as ``the very touchable'' Dakota Rae, and invites surfers to
view pictures of her in teeny bikinis or soaped up in a
bubble-filled bathtub. But if viewers register and agree to pay
$14.95 a month, they can see the dark-haired and much more exposed
Dakota Rae in steam ier stills.
</P>
<P>
   George appears in some shots engaging in sexual activity with
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The site also links surfers to her ``cousins,'' CBaby and Jilly.
</P>
<P>
   George says the site has been popular, but the couple still need
the money they make as on-call nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hospital is doing is taking our income away by
sticking their nose in our business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he said he and his wife made $92,000 ``because we
worked a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he considers his wife and himself as hospital regulars
because he has worked there two years and his wife has been there
three, each averaging 36 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   Sperduti said the hospital has no obligation to schedule fill-in
work ers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, George says, rumors are whirling around the hospital
that the Millers are wife-swapping swingers.
</P>
<P>
   But he said they have been married for 14 years, are faithful to
each other and still ``very much in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Posing for X-rated pictures, he said, ``is just something we
like to do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
