<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN IRELAND FACES LOSS OF LEGISLATURE IF IMPASSE ON PACT
CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: ADDS three grafs at end with Clinton's comment, details.)    (rm) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The British and Irish governments
delivered an ultimatum to the feuding politicians of Ulster Friday
night to resolve the impasse threatening the Northern Ireland peace
settlement or see their hard fought new legislature shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Ministers Tony Blair and Bertie Ahern issued their formal
challenge after personally devoting five grueling days to talks
that failed to produce an agreement between the Ulster Unionists,
the Protestant group that is the province's largest party, and the
Catholic group Sinn Fein, the political representatives of the
Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute had centered on the timing of which of two key steps
in the peace settlement formula would occur first _ the creation of
a power-sharing executive to run the new Northern Ireland assembly,
favored by Sinn Fein, or the beginning of the disarming of
paramilitary groups, demanded by the Ulster Unionists. The plan
includes a first-ever disarmament pledge by Sinn Fein and sets out
a sequence that makes the two events occur within weeks of each
other.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement read from the steps of the Stormont Castle
Buildings where the grinding marathon talks took place, Blair
wearily cast the document in upbeat tones but acknowledged that it
faced a test in convincing the distrustful Catholic and Protestant
communities to accept it as ``the way forward,'' as it was
entitled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most historic chance for peace that this land has
known for years and years,'' he said, ``and I ask you to give it a
chance.'' Ahern said it ``gives the whole island a bright future''
but added, ``if we can agree upon it.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing what had blocked progress in putting into effect the
much hailed April 1998 peace agreement, the document specified that
a power-sharing executive who will run the legislature will be
nominated in two weeks, and that disarmament of guerrilla weapons
will begin in August.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein is entitled to two of the 10 positions in the new
cabinet, in effect the new government of Northern Ireland, and the
Ulster Unionists have refused to permit the party to occupy its
seats until the IRA begins giving up its weapons. Under the
proposal, Sinn Fein achieves its aim of entering the government
without acceding to this condition, a result that left the
Unionists complaining of unfairness.
</P>
<P>
   What the British and Irish prime ministers hoped would placate
the Unionists was a first-ever statement from Sinn Fein that it
would seek full disarmament of the IRA by the May 2000 date in the
original agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders also sought to reassure the Unionists with the
promise of prompt British legislation setting out the punishment of
automatic and immediate suspension of the legislature and other
institutions set up by the peace agreement if the IRA does not live
up to the disarmament pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Disarmament of paramilitary weapons, called decommissioning
here, has long been the stumbling block to peace proposals in
Northern Ireland, and the matter was left deliberately vague in the
1998 peace accord in an effort to gain Sinn Fein backing for it.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Unionists' demand for immediate action on
decommissioning, and Sinn Fein's refusal to respond to it, held up
what is the most important stage of putting the overall peace
agreement into action _ the creation of the executive and the
accompanying transfer of powers from the British Parliament in
London to the Northern Ireland Assembly in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That delay became particularly dramatic this week when new
legislatures in Wales and Scotland received their powers from
London in the program of constitutional reform that Blair has
brought to Britain. Northern Ireland was supposed to be part of
that move; instead Northern Ireland became the reason why Blair had
to cancel his appearance at the ceremonial opening of the Scottish
Parliament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under Friday's blueprint, the formal exchange of powers from
London to Belfast will take place on July 18, three days after the
formation of the executive.
</P>
<P>
   The disarmament proposal that led to the prime ministers' master
plan was only spelled out Saturday morning when a long-awaited
document was submitted to them by John de Chastelain, a retired
Canadian General who heads up the International Independent
Commission on Decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
   The report was deliberately held up in recent days so it could
incorporate crucial compromises achieved since Monday. Thus, when
finally made public today, it referred to developments Thursday
that led the commission to conclude that Sinn Fein was now prepared
to persuade the IRA to start turning in guns on a scheduled
timetable and to have eliminated its entire arsenal by May 22,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will hold meetings promptly with representatives
of paramilitary groups to establish the dates and manner of turning
in weapons and will formally report progress in September and
December and then next May.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, the president of Sinn Fein, appeared buoyant in his
comments on the governments' proposal. He said he wanted to work in
``partnership'' with the Unionists and urged their leadership to
stand up to ``people who want to break this down.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Trimble, the Unionists' leader and the First Minister
of the Northern Ireland Assembly, questioned Sinn Fein's commitment
to peace and criticized the governments' plan as ``fundamentally
unfair'' to his party and vague and ``aspirational'' on points
where the Unionists had hoped for ``certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimble faces the task of selling a deal he clearly has little
enthusiasm for to his party members, some of whom are not
supporters of the original peace agreement and others who will find
it hard to step back from their hardline position of demanding IRA
disarmament before the entry of Sinn Fein into government. One of
them, Jeffrey Donaldson, a Unionist member of the British
Parliament, announced Friday that he opposed the way forward plan.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble will also have to confront the voluble opposition of the
Rev. Ian Paisley, the firebrand preacher-politician and head of the
Ulster Democrats, who is a much lampooned figure in British life
but still commands fervent backing from his hardline followers.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton called on both sides to bend to
reach an agreement, saying, ``No one is going to get something for
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing Trimble and his party members is the fact that if they do
not set up the executive on July 15 with the Sinn Fein members,
they will face the shutdown of the legislature that their party has
the most power in and of which Trimble is the first minister.
</P>
<P>
   The two weeks of deliberations come during the July season of
sectarian marches. The parade that has been a flash point for
violence is the procession of members of the Orange Lodge from
Drumcree Church, scheduled for this Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
