<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8147 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUCKS-BASEBALL-KAN &LR;      07-03 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUCKS-BASEBALL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR-LEAGUE BASEBALL IS BIG HIT IN SMALL MISSOURI TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OZARK, Mo. -- Juan Pacheco's 5-year-old daughter, Styler,
presses her face to the chain-link fence around the field. Her
Winnie-the-Pooh backpack slips as she clutches her Ozark Mountain
Ducks pennant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Styler looks away shyly as her dad asks Jason Thompson, the
spark plug center fielder, to sign her pennant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Thompson oblige, but he also takes the pennant to
three teammates sitting on plastic chairs in the bullpen. They
sign, too. When Thompson returns it, he acts as if little Styler is
doing him a favor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, minor-league baseball has changed; a supermarket's name
graces the stadium, the sports bar sells microbrews, and denim Duck
shirts go for $45. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Ozark has welcomed the Ducks like small towns embrace new
neighbors. The Ducks, in their first season, lead the league in
attendance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco was here on opening night. Scanning the roster, he saw a
few players with Latin last names. He figured he'd say hello. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next thing he knew, two players were bunking with his family. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hombre,'' he shouts in Spanish to Sergio Cairo, an outfielder
from the Dominican Republic. ``Your stuff is still at my house.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This isn't big-time baseball. Players make an average of $1,000
a month, so little that Pacheco didn't want his guests to pitch in
for groceries. The team operates by the seat of its pants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to figure out where to put them all. I might have
to sleep on the couch,'' Pacheco said as a peanut vendor hawked his
wares nearby. ``But they're good guys. I'm just glad to have
baseball here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long wait. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before World War II, the Springfield (Mo.) Cardinals were a
minor-league affiliate for St. Louis. Future stars such as Stan
Musial honed their craft before moving to the big leagues. The last
local team, an affiliate of the Chicago Cubs, left town in 1950. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since then, town leaders have tried to bring baseball back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Springfield voters rejected a plan in 1990 that would have
raised the city sales tax to partly fund a stadium. A 1995 plan to
move a Nashville, Tenn., team failed when the Missouri General
Assembly didn't OK funds for a stadium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Texas-Louisiana League, an independent outfit with
such franchises as the Bayou Bullfrogs of Lafayette, La., and the
Rio Grande Valley White Wings of Harlingen, Texas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   League officials saw Ozark, a fast-growing suburb south of
Springfield, as a ripe market. So much so that, for the first time,
the league paid to build a park. The stadium, which seats 4,127,
was finished with days to spare. Price Cutter paid an undisclosed
amount to put its name on the park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the team name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What the heck is a Mountain Duck anyway? It came from a
name-the-team contest. Brad Eldridge, the general manager, says it
combined several entries that mentioned mountains or ducks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, it looks good on a T-shirt,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As fans blew into plastic duck calls in the bleachers around
her, Madge Morris rolled her eyes when someone mentioned the name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the most ridiculous thing I've ever heard,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks have won over the skeptics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite bumbling to an 8-21 start, the team is averaging 3,392
fans through 15 home games, leading the seven-team league. The club
has sold 1,800 season tickets, far outpacing projections. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They're not the only minor-league sensation in Missouri. The
River City Rascals, who play in O'Fallon, sold out opening night
and have drawn strong crowds for their inaugural season in the
independent Frontier League. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks win fans over with friendly players and wacky
gimmicks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is that, even if the team just got creamed 15-2, fans
still walk away saying they had a good time,'' Eldridge said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, waiters from nearby Lambert's Cafe -- where bread
is thrown to diners -- heave rolls to fans, who dive for them as if
they were foul balls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then the ``K-Man'' is introduced -- one opponent each game. If
he strikes out -- registered as ``K'' in the scorebook -- fans win
five free hot wings at a nearby Hooter's. On this night, the K-man
was Chris Cassels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So how'd you like to be Cassels, 30 years old, a career
minor-leaguer, just off a 12-hour bus trip from Mississippi. The
pitcher gets two strikes and all of a sudden, the announcer starts
heckling you. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants hot wings?'' he yells. ``Let me hear you!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Cassels doesn't strike out all night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, too, because some of the Ducks could surely use the
meal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Hovey, a rookie pitcher from Kansas City, Mo., scrapes
by at $650 a month. Mark McGwire, the Cardinals slugger, will make
about twice as much an inning as Hovey will all season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hovey also gets $12 daily for meals. He deliberately sleeps in
so he can miss breakfast and save money. He eats fast food for
lunch. Players refuse to spring for a cab ride to nicer
restaurants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The team takes overnight bus trips of as long as 17 hours to
far-flung stops in Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is Hovey complaining? No way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hovey, who attended Southwest Missouri State University, hounded
the Ducks to give him a tryout. They like what they see. Hovey has
pitched four innings without giving up a run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is pro baseball's bottom rung. Hovey knows he's a few
hanging curveballs away from a real job. So far, he's enjoying his
pursuit of The Dream: hooking on with a major-league system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rough. I would guess that the travel and the money
eliminates a lot of guys,'' Hovey said. ``I wouldn't trade it,
though. I feel lucky. I'm doing something that I love.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is talent in this league. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few Ducks have played on minor-league teams. Most are raw.
Kendall Rhodes, the starting pitcher, threw bullets most of the
night. Unfortunately, three pitches hit the backstop on the fly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least the Ducks' advertising department is major-league. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost 60 ads cover the outfield wall at a minimum of $4,000.
The first inning has a sponsor. When a runner is caught stealing,
the P.A. man says: ``Fans, there's another runner that wouldn't
have got caught stealing if he'd have gotten his oil changed at Mr.
Smith's Fast Lube.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eldridge said the ads are necessary to keep ticket prices low.
The most expensive seats cost $8 and include waiters who bring
food. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some people think it's overcommercialized, but it has
to be from the revenue standpoint,'' he said. ``We always ask
ourselves: Will fans enjoy this or are we just prostituting
ourselves?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks will never be accused of being coldly corporate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And that old-fashioned neighborliness is winning over residents
of Ozark, which has doubled in population since 1990. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kozal, who lives a few blocks from the stadium, focused
his eyes on the field as the team from Greenville, Miss., staged a
late-game rally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't always a Ducks fan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors in a new subdivision groused about the traffic
tie-ups, noise and lights the stadium created. Kozal complained,
too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But during his first game, Kozal started talking to a team
official about Homer, the Ducks' mascot. Could they use a backup,
he wondered? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before he knew it, Kozal got the gig. After a few public
appearances, he performed in his first game last weekend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a fan on this night, Kozal kept his eyes focused on Homer,
who gets as manic as Jim Carrey on a double espresso. Kozal watched
the duck romp. He watched the children laugh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were going down to defeat -- again -- but he was
smiling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought baseball could be this fun,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
