<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8148 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERINTENDENT-SEARCH     07-03 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERINTENDENT-SEARCH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERINTENDENT CANDIDATES NARROWED DOWN TO TWO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and TANIKA WHITE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- The field of candidates for Kansas City
school superintendent is down to two. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   School board members are scheduled to meet privately with Pascal
Forgione Jr. at 7 p.m. Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The second candidate, Benjamin Demps Jr., contacted the school
district late Friday to say he still is interested in the position.
An interview has not been scheduled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two other finalists no longer are candidates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The board's initial choice, Air Force Maj. Gen. Jay T. Edwards,
withdrew abruptly Thursday after he and board members were unable
to reach agreement on a contract. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grandview (Mo.) School Superintendent John Martin then told
school district officials he no longer was interested in the post. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members are being pressured by the court-appointed
Desegregation Monitoring Committee to name the next superintendent
by Friday from the original pool of candidates identified by a
selection committee dominated by the monitoring committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring committee member Charles McClain said he wasn't sure
what would happen if the board failed to reach agreement with
either of the two candidates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to hope that isn't the case,'' McClain said.
``We're still hopeful something will happen next week.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, general administrator of the Oklahoma Corporation
Commission, returned to Oklahoma City on Thursday night after talks
with the board broke off. Reached Friday at his Oklahoma City
office, Edwards expressed disappointment about his Kansas City
experience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the money that stopped me,'' Edwards said. ``It was
a combination of things that led me to believe I would be unhappy
and unsuccessful.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said those included the lack of unified board support
and the board's refusal to grant him a three-year contract. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said he feared long-term bureaucrats would resist any
changes he initiated, thinking they could simply wait out his
tenure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some people in Kansas City said Edwards simply wasn't cut out
for the job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The general was a decent and dignified man who upon close
scrutiny probably lacked the temperament and fortitude to succeed
in this school district and develop a meaningful working
relationship with one of the primary constituencies _
African-Americans,'' district activist Clinton Adams Jr. said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Adams said, unlike some leaders in the black community, he
does not believe the next superintendent must be black. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The next superintendent needs to have a demonstrated record of
working with African-Americans to address the educational needs of
African-American students,'' Adams said. ``In my view, it's myopic
and ignorant to think that only a black person can do that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board President John Rios acknowledged Friday that Edwards
probably was not the best of the four finalists, but that politics
had clouded his thinking when he voted to support Edwards as the
finalist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Rios said Forgione was the best candidate for the
position. Rios initially opposed Forgione because Missouri
Education Commissioner Bob Bartman and Arthur A. Benson II, lawyer
for the plaintiff schoolchildren in the desegregation lawsuit, both
were urging the board to hire Forgione. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rios said he didn't want it to appear that others were dictating
whom the board should hire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board member Lance Loewenstein said he believed a clear majority
of the board now supports Forgione for the job. At least three
other board members agreed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But board member Terry Riley said those board members may be
mistaken. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just speculation,'' Riley said. ``Maybe (Loewenstein)
has talked to some board members, but he hasn't talked to all of
them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board member Lee Barnes Jr. reiterated that he will work with
whomever the board hires. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean that I am necessarily going to support it
when they vote,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he still is frustrated because he originally wanted
former candidate Grandview Superintendent John Martin for the
Kansas City post, but he was eliminated from the beginning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is always asked of us: `Will we support someone
if they aren't black?' '' Barnes said. ``Well, the question needs
to be asked of them: `Will they support someone if they're not
white?' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Riley said he will not be forced to support any candidate, even
if that candidate is the only candidate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This process has tied the hands of each and every board
member. These people have been thrown down our throats,'' Riley
said. ``I think there are a lot of people who are out there who can
possibly do the job, and I don't think Forgione is the man.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Forgione was among five leading candidates for
superintendent of the Austin School District in Texas. The Austin
school board's top choice has since withdrawn as a candidate, and
the school board is expected to meet with its search consultant
next week to review a new group of candidates. Forgione may be
among that group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forgione has been working as a consultant for Education
Secretary Richard Riley on a six-month contract since his term as a
commissioner at the U.S. Department of Education expired last
month. He formerly served as the state schools superintendent in
Delaware. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps was a longtime official with the Federal Aviation
Administration before serving as the director of the Oklahoma
Department of Human Services from 1991 to 1994. He owns an aviation
consulting company, Demps Enterprises Inc. in Oklahoma City. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8149 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRESS-CODE-KAN &LR;      07-03 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRESS-CODE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESS CODES AT CLUBS AND DISCOTHEQUES CHALLENGED AS RACIAL
DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN BORMANN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Jamiah-Khaliq just wanted to dance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When she and a group of friends showed up June 19 at Adolfo's
Discotheque, an upscale Kansas City nightclub at 1111 Grand Blvd.,
the 30-year-old dental student was wearing a two-piece navy suit.
She thought she measured up to the club's dress code. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But she was turned away, she said, because of her dreadlocks, a
hairstyle primarily worn by African-Americans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hairstyles and clothing do not make a person bad,'' she said.
``People obviously don't understand that this is discrimination.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Kansas City Human Rights Commission received a
complaint from another woman who said Adolfo's barred her because
of her hairstyle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll investigate them to determine whether this is'' racial
discrimination, said Michael Bates, the commission's director of
human relations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Adolfo's said that ``management feels that the
dress code is a reflection of the style of the club, and the items
listed in the dress code are not appropriate for the nightclub.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adolfo's dress code for Friday and Saturday nights bans
dreadlocks and braids, jeans, tennis shoes, athletic wear,
neon-colored and spiked hair, hats, baggy clothing, untucked shirts
and FUBU clothing. (FUBU, which stands for For Us By Us, is a
clothing line that was started by a group of African-American men
in New York City.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adolfo's, which is owned by Vincent Fries of southern Johnson
County, Kan., has 18 employees, 15 of whom are minorities, the
statement said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The club is the second at which issues of dress codes and race
have emerged recently. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Olathe, Kan., the owners of Roadhouse Ruby's South agreed in
June to change rules that forbid men from wearing corn rows, braids
or dreadlocks, and banned anyone wearing FUBU clothing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roadhouse Ruby's South co-owner Vicki Robertson said that club's
dress code had been misunderstood and that the restrictions were
not intended to discriminate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This might have been a perception, and that is damaging to the
business,'' Robertson said. ``We've always enjoyed the company of
anyone that wanted to come in.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the policy was aimed at the way patrons dress,
not their race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have tried to do is profile clothing,'' Robertson
said. ``It's a clothing thing. We don't want kids coming in there
sloppy, with clothing that would be less than desirable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henry Gueary III, president of the NAACP Olathe branch, said
Robertson told him that certain hairstyles were banned because a
security company told nightclub owners that corn rows, dreadlocks
and braids were typically worn by gang members. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamiah-Khaliq sees dreadlocks differently. To her, they're one
of the most beautiful and natural hairstyles that an
African-American woman can wear. It allows women to stray from the
mainstream, she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been called a gangster before,'' she said. ``We're
talking about them basing gang-related behavior on hairstyles and
clothing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP of Olathe received nine written complaints about
Roadhouse Ruby's South and several phone calls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Human Rights Commission did not receive complaints
about the Olathe business, but the commission's executive director,
Bill Minner in Topeka, Kan., said he was familiar with the dress
code and did not believe it violated the law because it was applied
to both black and white customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bates, of the Kansas City rights commission, disagreed with his
Kansas counterpart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly public accommodations can have a dress code, but if
that dress code is really designed to exclude certain groups of
people, then I disagree,'' Bates said. ``If we had a complaint
about that, we would take a very hard look at.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bates said that a local shopping center once identified patrons
wearing bandannas as troublemakers or gang members. Those people,
most of whom were black males, were asked to leave. Once commission
members worked with the mall, the policy was changed, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that on its face you say, `Well, why
is that necessary?' '' Bates said. ``What is the real motivating
factor?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gueary said he was continuing to work with Roadhouse Ruby's
South. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken a great first step in trying to assure that all
people will be respected the same,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, club owners have posted a sign at the club that
tells patrons to write ``if you feel you have been discriminated
against because of your race. Your concerns will be given the most
serious scrutiny and consideration.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adolfo's said in its statement Friday that it has no plans to
ease its dress code. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The only plans to change the dress code include management's
considerations to make the dress code more restrictive,'' Adolfo's
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamiah-Khaliq is determined to create something positive out of
her situation. Although she doesn't plan on walking back through
the dance club's doors, she said she would fight so that others can
have that right. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
