A8150 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-03 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISCAL YEAR 2000 BEGINS WITHOUT A BUG IN KANSAS, MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Kansas and Missouri say they began their
2000 budget year this week without a Y2K bug in sight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the rollover into the new fiscal year and everything
seems to be fine,'' said Morey Sullivan, an information resource
manager for the state of Kansas. ``If we were going to have
wholesale computer rejections it would have already happened.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A team of accountants and technicians fanned out across the
Kansas Y2K landscape Thursday but found nothing amiss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, Missouri and 44 other states began their 1999-2000
budget year Thursday. It was the first test of whether millions of
dollars worth of repairs had solved the states' Y2K problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a non-event,'' said Mike Benzen, Missouri's chief
information officer and president of the National Association of
State Information Resources Executives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now the question becomes: Will Y2K glitches that fall through
the cracks begin to surface in the coming weeks and overwhelm the
states' ability to manage their business? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, said Don Heiman, chief information technology officer in
Kansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once ``I can cross the July 1 barrier comfortably, I've
mitigated 25 percent of my system risk,'' Heiman said. ``So, it's a
big date for us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the fiscal boundary is significant because it tells
Heiman the state's Y2K testing procedures are sound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas didn't run into any data entry problems, even with as
many as 1,000 people logging onto the state's payroll and other
payment systems, Heiman said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, however, the July 1 date is no big deal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's because most fiscal year dates are not used to calculate
the payments that thousands of state residents receive every month.
Bills are paid, food stamps are issued, Medicaid payments are made
and vouchers are tracked by actual dates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ed Yardeni of Deutsche Bank Securities in New York, who predicts
a 70 percent chance of worldwide recession because of Y2K, warns
that ``non-event'' headlines may do more harm than good. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent these 1999 sideshows are set up as major tests
of whether Y2K is or isn't a big deal and they turn out to be
non-events, then people become even more complacent,'' Yardeni
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a meteor shower last November was supposed
to cause havoc with our satellites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital.)What's the big deal?(end ital.) people said later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Euro monetary conversion was another harbinger of Y2K woe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital.)Who cares?(end ital.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians got through their new fiscal year, and airlines
began booking flights into 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital.)It was all hype.(end ital.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This still doesn't mean we're going to get through Y2K
unscathed,'' Yardeni said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the record, as of June 23 Kansas had spent $7.2 million of
its $25 million Y2K budget to fix 187 mission-critical systems and
was 83 percent compliant. Missouri had spent $36 million of its $57
million Y2K budget to fix 225 mission-critical systems and was 88
percent compliant. &QL; 
 &LR; brk:Making it ...  &QL; 
 &LR; tx:Last Wednesday was the day many companies set as their deadline
to complete their year 2000 repairs, and some used the deadline to
trumpet their success. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. said it had found and
repaired its Y2K problems. Utilicorp United, which operates
Missouri Public Service, followed on Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Systems that provide natural gas and electricity to customers in
its eight-state area are year 2000 ready, said Bud Jeffress,
director of Utilicorp's year 2000 project. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We found very few items in our energy delivery systems that
needed to be corrected for year 2000,'' Jeffress said. ``We've
completed those necessary upgrades and replacements in systems
vital to providing the energy needs of our customers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Wolf Creek Nuclear Operating Corp. said all
crucial systems ``required for safe and reliable continued plant
operation are Y2K ready.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team has worked hard to ensure Wolf Creek will be online
Dec. 31, as well as Jan. 1,'' said Rick Muench, vice president of
engineering for Wolf Creek. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like all other area financial institutions, Commerce Bank was
required to complete its Y2K fixes by Thursday, and the St.
Louis-based financial institution said it made the deadline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right on track with the regulatory requirements for year
2000 readiness,'' said Charles F. Erker, corporate vice president
for Commerce Bancshares. ``We feel confident in our program and
look forward to a smooth transition into the year 2000.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some other area financial instutitions already had announced
they were compliant. &QL; 
 &LR; brk:Up in the air &QL; 
 &LR; txt:Despite visions of skydiving airplanes, some airlines say
bookings for Christmas and New Year's are as high as if not higher
than last year at this time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines spokesman John Hotard said bookings are up 5
percent over last year. And United Airlines, one of the world's
largest air carriers, reports that bookings are unchanged over last
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. computer reservation systems began accepting year 2000
travel requests on Feb. 4, easing fears that the Y2K bug could
snarl travel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
