<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICA-COMPETITION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICA'S OPPORTUNITIES FOR SKILLED WORKERS BENEFIT KC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Don't bet against high school dropout Tony
Criscione achieving his career ambition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to teach at the college level,'' said the 28-year-old
Prairie Village, Kan., man and SkillsUSA-VICA finalist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Criscione walked away from formal education a decade ago. Since
then he's found faith and a supportive wife, earned a high school
diploma and now stands just a few classes shy of a two-year
associate's degree from Johnson County (Kan.) Community College. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Virginia-based Vocational Industrial Clubs of America
Inc., he's also a reigning state champion and one of the nation's
best young practitioners at his skilled trade: heating, cooling and
ventilation equipment technician. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Criscione was one of 3,800 finalists who competed the past week
at the SkillsUSA-VICA national skills championships at Bartle Hall
in Kansas City Mo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth consecutive year the event has been in Kansas
City, and VICA officials announced this week they'll be back for at
least nine more years -- through 2008. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We love it here,'' said Stephen Danby, executive director of
the 34-year-old youth organization. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Danby said the Kansas City business and civic community's
financial assistance and volunteer support for the convention is
unprecedented. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotels treat our young people like adults,'' he said. ``We
have an excellent working relationship with the convention and
visitors bureau. They're real professionals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This (VICA convention) didn't just come to Kansas City,''
Danby said. ``You people are doing your jobs.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Reynolds, a VICA contest official and instructor at the
Kansas City Kansas Area Vocational Technical School, said the 80
computers loaned by Gateway Inc.'s Kansas City computer service
center are typical of the ``phenomenal'' level of community support
for VICA. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before Gateway stepped in, Reynolds said, students brought their
own computers to the competition. Readying that hodgepodge of
hardware for competition ``was a nightmare,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local unions contribute convention floor equipment and set-up
expertise, and scores of local companies provide judges, equipment
and supplies for the competition. Many more companies are
year-round VICA sponsors who furnish cash and other support to
VICA's classroom and on-the-job training programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VICA gives plenty back to Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Chappell, president of the Convention and Visitors Bureau
of Greater Kansas City, said VICA's 10,000 conventioneers spend
about $10 million while they're in town. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And this year they left behind more than greenbacks from their
wallets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross collected 43 units of blood that will be
used by blood banks in Missouri and Illinois. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VICA also may have helped a few Kansas Citians find jobs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, the organization set up a
public-access area where anyone could walk in, submit a resume via
e-mail, fill out a job application form and arrange for job
interviews with nearly three dozen participating companies, many of
them in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the organization will formally adopt the
SkillsUSA-VICA name it has used the past few years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some call VICA's annual competition the Olympics of everyday
life. High school and post-secondary education students such as
Criscione compete in 68 skilled labor events from computer repair
to welding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winners take home medals, scholarships and prizes of cash and
tools of their trade donated by a nationwide roster of sponsoring
businesses and corporations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessarily altruism on the part of private industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The auto industry will need 60,000 new auto technicians the
next few years,'' said Donald L. Gray, president and chief
executive of the industry's 3-year-old Youth Education Systems
group, which is active in training programs nationwide. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that VICA plays a critical role in our
industry,'' Gray said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with a nationwide skilled labor shortage, many
industries are desperate for experienced and trainable new
employees and VICA's 250,000 members are at the top of many job
applicant lists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All week Bartle Hall's massive convention floor was a jumble of
stoves, engines, air conditioners, hair dryers, computer terminals,
lumber, electrical wiring and other appliances, devices, gadgets
and tools used in business and industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One area was set up as a restaurant, where food and beverage
service contestants waited on judge-diners and were scored on their
performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One competitor, Jessica DeMotte, a 17-year-old junior at the
Johnson County Technical Education Center, said she is preparing
for a career in the hospitality industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I was a little girl the thing I love to do is
cook,'' DeMotte said. ``I hope someday to own my own restaurant.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, husband-and-wife team Gerald and Billie Randall
staffed a union booth at VICA's career and technical education
fair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City couple retired from TWA a few years ago but
remain active in Local 1650 of the International Machinists and
Aerospace Workers union. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Randall observed that times have changed for skilled
workers. ``I came out of a cornfield'' in 1949, he said, when a
friend found him a job at the old Fairfax Airport in Kansas City,
Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people today have a lot more opportunity than I had at
that age,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two vocational and technical students from Missouri and
Kansas qualified for competition this year, and several won top
honors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Morche, from Johnson County Community College, won first
place in the post-secondary schools division for nail care. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Harrisonville, Mo., team of Nanette Bosley, Cheri Graham,
Kelly Jennings and Misty Owens won second place in the
post-secondary Health Knowledge Bowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also, Stefanie Ribbing, of Springfield, Mo., was elected to be
national VICA Post Secondary Division secretary. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
