A8156 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTIFACTS-COLLECTION-     07-03 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIFACTS-COLLECTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM PRESERVES EXTENSIVE COLLECTION OF AMATEUR ARCHAEOLOGIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOSEPH, Mo. -- Two weeks ago, the daughters of the late J.
Mett Shippee, a pioneering Kansas City, Mo., area archaeologist,
delivered their father's remarkable collection to the St. Joseph
Museum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The collection, which includes most of Shippee's field notes,
encompasses more than 20,000 specimens, including pottery, spear
and arrow points, stone knives, ornamental items and numerous
tools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The items range in age from recent times back to what
archaeologists call the Paleo-Indian era, more than 10,000 years
ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the finest and most comprehensive array of artifacts
ever assembled in the Kansas City region,'' said Jim Feagins, a
retired science teacher and a member of both the Missouri and
Kansas City archaeological societies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``And because of the quality of Mett Shippee's field notes, it
is a gold mine of scientific value.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the collection's importance, Shippee's four daughters
spent years seeking a proper home for it. Initially they hoped to
place it in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Shippee's eldest daughter, Joan Wagner, who herself lives in
Kansas City, said that she and her sisters finally chose the St.
Joseph Museum because its staff seemed to understand the
collection's scientific value better than staffers at any Kansas
City facility they had visited. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, sad to say, St. Joe seems to have a greater
appreciation for history than Kansas City,'' Wagner said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't tear things down or throw things away like Kansas
City does. And my father always wanted to preserve the past.'' &QL; 
Drawn to digs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shippee, who died in 1985 at age 89, was first drawn to
archaeology during a visit to Illinois when he was 11 years old. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While walking in a field there, he found a chipped-stone spear
point. And as he turned it in his hand, examining the fine
workmanship, something awakened in him that remained vibrant for
the rest of his life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hooked then and there,'' Wagner said. ``He was
absolutely fascinated by the idea that there had been other people
on that land, literally thousands of years before he was, people
who could make these wonderful objects.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his early adult years, Shippee earned his living as a
carpenter. But he was constantly drawn away from his paying job and
back to archaeological digs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most amateur ``pot hunters,'' he kept meticulous notes
and detailed diagrams related to everything he found. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``From his voracious reading and study, he understood the value
of scientific methodology,'' Wagner said. ``He documented
everything down to the smallest detail.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shippee's observational abilities and intuitions as a field
archaeologist were often astounding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once while he was driving on old Route 10 through Avondale, Mo.,
with his daughter Helen, something caught his eye. He suddenly
braked the car, got out, walked into a field, and pulled a
beautiful stone point from the side of a hill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Years later, while walking on a sandbar in a northwest Missouri
stream, he plucked a chipped point from beneath the sand. It was a
Clovis point, made by one of the still-mysterious nomadic hunters
who roamed the plains some 10,000 years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each new discovery was for him a source of almost immeasurable
delight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wagner recalls a day in her childhood when her father drove home
in his old 1926 Ford. He was so excited he could barely talk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While digging in Platte County, near Riverside, Mo., he had
found a wonderful specimen, a large and beautifully made ceremonial
stone knife, perfectly preserved. It was, he estimated, several
thousand years old. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he was proud as a peacock that day,'' Wagner said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shippee's wife, Margaret, a brilliant woman with a strong
personality, had until then been dubious about his low-paying
archaeological work. She worried that it stole too much time from
making a living. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But after that day, everything changed. She had been greatly
moved by his joy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it looks like your father is going to be doing this work
permanently from now on,'' she told her daughters. ``And I guess I
might as well just make up my mind to it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She then went back to college and became a teacher, and her
earnings were soon the family's main financial support. &QL; 
Smithsonian sends help &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Shippee sent a letter to the Smithsonian Institution in
Washington outlining his work up to that point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His letter so intrigued the Smithsonian's staff that they sent a
young professional archaeologist named Waldo Wedel to work with
Shippee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greatly impressed by Shippee's discoveries and notes, Wedel gave
him the equivalent of a post-graduate education in field technique.
And together they made some of the most significant finds in the
history of Midwestern archaeology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s they found and excavated two sites of major
importance. One, known as the Steed-Kisker site (after the
landowners on whose property the excavation took place), was
located on the east bank of the Missouri River between Farley and
Weston. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There the two men uncovered the existence of a previously
unknown farming people whose hamlets had flourished along the river
between 1000 and 1250 A.D. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The other major dig was near Riverside. There they found
convincing evidence that the ancient Hopewell people, whose
once-great culture was centered in Ohio and Illinois, had extended
their range into the Missouri Valley before 600 A.D. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s, Shippee found significant traces of a much
older society near Missouri City. He named it the Nebo Hill site,
after a nearby church, and there he documented the existence of an
archaic culture that dated back as far as 3000 B.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Midwestern archaeology proved to be a fantastic field of
study,'' Feagins said. ``And Mett Shippee was right on the cutting
edge.''
`Salvage archaeologist' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As his work progressed, Shippee developed an ever-deepening
sense of kinship with the cultures whose traces he encountered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He would sit for hours pondering a specimen,'' Wagner said.
``I remember hearing him ask aloud, `How did the maker of this feel
as he worked? What did he think?' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken, gentle man, Shippee was rarely angered. But the
thought of untold archaeological treasures being bulldozed into
oblivion under new highways and subdivisions drove him into a
fury. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``His blue eyes just flashed with rage when he talked about
that,'' Wagner said. ``He knew that things of inestimable value
were being lost forever.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Shippee's friends in later years was a younger
archaeological enthusiast named Mike Fisher. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mett spent his last years trying to save sites from
destruction,'' he said. ``He began to see himself as a salvage
archaeologist.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is now working with the St. Joseph Museum team cataloging
Shippee's collection, a job that will take at least a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mett would be glad his work is here,'' Fisher said.
``He wanted to preserve history for everybody, not just for
academics or the rich. And that's what this place is all about.
It's for everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
