r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-     07-03 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREER DELIVERS WINNER IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers right-hander Rick Helling delivered
the game's first pitch in Texas' typical 90-degree July heat.
</P>
<P>
   That would pale in comparison to the emotions experienced last
night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers overcame the sixth-inning ejections of second
baseman Luis Alicea and manager Johnny Oates and a ninth-inning
failure by closer John Wetteland to beat the Seattle Mariners, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer delivered shortstop Royce Clayton
across the plate with the game-winning run with a one-out,
ninth-inning single off Mariners left-hander Jordan Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the second time this season and the 15th since the
start of the 1995 season that Greer drove in the game-winning run
during the Rangers' final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collectively as a team, we're playing with such confidence
that nobody panicked,'' said Clayton, who led off the inning with a
double against Mariners right-hander Ken Cloude (3-4). ``It was
like, `Now, let's just take care of business and take it from
here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something this team is getting a grip on. We're getting
some swagger and confidence, and there's no time like now to get
that going into the All-Star break and playing against teams in our
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer entered last night hitting .224 (24-for-107) during the
past 28 games, but the Rangers' red-headed outfielder came through
once again with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I've been swinging the bat recently, it just feels
good to contribute,'' said Greer, who deposited a 3-1 fastball into
the gap in left-center field. ``I'm up there trying to find it on a
daily basis. One at-bat I feel good; the next at-bat I don't. I
just have to keep battling.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the Rangers after Wetteland (2-2) failed to protect the
one-run lead that center fielder Roberto Kelly provided with his
one-out, eighth-inning home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good win, and that's the point,'' said Wetteland, who
lost his bid for save No. 26 when Charles Gipson scored on the
sacrifice fly by shortstop Alex Rodriguez. ``It probably should
have ended a half hour earlier before it did. I'm not disappointed,
though. I threw the ball extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions swelled during the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered the bottom half of that inning staring at a
5-2 deficit after the Mariners chased Helling during the top half
with their three-run, four-hit outburst.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Rangers rallied against Mariners left-hander Jamie
Moyer with consecutive one-out doubles by Greer and right fielder
Juan Gonzalez, and third baseman Todd Zeile and first baseman Lee
Stevens delivered two-out, run-scoring singles.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' single scored Zeile with the tying run and forced
Mariners manager Lou Piniella into his bullpen. Piniella summoned
right-hander Ken Cloude, who promptly loaded the bases by hitting
Clayton with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Alicea to the plate, whom Moyer retired twice on
called third strikes by plate umpire Marty Foster. Alicea worked
the count full before again watching a called third strike go by
with Foster behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Foster ejected Alicea for arguing balls and strikes and Oates
soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking to the wrong people,'' Oates said of the
ejections. ``Go to the umpires' room if you want to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Rangers escaped with their fourth consecutive
victory and extended their lead to seven games in the American
League West with Greer's ninth-inning heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing was I couldn't get my slider over the plate,''
Zimmerman said. ``I threw three sliders. They were all balls, and
he caught me on a fastball on the outside part of the plate. It's
my job to get a left-handed hitter out, and I just didn't get it
done.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
