A8158 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONVICT-CONFESSION-KA     07-03 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVICT-CONFESSION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN PLEADS GUILTY IN MURDER OF WOMAN WHO HELPED HIM ESCAPE PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within hours of killing Tracy L. Hayes last November, Chipper
Cox turned himself in and confessed to police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He admitted his crime again Friday in court, pleading guilty to
strangling Hayes with his hands and her bra after she helped him
escape from prison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cox, 31, must spend at least 25 years in prison before he can
seek parole under Friday's agreement between Chief Public Defender
Byron Cerrillo and Assistant District Attorney Rick Guinn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cox pleaded guilty in Johnson County (Kan.) District Court to a
charge of first-degree murder, which carries a mandatory life
sentence with parole eligibility after either 25 or 40 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for his guilty plea, prosecutors will not seek the
``Hard 40'' sentence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, 27, was left dead in a Shawnee, Kan., field Nov. 5. Cox
turned himself in to Oklahoma police and directed officers to her
body, which he had hidden under grass and pieces of clothing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He told police that he killed Hayes after she refused to drive
him back to his minimum security work assignment outside the walls
of the Lansing Correctional Facility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She and Cox had a 9-year-old son together, and prosecutors said
he lured her into helping him by promising to give her thousands of
dollars to pay off her mounting debts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They alleged in court documents that he concocted phony letters
to convince her that someone had paid him a large sum of money for
protecting his son in prison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cox was serving a 10- to 20-year sentence for the robbery and
attempted kidnapping of a woman in Edgerton, Kan., in 1992. He had
just been denied parole the month before the killing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hayes' mother, Becky Hamill, was in the courtroom Friday to
witness Cox's plea. Afterward, she said she would have preferred to
see Cox get the death penalty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to squirm and be afraid like my daughter was,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hamill said she has known Cox since he was a teen-ager. He has
always been a violent, foul-tempered ``conniver,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's done away with in prison,'' she said. ``I'll jump
for joy if it happens.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hamill said her daughter was a loving spirit who was as close to
a perfect daughter as possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Her problem was believing that scum,'' Hamill said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Thomas Bornholdt scheduled sentencing for Cox for
Aug. 6. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guinn said the case would have not qualified for the death
penalty under Kansas law. He said the plea ensures that in all
likelihood Cox will die in prison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guinn said he would continue to pursue a battery charge filed
against Cox for allegedly assaulting a deputy in the Johnson County
Jail in May. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And sentencing is still pending for Cox in Leavenworth County,
where he pleaded guilty to a charge of escape. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
