<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8161 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-tech-assault-HNS &LR;      07-03 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-tech-assault-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tech track coach Sholars charged with assault
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former assistant alleges she was bitten, punched
</P>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The head coach of Texas Tech's men's and women's track and field
teams, Greg Sholars, has been charged with assault as a result of
an incident in which he allegedly bit and punched a female
assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Sholars has been charged with misdemeanor assault as a result of
a March 16 incident in which he allegedly bit and punched Trece
Hayslett, then one of Sholars' assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Lubbock County court records show the charge was filed June 1
and that Sholars was arrested June 11. He posted $1,000 bond and
was released.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum sentence for misdemeanor assault is one year in jail
and a $4,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   According to an offense report prepared by Tech police, the
alleged assault occurred when Sholars and Hayslett argued in a
parked car on the Tech campus.
</P>
<P>
   The report states Hayslett immediately reported the incident to
Judith Henry, Tech's associate athletic director/senior woman
administrator, and was led to believe the matter would be
investigated by the athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Hayslett showed Henry a bite mark on
her left thigh. The report also indicates Sholars later
acknowledged to Henry that he had bitten Hayslett's leg.
</P>
<P>
   Hayslett reported the matter to campus police May 5, the police
report states, following a meeting in which she believed she had
been verbally abused by Sholars. According to the report, she
provided police with a series of photographs she had taken soon
after the alleged assault, one of which shows a bruise and teeth
marks on her left leg.
</P>
<P>
   The report quotes Hayslett as saying she planned to take a leave
of absence from Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Although the alleged assault occurred three days after Tech's
first meet of the 1999 outdoor track season, Sholars continued to
coach the men's and women's teams. The Tech women finished 12th at
the NCAA championships on the strength of the performance of
distance runner Leigh Daniels, who placed first in the 10,000
meters and second in the 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tech athletic director Gerald Myers said Friday he could not
comment on the alleged assault because it is a personnel issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something like that did happen _ and I'm not saying more
than if _ then we have policies in place to look into it,'' he
said. ``We would involve personnel (officials) and legal counsel.
That's not something we'd let slide.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to contact Sholars at his home and office Friday were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Sholars' attorney, Jesse Mendez, declined to discuss specific
aspects of the case but said his client is not guilty of assaulting
Hayslett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you his position is he's not guilty of anything
he's been charged with,'' Mendez said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry declined comment, saying questions regarding the matter
should be directed to Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted at her parents' home in Memphis, Tenn., Hayslett said
she did not want to comment on the details of the alleged assault
other than to say the police report is a true account.
</P>
<P>
   She said she initially did not go to police because she wanted
to protect Tech's track program and its athletes from negative
publicity and because she believed downplaying the incident would
improve her chances of becoming head women's track coach if the
program was split for the 1999-2000 school year.
</P>
<P>
   But as the spring wore on, she said, her responsibilities were
diminished and she became a target for harassment from Sholars and
other members of the track coaching staff. She said Sholars tried
to portray her as suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   When she mentioned her problems to Myers, she said, the athletic
director suggested she consider a leave of absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Myers) told me, `You can either work for him (Sholars), or
you can leave,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting in which Sholars was particularly hostile,
Hayslett said, she decided to contact campus police and return to
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, I realized the only one who could protect me is
me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayslett said she returned to Lubbock last week to put some
items in storage and meet with Henry. During the meeting, Hayslett
said, Henry asked her to return any items in her possession
belonging to the university and informed her that her last day of
employment would be June 30.
</P>
<P>
   She said Henry could not give her specific information regarding
Sholars but indicated Tech would turn over its entire track and
field staff by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Myers said Hayslett's employment as an assistant coach ended
June 30 because her contract was up. He declined comment on
Sholars' status except to say an announcement would be
``forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Sholars, 33, came to Tech as men's track coach in 1995 after
three years as assistant women's track coach and head women's cross
country coach at the University of Texas. He was given
responsibility for both the men's and women's track teams at Tech
when the programs were merged in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hayslett, 28, was hired by Sholars as an assistant coach at Tech
in 1997. She worked with hurdlers, jumpers and sprinters and had
responsibilities relating to recruiting and managing events. Before
coming to Tech, she worked as an assistant coach at Tulane and
Stephen F. Austin and as an intern in athletic administration at
UT.
</P>
<P>
   According to the offense report prepared by Tech police,
Hayslett said she and Sholars began arguing in Sholars' car March
16 because Sholars had taken a gun from her apartment without her
consent. She said Sholars left his vehicle with the gun, which was
in a case, and she left the vehicle with a pair of Oakley
sunglasses belonging to Sholars.
</P>
<P>
   Hayslett told police she went to her car with the sunglasses and
was pursued by Sholars, who beat on the window and asked loudly
that his sunglasses be returned. When she let him in her vehicle,
she said, he lunged for the sunglasses, which had fallen on the
floor, and bit her left thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Hayslett reported that Sholars also scratched her leg and
punched her twice with a closed fist on her right side. She told
police she went directly to Henry's office to report the incident
and showed the Tech official the teeth marks on her thigh.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hayslett's account, the police report includes a
summary of an interview with Henry conducted May 7 in which the
administrator described seeing a bruise and teeth marks on
Hayslett's leg. Henry also told police Sholars had voluntarily come
to her office the next week and admitted biting Hayslett.
</P>
<P>
   Sholars, when contacted by campus police, said he did not want
to answer questions without first consulting an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Hayslett called the investigating
officer May 10 and 11 from Memphis stating that she did not want to
press charges against Sholars, in part because she feared she would
be subject to personal and professional retaliation. The report
states Hayslett was told the case would be presented to Lubbock
County prosecutors even if she wanted it dropped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
