<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAININAN-VISIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UKRAINIAN OFFICIALS LEARN ABOUT CITY PROGRAMS, IDEAS DURING KC
VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YANG JIANXIANG  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Two Ukrainian city officials concluding a
two-week visit to Kansas City said they enjoyed a city with
``fairy-tale'' beauty and an impressive level of citizen
participation in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one person or one place we met with or visited we did not
enjoy,'' Olena Maksymivna Pshenyshnyuk, deputy mayor of Pervomaisk,
said at a press conference Friday morning at the Greater Kansas
City Chamber of Commerce. ``What I have seen here exceeded my
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Pshenyshnyuk and Valentyna Hryhorivna Zavadska, director of
Pervomaisk's Economic and Reforms Unit, came as part of a Community
Partnerships project pairing 18 Ukrainian cities with U.S.
counterparts. The three-year partnerships project, started a year
ago, provides training and education to local governments in
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Pervomaisk is a city of 82,800 people in south-central Ukraine.
It was a center of nuclear missile construction in the former
Soviet Union, and now faces the problem of shifting a heavily
military-based industrial base to a civilian one.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, the Ukraine officials observed a variety
of local government activities around the metropolitan area. They
toured a Missouri Area Agency on Aging office, participated in a
``Clean Sweep'' neighborhood clean-up in Kansas City and visited
the Summit Technology Campus in Lee's Summit, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   They also went to Whiteman Air Force Base in Knob Noster, Mo.,
where they watched U.S. technicians dismantle nuclear missiles once
aimed at the former Soviet Union. A team of three Kansas Citians
witnessed a similar scene in Pervomaisk last November.
</P>
<P>
   Pshenyshnyuk said she hopes the partnership between the two
cities could focus on business in the near future. The two
officials spent part of their time here trying to line up potential
retail outlets for Ukrainian crafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to establish a business center in
Pervomaisk to promote economic development,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pshenyshnyuk expressed thanks for three Y2K-compliant computers
donated by Sprint, which will be installed in the new business
center.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors said they were impressed by the ``very high level''
of citizen participation in government here. They said they believe
the right kind of government encouragement can promote greater
participation, and that was a focus of much of their conversation
with local officials.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were also amazed at the good working atmosphere
in all the places they visited. ``People talk openly and freely,
regardless of their positions,'' Zavadska said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ukrainian guests said they had learned in advance that the
United States was a rich country offering ``many possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wonderful country,'' Pshenyshnyuk said. ``We may not
achieve that level in the short term. But it is what we're looking
at in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   The learning was reciprocal. Roger L. Kroh, director of Johnson
County's (Kan.) Department of Planning, Development and Codes, said
the exchange of views with the visitors made him more appreciative
of what Americans' ancestors have done with this country.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur A. Davis III, associate director of the Civic Council of
Greater Kansas City, said he was now convinced that a truly
successful democracy starts with local government, not
``top-down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pshenyshnyuk said the biggest surprise she had was witnessing
the crowd stand for the national anthem at a Royals' game.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the people stood up, even children who might not know very
well what that means. It's a good way to show respect to your
country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Zavadska was impressed with a retirement community they visited.
They talked with a resident whose grandparents came from Ukraine.
There are no such communities in Pervomaisk, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City is beautiful, like in a fairy tale,'' Pshenyshnyuk
said. She thought highly of the ``Clean Sweep'' activity, a Kansas
City program in which city workers and neighborhood volunteers
clean up a neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials will depart for home today from Kansas City
International Airport. Another team of three from Kansas City will
leave for Pervomaisk in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
