<HEADLINE>
AL EXEC ASKS TORRE NOT TO PICK GONZALEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Phyllis Merhige, the American League's senior
vice president, advised Yankees manager Joe Torre not to select
Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez as a reserve for the 1999
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Merhige determined yesterday that Gonzalez does not plan to
attend the All-Star Game if selected after conversations yesterday
with Rangers officials. Gonzalez reiterated that position before
last night's game at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Merhige also spoke with Torre in New York, but the final
decision rests with the Yankees' manager, who will select the
league's pitchers and reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just do my job, and that is make my choices,'' said
Torre, who will manage the AL. ``If Juan chooses not to go, I'll
choose somebody else. I hope he comes, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez refused to budge from his position despite yesterday's
plea from Torre. Gonzalez remains miffed by the balloting process
and described it as ``a popularity contest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' two-time AL most valuable player remains fifth in
the balloting behind Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. and Cleveland's
Manny Ramirez, Kenny Lofton and David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to recharge my batteries and come back strong for
the second half to help my team,'' Gonzalez said. ``I don't play
for the league. I play for the Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, whose contract calls for him to receive a $50,000
bonus if selected to play in the All-Star Game, appreciated Torre's
comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with Joe,'' Gonzalez said. ``Joe is a
great guy and a great manager.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
