u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MULLIN-NYT &LR;      07-03 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MULLIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN MULLIN, 85, WHOSE MAGNETIC TAPE FREED RADIO BROADCASTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John T. Mullin, who brought broadcasting and the record industry
together with the magnetic audiotape technology that revolutionized
them in the late 1940s, died June 24 at his home in Camarillo,
Calif. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   An electrical engineer, Mullin became interested in magnetic
audiotape when he was a lieutenant with the U.S. Army Signal Corps
in England in 1943. He heard, inexplicably, what sounded like live
classical music, free of clicks and scratches, coming 24 hours a
day from a German radio station.
</P>
<P>
   After the war ended, Mullin was sent to Paris, where he
discovered two German magnetophones, high-fidelity magnetic
audiotape recorders.
</P>
<P>
   He then brought the machines to the United States, where he and
a colleague, William Palmer, improved them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, their creation was the first machine in the United
States to produce a master tape that was turned into a commercial
recording, ``Songs by Merv Griffin.''
</P>
<P>
   The masters from which records were produced had until then been
made by recording directly onto an acetate disk, which made editing
almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Bing Crosby was so impressed with the quality of the tape's
sound and, especially, the ability to edit recordings that he
backed Mullin and Palmer financially.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, Crosby, who hated live performances, used the
technology to record his show on the ABC network, ``Philco Radio
Time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first coast-to-coast commercial broadcast using
magnetic tape instead of a live performance.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin and Palmer also used the ability to edit audiotape for
less artistic purposes. For Crosby's show, at the singer's behest,
they made some of the first laugh tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Using scissors and tape, the pair added applause and laughter to
tapes of live performances that didn't inspire enough audience
reaction or that weren't really live at all.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Mullin and Palmer, working with Ampex
Corp., made the first commercial audiotape recorder, called Model
200. And in 1951, Mullin and another engineer, Wayne Johnson,
working again with Crosby Enterprises, also developed a prototype
of the video camera, which they called ``the filmless camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullin, known as Jack, was born Oct. 5, 1913, in San Francisco.
He graduated from Santa Clara University with an engineering
degree.
</P>
<P>
   Besides working with Crosby Enterprises and Ampex, Mullin spent
28 years at the 3M Company, which bought Crosby's electronics
company in 1956, as the head of its Mincom division. He retired in
1975.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a daughter, Eve Collier of Camarillo; two
sons, John C., of Los Osos, Calif., and Peter B., of Huntington
Beach, Calif., and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8167 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-GORDON-TEX     07-03 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-GORDON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH THE REAR-VIEW MIRROR: GORDON MIGHT BE CLOSER TO THE FRONT
THAN HE APPEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Two-time champion and noted commentator
Ned Jarrett has a reputation as one of the foremost experts on
stock-car racing, but his bosses at CBS Sports might want to
re-evaluate his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup season hits the midway point with the running of
the Pepsi 400 tonight at Daytona International Speedway, and
Jarrett said the guy to beat in the points race is not the guy in
first, second, third or fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's favorite is the driver in fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the way they run, the way they approach things, he is
still the man to beat, even as far back as he is,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Jarrett isn't so crazy. ``He'' is three-time champion
Jeff Gordon, and although Gordon is 314 points behind leader Dale
Jarrett, Gordon's No. 24 DuPont Refinishes Chevrolet looms large
going into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never count the 24 car out,'' said Jimmy Makar, crew
chief of the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac that Bobby Labonte
has driven to second place in the standings. ``That's a very
capable race team.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a tribute to the talents, reputations and accomplishments
of Gordon and crew chief Ray Evernham that they would even be
mentioned as a possible team to beat in the second half,
considering the hole they dug in the first 16 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather be leading the points and have guys try to
knock me off than be where we're at,'' said Gordon, who led after
the 17th race last year en route to his third championship in four
years. ``We have a lot more work to do from where we're at now than
we would if we were leading.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of work might be an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Gordon in fifth place, but he trails a veritable
who's who of NASCAR superstars. Jarrett is first, followed by Bobby
Labonte, Mark Martin and Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett might be due to win his first championship. The driver
of the No. 88 Quality Care/Ford Credit Ford finished third in the
points in 1996, second in '97 and third last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since getting caught up in a wreck and finishing 37th at the
season-opening Daytona 500, Jarrett has dominated. He has won two
races, finished in the top five 12 times, and in the top 10 14
times. He is 157 points ahead of Labonte, the biggest lead of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically haven't had any problems since Daytona,'' Jarrett
said. ``There's been days that we've struggled, but we've made
something of it. Hopefully, we can continue and the next time I'm
in Daytona, we'll be talking about my first Winston Cup
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is having the best season of his career, despite four
finishes of 24th or lower. He has won twice and finished in the top
five 11 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can gain on things even more through the rest of
the year,'' said the Texas native, whose best Winston Cup finish
came last year, when he was sixth. ``We've got a long ways to go.
We're just trying to run every race just as good as we can and
we're not going to worry about the points.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin is having his usual season of quiet, consistent
excellence. The driver of the No. 6 Valvoline Ford, who has been in
the top five in points eight times this decade, has won once and
finished in the top 10 in 13 of the first 16 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really pleased with the performance of this team,'' he
said. ``We may not have won as many races as last year yet, but
there have been many races that we were in a position to win. Even
though we may not have the best car every week, if we are
consistently competitive, we will be up front to capitalize on an
opportunity to win a race that we might not have dominated.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton is the only one of the drivers leading Gordon who isn't
running well at the moment. He finished 36th and 24th in the past
two races, and starts 37th tonight after blowing an engine in
qualifying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Burton was good enough earlier in the season to win
three races this year and to finish in the top five nine times, and
expects to turn it around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we're going to go out and win 10 of the next 16
races, but I am saying that I think we'll have the chance to win
some races,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With that foursome ahead of him, it will be difficult for Gordon
to ascend to the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Dale Jarrett, Bobby Labonte, Mark Martin, Jeff
Burton, those guys have just really been doing what they need to
do, and that's finishing up front and winning races,'' Gordon said.
``As long as they're doing that, we're going to have a tough time
catching them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon will have to avoid the problems that plagued him thus
far.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly invincible driver was shockingly mortal at times
in the first half. He failed to finish four races, including the
Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway on March 28, when he hit the
wall in Turn 4 and finished last for the first time in his career.
He had only two DNFs all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've got going against them this year that they
haven't in the past few years is the luck factor, that bad
fortune-good fortune thing,'' Ned Jarrett said. ``They were in
quite a few situations in years past that I'd see them drive
through, around and not get involved in. This year, they seem to be
getting caught up in things. That's all it takes in this business
to find yourself down a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, though, is back up at the moment. He climbed three spots
in the standings in the past four weeks with one victory and three
second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, team morale is good, and our confidence level is
there,'' Gordon said. ``We feel like we're capable of winning each
time we go out. We're performing excellent right now. We've got the
consistency, and that's what we need to continue to do.''
</P>
<P>
   If he keeps it up, Ned Jarrett's prediction of Gordon as the man
to beat in the second half might not seem so crazy after all.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
