r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVEST-AZR &LR;      07-03 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO ANNOUNCE VENTURE CAPITAL PLAN FOR SMALL BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Small businesses in low- and moderate-income neighborhoods in
Arizona will get the same kind of economic boost that gave Intel
Corp. and Federal Express Corp. their start under a plan President
Clinton will announce Wednesday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   A new investment company being formed will be the first of its
kind in the nation aimed at ``New Markets,'' companies locating or
hiring in lower-income areas such as south and central Phoenix,
White House officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Six major banks in the Valley already have committed $5 million,
the minimum needed to form the Small Business Investment Company,
to be called Magnet Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers, led by the Arizona MultiBank, have been forming the
plan and raising money since September. On Wednesday, Clinton will
officially announce their application for a license for the
investment company.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers say this is what Clinton will deliver to the
Valley, specifically to lower-income areas in Phoenix. For small
businesses, the investment company will fill the huge gap that
exists in Arizona between traditional bank loans and big-bucks,
hard-to-get venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do the right things and do them in a businesslike
manner,'' said Andrew Gordon, president of the Arizona MultiBank.
``Only with profits can we sustain our positive impact in the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The SBIC is an example of the private investment Clinton hopes
to encourage on his tour next week. About 336 similar investment
companies already operate in the United States, with $9.9 billion
invested or ready to invest. But the Phoenix firm will be the first
to apply under new rules aimed at developing investment in New
Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Magnet &UR; Capital is expected to open next spring. It will
emphasize investment in lower-income areas but will do deals
statewide, said Gordon and Mike Shields, national projects manager
for Bank One.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One, Wells Fargo Bank, Arizona MultiBank, Sears National
Bank, Union Bank of Arizona and Northern Trust Bank have signed on
as investors. More are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Magnet &UR; Capital will be a for-profit, limited partnership with
separate management from the MultiBank. Shields and Greg Mischel, a
former Bank of America executive and small-business consultant,
will be the general partners and managers of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; It will look for younger, fast-growing companies that don't
necessarily have enough tangible assets or income to get bank
loans. &UR; Instead it will provide ``patient capital,'' Gordon and
Shields said.
</P>
<P>
   It will look to invest in manufacturing, wholesale and service
businesses, ``non-glamorous'' companies that do an estimated $96
billion in sales in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be looking for a business in the less glamorous
category than high tech and the Internet; the more common kind of
manufacturing, wholesale and service-sector businesses,'' Shields
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``They will be generally younger businesses that appear to be
growing rapidly and that have a need for `patient' capital,
generally less than $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona MultiBank is a non-profit corporation founded in
1992 as an initiative of the Arizona Bankers Association to finance
deals considered too risky for traditional banks. Since then, it
has made 203 loans totaling $12.7 million, with 86 percent of the
deals going to small businesses and the rest to non-profit
corporations and affordable housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The MultiBank started seriously investigating the idea of an
SBIC last fall, Gordon said, when it started seeing more businesses
that need equity financing rather than loans.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers made a presentation to the SBA in February, about the
same time the proposed regulations on New Markets investment
companies came out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The banks are interested in Magnet Capital because they already
have branches and employees in lower-income areas, and this could
help grow businesses that could become their customers, Gordon
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The U.S. Small Business Administration, which oversees the SBIC
program, plans to offer a number of incentives to the investment
companies. Some of them:
</P>
<P>
   The SBA will double or triple the private investment, allowing
SBICs to borrow millions of dollars in additional capital at
favorable interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The SBIC will not have to make payments to the government for up
to five years, allowing it to be ``patient'' with the companies it
invests in.
</P>
<P>
   The SBIC would be allowed to own a controlling interest of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SBICs also would have the chance to make greater profits,
because they could negotiate for warrants or stock options, which
can pay off handsomely if a company prospers.
</P>
<P>
   SBICs have generated returns of 8 percent to 19 percent over the
past four years, but that is considered conservative because many
of the investments are still with the companies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gordon and Shields believe the Valley has plenty of companies
with untapped potential for the new SBIC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Despite the large amount of economic growth we've seen in
Phoenix and Arizona, I'm not sure some of the underserved
geographical markets have moved along at the same pace,'' Shields
said. ``I think there are wonderful opportunities out there.'' &QL; 
Jane Larson can be reached at (602) 444-8280 or
jane.larson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
