<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-Y2K-LIABILITY-NY     07-03 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-Y2K-LIABILITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: Y2K LIABILITY LIMITS
</HEADLINE>
  (rk)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 3:
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's ill-advised turnabout on
legislation designed to limit the liability of computer and
software manufacturers for year 2000 computer problems will hurt
consumers and small businesses. The Y2K defect is in some computers
and software that record years by the last two digits. Unless
corrected, the glitch could cause serious malfunctions when the
date rolls over to 2000 and a computer confuses that with 1900. For
months the White House voiced opposition to both House and Senate
bills that would restrict the legal rights of those injured by a
Y2K computer failure.
</P>
<P>
   But with the high-tech industry worried about frivolous lawsuits
and demanding legal protections, the White House changed its tune
and agreed to a compromise that is not much better than earlier
bills it had rejected. The compromise bill's provisions would not
merely discourage frivolous suits, they would reduce the rights of
those with legitimate claims. Worse, they might lessen the
incentive for industry to identify and correct Y2K problems before
they arise. The bill, approved by Congress on Thursday, would make
it harder to bring class-action suits. It caps punitive damages at
$250,000 against companies with fewer than 50 employees and gives
companies 90 days to cure a Y2K problem before they can be sued.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also suspend ``joint and several'' liability, the
legal principle that makes any defendant liable for the entire
judgment in case other responsible parties cannot be sued or are
otherwise unable to pay. The bill would limit financial liability
in most Y2K cases to a formula based on a defendant's share of
responsibility, a significant departure from tort law principles
designed to fully compensate injured plaintiffs. Only in cases
brought by individual consumers would joint and several liability
still apply. Just two months ago, the administration said it would
accept a change to these liability rules only for defendants who
had taken steps to prevent or minimize Y2K breakdowns. The
compromise bill fails to include this crucial requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says the bill addresses a unique problem and
will not set a precedent for broader tort reform. The bill applies
only to Y2K-related claims arising before 2003. But people and
businesses with losses caused by the Y2K bug will find it harder to
get redress from those responsible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
