<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8203 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-LADN     07-03 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE IN HIDE-N-SEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When that wacky major-league schedule finally
brought the San Francisco Giants to Dodger Stadium Friday night _
just about two months into the season _ you wondered if they'd have
the nerve to show up.
</P>
<P>
   After their shameful display last weekend at 3Com Park, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   Not losing two out of three games to the Dodgers, shameful as
that might have been.
</P>
<P>
   What was disgraceful was pulling the hidden-ball trick on the
Dodgers in the Saturday afternoon game.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, taking advantage of the weak-minded that way.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, generations of Californians, southern and northern,
have understood the Giants will stop at nothing to frustrate the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Candlestick Park groundskeeper used to muddy the baselines
to slow Maury Wills. Dick Dietz tried to end Don Drysdale's shutout
streak by (begin ital)letting(end ital) a pitch hit him; he didn't
get away with it. In the notorious case of Juan Marichal and Johnny
Roseboro, the Giants resorted to bopping their rival on the head
with a stick; Marichal got off light with a $1,750 fine and an
eight-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows what Gaylord Perry had up his sleeve?
</P>
<P>
   All in the spirit of competition, those things.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the Giants sank too low.
</P>
<P>
   We already knew the Giants were the savvy, resourceful team and
the Dodgers were the brawny, big-money team.
</P>
<P>
   The hidden-ball trick?
</P>
<P>
   That was rubbing it in.
</P>
<P>
   It happened with two out in the fourth inning, with Chris Brock
on the mound for the Giants, after Dodgers pitcher Carlos Perez
legged out a bunt single that scored Devon White with the run that
made the lead 3-1 in a game Los Angeles won 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Giants first baseman J.T. Snow realized he had a
live one, like guy with a shell game spotting a tourist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a close play,'' Giants first baseman J.T. Snow said
before Friday's game, ``and when I turned around to see the
umpire's call, I saw that Perez and the first-base coach (John
Shelby) had their backs turned, so they wouldn't know if I threw
the ball back to Chris.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow tucked the ball in his glove and hovered near first base as
Perez sauntered back to the bag, conversing with Shelby as he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mouthed to Chris that I had the ball, and he nodded,'' Snow
said. ``Pitchers are good guys to use it on because they're not on
base that much. (Perez) was a good guy to try it with because he's
emotional. He gave it a little (celebration) when he was called
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick depended on Brock's acting ability, on Perez's sloppy
fundamentals and nobody else in blue shouting a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Brock had to look busy until Perez wandered off the bag, an
assignment complicated by the rules that say standing on the
pitching rubber without the ball constitutes a balk.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Giants had to hope Perez wasn't taught to stay on
the base until the pitcher toes the rubber.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ironic thing about the play was that Chris got up on the
mound, and that's when Perez stepped off the bag. I couldn't tag
him then, because Chris was near the rubber,'' Snow said. ``I just
kind of stared at Chris and looked over at Perez.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock took the non-verbal cue and walked off the back of the
mound, as if he was going to the resin bag. Perez, a few feet off
the base, looked stunned when Snow slapped him with his glove and
umpired Charlie Reliford delivered an emphatic ``out'' call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about doing a little dance myself,'' said Snow,
referring to the shimmy with which Perez punctuates strikeouts _ to
the annoyance of his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco fans loved it so much, a video clip of the play is
a new fixture on the Giants Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The hidden-ball trick is something you pull on your kid brother
who doesn't quite understand the game. It rarely fools
big-leaguers. It's rarely (begin ital)tried(end ital) against
big-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager Dusty Baker said this was the second time he'd
seen it work in 27 years as a major-league player, coach and
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're all professionals,'' said Giants second
baseman Jeff Kent, ``and we know where the ball's going. Plus
you've got 25 guys in the other dugout _ plus coaches _ to help the
runner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't work, it kind of backfires on you,'' said Snow.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if the runner catches on, (begin ital)you're(end
ital) the idiot.
</P>
<P>
   But the way the Dodgers-Giants rivalry runs these days, it's no
surprise the stunt worked.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry has changed since the days of Wills, Marichal and
Perry, when the best the Giants could do was nip at the Dodgers'
ankles.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have gone 64-61 against the Dodgers in the 1990s. The
Giants have put up 26 more regular-season wins than the Dodgers
since the start of 1986 and finished higher in the National League
West standings in seven of those 13 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-3 victory Friday _ with Brock defeating Perez but without a
hidden-ball trick _ kept the Giants at the top of the division and
the Dodgers at the bottom. No longer do the Giants live to
frustrate the Dodgers. And the Dodgers are plenty frustrated with
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giants are a talented club (and) they know what it takes
to win,'' said Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone, asked about
the contrast during batting practice Friday. ``I think we've got
talent comparable with any team we play. We have winning players.
Now we need to come together and be a winning (begin ital)team(end
ital).''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the tricks the Giants seem to know and the Dodgers
need to learn. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
