<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER HAS NO PITY FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when the essence of Dodger baseball is being
challenged on a daily basis, and now from the unique perspective of
last place, it is disconcerting to see Dusty Baker in a San
Francisco Giants uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The fact he has been wearing one for 12 years now, the last
seven as manager, doesn't change the feeling. The Dodgers no longer
look like the Dodgers. But when you look at Baker, even in the
Giants' Halloween colors, you still see Dodger Blue.
</P>
<P>
   He wore the uniform for eight years and in more games than any
other, and was part of four division champions. When you talk about
the Dodgers' past, and lord knows there's little reason to talk to
about the present, Baker is as much a part of it as any other '70s
and '80s icon.
</P>
<P>
   He served up an example of the good old days sitting at his desk
in the visiting clubhouse Friday evening. He was putting together
his lineup card while a TV interview of former teammate Don Sutton
played in the background. As Sutton made a reference to ``his not
being cocky or arrogant,'' Baker, head down, said, ``Awwww,
Sutton.''
</P>
<P>
   It broke the room up. It was one more laugh than the Dodgers
have had this season.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's Dodgers never had their heart or work ethic questioned,
as the '90s Dodgers have, and the clubhouse attitude reflected why.
It was a happenin' place to be. Teammates occasionally quibbled
i.e., Steve Garvey versus Sutton, still good for a smile 20 years
later but the sense of purpose never wavered. Considering the
inertness of the '90s Dodgers, a good old scuffle might be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's Giants clubhouse has a happenin' atmosphere. There was
plenty of noise, talk and attitude in the hours before game time,
loud counterpoint to the Dodgers' daily funeral mass.
</P>
<P>
   It has essentially been that way since Baker was named manager
in 1993, which may explain why the Giants have contended for a
division title or postseason play every year but one, the
injury-wracked 1996 team.
</P>
<P>
   Baker takes no credit for it. ``It comes from them,'' he said.
``This is my office. It's their clubhouse. What I can do is head
things off when I see a potential problem coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give them the freedom to enjoy themselves, so long
as they know when it's time to get serious. It can't be grab-ass.
All I ever ask of them is to play hard and play smart.''
</P>
<P>
   But would the Giants have been in contention so often this
decade if not for Baker? Probably not. This team has been known as
Barry Bonds and his Octet now for seven years. Only one other every
day player has been an all-star since '93, Matt Williams, who has
been gone for three years.
</P>
<P>
   And can you name a Giants starting pitcher from the last seven
years? It's a brain teaser. The Giants have had six different
pitchers lead the team in wins the last six seasons, and they're
headed for a seventh if Russ Ortiz (9-5) holds his lead.
</P>
<P>
   Baker does not have sympathy, advice or time for the Dodgers.
There's no crying in baseball, and there's no sympathy, either.
``If you're looking for sympathy, you're in the wrong business,''
he said. ``And I have no time to worry about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker freely admits that playing and beating the Dodgers does
not have the same feeling as it did three years ago. Giant fans may
take the rivalry quite literally ``It's a north-south, L.A.-San
Francisco thing. Fresno is the Mason-Dixon line, and L.A. stole our
water,'' he said but beat L.A. is not a rallying cry for the team.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't bury them, either. He respects Dodgers General
Manager Kevin Malone, he of the spring training World Series
proclamation that now hangs from his neck like a two-ton necklace,
and he says times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like and respect Kevin,'' he said. ``The problem with making
a statement like that is, if you're wrong, you've got to live with
it, and it can put a lot of pressure on the team and manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said teams do not grow up together, as the Dodgers once
did, and the sense of ``home'' has been skewed by so much player
movement. Baker and Reggie Smith were additions to the
Garvey-Sutton group, but they stayed long enough for them to be
considered Dodgers for life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the wake of the Fox-for-O'Malley transaction, the
Dodgers change faces with as much abandon as any team,. There are
only two regulars and not a single pitcher left from 1993, Baker's
first season as a manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it's not the same organization when people you knew
and cared about are no longer there,'' he said. ``You get used to
seeing the same batting practice guys and same stadium people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But nothing lasts forever. It's no different than in the
corporate world, when a new CEO brings in his own people. They can
do whatever they want. It's their organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The reminder was apropos, but not needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
