<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DEFEAT A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ It was a fresh start, a chance for some healing.
</P>
<P>
   After the Angels lost three in a row to the Texas Rangers
earlier in the week, they got a chance to move onward with a
three-game series against the Oakland A's, whom they swept last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took their cue and beat the A's 10-6 before 8,570 at
the Oakland Coliseum. The Angels scored what turned out to be the
winning run not on a hit, but on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Velarde, who had four of the Angels' 14 hits, scored from
third when Chad Harville's breaking ball got past catcher A.J.
Hinch, giving the Angels a 7-6 lead with one out in the eighth. The
Angels added three runs in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the fifth time in the last 35 games the Angels have
scored at least five runs in a game. Reliever Mark Petkovsek (7-2)
earned the win over Harville (0-1).
</P>
<P>
   The Texas series, as much as anything, showed the Angels how far
they have to go. They were swept by scores of 9-1, 5-0 and 18-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed me we have tough work to do,'' shortstop Gary
DiSarcina said. ``Obviously, we're not where we want to be. I don't
care if we lose 3-1, 3-1, 3-1 or 15-2, 15-2, 15-2. The bottom line
is we lost all three games and we lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me personally, it's disappointing because we were exposed
in every facet where we are weak. We have a lot of work to do, it's
a long road ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   That road started with Friday's game against Oakland. No matter
how discouraging the losses to the Rangers were, DiSarcina said the
Angels must realize there is still more than half the season
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game where you have to file the disappointments real
quickly or you'll end up dwelling on it for weeks,'' he said. ``You
have to move on and accept the fact they pummeled us. You don't
want to dig a hole, bury our heads in it and give up.''
</P>
<P>
   With Tim Salmon and Jim Edmonds out of the lineup because of
injuries, the Angels have little room for error, DiSarcina says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't moan about what you don't have,'' he said. ``That's
wasted energy. You have to do the little things when you're missing
the big guys. Move runners over, and make sure you don't give a
team four outs.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina had a chance to make a big play in the fifth inning
Friday but came up short. With the game tied at 4, the A's had
Jason Giambi at third with two out. Ramon Hernandez hit a grounder
up the middle that DiSarcina smothered, but his throw to first was
late and Giambi scored to give the A's their first lead of the game
5-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rallied in the seventh, taking a 6-5 lead on Troy
Glaus' two-run double. For the slumping Glaus, it was just his
third extra-base hit in 75 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But the A's came back again, tying the game at 6 on Hinch's RBI
single in the bottom of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde, who raised his average to .305, started the Angels'
winning rally in the eighth with his third hit. He went to third on
Mo Vaughn's single before coming home on the wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels won the game despite losing the services of pitching
coach Dick Pole, who was ejected in the bottom of the first inning
by first-base ump Terry Craft.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and one out, Matt Stairs hit a
grounder to Vaughn at first. Vaughn threw to DiSarcina at second
for the force, and his relay to pitcher Steve Sparks, covering
first, appeared to be in time. But instead of being the final out
of the inning, Craft called Stairs safe.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Pole was ejected for arguing from the bench.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
