<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISIONIST THINKING HAS JARRETT WINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the fourth week of Jeff Burton's reign atop the NASCAR
Winston Cup points standings this season, I had a phone
conversation with one of Ford Motor Co.'s public relations
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Burton was flexing real muscle in his Ford Taurus at that point.
He had taken a lead that had shrunk to two points over Bobby
Labonte and expanded it to 85 over Dale Jarrett after the Goody's
Body Pain 500 at Martinsville (Va.) Speedway on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, the reigning and three-time Cup champion, was
fourth at that juncture, 129 points behind Burton. What was
bothering my friend at Ford was that practically every mention of
Burton was almost immediately followed by a reference to Gordon,
who happens to drive a Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   Brand loyalty aside, the point was this: When does it become
time to write off Gordon's chances of repeating as Cup champion?
</P>
<P>
   We may be able to stick a fork into Gordon and the Rainbow
Warriors soon, although not after tonight's Pepsi 400 at the
Daytona International Speedway. Gordon runs great in restrictor
plate races at DIS, where he is the defending event champion and
where he won the season-opening Daytona 500 on Feb. 14.
</P>
<P>
   But standing between Jarrett and Gordon in the points chase are
a growing-in-confidence Bobby Labonte, the relentless Mark Martin
and his clone, Burton. That's a lot of heavy metal and mettle to
leapfrog during the remaining 18 races.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon clearly will need a repeat of his awesome 1998
second-half to make a run for it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that one year ago _ after 16 races _ Gordon had put up
these stats: Five poles, four victories, 10 top-fives, 11 top-10s
and two Did Not Finish results. He was leading the standings by 40
points over Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's stats heading into tonight? Five poles, four victories,
10 top-fives, 11 top-10s _ the same as last year in each category _
but four DNFs.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Race No. 17 last year at Loudon, N.H., Gordon
went on a 14-race romp that produced seven victories, four
runner-ups, a third and two fifths. It's difficult to imagine even
Gordon _ winner of a single-season record-tying 13 races last year
_ consistently putting those kinds of whippings on Jarrett,
Labonte, Martin ``and'' Burton this time around.
</P>
<P>
   My revised choice to replace Gordon, then, is Jarrett, who has
finished third or better in the final standings for three
consecutive years. At 42, the clock is ticking on his bid to join
father Ned as a Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has racked up more top-fives (12) and top-10s (14) this
season than Jarrett and crew chief Todd Parrott, who also have
suffered only one DNF. NASCAR's points system rewards that kind of
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Gordon. And the system will crown Jarrett a first-time
champion on or before the season-ender on Nov. 21.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
