<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, July 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   QATAR-ARAB-TV (Doha, Qatar) _ In millions of homes and offices
across the Arab world, television sets are regularly tuned these
days to Al Jazeera, a hard-hitting Arabic-language news channel
that explores issues long suppressed by the region's rulers,
including the lack of democracy, the persecution of political
dissidents and the repression of women. By John F. Burns. (With
photo, map.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERB-CHURCH (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ To see and hear
Father Stojan Stokic speak is to believe that something fundamental
is changing in the soul of the Serbian Orthodox Church, which 10
years ago welcomed Slobodan Milosevic's violent nationalist land
grab in the collapsing Yugoslavia and whose most senior bishops
traveled in the war zones of Croatia and Bosnia, blessing Serb
forces shelling towns such as Sarajevo. By Blaine Harden with
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Ecatepec, Mexico) _ Battling to maintain
control over Mexico's most populous state, the governing party has
been testing the limits of electoral legality, buying or coercing
the votes of poor Mexicans who are to cast ballots in elections for
governor on Sunday, according to electoral watchdog groups and
interviews with residents. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (Islamabad, Pakistan) _ Nearly two months into an
armed conflict over the disputed territory of Kashmir, India and
Pakistan _ the world's newest nuclear powers _ are once again
playing the tired roles of time-tested enemies. By Celia W. Dugger
with Barry Bearak. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-VOTE (Kuwait) _ Kuwaitis voted today in what may be the
country's last all-male elections, after a campaign dominated by a
heated national discussion of whether it is time to allow women
political rights. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-OLYMPICS (Geneva) _ Like chocolate, cheese, precision
watches, the Red Cross, skiing and banking, the Olympic movement
has been linked for decades with Switzerland. So it has been doubly
infuriating for the Swiss to endure what is widely perceived as the
latest blow to their national pride: the decision to award the 2006
Winter Olympics not to the front-running Alpine resort of Sion, but
to an upstart Italian rival, the industrial city of Turin.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHIRELAND-ASSESS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Understanding
how much more readily negative responses than positive ones occur
to the quarreling and distrustful politicians of this conflicted
province is the only way to comprehend the bewildering week that
has just passed and the perilous days for the peace settlement that
lie ahead. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ROGUE-TRADER (London) _ For a while, he was the kid from
nowhere whose Midas touch made millions for his patrician
overlords. Then, when it all turned sour, he was the rogue trader
whose breath-stopping losses epitomized the dizzy excesses of the
markets in the mid-1990s. And Saturday, as Nick Leeson was set to
fly back to Britain after almost four years in a Singapore jail,
the 32-year-old former trader who brought down Britain's oldest
merchant bank faced a bittersweet homecoming. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-FAMILIES (Milwaukee, Wis) _ Loving a troubled relative
to death, a struggle often forgotten in policy forums, is one of
the most common situations poor women face when leaving the welfare
rolls. Loyalties to the job often conflict with loyalties at home.
Addicted sisters, imprisoned brothers, needy cousins and aunts _
the great national drive from welfare to work winds through a
forest of familial distractions. By Jason DeParle. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   See also WELFARE-ACADEMY sidebar.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-EDUC (Evanston, Ill.) _ Taking on one of the most
troublesome and contentious issues in American education, school
officials and educators have begun a nationwide discussion of why
black middle-class and upper-income students lag behind whites of
comparable economic status. By Pam Belluck. With photos, map,
graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   CITIZENSHIP-TEST (New York) _ As part of one of the biggest
naturalization movements in the country's history, 1.8 million
applicants for citizenship _ the biggest group ever _ are waiting
anxiously to be tested on their knowledge of English, civics and
history. The test is at the core of one of the weightiest decisions
any nation can make: who should be a citizen? By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   RV-LUXURY (Thorntown, Ind.) _ It is simple, Clarence and Maryann
Cornell said. Financially secure, they wanted to travel and they
wanted to do it in comfort and style, their two yelping dachshunds
in tow. With that, the Cornells, owners of two stationary homes _
one in Minnesota, the other in Florida _ explained their latest
acquisition: a $112,000 Fleetwood Southwind motor home. The
Cornells are part of a national trend. By Peter T. Kilborn. (With
photos.)
</P>
<P>
   FENWAY-FRACAS (Boston) _ Apologies to organized religion, but
surely any candid clergyman would concur: The most widely revered
shrine in Boston is Fenway Park. So the fight brewing here stands
out from the slew of stadium battles that have cropped up around
the country. To hear some talk, at stake is the legacy of Babe
Ruth, the cream of all sports-fan experiences, yea, the very
Valhalla of baseball. Plus a lot of money. And a city neighborhood.
By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ By the federal reporting period
that ended June 30, George W. Bush, the governor of Texas, had
amassed $36.3 million. No presidential candidate has ever collected
that much even over an entire primary season. And Bush's money
machine is only warming up. A look at how he got where he is today.
By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ The latest splendid effort from the documentary
filmmaker Ken Burns is about two women who barely register in the
consciousness of late-20th-century America, but whose lives were
critically important to the freedoms most of us take for granted.
If you mention Thomas Jefferson, or Lincoln, or Martin Luther King,
you'll get a sense, at the very least, that people know whom you're
talking about. Mention Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony
and you're likely to encounter an epidemic of blank stares. By Bob
Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   MAUREEN DOWD is on vacation.
</P>
