<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2376 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTHERS-POLITICS-REVI     07-03 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHERS-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS TRY PITCHING TO MATERNAL INSTINCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a news conference recently in one of the
Capitol's many gilded chambers, Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md.,
offered a myriad of reasons why a Democratic proposal to give
patients new rights within their health insurance plans made sense.
She spoke of longer hospital stays, greater access to specialists,
better overall care.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most intriguing part of her sales pitch was a
less technical one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care is a women's issue,'' Ms. Mikulski told an
audience of several dozen reporters. ``Women will do anything to
make sure their children have the kind of health care they need.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few sentences, Ms. Mikulski equated being a woman with
being a mother. She thereby underscored a peculiar paradox in
Democratic politics right now: The party that fought hard to make
sure women were not defined simply as the bearers and rearers of
children is spending an awful lot of energy these days casting
women in those terms, or at least appealing to them along those
lines.
</P>
<P>
   That is a tack evident in the Democrats' continuing debate with
Republicans over how extensively to regulate health maintenance
organizations and other health insurance providers. Democrats, for
example, are insisting on a measure that gives women _ but not men
_ the right to choose a specialist as a primary doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just any specialist a woman can choose. It is an
obstetrician-gynecologist, the caretaker of her reproductive health
and her ascent to motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Motherhood was also the backdrop of Democrats' oratory in the
recent debate over gun control. Their plea for new restrictions on
firearms was framed not in terms of slain police officers or
Uzi-toting drug dealers, but in terms of child safety.
</P>
<P>
   While that partly reflected the series of shootings at public
schools that had given the issue new momentum, Democrats conceded
that it also took into account internal polls that showed that
women were more likely to support new gun control measures than men
were.
</P>
<P>
   And t hinged on the thinking that the easiest, most visceral
way to reach women was to tap their maternal instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman may have a unique perspective on how to protect and
nurture our children,'' said Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lowey belonged to a trio of female lawmakers in the House
who held news conferences just about every other day to reiterate
the statistic that 13 children in America die from gun violence
every day.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pitch made to women, by women, on the tacit assumption
that they spoke the same language. ``These issues resonate with
women,'' Ms. Lowey said, ``because mothers worry about their
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Christina Hoff Sommers is the author of the 1994 book ``Who
Stole Feminism?'' She does not quibble with the assessment. In
fact, she believes there are intrinsic differences between women
and men, and that women are indeed more interested in child
rearing. But Ms. Sommers, now a fellow at the American Enterprise
Institute, a conservative research center, said she found some
irony in the fact that Democrats were making such arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one moment, they're deploring the stereotypes, and at the
next, they're exploiting them,'' Ms. Sommers said, noting a change
over the last two decades in the thrust of Democrats' appeals to
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, there was more of a commitment to the idea that the
sexes were interchangeable,'' she said. ``Now they market all of
their family-friendly policies to women. You don't have to be a
logician to note the inconsistency in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Democrats aren't doing anything that Republicans
haven't done, but Republicans never cried out for women to be
unshackled from the constraints of motherhood with quite the vigor
that Democrats did.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are also simply showing themselves to be in synch with
the part of the women's movement that has altered its emphasis from
repelling any reductive, sex-based assumptions about women to
advocating policies that help women balance the demands of career
and motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is often portrayed as an inevitable, universal
aspiration, despite the fact that more women than ever are not
having children. For example, in 1995, the most recent year for
which the Census Bureau provides such a breakdown, 17.5 percent of
women between the ages of 40 and 44 had not had children. Two
decades earlier, that figure was just 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers also confirm that the vast majority of women
still indeed become mothers, and while polls show that Democrats
have a pronounced advantage among young, single, childless women,
the competition with Republicans for the votes of married women
with children is unpredictable and keen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters tend to become more Republican in their thinking when
blessed with what I like to call the three M's _ mortgage, marriage
and munchkins,'' said Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, a Republican pollster.
</P>
<P>
   So Democrats are waging a particularly spirited fight on that
battleground, and Democratic political consultants noted that the
one thing shared by all these mothers _ richer or poorer, suburban
or rural _ is the responsibility of child rearing, and the worries
that accompany it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many ads we did last year using kids,''
said Rachel Gorlin, a Democratic media consultant, referring to
both state and national campaigns. That parade of children, she
added, was in pursuit of the women's vote in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that women define themselves only in terms of their
kids,'' Ms. Gorlin said. ``But if you're looking for an
across-the-board touchstone to reach the largest number of women,
this is probably a good way to do it. At a certain point, this is
universal.''
</P>
<P>
   To acknowledge that, Ms. Gorlin said, was not to reduce women
simply to being mothers, but to recognize reality: that the act and
obligations of parenting remained bigger parts of women's lives
than of men's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gross generalization,'' Ms. Gorlin said, ``but women
are more preoccupied, regardless of what they do for a living, with
the issue of child-rearing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
