<HEADER>
A8282 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-FUNDRAISING-REV     07-03 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FUNDRAISING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDEFINING BUSH-LEAGUE FUND RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even though he has done it faster than anyone else,
Gov. George W. Bush is not the first Texan to raise several
gazillion dollars to run for president. He is the sixth or seventh,
depending on whether you count Lloyd Bentsen.
</P>
<P>
   Put aside Ross Perot, as Bush's father would have liked to do in
1992, because the cranky billionaire's chief fund-raising device
was his personal checkbook. After that, Gov. Bush's broad-brimmed
$36.3 million, even adjusted for inflation, puts most other Texans
in the shade, though not Lyndon B. Johnson and George Bush the
elder.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spent $10.5 million in 1964, according to Herbert E.
Alexander, professor emeritus at the University of Southern
California and founder of the Citizens Research Foundation, a
nonpartisan group that studies campaign finance. In 1999 dollars
that is about $56 million. But almost all of it went for the
general election, after Johnson had run surrogates against Alabama
Gov. George C. Wallace in three Democratic primaries.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, Gov. Bush has probably raised more money at this
point in the fund-raising cycle than any previous candidate for
president. Even if Bush's pace slackens a bit, he should pass
Johnson's total by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Perot's 1992 total of $67 million, mostly for general
election costs, out of Bush's reach _ not even when adjusted to $79
million in current dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the most telling comparisons are not with either of those
Texans.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Perot spent his own money and Johnson ran before
there were any real limits on campaign financing, especially the
$1,000 cap on individual contributions to candidates _ a limit Bush
said last week he wanted raised, although he didn't specify a
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen ran for the Democratic nomination in 1976 and
spent about $2.25 million ($6.5 million in 1999 dollars) before
giving up as the caucuses and primaries were beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous case of a Texan being the political equivalent
of all hat and no cattle is John B. Connally. A former Democratic
governor, he had never been elected to anything as a Republican,
but raised $13.7 million to run in the Republican primaries in
1980. That's $38 million in today's dollars, a figure Bush will
pass sometime in July.
</P>
<P>
   But Connally's blustery campaign never caught on, and he won
only a single delegate, Ada Mills, for many years the treasurer of
the Arkansas Republican Party. Mrs. Mills became known as the ``$10
million delegate'' (a nice round number), and is living in
Clarksville, Ark., no longer active in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there was Sen. Phil Gramm in 1996. He raised $13 million
by May 1995 and was eagerly advertising his money-raising skills.
They didn't do him much good; he was spending money almost as fast
as it came in, partly because his message of Republican populism
conflicted with his opulent fund raising and partly because Patrick
Buchanan had a better pitchfork. Gramm ultimately spent $25 million
and won 10 delegates, proving minimally more effective than
Connally.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be hard for Bush to get delegates more cheaply than
Gramm, who paid $2.5 million apiece. Dozens of Republican officials
who are sure to be delegates are already pledged to him.
</P>
<P>
   The money he has raised so far is not more than anyone has ever
spent to win a nomination. Bill Clinton reported spending $36.4
million in 1996 while Bob Dole spent $37.4 million (each amount
supplemented by national committee spending).
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted for inflation, Dole's spending equals $39.6 million
today, and the Clinton total $38.3 million. Those figures include
federal matching money, which does not become available until the
election year itself.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to think that Bush will stop raising money,
and he has more than a year to do so before the national
convention. Even if he did stop, enough money would probably
trickle in to allow him to exceed his father's standards. The elder
Bush spent $19 million in 1980 and lost the presidential
nomination, $27.6 million in 1988 and won it, and $32.7 million in
1992 and won it.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted for inflation those sums equal $38.1 million, $38.5
million and $38.5 million in 1999 dollars. They are similar because
the elder Bush accepted federal matching funds, and that obliged
him to abide by federal spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush the younger will almost certainly not take the federal
money and will spend as much as he can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2381 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-FUNDRAISING-REV     07-03 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FUNDRAISING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDEFINING BUSH-LEAGUE FUND RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
