<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8293 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-REVI     07-03 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAST, MODEST TRY AT HEALTH REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Midway through announcing his proposal to revamp
Medicare last week, President Clinton seemed to notice that there
were ghosts in the room.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the first time he came face to face with the
suffering of older Americans forced to choose between medicine and
food _ during the rough, recessionary days of the 1992 presidential
campaign, when the plight of the uninsured and the under-insured
burst into the public's consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was almost seven years ago,'' Clinton said, somewhat
ruefully, ``but it still happens today.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Clinton's new proposal for Medicare, the giant
federal health program for the elderly and the disabled, seemed to
be something more than another ritualistic exercise in
policy-making by a waning administration.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed, instead, to be one last attempt to come to grips with
a nation's contradictory desires on health care, and an
acknowledgment of the hard lessons learned in the past seven years.
There were, indeed, a lot of ghosts in the room, from the
bright-eyed Clintonians who tried, and failed, to reconstruct the
American health care system in 1993, to the confident Republicans
who tried, and failed, to overhaul the Medicare system in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ghosts in the room last week was President Lyndon B.
Johnson, the political godfather of Medicare, quoted by Clinton _
and perhaps invoked for his talismanic power.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over health care, in retrospect, was one of the
defining political conflicts of the 1990s. And most of its tensions
were evident again last week as Clinton unveiled his plan to
fortify Medicare's finances, add prescription drugs to its benefits
and spur more competition for its beneficiaries among private
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Congress and the White House faced a debate over how
to hold down costs while still delivering high-quality care. Once
again, the subtext was how much faith to place in the corporate
sector and the power of the marketplace, and how much trust to
reserve for the government.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, politicians were asking how much Americans were
willing to spend to insure that the technological revolutions of
modern medicine _ like the newest, most expensive prescription
drugs _ are available and affordable to those who need them.
</P>
<P>
   In one forum or another, those issues have been debated since a
little-known Pennsylvania Democrat, Harris Wofford, put health care
reform on the political map by riding it to victory in a special
Senate election in 1991. For all the struggle over health care,
though, only the murkiest consensus has emerged. At the end of the
day, said Drew Altman, president of the Kaiser Family Foundation, a
health research group, ``there's a broad sense that nothing's easy
in health policy and there are no magic solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest Clinton plan is a sadder-but-wiser guess at what is
still feasible and politically palatable among the grand theories
and principles that have dominated health care thinking over the
past 10 years. It is perhaps most striking for what it doesn't do.
As Marilyn Moon, a health care analyst at the Urban Institute in
Washington, put it, the plan ``doesn't lock us into big-time
structural change before we really know where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton proposal seeks a mixed solution of managed care
(health maintenance organizations and other entities that try to
control costs and coordinate care) and traditional fee-for-service
medicine (in which patients have a free choice of doctors
reimbursed by the government).
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say their new plan would protect and
buttress traditional Medicare for anyone who chooses it while
creating new incentives for competition among private health care
plans for Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not radical restructuring, but it's not incremental
reform either,'' said Robert Reischauer, an economist at the
Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in a sense, another Clintonian compromise, this time
between the ardent defenders of traditional Medicare and the true
believers in the marketplace, who argue that the government has
never really given managed care plans a fair shot at competing for
Medicare business.
</P>
<P>
   But it also reflects a more realistic appraisal of ideas that
once looked so promising. In 1993, there was a lot more hubris:
When the administration first attempted to restructure the rest of
the health care system, many of its health planners saw managed
care and a well-organized marketplace as nothing short of wondrous
in their ability to control costs and improve quality.
</P>
<P>
   Today, after a private sector revolution that pushed most
working Americans into managed care with mixed results, a lot of
that euphoria is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's hardly anybody left who really believes we're
on the dawn of offering dramatically better service to people at a
lower price,'' said Robert Blendon, an expert on public opinion and
health at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this month the Senate will begin debate on legislation
to create a ``patients' bill of rights'' to protect consumers in
the new world of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Medicare's experience with managed care in the past
few years has hardly been an unalloyed success. Last week, HMOs
announced further pullbacks from the Medicare market as well as
benefit cuts and premium hikes, claiming the government has been
underpaying them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
