 WASHINGTON: underpaying them.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of making Medicare more like a private health care
market say such difficulties are a result of too much government
regulation. But others say Medicare needs to move cautiously, given
the difficulties of shifting an older, medically vulnerable
population into the private marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton plan also tries to deal with a longstanding question
of access to health care: It proposes prescription drug coverage in
Medicare, at a time when new pharmaceuticals offer extraordinary
promise to older Americans but confront them with extraordinary
expense. This proposal, too, reflects the sadder-but-wiser approach
to health policy; most expansions of benefits or coverage since the
failure of the Clinton effort in 1993-94 have been discrete,
focused efforts like this, from protections for people changing
jobs in 1996 to coverage for uninsured children in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It is noteworthy, perhaps, that even when the government is
awash in surpluses, there is very little serious discussion in
Washington these days about reducing the vulnerability of the 43
million uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ever get closer to universal coverage, it'll be through
a hundred incremental programs, because of the legacy of
extraordinary cynicism and distrust of government,'' Blendon
predicts.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the health care wars, of course, Clinton
promised to give every American a health security card and the
benefits to go with it. The collapse of his plan was seen as such a
repudiation of government that few politicians dare broach the
subject of universal coverage these days.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that it will take a crisis _ perhaps a
major economic downturn and an even greater increase in the numbers
of uninsured _ before that issue rises to the top of the agenda
again.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may be long gone by that time; the Medicare proposal may
be his last on health care. It is almost certainly less than what
he thought he would accomplish when health care first arose in the
1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But no one considers passage of his plan, or some equivalent, to
be a sure thing.
</P>
