<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANTON AND ANTHONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest splendid effort from the documentary filmmaker Ken
Burns is about two women who barely register in the consciousness
of late-20th-century America, but whose lives were critically
important to the freedoms most of us take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   If you mention Thomas Jefferson, or Lincoln, or Martin Luther
King, you'll get a sense, at the very least, that people know whom
you're talking about. Mention Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
Anthony and you're likely to encounter an epidemic of blank stares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just think about it,'' said Burns in an interview last week.
``When these two women were born in the early years of the 19th
century, women could not attend college. They were barred from the
professions. They could not keep or invest their earnings. They
could not testify at a trial, were actually considered incompetent
to testify. They had fewer rights than an insane lunatic _ male, of
course _ in an asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could not own or inherit property. They could not win
their children in a custody battle. Women were the property of
their husbands. Their bodies were literally owned by their
husbands. And, of course, they couldn't vote.''
</P>
<P>
   That grim 19th-century picture was transformed in large part
through the lifelong revolutionary efforts of Stanton and Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their story is so incredible,'' said Burns. ``When they died
in the early years of the 20th century, all of those rights _ which
seem to us to be self-evident _ had been achieved, with the
exception of the right to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was the thing Stanton and Anthony wanted most, the
thing they had dedicated their lives to. They drove the women's
suffrage movement. But they were about more than just the vote.
They fought for the abolition of slavery. They embodied the women's
movement, and its radical idea that women are the equal of men and
have the same rights. And their relentless activism in the face of
overwhelming opposition heralded the great civil rights movement of
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The primary goal of Stanton and Anthony, the right of women to
vote, finally was achieved with ratification of the 19th Amendment
to the Constitution in 1920. Stanton had died in 1902 and Anthony
in 1906. The 19th Amendment was known as the ``Anthony Amendment.''
It was, word for word, the same amendment Stanton and Anthony had
been submitting to Congress year after year, beginning in 1878.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for Ourselves Alone: The Story of Elizabeth Cady Stanton
and Susan B. Anthony'' will debut on PBS in November. General
Motors is the corporate underwriter and Burns made the documentary
with the award-winning filmmaker Paul Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Said Burns: ``I don't think I could call myself a documentary
filmmaker interested in surveying the terrain of my country's
history, as I have been doing for the past 25 years, without
expressing artistically my outrage at why this story, the largest
social movement in the history of the United States, is given
essentially a picture and a caption in our history books.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary is a compelling piece of work. Stanton and
Anthony were powerful, complex, controversial and often difficult
individuals. They reacted brutally in 1869 when friends they had
worked with in the abolition movement supported the 15th Amendment,
which guaranteed the vote for black men but did not give it to
women.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton and Anthony felt betrayed, and Stanton erupted in a
racist rant. ``Sambo,'' she said, ``wasn't ready for the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   That caused Frederick Douglass, who had considered himself a
friend of Stanton's, to feel betrayed, and he said so. He also
said, ``There is no name greater than (Stanton's) in the matter of
woman's rights and equal rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on that part of the story, Burns said, ``It gets
complicated, and we've tried not to blink.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for Ourselves Alone'' is about the perennial struggle to
realize the great idea that is the United States of America. It's
also about a great and complicated friendship.
</P>
<P>
   American women, more than eight million of them, voted for the
first time on Nov. 2, 1920. The narrator of the documentary notes
that the two women who fought the longest and hardest for that
right ``had not lived long enough to cast a ballot themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
