<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8318 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLPARKS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-03 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLPARKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW BALKS AT CLOSING BALLPARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash., Mich., Texas, Wis.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (Duplication warning: also sent with `s' code)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN SCHWARZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few months ago, Seattle Mariners executive Dave Aust was
wracking his brains for a fitting send-off for the Kingdome, the
Mariners' ballpark since 1977, which closed Sunday, June 27.
</P>
<P>
   He had an explosive notion: Sell thousands of detonating
plungers to Mariners fans for a couple of bucks apiece, and let
them take part in blowing the place up when it is scheduled to be
leveled with dynamite next March. ``A lot of people would pay money
to do that,'' Aust said. ``Everyone wants to see it blown up.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, some ballparks today don't evoke the same wistful
nostalgia that others did a generation ago. Mention the demolition
of Ebbets Field in 1960 and many Brooklynites, still drying their
eyes over Valentino, begin to tear up again. But with five new
major league stadiums set to sprout in the next 12 months,
sentimentality has been put on waivers.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The Kingdome, an indoor park once known as the Tomb
for all its gray, empty concrete, has been a blight on the baseball
landscape for a generation. And the four stadiums still limping
through their final season _ Tiger Stadium in Detroit, the Houston
Astrodome, County Stadium in Milwaukee and 3Com (formerly
Candlestick) Park in San Francisco _ won't inspire many weepy
eulogies either.
</P>
<P>
   In its early years, the inside of the Kingdome roof camouflaged
pop flies so well that they often fell among several helpless
fielders. One sure-fire Dave Kingman home run was caught for an out
after it hit a support wire above the field. And in 1994, four
15-pound tiles plummeted from the ceiling a half-hour before game
time, one of them landing 50 feet from the Baltimore Orioles iron
man Cal Ripken Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no current ballpark has earned more abuse than San
Francisco's, which by virtue of sitting on the tip of Candlestick
Point in the Bay rivals the climate of arctic tundra. Salty wind
gusts regularly separate players from their caps; during the 1961
All-Star Game, Stu Miller of the hometown Giants was blown clear
off the pitcher's mound. Since 1983, the club has awarded a ``Croix
de Candlestick'' pin to all fans who weather a frigid, extra-inning
affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great going there in July and freezing your butt off,''
said New York Yankees manager Joe Torre, who played in Candlestick
throughout his 1960-77 playing career. ``Willie Mays would hit a
lot of balls to left field and, man, they wouldn't go anywhere,''
he recalled. ``I was catching one day, and Felipe Alou hit a ball
that went out of the park _ and came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Stadium, tied with Boston's Fenway Park as the oldest park
in the majors, opened on April 20, 1912 _ five days after the
Titanic sank. More fans would have seen Ty Cobb, Hank Greenberg, Al
Kaline and other Tigers legends play there if the view of thousands
hadn't been obstructed by jutting roofs and steel pillars. Players
complain that the dugouts are so deep that when they sit down, they
can't see the outfielders. Then there was the sign long posted
outside a locker room: ``Visitors Clubhouse _ No Visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astrodome has had more than human visitors in its 35
seasons. Once known as the Eighth Wonder of the World, the stadium
that gave America artificial grass now finds cats and rats
scurrying across it. The rodents are so big that Giants manager
Dusty Baker said, ``I've heard stories of cats running from rats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come when the team's out of town,'' said one Astros
employee, ``the cats are hanging around first base and the
pitcher's mound. During a stadium tour, the cats were looking at us
like, `What are you doing, invading our home?'''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to improve the fans' experience at County Stadium in
Milwaukee have fallen a little flat. The mascot Bernie the Brewer,
decked in lederhosen, slides down into a huge beer stein when a
Milwaukee player hits a home run, but the team's offense can be so
weak he gets as scarce as the Maytag repair man.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the gaggles of gulls from Lake Michigan that
feast on tailgaters' garbage in the parking lot. Roars from a
nearby Harley-Davidson convention in 1993 scared the birds into the
ballpark, where they congregated on the outfield grass during
games. A pooch named Gus the Wonderdog was brought in to chase them
away, but Gus was unconditionally released after leaving some
souvenirs of his own.
</P>
<P>
   These five parks will be replaced by fan-friendly
techno-stadiums that should make fans forget all about their
predecessors. Retractable domes on the new Safeco Field in Seattle,
the Ballpark at Union Station in Houston and Miller Park in
Milwaukee will tip their caps when the weather's nice. At Pacific
Bell Park in San Francisco, fans can marvel at long home runs to
right field plunking into the China Basin Channel. Comerica Park in
Detroit will feature the world's largest scoreboard, not to mention
a barbecue-and-beer garden.
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry, fans. Like every other new baseball stadium
these days, the new parks will be packed with so many interactive
doodads for the kids that they couldn't possibly be distracted by
some ballgame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2417 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLPARKS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-03 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLPARKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW BALKS AT CLOSING BALLPARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash., Mich., Texas, Wis.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (Duplication warning: also sent with `s' code)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
