<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8319 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-TENSIONS-     07-03 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-TENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA OUSTS U.S. OFFICER AMID TENSION OVER KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a fresh sign of the tensions that have grown between
the United States and Russia since the war in Kosovo, Moscow has
ordered an American military attache to leave the country, U.S.
officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The American officer, Lt. Col. Peter Hoffman, the assistant Army
attache at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow, was declared persona non
grata and left Russia Thursday evening, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy declined to say why the officer been expelled.
But some American officials suggested that he might have been
caught up in tit-for-tat accusations of spying.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said he was going about things he was not supposed to,''
a senior Clinton administration official said. ``We don't comment
on intelligence matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was the latest in a series of strains between the U.S.
and Russian militaries that have emerged since NATO's war against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO's 78-day bombing campaign ended, the Clinton
administration has sought to rebuild ties with Moscow by involving
the Russian military in the effort to enforce the peace.
</P>
<P>
   But that has resulted in new tensions. Hoping to bridge the
differences, U.S. and Russian officials worked out an agreement
last month in Helsinki, Finland, on peacekeeping operations in
Kosovo. But the accord was somewhat vague and the two sides have
interpreted it differently.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, for example, acknowledges that Russian
peacekeeping troops will not formally report to NATO commanders.
But Washington says Russia's forces should be prepared to follow
instructions from NATO commanders in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, though, has underscored that its troops will be under a
separate Russian command, and it has never been clear how closely
the Russian military is prepared to cooperate with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   And NATO and Russia still differ over where the Russian troops
should be stationed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As the wrangling has continued, the United States last week
blocked Moscow from sending additional peacekeepers to Kosovo by
asking Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria not to let the Russians to use
their airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the surprise dispatch of 200 Russian troops to
Pristina airport last month, Washington does not want Moscow to fly
in reinforcements until disputes over peacekeeping arrangements are
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   That has not been the only source of tension. Recently the
Russians held a Cold-War-style military exercise in which two old
Bear bombers approached Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   The episode was not worrisome in a military sense and appeared
to be an effort by the Russian Defense Ministry to demonstrate that
it was still a force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the expulsion of Hoffman, which was reported by The
Washington Times last week.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials in Washington, Hoffman was a specialist
in military intelligence, which is not unusual for an Embassy post
that has long been used to monitor Russian military development.
</P>
<P>
   He served on the U.S. delegation that negotiated the Helsinki
accord on peacekeeping operations in Kosovo. One Clinton
administration official speculated that the expulsion might have
been a response to a recent decision by the United States to expel
an official at Russia's Mission to the United States on accusations
of spying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
