</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 The Week in Review  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Pauses for a Tall Tale
</P>
<P>
   On the last leg of what still seems a remarkable journey, Edwin
Daniel Sabillon charmed the city. The 13-year-old Honduran boy told
a heart-rending, though made-up, tale to strangers he met in Miami,
who bought him a bus ticket to New York City. He arrived Sunday,
June 27, and after a few hours of sightseeing, he was picked up by
a taxi driver who was captivated by his smile and touched by his
story. The driver alerted the police, the police alerted the news
media, which naturally alerted the mayor, and Edwin was a
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone believed, perhaps because they wanted to, his tale of
losing his mother to a mudslide and of making his way alone across
3,200 miles and three countries in search of his father in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the essentials of Edwin's narrative are not
true. His mother is alive, although she gave him over to his
paternal grandmother when he was an infant. His father is dead, but
he was far away in the United States for most of Edwin's life. His
relatives say he ran away some months ago from his grandmother's
house in Honduras and showed up one day in Hialeah, Fla., where an
aunt lives. How he got there is still a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   His future now is uncertain, although perhaps no more uncertain
than it was before he embarked on his grand adventure. Some in New
York seemed as quick to cast him as a villain as they had been to
embrace him as a hero, leaving no room for him to be just a
troubled young boy. Others said they still wanted to adopt him. He
is, for the moment, a ward of the city, thanks to no less a patron
than Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who was tickled by Edwin's spunkiness.
Edwin, after all, did what many have done before him: He came to
America to reinvent himself.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SUSAN SACHS
</P>
<P>
   Vodka and Water, a Deadly Mix
</P>
<P>
   Vodka is Russian for ``little water,'' a playful diminutive
ludicrously out of place given what it does to those who drink it
before taking a swim. In Moscow alone, 144 swimmers drowned between
May 1 and June 21, and on a particularly brutal weekend in
mid-June, as many as 16 died each day _ three more than the daily
average for the entire United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow coroner's office, which examined June's 89 deaths at
a reporter's request, concluded that 94 percent of the swimmers
were drunk when they drowned. All but 10 were men, usually between
the ages of 20 and 40. Indeed, two in every 10,000 men in that age
group drowned in 1997, a pace that beats even the infamous homicide
rate in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Shocking as it is, the drowning rate only hints at a broader
connection between alcohol and accidents, especially among men.
From falls to fires to poisonings, Russia has one of the highest
accidental death rates on Earth, and vodka is usually a factor.
More shocking, at least to health experts, is the nation's blase
attitude toward the carnage, which is almost unnoticed among
ordinary Russians.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of Russia's larger problem of weak public health
measures, said Martin McKee, an expert on Russian mortality trends
at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine.
Alcohol-related accidents are almost entirely preventable, but
preventive medicine is in its infancy in Russia _ and civic
movements like anti-drunk-driving campaigns are unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it could be worse _ and was. Vodka consumption has been
slowly falling since drinking peaked in 1994. That year, the
drowning rate among men was 30 percent higher than was reflected in
the 1997 statistics.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL WINES
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
