<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8326 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COP-POET-LADN     07-03 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COP-POET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER PUTS LITERATURE LESSON TO WORK ON CITY STREETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By night, Los Angeles police Officer Sunil Dutta
reads crooks their rights on some of the meanest streets in
America.
</P>
<P>
   By day, the 35-year-old with a doctorate in biology reads the
verse of renowned Indian poet Ghalib and painstakingly translates
it into English.
</P>
<P>
   Dutta believes poetry and policing are a natural fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting mix of complex emotions and feelings to be
a police officer and a writer and a poet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm acting as a psychologist, counselor, teacher and a vent
for people who are extremely mad,'' Dutta said. ``You see children
who are victims and children who are vicious criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get many different experiences out on the
streets,'' he said. ``It's so totally flabbergasting.''
</P>
<P>
   His father-in-law, Robert Bly, winner of the National Book Award
for poetry and recognized as America's most influential living
poet, said he was perplexed by Dutta's decision to become a police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed myself,'' Bly said. ``But I understand he's an
excellent officer. It would be hard to imagine a well-known
American writer joining a police force. I thought it was a very big
stretch for him to do this, yet I thought it was a brave thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Now after four years of work, the West Valley Division patrol
officer is anticipating the July 1 release of ``The Lightning
Should Have Fallen on Ghalib,'' published by Ecco Press/Harper
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Dutta's fellow officers in the West Valley and Van Nuys
divisions where he's worked have ribbed him about his moonlighting
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the sergeants at Van Nuys used to kid me all the time:
What are you doing when you're a biochemist? You don't belong,'' he
said. ``Some of them made fun of me: What is an artist doing
here?''
</P>
<P>
   West Valley Division Officer Migdalia Rodriguez said in the
Police Academy, Dutta was often teased for standing up for female
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very respectful of British women rulers,'' she said. ``He
would always stand up for women being in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   West Valley Division Sgt. Cory Palka said Dutta has a unique way
of expressing ``life's values outside of police work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful expression because behind every badge is a
person of many great attributes and character,'' Palka said.
</P>
<P>
   Dutta grew up and got his bachelor's degree in botany in India,
his master's in plant biology in Florida and his doctorate at the
University of California, Davis.
</P>
<P>
   After hiking in Norway, studying music under Indian masters and
teaching in inner-city and rural schools in the United States, he
came to Los Angeles 18 months ago and joined the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dutta patrols the streets of Van Nuys and the West Valley
area, taking on gang members and street thugs.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls one night when he and his partner were called to a
gang fight, only to find a car had been destroyed, and its owner
chased away.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Dutta encountered a group of men outside a
liquor store and found they were armed. They ran, but Dutta and his
partner quickly caught them, and found one was the same man whose
car had been destroyed earlier. He had been preparing to take
revenge on the gang members who had chased him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get the gun from him without using force and
we prevented a drive-by shooting that night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with these experiences, Dutta is writing a book on social
problems in the United States. Among his conclusions is that
political leaders debate issues in black and white or as left or
right politically, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``American's social and intellectual debates are so narrowly
focused that we miss the big picture,'' he said. ``We don't discuss
issues broadly enough.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
