<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BRITAIN-NYT &LR;      07-03 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO KOSOVO ALBANIANS SLAIN AS PEACEKEEPERS OPEN FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ British peacekeeping troops shot two
Kosovo Albanians dead Friday night, one of them a well-known Kosovo
Liberation Army soldier. Two civilians were severely wounded in the
same incident, which occurred during a wild street celebration
marking the Kosovo Albanians' freedom from Serbian rule.
</P>
<P>
   The dead soldier was identified as Avni Dudi, 19, known as
Liusha, who was said by witnesses to have been standing on top of
the car on which the British opened fire. Dudi had been
sporadically firing an automatic weapon into the air and then
hiding the gun in the car, the witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Pristina said Dudi was a veteran of several battles
against the Serbs fought by the Albanian militant commander known
as Remi, who commanded the force in territory north of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's celebration was timed for Republic Day, the
eighth anniversary of the founding of an underground parliament by
former Albanian legislators dismissed from their posts by the
Serbian leader, Slobodan Milosevic, in his takeover of the
government here.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people swarmed through the center of this provincial
capital on Friday night, cheering, chanting, dancing, hugging one
another and waving at NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   As the night wore on, many of the celebrants began firing their
guns into the air, which led to the fatal episode.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of the two Albanian men showed the continuing
volatile potential of the NATO peacekeeping mission, as the troops
seek to keep a neutral stance between the returning Albanians, who
feel themselves victorious, and the remaining Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 Serbian officials and former local party leaders are
maintaining offices in the Executive Building, the former
government headquarters. British paratroopers are maintaining a
guard at the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the crowd, Maj. Jan Joosten, a NATO spokesman said, the
Serbs asked for extra protection, and the paratroopers sent an
additional patrol, putting about a dozen soldiers in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Joosten said that eight men in a car approached the building and
opened fire. Several soldiers, he said, believing their lives to be
in danger, ``aimed fire'' at the car, hitting four of the
occupants. One was killed immediately, and another died in the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses said, though, that the men in the car were
shooting in the air _ not at the soldiers _ as they had been seen
doing a number of times before as the honking procession of
vehicles moved through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The British military police are investigating the incident,
Joosten said. But he said that any soldier in the peacekeeping
force who feels his life is in danger has the right to fire.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO spokesman said that as the celebration progressed and
an increasing number of gunshots rang out, the British troops did
not attempt to disarm anyone, because they ``recognized that
celebratory fire is normal in this part of the world.'' In
addition, he said, the troops ``did not intervene, because it would
have inflamed a good-natured situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8330 &Cx1f; taf-z
