<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF TO FACE DAVENPORT IN A QUEST FOR 8TH TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Steffi Graf, whose reverence for Wimbledon
and its quaint Center Court lawn is symbolized by her seven titles,
and Lindsay Davenport, who has finally outgrown her disdain for
this ever-mutating surface, dispatched a pair of teen-agers
Saturday in the semifinals and gained a final-round berth in
Wimbledon's Super Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1989, when Boris Becker and Graf
presented Germany with a daily double in the men's and women's
finales, bad weather has forced the women's final to share the
schedule with the men on Sunday. But neither Graf nor Davenport
were worried about getting equal billing on finals day at the Grand
Slam tournament that steadfastly refuses to give them equal pay.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, after all, had pronounced herself ``drunk with success''
after capturing her 22nd career slam last month at the French Open
and Saturday brought herself to the brink of achieving the game's
hardest double with a 6-7 (3-7), 6-4, 6-3 comeback against the
17-year-old Mirjana Lucic. And Davenport, who screamed with joy
after reaching her first Wimbledon final, regained the No. 1
ranking with her 6-1, 6-1 rout of 18-year-old Alexandra Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   Both Graf and Davenport were simply delighted to get to the
final, but they achieved their spots in vastly different fashion.
Davenport's 48-minute power-tennis diatribe showed the qualifier
Stevenson that she was under-qualified for this Center Court
hurdle, and Graf, who dropped the first-set tie breaker to the
Croatian aspiring to replace her someday as the queen of flashy
forehands, prevailed after a 1-hour-50-minute workout.
</P>
<P>
   The third-seeded Davenport, a Wimbledon underachiever who came
into this year's event riding a wave of confidence that seemed
invisible to everyone but herself, pulverized Stevenson, the
strapping Californian who became the first female qualifier to
gate-crash this Slam's semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Normally taciturn on the court, Davenport let out a shriek of
relief, and anticipation, after Stevenson soared a forehand return
beyond bounds at triple match point, and later attributed the
outburst to sheer delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get to the Wimbledon final, it just means so much to me,''
Davenport said. ``To get the No. 1 ranking back is a great
pleasure, but getting to the Wimbledon final far outshines it.
Getting a chance to play for another Grand Slam title, and getting
to do it on a surface I used to hate in `93 and `94, is what we
play for,'' said Davenport, the 1998 U.S. Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, the victor of all seven Wimbledon finals she has contested
since settling for second-best against the nine-time champion
Martina Navratilova in 1987, secured a spot in her ninth career
finale here, the lowest-ranked women's semifinalist at Wimbledon in
the Open Era.
</P>
<P>
   Graf leads her rivalry with Davenport by 8-5, but the two have
never met on grass, Graf's favorite stomping ground and suddenly,
now that she's gotten to the final, a close second to hard courts
in Davenport's estimation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's special to be in the finals again; everything I did in
the last few months was for this tournament,'' said the 30-year-old
Graf, who entered the French Open with the aim of honing her
competitive edge for this Slam, wound up winning the Roland Garros
title, and promptly declared her retirement from the clay.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, two Wimbledons shy of Martina Navratilova's record nine
and two Slams short of tying Margaret Court's all-time slam record
of 24, admitted that an 8th Wimbledon championship might whet her
appetite for future competition rather than retirement from the
grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it is pretty tempting,'' said Graf, who gained the final
when Lucic, who appeared to switch to surrender mode midway through
the final set, plopped a disinterested forehand return into the net
at match point.
</P>
<P>
   Graf termed her match difficult because of Lucic's go-for-broke
playmaking, the same hit-or-miss exuberance that carried Stevenson
to the semifinals and then deserted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``These young girls, they're playing aggressive tennis,'' said
Graf. ``They feel they have nothing to lose, and that's what it
takes to go up, and it's good that they're taking the risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
