<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROADBLOCK TO A PEACE PACT: IRISH MOSTLY SAY `NO'
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ John Hume, a 1998 Nobel Peace Prize
winner who heads the moderate Catholic Social Democratic and Labor
Party, nodded toward the lumpen brick Stormont Castle Buildings
where talks to keep the Northern Ireland peace agreement alive were
in their fifth grinding day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you took the word `no' out of the English language,'' he
said, ``there'd be a lot of speechless people in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding how much more readily negative responses than
positive ones occur to the quarreling and distrustful politicians
of this conflicted province is the only way to comprehend the
bewildering week that has just passed and the perilous days for the
peace settlement that lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extraordinary full-time personal involvement in the
marathon negotiations of two prime ministers _ Tony Blair of
Britain and Bertie Ahern of Ireland _ the future of the peace
accord of April 1998 remains in doubt and subject to rejection. It
was aimed at ending three decades of sectarian violence that has
cost more than 3,200 lives in the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to wrest willing compromise from the naysaying political
leaders, Blair and Ahern on Friday night issued their own solution
to an impasse that had been blocking progress and said that if the
Ulster political leaders did not accept it, they would lose their
hard-won right to govern themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Their ultimatum proposed a trade-off that called for the
creation in two weeks of a joint Roman Catholic and Protestant
Cabinet to run the new Northern Ireland Assembly, a Sinn Fein
priority, and a month later the beginning of the dismantling of the
Irish Republican Army arsenal, a Unionist demand.
</P>
<P>
   The take-it-or-leave-it plan was an effort to break a deadlock
that had halted progress in putting the peace accord into place at
a pivotal moment, the time when the British Parliament was supposed
to transfer authority to the new legislature in Belfast. Under the
plan, that will now occur on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   It became embarrassingly evident how Northern Ireland was
falling behind when similar new regional parliaments in Wales and
Scotland received their powers on Thursday as scheduled under
Blair's ``devolution'' constitutional reform policy of distributing
political power to the regions of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The prime ministers' blueprint offered what it called
``fail-safe guarantees'' to the two warring parties that if either
of the steps did not take place on time, the legislature itself
would be shut down. The two leaders are counting on the fact that
the politicians would be loath to give up the salaries and
amenities they have enjoyed in the year since the assembly
officially opened or to forfeit the chance to repatriate the
legislative powers that reside in London.
</P>
<P>
   The two governments' recommendation is expected to gain the
support of Sinn Fein, but its reception in the Unionist community
is more doubtful. David Trimble, the Ulster Unionist leader who now
must sell the arrangement to his restive constituency, called it
``fundamentally unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Protestants are already in a resentful mood over the
government's action last Monday banning Sunday's Orange Order march
from Drumcree Church outside Portadown through a Catholic
neighborhood. July is traditionally the most volatile period in
Northern Irish politics since the parades often provoke riots,
bombings and even death.
</P>
<P>
   The five days of talks did succeed in bringing forth from Sinn
Fein its first-ever pledge to seek the full disarming of the IRA by
next May, as envisaged but not spelled out in the peace accord. In
exchange, Sinn Fein won the right to take up its seats in the
cabinet on July 15 without having to meet the Unionist condition of
surrendering IRA arms ahead of time. Their victory was largely
symbolic, though, since the assembly goes into summer recess four
days later and returns only in September after the date by which
some arms are to be turned in.
</P>
<P>
   In many places, such an arrangement might be viewed as artful
face-saving compromise. But not here. Ken Maginnis, the Ulster
Unionists' security spokesman, told the BBC Saturday morning that
in his party ``there is general unanimity that Tony Blair has
betrayed us.''
</P>
<P>
   What is at stake is an already far advanced process that has
brought Northern Ireland a level of peace, a promise of prosperity
and a climate of cross-community cooperation it has not known for
most of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the peace accord, paramilitary groups have been on
cease-fire for more than two years and parties representing them,
like Sinn Fein and the Protestant Progressive Unionists, have
chosen politics over war.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of prisoners convicted of sectarian crimes have been
given early release, add British troops have left the streets of
Northern Ireland to return either to their barracks or to England.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution of Ireland has been changed to drop its claim
on the North, a power-sharing government representing Northern
Ireland's two religious traditions has been started, commissions on
policing and human rights are at work, a council linking Ulster
with England, Wales and Scotland is planned and new all-island
governmental agencies bringing together ministers from Belfast and
Dublin are to be created.
</P>
<P>
   The two remaining steps are the ones addressed by Friday night's
directive from the prime ministers _ disarmament and devolution.
With them, the peace settlement becomes irreversible. Without them,
it slides back toward a history that can unite Catholics and
Protestants only in their common desire not to relive it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
