<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Jordan, river of return closed
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All those rumors originating in Los Angeles about
Michael Jordan returning to the NBA to be reunited with new Lakers
coach Phil Jackson? Well, forget 'em. Jordan said so himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing basketball again,'' Jordan said last week.
``Ninety-nine point nine (percent).''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't Jackson plotting the return?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he's not,'' Jordan said. ``Haven't talked to Phil at all.
But he knows I'm happy with his decision, and I wish him the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said Jackson, the Lakers' talent and the vaunted triangle
offense he will install can create a championship-caliber team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great team to work with _ If they listen to him,''
Jordan said. ``(The triangle offense) is not something you can just
do over a year's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Boo-hoo at No. 2
</P>
<P>
   One of the memorable visions of Wednesday night's NBA draft was
the less-than-joyful look on the face of former Maryland star Steve
Francis when he was selected with the No. 2 pick by Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   He was a strong candidate at No. 1, which went to Duke forward
Elton Brand with the Bulls. He knew Charlotte, which picked third
and isn't too far from his hometown area of Washington, coveted
him. And with the Grizzlies already with Mike Bibby in place at
point guard, Frances had every right to believe he would not be
selected by them.
</P>
<P>
   But he was, which means he either will be traded after Aug. 1,
when NBA franchises can resume trading, or will team with Bibby to
make up a small backcourt. Either way, Francis said the Bulls just
might rue the day they passed on the high-flying, flashy 6-foot-3
guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took a great gamble by not picking me,'' Francis said.
``I'm happy to be selected, and I'll continuously play basketball
for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   How upset was he that he went to Vancouver?
</P>
<P>
   After being picked, he said, referring to his Grizzlies cap,
``As soon as I get a chance, I'm going to take it off.... This will
give me incentive all season to prove to everybody that I'm the
best player.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis said he has not ventured north of the border and knows
little about Vancouver. And what he does know was not comforting to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's far from home,'' he said. ``It's cold. It rains a lot,
and they take a lot of your money (via Canadian taxes).''
</P>
<P>
   A Nugget of truth
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly for a team of poor shooters, the Denver Nuggets
contend they were happy that Duke guard Trajan Langdon was taken by
Cleveland with the 11th pick.They knew then that, with the 18th
pick, the Nuggets would get one of a group of forwards they
coveted.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be James Posey, who played at Xavier. General
manager Dan Issel said there was lots of cheering during the draft
at the team's headquarters. ``I think the loudest one was when
Trajan went where he did. That meant for sure we would get one of
the players that we liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Quotable
</P>
<P>
   Boston Celtic coach Rick Pitino on the rumors that he was
considering resigning because of stress: ``Today, the way the
Internet is, it's like a grocery-store publication, people landing
from different planets. That story is in line with that. We're
having a blast. I'm very excited with the dedication of our
players.''
</P>
<P>
   High-schooler Jonathan Bender, refreshingly candid about what it
will take for him to be successful in the NBA: ``How fast things
happen depends on how well you adapt to the new organization, how
well you listen, your attitude and how you play. You have to play
hard all the time. I plan to do a lot of listening. I'm very
patient. I'm willing to work. If I listen, I can succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
