u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEMENTPLANT04-COX     07-03 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEMENTPLANT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cement plant plans may sink river pleasures
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRANFORD, Fla. _ It's one of those simple, Deep-South pleasures
that country folk take for granted and city folk may drive hours to
enjoy: floating down an ice-cold, spring-fed river in the dead of
summer on a rubber tire tube.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands flock each summer to North Florida's Ichetucknee
Springs State Park to do just that, drinking in the unspoiled
natural splendor of a crystal-clear river winding beneath a canopy
of gorgeous overhanging trees.
</P>
<P>
   But a proposal to build a large cement plant a few miles away
from the river has triggered a divisive controversy, splitting the
small communities that dot the rural countryside near the
Ichetucknee.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Department of Environmental Protection two weeks ago
denied an air-quality permit for the plant, citing the poor
environmental record of an affiliated company. But company
officials said they will go to court to try to overturn the
decision, and some community leaders have indicated they will
support that effort.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is a familiar one in Florida and other booming
Southern states, where development and preservation, growth and
environmental concerns, butt heads with increasing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all for the plant,'' said Lori Frierson, town clerk in
Branford, a sleepy village of 700 a few miles from the park.
``There is no work here and I want my children to be able to grow
up with the chance to stay here instead of having to move away to
find a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the environmental risk is too great. They want the
plant moved to a more industrial setting such as Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any question mark, we shouldn't allow this next to
such a fragile resource,'' said Bill Ogle, a Gainesville lawyer
representing nearby landowners who oppose the plant. ``We've
learned the hard way with the Everglades and other Florida
ecosystems that things we were told wouldn't have an impact did
have an impact. And we only found out too late.''
</P>
<P>
   A company called Suwannee American wants to build the
80-employee, $130 million plant in Suwannee County about 40 miles
northwest of Gainesville, home to the University of Florida. The
principals are owners of one of Florida's largest road-paving
firms, Anderson Columbia Inc., which has been embroiled in several
political and environmental controversies in other projects.
</P>
<P>
   Suwannee County commissioners and Branford's town council have
voted in favor of allowing the plant, citing the jobs and tax base.
</P>
<P>
   But on a recent weekend, Gov. Jeb Bush and DEP Secretary David
Struhs joined some of the 200,000 people from North Florida and
South Georgia who annnually visit the river, canoeing through the
park with a heavy local media contingent on hand. A recent National
Geographic profile brought international attention to the
Ichetucknee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush raved about the river's beauty, and Struhs' agency examined
Anderson Columbia's environmental record before denying the
proposed plant's air-quality permit.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Yagel, vice president of Suwanee American, said in a
statement responding to the DEP decision that although the two
companies have common ownership, they are under separate
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also are confident that DEP's denial of our permit request
based on a list of minor environmental violations over a 12-year
period by the Anderson Columbia company will not be sustained in
the courts,'' Yagel said.
</P>
<P>
   Plant officials have seemed frustrated by the scrutiny and the
media attention, refusing to speak with most reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Project engineer Frank Darabi, a Gainesville consultant who has
emerged as the chief spokesman for Suwannee American, insists the
plant would violate no pollution regulations and that critics have
managed to stir up opposition based on emotion instead of facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plant is 3.5 miles from the spring itself and there is
zero water discharge,'' he said. ``It's a dry process, and the air
emissions will be much less than from your car exhaust.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has promised to continuously sample the river for
pollution and to install sophisticated air monitoring devices that
would feed data directly to environmental regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been so much misinformation,'' Darabi said. ``Some
of the people against the plant live next to the river and have
septic tanks. When the river floods, their raw sewage washes
directly into the river. There are also farms with cow pastures
that are damaging the river more than the plant ever will.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists doubt the claims, and cite their own engineers
who say the plant would rain a fine dust containing mercury and
even highly-dangerous dioxin onto the river and surrounding
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know what the impact will be,'' Ogle said.
``What they're asking us to do is put at risk an environmental
treasure enjoyed by millions of people from all over the world for
80 jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also point to Anderson Columbia's frequent skirmishes
with regulators at its asphalt plant in the Florida Panhandle, as
well as the huge cash gifts it gave to two high-ranking Florida
politicians recently convicted of income tax violations stemming
from alleged influence-peddling schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a scandalous record, and we're hoping they will
deny the permit based on their reputation,'' said Virginia
Seacrist, head of a citizens group that opposes the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Ogle's lawsuit challenges the plant's county approvals, which he
says were illegal because they allowed an industry on land zoned
for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're euphoric that they denied the permit, but Anderson
Columbia is an adversary to be taken very seriously,'' he said.
``We've got to remain vigilent and keep our guard up.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the controversy has revealed a rift in
rural Suwannee County that isn't likely to heal soon: Many longtime
locals who want some of the prosperity that's come to the rest of
Florida, while others want to curb development in one of the
state's few remaining pristine areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all love the Ichetucknee because we grew up with it,'' said
Lori Frierson, a supporter of the plant. ``What we really resent is
these people from Gainesville and the outside coming in and telling
us what's best for us and how to run our town and our county.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
