</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOCKEY-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soft free-agent market counter to expectations
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NHL might have found a partial cure to
skyrocketing payrolls and the rising tide of red ink in front
offices.
</P>
<P>
   A dead free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, every NHL owner either complained about salaries or
spent millions on a free agent. Some, apparently suffering from
amnesia, did both. Among the players who secured financial security
for future generations were Brett Hull ($17 million), Curtis Joseph
($24 million), Doug Gilmour ($18 million), Ron Francis ($20.8
million), Steve Duchesne ($11.25 million). But because of a thin
market and some gun-shy general managers, who have been burned by
big-buck busts, few players figure to hit it big in the next two
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams spent a lot of money and didn't get any
better,'' Anaheim general manager Pierre Gauthier said. ``There
were lessons learned.''
</P>
<P>
   The only player who figures to strike a major deal is winger
Theo Fleury, expected to sign with the New York Rangers for $8
million to $9 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   But even Fleury will be hurt. His desire was either to re-sign
with Colorado, which swung a late-season deal with him, or go to a
team on the West Coast. But the Avalanche dropped out of the
bidding when Fleury went goal-less in the last nine playoff games,
then demanded a no-trade clause in negotiations. Los Angeles, which
had been interested, was burned by Duchesne, then swung a major
deal for New York Islanders forward Ziggy Palffy. San Jose directed
its resources into re-signing goalie Mike Vernon ($3.2 million for
one year) and Vincent Damphousse ($18 million for four). Vancouver
is more interested in signing Daniel and Henrik Sedin.
</P>
<P>
   Sharks general manager Dean Lombardi doesn't think Fleury will
be too hurt by geography: ``For $10 million, he might play in
China.''
</P>
<P>
   Word has circulated that the biggest reason the Avs won't
re-sign Fleury is because the sale of the team from Ascent
Entertainment to Bill Laurie has been held up. Don't believe it.
Colorado general manager Pierre Lacroix was upset about Fleury's
playoff fizzle and upset that the forward sat out a game with a
stomach virus, somewhat verboten in the NHL. Add to that what
Lacroix gave Calgary to land Fleury: top prospect Robyn Regehr, two
players and the rights to a compensatory second-round draft pick if
Fleury signed elsewhere in free-agency.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury will land in New York because the Rangers need a big name
to replace Wayne Gretzky. And given the unrestricted free agents
available _ Joe Murphy, Valeri Kamensky, Pat Verbeek _ Fleury's the
only one with marquee value.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers update
</P>
<P>
   General manager Don Waddell could name his coach as early as
later this week, but next week is more likely. It is believed that
Orlando coach Curt Fraser, whom Waddell hired four years ago, and
former Buffalo coach Ted Nolan are the top two candidates. Waddell
has held out the possibility of interviewing one more candidate,
but that person is not expected to be any of the names that have
circulated, including Buffalo assistant Don Lever, Colorado
assistant Bryan Trottier.... Waddell would like to sign about three
forwards during the free-agency period, although it won't happen
quickly. The Thrashers will not pursue any of the big names
available. More than likely, they will wait to see what market
develops for some of the mid-to-lower range unrestricted free
agents and also survey the restricted free agents who aren't
re-signed by their teams.... Finnish forward Tomi Kallio, an
unsigned Colorado draft pick acquired in the expansion draft,
probably will spend one more season in Finland before playing in
Atlanta. But Waddell hopes Swede Andreas Karlsson can step into the
lineup this season. Karlsson, a former Calgary draft picked
acquired for ``future considerations'' on draft day, had 18 goals
and 15 assists for Leksands, his team in Sweden. ``He's a big
centerman _ I think he'll play for a long time,'' Waddell said....
Waddell said he is not upset that a deal that would have sent
defenseman Jamie Pushor, claimed from Anaheim, to Phoenix fell
through. ``We also had a trade with another team that we walked
away from because we thought we could do better,'' Waddell said.
``We like Jamie. I know him pretty well. He's an asset.''... No. 3
goalie Corey Schwab has come up in trade rumors, but Waddell says
he wants three goalies with NHL experience in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Et cetera
</P>
<P>
   Chicago general manager Bob Murray shot down a rumor that the
Blackhawks are about to deal free-agent bust Doug Gilmour to the
New York Rangers. But Murray is shopping defenseman Dave Manson (23
points, 155 penalty minutes and winger Bob Probert (21, 206)....
Detroit center Steve Yzerman is close to signing a three-year,
$25.5 million.... Colorado forward Peter Forsberg, who ended up
being the leading scorer in the postseason (24 points), despite the
Avalanche's elimination in the Western Conference finals, will have
to live off that feat for a while. Forsberg could miss as much as
the first three months of the season rehabbing from shoulder
surgery _ necessitated by a check from Dallas defenseman Richard
Matvichuk. Forsberg got a second opinion from his doctor in Sweden
before going ahead with the surgery. ``This was the right thing to
do in order to avoid any complications in the future,'' he said.
``I have complete trust in the advice I received along the
way.''... How concerned is Ottawa over finances? In addition to
getting winger Rob Zamuner, a second-round draft pick and a $1
million payment from Tampa Bay as compensation for losing general
manager Rick Dudley, the Senators insisted on _ and received _ all
of the gate receipts for three exhibitions to be played between the
teams in September.... The Senators weren't crying too much over
losing forward Andreas Johansson in the deal. He scored 21 goals
last year, but only four of those came in the second half....
Everybody always wants to look younger in Los Angeles, so the Kings
have decided not to offer contracts to Dave Babych (38), Ray
Ferraro (34), Russ Courtnall (34) and Doug Bodger (33).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
