<HEADER>
A8356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-ROGUE-TRADER-     07-03 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ROGUE-TRADER-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN AWAITS ROGUE TRADER WITH INTEREST IN THE LOOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For a while, he was the kid from nowhere whose Midas
touch made millions for his patrician overlords. Then, when it all
turned sour, he was the Rogue Trader whose breath-stopping losses
epitomized the dizzy excesses of the markets in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   And Saturday, as Nick Leeson was set to fly back to Britain
after almost four years in a Singapore jail, the 32-year-old former
trader who brought down Britain's oldest merchant bank faced a
bittersweet homecoming, his assets reportedly frozen, his future
unclear and his freedom flawed by the same question as undid him:
What happened to the money?
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating his release from Singapore's Tanah Merah prison,
tabloid newspapers have been quoting some of Leeson's former fellow
prisoners as saying he told them of millions stashed away from the
days when he traded fast and loose in Singapore, racking up a
staggering $1.4 billion in losses. His lawyers have denied those
reports.
</P>
<P>
   But another newspaper, The Daily Mail, has reportedly clinched a
$160,000 deal for exclusive interview rights. Questions have been
asked, too, about what happened to the $700,000 advance for his
memoirs in a ghostwritten book titled ``Rogue Trader.'' A film
based on the book _ starring Ewan McGregor, who has the role of
Obi-Wan Kenobi in the latest episode in the ``Star Wars'' saga _
was just released here to awful reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the movie rights may have earned Leeson money that
Barings' creditors might think is due to them. And so, according to
the British Broadcasting Corporation, Barings' liquidators obtained
a High Court order Friday night freezing Leeson's assets, including
income from movie rights, to prevent him from cashing in on his
notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are monitoring the situation very carefully,'' said Judith
Dow, a spokeswoman for the accountancy firm Ernst &AMP; Young, the
Barings' liquidators, before the court order was granted.
</P>
<P>
   But his lawyer, Stephen Pollard, insisted that Leeson was not
trying to garner huge wealth from his misdeeds. ``Mr. Leeson has
never intended in anything he has done or I have done for him to
try and create a situation where he can come out and lord it as a
wealthy man,'' Pollard told the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as his return to England approaches, there are some
prepared to tout another side to the story _ the side that mimics
Aristotelian theory of hubris and downfall, pride and pain, the
tragic error that leads to a catharsis and relief that seems to
have eluded Leeson to this day.
</P>
<P>
   While he was in prison, his wife, Lisa, divorced him to marry a
fellow trader. Last fall, he was found to have colon cancer and
physicians say he has a 30 percent chance of dying in the next five
years, despite treatment in Singapore last year. His father, too,
has cancer, said Edward Whitley, the ghostwriter of Leeson's 1996
memoir. Even with time off for good behavior, he has served four
years of a six-and-a-half year jail term for fraud and forgery.
</P>
<P>
   Leeson's story, Whitley said in a newspaper article, is ``the
story of one naive and foolish man's life being slowly and
catastrophically smashed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see him next weekend, it will be a very different Nick
Leeson,'' the article said. ``Among all his other blows, Leeson has
had six months of chemotherapy for cancer. Most of his hair has
gone. His weight has plummeted. His complexion is the color of wax.
If he manages a smile, it will be a triumph of the human will.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is not how he is remembered here. As the son of a lowly
plasterer from down-market Watford, whose formal education was
limited, Leeson seemed to embody the chutzpah of a new generation
of traders taking risks on the open-outcry trading floors of
derivatives exchanges. His baseball cap and cocky grin seemed a
symbol of the markets' break with a tradition of bowler-hats,
pin-stripe suits and upper-crust accents. Yet, to his superiors at
Barings _ the 232-year-old British merchant bank that had financed
governments and banked for royalty from the Napoleonic Wars onward
_ he was a rainmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, two years before the bank collapsed, Peter Baring,
chairman of Barings at the time, famously remarked that, ``It was
not actually terribly difficult to make money in the securities
business'' _ a comment that has entered the annals of banking as
denoting what Whitley called the arrogance and incompetence with
which Barings allowed Leeson to run up huge debts.
</P>
<P>
   Leeson worked for Barings' Singapore office and had been
considered a highly successful derivatives trader, remembered for
big bonuses and for setting fire to high-denomination bank notes at
Harry's Bar in Singapore. Even now, a cocktail commemorating him at
Harry's Bar is known as the ``Bank Breaker.'' Only a few of his
former colleagues gathered for a party there Friday before his
release Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But in February 1995, Leeson and his wife fled Singapore after
running up huge debts in trades on the futures and options markets
in Singapore and Japan. Leeson had been frantically trying to bid
up the market to cover his losses, but the Japanese market,
hammered by the Kobe earthquake, continued to fall. By his own
admission in ``Rogue Trader,'' he had tallied his losses on a
secret account, numbered 88888, which he hid from his superiors.
When he fled, he said in his memoir, he stuffed details of the
account into a desk drawer, switched off his cellular phone and
walked out the door.
</P>
<P>
   His escape _ and his freedom _ ended when he was arrested at
Frankfurt airport while in transit between Asia and England.
Despite efforts by his lawyers to prevent it, he was subsequently
sent back to Singapore to face trial and was sentenced in December
1995 _ the last time he was seen in public before Saturday.
Photographs taken of him at the time show a smirking young man in a
baseball cap who apparently thought there was still a way to trade
his way out of the mess he had made.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 29, 1995, Barings collapsed under the huge debts and was
sold for one pound sterling, or $1.60, to the Dutch ING Groep NV.
The new owners seem to want nothing to do with him when he lands in
London early on Sunday. ``We have no interest, nothing to pursue,
that's it,'' said Edward Naylor, a spokesman for ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the bank's creditors. Singapore-based lawyers
representing Barings' liquidators say they will continue to
investigate whether Leeson has hidden ill-gotten gains in a secret
account someplace. Simon Forster, a spokesman for the Barings
Preference Shareholders Action Group, said any sums paid to Leeson
by newspapers ``should be going to those people who lost out'' in
the bank's collapse, not to finance his considerable legal and
medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly Leeson will be able to do remains uncertain. The
markets will likely be out of bounds. Leeson was not licensed to
trade on the London International Financial Futures and Options
Exchange, a Liffe official said, ``and I wouldn't think he would be
allowed to now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
