<P>
   SUMMER-SCHOOL _ WASHINGTON _ Summer school, long the dreaded
fate of a handful of students taking make-up courses, has become a
destination for two much larger groups. Today, more poor performers
than ever must go to summer school because they failed to pass
promotion tests, and more top performers choose to go because they
want to add another line to the resume they hope will be their
ticket to an academically exclusive college. At some schools in
Chicago, more than half the eighth-graders must go to summer
school, while in one hotsy-totsy suburban high school outside
Chicago, 40 percent of the students choose to do so. (Mollison, Cox
News Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
