<SLUG> BC-KUWAIT-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUWAITIS VOTE IN WHAT COULD BE LAST ALL-MALE ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT _ Kuwaitis voted Saturday in what may be the country's
last all-male elections, after a campaign dominated by a heated
national discussion of whether it is time to allow women political
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Many candidates for seats in Kuwait's 50-member Parliament have
vowed to block an emiri decree that would allow Kuwaiti women to
vote in the next election, expected in 2003. The decree must be
approved by the new Parliament, which is expected to convene by
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Some women, including Masoumah al-Mubarak, a leading political
activist, have already declared their candidacies for the next
election, and most believe that the all-male Parliament that was
being elected Saturday will ultimately bow to the emir's wishes.
But many experts also warn that the parliamentary battle could be
fierce, with most of Kuwait's powerful Islamic political groupings
and the leaders of the country's traditional tribes already on
record as opposing the idea of women voting and holding office.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait is the only Arab Gulf state with an elected Parliament,
and a move to allow women to vote and hold office would put it even
further ahead of its neighbors in allowing equal political rights.
While the royally appointed government maintains the upper hand,
politics in Kuwait are traditionally free-wheeling and raucous.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mubarak, who with other Kuwaiti women convened a news
conference last week to address the issue, said she was ``hopeful
that sufficient positive-thinking males who support women's rights
fully will be elected.''
</P>
<P>
   The emir's decree came as a surprise to most people here, and
its announcement has energized support for Islamic and tribal
candidates who form the country's largest opposition bloc. Some
candidates have pointed to the decree by the emir, Sheik Jaber
al-Ahmed al-Sabah, as an indication that Kuwait's government may be
out of step with the more conservative sentiments of most ordinary
Kuwaitis.
</P>
<P>
   The emir dissolved the last Parliament in May, 17 months ahead
of schedule, after its relationship with the government became so
distressed that little political business could be done. But if the
predictions of most experts here hold true, Saturday's election is
unlikely to heal the rift. Most people expect that opposition
candidates will once again dominate the Parliament, and a report by
the independent Al-Shall Economic Consultants has predicted that
the opposition will emerge from the election with an even stronger
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confrontation is certain, and it will occur very early,'' said
Jasem al-Saadoun, an economist and political analyst. Many people
believe that the tensions could grow if the government, led by
Sheik Saad al-Sabah, the crown prince and prime minister, names a
woman as a government minister.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwaiti women have been lobbying for political rights for more
than three decades, and most Westernized Kuwaitis have welcomed the
emir's decree with enthusiasm. But many other Kuwaitis say they
have reservations about women voting and holding office, because
conservative mores do not permit unrelated men and women to mix in
public.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians, including those who represent two main Islamic
movements, have contended that allowing women to vote and hold
office would violate the tenets of Islam. Many others, however,
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   More than 280 candidates were competing in Saturday's election.
Out of Kuwait's population of more than 1.8 million, only about
113,000 men were eligible to take part; under Kuwaiti law, most
male immigrants as well as women are not allowed to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Voter turnout was high, even in weather with temperatures that
exceeded 110 degrees. The results were expected to be announced
late Saturday or early Sunday, but experts said it would probably
be several weeks before it became clear whether opponents of the
emir's decree could muster the strength to block it.
</P>
<P>
   The elections were the third in Kuwait since the United States
and its allies liberated the tiny country from seven months of
Iraqi occupation in 1990 and 1991. The emir, who had dissolved the
Parliament in 1987, restored the institution in 1992 under Western
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the contest has been the focus of Kuwaiti life, with
streets lined with candidates' placards, and election tents filled
to overflowing each night with men who gather to sip coffee, accept
lavish meals provided by the candidates, and listen to speeches
that typically denounce the government for what is seen as
irresponsible overspending.
</P>
<P>
   In Parliament's absence, the government has turned up the
temperature by ruling by decree _ not just on the question of
women's voting rights, but in other controversial areas.
</P>
<P>
   Many candidates have denounced that high-handedness, and one
powerful opposition figure, Ahmed al-Saadoun, the speaker of the
last Parliament, has said that he will fight to block all the
edicts, including several that have instituted economic reforms in
hopes of making Kuwait more attractive to foreign investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
