</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS OF COERCION IN A MEXICAN ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SAM DILLON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ECATEPEC, Mexico _ Battling to maintain control over Mexico's
most populous state, the governing party has been testing the
limits of electoral legality, buying or coercing the votes of poor
Mexicans who are to cast ballots in elections for governor on
Sunday, according to electoral watchdog groups and interviews with
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Mexico vote is the country's most important
electoral face-off before presidential balloting next year. Waging
a carrot-and-stick campaign that appears to be a rehearsal for the
presidential race, the governing party has been handing out
groceries and building supplies, and threatening to cut off
subsidized milk rations to nursing mothers.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews conducted in the final days of the hard-fought
race in the horseshoe-shaped state that cradles the nation's
capital, voters described numerous irregularities in what appears
to be a systematic campaign to deploy government resources and
influence on behalf of President Ernesto Zedillo's Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The party's candidate for governor, Arturo Montiel Rojas, denied
the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said that in Ecatepec, a sprawling working-class
suburb of Mexico City controlled by the party, municipal
authorities have been allowing men in party uniforms to use city
trucks to clean streets and sewers even as they distribute party
campaign literature.
</P>
<P>
   In one neighborhood, party leaders have been giving poor
housewives boxes of rice, beans and other foodstuffs purchased by a
government charity headed by Zedillo's wife, residents reported.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tactics may constitute crimes, although most appear
to be abusive but not illegal, voting experts said. The campaign
resembles other recent state contests in which extensive
vote-buying by the governing party has provoked angry postelectoral
protests by opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   Election watchdog groups and polling organizations reported
similar irregularities in cities all across the state, a polyglot
region of industrial suburbs and hardscrabble farms with a
population of 13 million people and the country's single richest
electoral cache, 7 million votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we don't think the fraud will occur on Election
Day,'' said Silvia Alonso Felix, executive secretary of the Civic
Alliance, a private organization that investigated reports of
campaign abuses in 36 of the state's 122 counties. ``It's been
forged throughout the campaign by purchasing and coercing the votes
of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting in Mexico City on Wednesday with foreign
journalists, Montiel portrayed the charges as lies invented by the
opposition parties. ``Our party doesn't have to rely on those kinds
of activities,'' Montiel said. ``We condemn them. They're not
authorized. They're not our work.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet residents interviewed in several neighborhoods of Ecatepec
described a variety of questionable campaign tactics. Several
government dispensaries that channel milk subsidized by the federal
government to destitute mothers have announced that recipients who
fail to attend rallies for Montiel will be cut off, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders have told market vendors that they will lose their
market licenses, issued by the governing-party-controlled city
government, if Montiel loses the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that if Montiel wasn't elected, we'd face the
consequences,'' said Maria del Socorro Garcia, an Ecatepec street
vendor.
</P>
<P>
   In the final pre-election poll published by the Mexico City
newspaper Reforma, Montiel, a former president of the party's state
organization, was backed by 43 percent of potential voters. In
second place with 34 percent was Jose Luis Duran, who took a leave
as mayor of Naucalpan, a large Mexico City suburb, to become the
candidate of the center-right National Action Party, known as the
PAN.
</P>
<P>
   Higinio Martinez, the candidate of the center-left Party of the
Democratic Revolution, was in third place with 23 percent. Other
polls showed Montiel's lead over Duran to be narrower.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The governing party has carried out a systematic campaign to
collect photocopies of thousands of voters' electoral credentials,
the photo identification cards that look like a driver's license
and are a requisite for voting here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a coercion mechanism,'' Martinez, the Democratic
Revolution candidate, said in an interview on Friday. ``When they
ask the humblest people for their election-card number, people feel
like they've been identified, that the authorities will now know
how they vote. It's one of the ways they pressure people to vote
for the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Copies of the credentials have been collected in many different
ways. In some cases, Montiel campaign workers simply go
door-to-door; some governing party workers said the party has
promised them 150 pesos, about $16, for each voting credential they
copy. In other cases, teachers in primary and high schools
administered by the state, whose current governor is a PRI member,
have urged students to bring photocopies of their parents'
electoral credentials to school.
</P>
<P>
   The party has also organized several giant raffles in which cars
and stereos are to be given away after Sunday's vote; tens of
thousands of tickets, bearing Montiel's name and the party logo,
have been distributed to state voters in exchange for copies of
their voting credentials.
</P>
<P>
   In the hillside shantytown of Ecatepec, known as Lomas de San
Carlos, the governing party's campaign has developed on multiple
fronts. The local party chief, Pedro Perez Munoz, has boosted the
party's popularity by distributing to poor mothers low-cost
groceries subsidized by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Party workers have gone from adobe hut to adobe hut, asking to
see residents voting credentials and distributing party literature.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, dozens of neighborhood women were summoned to
Perez's home, where a governing-party worker told them that if they
would bring their electoral credentials, the party would give them
each a free raffle ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In the meeting with reporters on Wednesday, Montiel denied that
the party had organized any campaign raffle, and he accused his
opponents of printing the tickets with his name and the party logo.
</P>
<P>
   But Perez, in an interview, said the party's raffle had been
organized by Jorge Hernandez Hernandez, Ecatepec's municipal
director of social development.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at Hernandez's municipal office said Hernandez had taken
a leave to work in the Montiel campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a form of vote coercion,'' said Miguel Angel Juarez, a
member of the State Electoral Institute, the autonomous state
agency that is organizing Sunday's vote. ``This is outlined as an
electoral crime, it's using a form of remuneration, in this case
raffle tickets or gifts, to try to commit voters to cast their
ballots in favor of a party or candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
