<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-AR     07-03 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STEVENSON SAGA SHOWS THE INITIATION OF A RISING
STAR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time I met Alexandra Stevenson, in the late '80s, she
was a merry child in San Diego splashing through swimming lessons
and slamming a tennis ball over the net. She was big and strong for
her age, and her paternity _ all I knew then was that her father
was a famous former professional athlete _ promised major jock
genes. Her mellow sweetness was a contrast to her mother's
intensity. Later, I thought it might also be a result of it.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Stevenson, a friend and colleague, is always tenacious
as a freelance reporter, frequently for The New York Times, and
often tendentious as her daughter's protector. She once told me
that she had decided early that Alexandra, as a dark-skinned child
in a pale sport, needed to be armed with a skill to combat the
obstacles people would throw in her way. Early in the Wimbledon
tournament, Stevenson kicked up a fuss over prize money _ officials
were slow acknowledging Alexandra's professional status _ and this
was followed by her recounting racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   Embattled parents often inject their children with some of the
rages that fuel them. But Stevenson seemed to use her energy to
create a kind of psychic bubble, neither hothouse nor bunker, in
which Alexandra could find her personality and talents, and let
them flower. It was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Watching and listening, usually from a safe distance along a
telephone line, I don't remember a time in the last two decades
when Stevenson was not railing at some school, coach, official, or
other tennis parent for sexist or racist slights _ usually real,
though often subtle. Yet she usually managed to place herself
between Alexandra and the hit. Stevenson's access to the news media
_ including her candid diaries of the junior tennis life published
in World Tennis magazine and The Times _ seemed to antagonize and
intimidate the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Something worked. To reach the Wimbledon semifinals at age 18, a
qualifier, unheralded yet highly schooled, and still an endearing
person, is a tribute to Mom. Alexandra is a rarity in sports these
days, a fine wine that was not uncorked before its time. For
Alexandra, the timing was critical, and beyond tennis; the factoid
frenzy over her paternity began early last week when The
Sun-Sentinel of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., published a copy of her
birth certificate listing Julius Winfield Erving 2nd as her father.
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago, the basketball Hall of Famer, now an Orlando Magic
executive, acknowledged paternity in a statement in which he also
said, ``I applaud her mother's efforts and courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than money, which came through a lawyer, there was very
little contact between Erving and the Stevensons. Mother and father
knew each other in 1980, while he was playing for the Philadelphia
76ers and she was a sportswriter. Erving said he had met Alexandra
once, when she was 3. He has been married since 1972, and has four
children with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Stevenson has been circumspect, although
sometimes coy, about Alexandra's father. Stevenson always knew that
when Alexandra showed up on the back pages, her father would show
up on the front pages. The fact that she chose not to press the
issue or write about it _ even though her financial circumstances
have always seemed tenuous _ was a clear message to others to mind
their own business.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a valid news story now? Beats me. By the time I found out,
in recent years, that Erving was the father, it seemed only
genetically interesting. What was the point of disrupting the lives
of a dignified, thoughtful businessman and a shining young woman?
</P>
<P>
   Outing is usually done for the sake of a journalist's ambition
under the banner of the public's right to know, be it about Arthur
Ashe's AIDS or Greg Louganis' homosexuality, a story in which I
participated, for my own ambition.
</P>
<P>
   A more interesting story, and one I hope Stevenson writes
herself, is the successful raising of a multiracial child by a
single white mother in one of the harshest sports environments.
Even nuclear families explode in tennis. The relationships between
parents and children are a study in dysfunction and sometimes
white-collar crime, and the addition of such parental figures as
coaches is frequently volatile.
</P>
<P>
   One of Alexandra's earliest coaches was Pete Fischer, who is
credited with outfitting Pete Sampras with his rocket serve.
Alexandra has a version of that serve. Fischer is in jail after
being convicted of molesting boys at his medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old Jelena Dokic, whom Alexandra beat in the
quarterfinals, knocked off Martina Hingis in an earlier round.
Jelena's father was recently arrested for disorderly conduct at a
tournament. Martina's longtime coach, her mother, was mysteriously
absent from Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   My own fantasy was to see Alexandra and Steffi Graf in the final
_ Steffi made it; Alexandra didn't _ for a number of reasons, the
least of which had to do with theories on the importance of dads:
Herr Graf was jailed for tax evasion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1417EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
