<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather will cover a large area from the eastern Rockies to
the Atlantic Seaboard as a strong and expansive area of high
pressure stretches from the central Atlantic Ocean to the
Mississippi Valley. Very warm air aloft near the center of the high
pressure zone will discourage thundershowers over much of the
Eastern states. However, disturbances traveling along the periphery
of the high will promote clusters of thunderstorms from the
northern Plains to the interior Northeast and from the southern
Rockies to portions of Texas and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Dissipating thunderstorms will drift across the eastern Great
Lakes into the interior Northeast early Sunday. By midday, most of
the Northeast will be hot and humid with hazy sunshine. Winds from
the Southwest will be warmed further as they descend from the
Appalachians. As a result, afternoon temperatures in the middle and
upper 90s will be common from metropolitan New York to eastern
Virginia. A few strong thunderstorms will erupt over the interior
Northeast during the heat of the afternoon. The storms will drift
toward the coast Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain will produce local flooding over parts of Florida,
especially near the eastern coast. A few afternoon thunderstorms
will form near the Gulf Coast. Otherwise, the Southeast will be
very warm and humid with little chance for rain.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will develop from the northern Plains to
the western Great Lakes as a cool front approaches. Meanwhile, the
Northwest will stay unseasonably cool.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Aphelion
</P>
<P>
   Although this is hottest time of year, the Earth will reach
aphelion, its farthest point from the sun, on July 6th. But now,
the Northern Hemisphere is tilted toward the sun, accounting for
the greater energy that is reaching the northern latitudes than
when the Earth makes it closest approach in January. Although in
the current era, the Earth is farther from the sun during the
Northern Hemisphere summer, that is not always the case. The Earth
wobbles on its axis like a spinning top. As a result of the slow
wobble, 11,000 years from now the Earth will be closest to the sun
during the northern summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
