<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENWAY-FRACAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONS RUN HIGH OVER PLANS FOR FENWAY
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also being sent `s' code.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Apologies to organized religion, but surely any candid
clergyman would concur: The most widely revered shrine in Boston is
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   So the fight brewing here stands out from the slew of stadium
battles that have cropped up around the country. To hear some talk,
at stake is the legacy of Babe Ruth, the cream of all sports-fan
experiences, yea, the very Valhalla of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Plus a lot of money. And a city neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   One would think Bostonians would be fed up with stadium issues
after the recent months of ``will they, won't they'' drama over
whether the New England Patriots would move from Massachusetts to
Hartford. (They won't.)
</P>
<P>
   But this one has some new twists. A group of Fenway purists
contends that the old park can and should be saved and a group of
long-suffering Fenway-area residents denounce plans for the new
park as downright stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the sacred nature of 87-year-old Fenway, one of the
two oldest major league ballparks, and this sports-mad city is
embarking on its newest stadium saga with a much higher wattage of
emotional electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Already, John Harrington, the Red Sox chief executive, has
repeatedly choked up when speaking publicly about leaving old
Fenway Park. And many Bostonians have a Fenway Park reflex that,
when triggered, unleashes a maudlin speech that begins, ``I first
went there with my Dad, when I was 5 years old ...''
</P>
<P>
   Some details about the new $350 million stadium that the Red Sox
are proposing to build next to the old one remain unclear, in
particular, how much public money the state and city would be asked
to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   But since the unveiling of the stadium plan in May, the outlines
of the project have emerged, as have the battle lines.
</P>
<P>
   On one thing, the consensus is near-total: Fenway Park, the
smallest in the Major League, is obsolete. Fans love its intimacy,
and talk about being close enough to the players to catch a whiff
of their sweat, but its seats, aisles, and concourses are narrow,
it has flooding troubles, obstructed views, and other physical
problems. And from the Red Sox point of view, it is too small to
bring in enough money to make the team more competitive. (Read:
Maybe with more money, they could win a World Series, which they
have not done since 1918.)
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox plan to keep the best of old Fenway _ part of the
famed Green Monster fence, the infield and left field _ but in a
park next to the new stadium, a sort of museum version of Fenway.
The new stadium would include replications of the best _ the fence
and intimate layout _ but include over 10,000 more seats, bringing
capacity to 44,000, and an array of improvements, from wider seats
and concourses to a better sound system and more bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox officials say that fan reaction has been strongly
positive, and a team brochure even quotes former Red Sox great Ted
Williams: ``I want Boston to have the best. If any city needed a
new ballpark they need it. I won't shed a tear.'' City and state
officials, too, have been making positive noises, though largely
withholding final judgment.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of Old Fenway loyalists called Save Fenway Park is
proposing an alternate stadium plan that would involve renovating
the current stadium, and have been meeting in recent days with top
politicians. The loyalists argue that by adding an upper deck of
seats and other improvements to Fenway, they could preserve a
national landmark while increasing income.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the neighborhood opposition, from residents who
say that the Red Sox have been a bad neighbor and a new park would
make them an even worse one. Air quality, already terrible, would
get worse, as would traffic and parking. Perhaps, they say, an
already congested neighborhood in the center of the city is not the
best place for a ballpark, and a more serious search should be
undertaken for a site that would not involve 2-hour traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gridlock now,'' said Jim Morgan, a member of the Fenway
Action Coalition, on a noisy street corner near Fenway. ``There's
no way they can get a million more people a year in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when asked what the greatest hurdle remaining for the new
Fenway was, Harrington of the Red Sox mentioned neither neighbors,
some of whom the Red Sox say are on board for the project, nor Save
Fenway. The big challenge, he said, is lining up the financing for
the project, which has an estimated price tag of $545 million: $350
for the stadium, $65 million for land purchases, $80 million for
two parking garages and $50 million for ``infrastructure'' like new
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Sports commentators in Boston tend to describe the Red Sox
proposal as a juggernaut, with strong initial momentum and backing
from big money, big sentiment and a phalanx of fixers.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Boston, a city of politicians even fiercer than its
sports stars. Under the Red Sox best-case scenario, the new park
would open in 2003. Sox fans may want to stay tuned. But very, very
patiently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
