u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISS-OLYMPICS-575&AMP;AD     07-03 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-OLYMPICS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUL-SEARCHING FOR SWISS AFTER THEY LOSE OLYMPIC BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Like chocolate, cheese, precision watches, the Red
Cross, skiing and banking, the Olympic movement has been linked for
decades with Switzerland. The city of Lausanne has long been
headquarters for the International Olympic Committee and home to
its spectacular lakeside museum.
</P>
<P>
   So it has been doubly infuriating for the Swiss to endure what
is widely perceived as the latest blow to their national pride: the
decision to award the 2006 Winter Olympics not to the front-running
Alpine resort of Sion, but to an upstart Italian rival, the
industrial city of Turin.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected and very public blow came when Switzerland was
climbing out of a lengthy economic downturn and beginning to come
to terms with the painful revelations of recent years that Swiss
actions during World War II may well have been concerned less with
self-preservation than with profit.
</P>
<P>
   Sion's loss to Turin sparked street protests and and nationwide
accusations that the vote was an act of revenge for the Swiss
member of the International Olympic Committee who blew the whistle
late last year on widespread corrupt practices within the Olympic
movement. That led to resignations and expulsions of members of its
clubby committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sion's bid for the Winter Games enjoyed widespread popular
support and Olympic rings in the red and white Swiss national
colors adorned everything from toilet paper to trains. So the
rebuff was felt nationwide, and the fury enhanced by knowledge that
the committee's formal evaluation gave the edge to Sion, while the
52-36 vote went heavily against the Swiss resort.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection prompted a wave of self-examination. One
mass-circulation daily, Blick, published a survey of foreigners'
views of the Swiss, ranging from what it described as the Israeli
view that the Swiss are anti-Semitic, to the French observation
that they are racist and the American perception of the Swiss as
colorless and out for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pedantic and humorless,'' Blick concluded. ``We are
greedy profiteers. We are arrogant. We are bad losers _ that's how
the world sees us.''
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland has long prided itself on what is nationally seen as
self-sufficiency, which in foreign affairs translated into
neutrality and choosing not to join either the United Nations or
the European Union. Today, however, that attitude is increasingly
seen as perilously insular.
</P>
<P>
   Federal minister Adolf Ogi, who oversaw the unsuccessful bid for
the 2006 Games, said afterward in published remarks that despite
Switzerland's healthy international economic position, it is
``politically alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogi, who was photographed visibly shaken when he heard the news
announced in Seoul, South Korea, said later: ``I heard delegates
say they wanted the Swiss to lose. People don't like Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was the disheartened Ogi's interview published when
reports surfaced that the country's role in seeking the Games may
not have been squeaky clean. A Swiss news weekly, L'Hebdo, said
Swiss tax officials had overlooked past Olympic Committee tax fraud
to smooth the way for Sion's bid. L'Hebdo printed what it said was
a secret government memo that Olympic Committee workers declared
lower salaries than they received, to avoid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Committee has denied any wrongdoing, saying that tax
arrangements, often murky in Switzerland for the rich and famous,
were longstanding and legitimate. Swiss officials also denied
wrongdoing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last month, a rare alliance of conservative and left-leaning
political parties blocked a constitutional amendment that would
have enabled Switzerland to sell some of its gold reserves to
finance the Solidarity Foundation, designed to help victims of
poverty, disaster and human-rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents argued that any benefits from gold sales should go
to Switzerland's sagging state pension fund, not to the special
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Ogi, who oversees Swiss defense and sports matters, saw the
recent controversy over the country's role during World War II and
the Olympic corruption disclosures as part of a ``mosaic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It also has to do with our attitude,'' he added. ``We think we
are the best, we play at being schoolmasters, we give lessons, we
wish to profit but not to get involved. We overestimate
ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI-2     07-03 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY AND MAYOR TRY TO TURN DOWN THE GLARE ON THEIR SENATE
BIDS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Hillary Rodham Clinton shows up at Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan's upstate New York farm on Wednesday, offering
herself as his potential successor after his retirement next year,
it will be a full 482 days until the election. Nevertheless, as of
Saturday, nearly 200 reporters and other media representatives from
around the world had signed up to record the event, and then to
chase the first lady across central New York for four days of
``listening to New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Most candidates for U.S. Senate would revel in that kind of
attention, particularly in a state like New York, where campaigns
rarely draw serious notice until well after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a growing perception among New York's political
leaders that the 16-month campaign for Senate that begins with Mrs.
Clinton's appearance in Pindars Corners will pose an extraordinary
challenge for the Democratic first lady and Rudolph Giuliani, the
Republican New York City mayor, who is also likely to run for the
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani have actually begun
talking about turning down the volume on this contest, as difficult
as that may be in this superheated media environment, with both
sides concerned about overexposure or making mistakes under such
close scrutiny and over such a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's aides said she intended to avoid making major
news over the course of her visits to New York this summer. She
plans no major speeches and will spend most of her time
``listening, listening, listening and listening'' at small meetings
with voters, said her senior political adviser, Harold Ickes. And
Giuliani has been attempting to lower his Senate candidacy profile
as well, one adviser said, concentrating on activities like raising
money while turning down invitations to appear on network
television shows devoted to the race.
</P>
<P>
   The race for senator from New York for 2000 is, given the likely
presence of a sitting first lady, upending the rules by which
politics are played in New York. It has pushed all the players into
unfamiliar territory, from the strategists who are trying to plan a
campaign unlike any they have seen before, to the television news
directors and newspaper editors who are faced with decisions about
how many staff members they should devote to a Senate race that is
effectively beginning more than a year early.
</P>
<P>
   Those decisions could prove to be nearly as significant in
shaping the public perception of the race in the next 12 months as
what the candidates themselves do.
</P>
<P>
   Against that unsettled background, there is a sense among the
first lady's associates that a long run on a high-profile stage
could present unwanted complications for a novice candidate who is
trying to learn a new career and get to know a new state. While
Mrs. Clinton's stature carries obvious advantages _ this is one
candidate who never has to worry about walking into a room filled
with empty chairs _ the concern has colored much of the planning
Mrs. Clinton's aides have done for her inaugural campaign visit.
</P>
<P>
   How, asked one of her friends, is Mrs. Clinton going to learn
about the concerns of everyday New Yorkers when she is being
shadowed by a press corps so huge that its numbers are filling
hotels from Oneonta to Albany? Will she be able to walk down the
street, talking to shop owners or buying a quart of milk, with
reporters and Secret Service agents packed around her?
</P>
<P>
   A critical aspect of Mrs. Clinton's effort to become grounded in
New York is the discussions with small groups of New Yorkers that
will begin on Wednesday in Oneonta. ``She wants them to be as
intimate as possible,'' said Mandy Grunwald, a longtime adviser to
Mrs. Clinton. ``She wants to speak to people, listen to people, and
not have 200 cameras there to make it more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But those events are, so far, shaping up as something less than
private. Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's new press secretary, said
he had processed requests for press credentials from television
crews from Japan and Britain. While Wolfson said the campaign would
try to restrict coverage of some of the events to a small,
representative group of pool reporters, Mrs. Clinton will arrive at
Moynihan's farmhouse in the rolling hills of Delaware County to
find a huge wooden platform constructed to accommodate the
television crews and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases,'' Wolfson said, ``a large press corps may not
be helpful to facilitating this.''
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, Mrs. Clinton, and to a lesser extent
Giuliani, will not have the luxury of traveling the state, learning
the issues and making unnoticed mistakes in the process, a luxury
most new candidates have. Mrs. Clinton's friends say this will not
be a problem for this particular first lady, given her husband's
skills. ``She knows what it takes, having been through numerous
campaigns throughout her husband's career,'' said Lisa Caputo, who
served as Mrs. Clinton's press secretary in the White House. ``I
would argue she's pretty seasoned.''
</P>
<P>
   But the sheer length of the campaign invites opportunities for
high-profile errors by any candidate, particularly one who is
inexperienced. That became distressingly clear to the first lady's
friends when she donned a New York Yankees baseball cap at a White
House ceremony and declared herself a Yankee fan, a moment that
even her closest associates described as clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Mrs. Clinton, Sen. Charles Schumer, at a similar
point in his own campaign to unseat Alfonse M. D'Amato last year,
was traveling the state constantly, with a single aide and largely
unnoticed. Schumer, a Democrat who had served in the House, said he
had used that time to raise money, educate himself on state issues
and build political support.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense it was easier, because no one was paying attention
to me, and I could focus on what I had to do,'' Schumer recalled.
``And in a sense, it was harder because no one was paying attention
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has far more experience campaigning than Mrs. Clinton.
However, even his friends say his bellicose manner, particularly in
the environment of Gracie Mansion, invites mistakes as well. And
even Giuliani's friends do not dispute that he lacks the kind of
personality that wears well with voters over time.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani may get more attention if Rep. Rick A. Lazio, a Long
Island Republican, keeps his promise to challenge the mayor in the
primary. In the meantime, Bruce Teitelbaum, the head of the mayor's
political action committee, said Giuliani had no intention of
conducting the kind of explicit campaigning now that would focus
attention on the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really focusing on things we need to do _ and much less
on what the media thinks, or the attention the media is paying on
the things that are happening,'' Teitelbaum said. ``We are
concentrating on the things that we need to get ourselves ready.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's advisers are trying to remedy the problem of
having too many reporters following her by, in effect, trying to
bore them out of town. ``I hope that over time the novelty will
wear off and she'll be able to get out there and really travel
without the full circus that will travel with her at the
beginning,'' Ms. Grunwald said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But there are indications that this is one race where
there will be a continual media presence. Steve Paulus, the general
manager of New York 1, the all-news cable station in New York City,
said his station was gearing up to enthusiastically cover every
turn of the campaign, no matter how long it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be following the candidates wherever they go,''
Paulus said. ``I think the interest is just going to be so high
that we can't miss covering it like a glove. It'll sustain itself
and it'll be that interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mark Halperin, the political director for ABC News, said he
expected the networks to cover a Clinton-Giuliani race, assuming it
shapes up that way, much the way they cover the candidates for
president. ``It is safe to say that from September 2000 through the
elections, the networks will cover her every day,'' Halperin said.
``And all the networks will likely assign full-time off-air
reporters to cover her, as early as this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
