A8377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRA-SIZES09-COX     07-03 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRA-SIZES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trying on several bra styles essential to finding good fit
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If your bra slips, slides or sags, causing you to
bounce and bulge, you're probably one of the 85 out of 100 women
wearing the wrong bra size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-five percent of women are wearing the wrong size bra
because they don't know the proper size of bra they should be
wearing,'' said Corene Hennig, an international executive director
with Jeunique International, who sells custom-fitted Sculptress,
Pennyrich and Jeunique bras.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Nutritional Research Foundation, many women
wear ill-fitting garments that give little or no support or that
redirect the breast tissue, impeding circulation and lymphatic
drainage.
</P>
<P>
   Many women squeeze themselves into a bra that's too small,
reasoning that going up a size is a sign of gaining weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Squeezing into a smaller bra is not only uncomfortable, it can
cause unsightly bulging and spilling out in the front,'' said Cyndy
Shirey, who worked for three years in the lingerie department at JC
Penney. ``That can be OK if you're going out in the evening and
you're wearing a low-cut dress and you want to show, but not when
wearing a T-shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not only unflattering to wear the wrong-size bra, it's also
unhealthy, Hennig added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bust should be held at a 45-degree angle to your chest
wall to allow for proper circulation and lymphatic drainage,'' she
said. ``Then they don't have that old matronly look where they're
going down, down ... When they are held up, it takes pressure off
the diaphragm and you can breath a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonsupport bras and gravity work together causing the woman's
breasts to sag, stretch downward and lose prominence and firmness.
</P>
<P>
   With a supportive bra and the proper-fitting clothes, a
well-endowed woman can have a great-looking chest, said Hennig, who
has been selling custom-fitted bras for 29 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't notice your breasts if you're wearing
proper-fitting clothing. What they notice is if you're flopping,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   For a proper fit, the bottom of the bra should fit on the rib
cage, not on the breast. In the back, the bra should come down
below the shoulder blades. All of the breast tissue should be
contained inside the cup and the bra should hold the breasts firm
with no or little give when you jump in the air. The bust should be
supported from underneath the breast, not from the shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bras are just like blue jeans. Most of the time you have to
try on several kinds of bras,'' Shirey said. ``Every bra fits
differently and it will fit differently on every person.''
</P>
<P>
   Tips for finding a bra that fits:
</P>
<P>
   _ Get measured. Some department stores have a fitting consultant
or fitting specialist that can help you.
</P>
<P>
   To measure for most store bras, put the tape measure around your
back and directly above the breasts to get a band size. For the cup
size, measure directly over the fullest part of the breasts.
Subtract the band size from the cup size and the difference
determines what letter your cup size will be.
</P>
<P>
   If the numbers are the same, the cup size is AA; if the
difference is 1 inch, the cup size is A; for 2 inches, the cup size
is B; 3 inches, the cup size is C; 4 inches, the cup size is D; 5
inches, the cup size is DD; 6 inches, the cup size is DDD.
</P>
<P>
   Custom-fit bras are sized differently than most store-bought
bras. Corene Hennig, who sells custom-fitted Sculptress, Pennyrich
and Jeunique bras, measures customers before fitting them with a
bra.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you try on a bra, bend at the waist to make sure the
entire bust stays in the bra. Stretch every way and do several
jumping jacks to make sure the bra doesn't ride up in the back or
front, which would mean it was too big or too small.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to fit against your breast bone, but you still need
to be able to get a finger under there,'' said Cyndy Shirey of JC
Penney.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cinch bras up if they sag in the front or if straps tend to
fall off the shoulders. Or look for a T-back bra.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small chested women should avoid sheer bras or bras with no
fiberfill. Such bras tend to bunch up or pucker. A contour cup
offers a more rounded, even look.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go bra shopping only when you're in a good mood and aren't
tired. First thing in the morning is a good time because you
probably will have to try on multiple bras to find that perfect
one, Shirey said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Just because a bra is the size you normally wear doesn't mean
it will fit you, especially since there are many types of bras made
for different lifestyles, outfits and coverage, including push-up,
contour, seamless, front hook, padded, full-coverage, sports,
underwire and strapless bras.
</P>
<P>
   Often when women try on bras, they'll go from an underwire to
something without an underwire or from a fiberfill to a sheer.
Switching styles can make it more difficult to find a bra that
fits.
</P>
<P>
   Well-endowed women need to look for a bra that supports them
well. A lot of people think underwire bras are the best, which
isn't necessarily the best bra for well-endowed women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the minimizer bras,'' said Shirey. ``They lift and
separate, which gives you a lot more support. A piece of material
in the middle separates and keeps the breasts from appearing to
stretch all the way across the chest.''
</P>
<P>
   A crisscross performs similarly.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have trenches in your shoulders where your bra has been
digging, try selecting a bra with wide shoulder straps or padded
straps, also called comfort straps.
</P>
<P>
   _ For daily wear, avoid bras that don't give a natural fit, such
as push-up bras and sports bras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people wear sports bras 24 hours a day, seven days a
week. That's not good for you because it compresses you and it's
not really healthy,'' Shirey said.
</P>
<P>
   Save push-up bras for special occasions, like dances and a night
out on the town, when a little more cleavage is desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it makes you feel better to wear one of those little
ditties on a Saturday evening out, go for it. But on Monday
morning, put back on your good support bra,'' Hennig said.
</P>
<P>
   Bra types:
</P>
<P>
   Soft cup _ An everyday basic that works well with any wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Padded _ When you want to add an inch, while maintaining a soft,
natural shape.
</P>
<P>
   Push-up _ For maximum cleavage. Features underwire and padding
to shape and lift.
</P>
<P>
   Minimizer _ Reduces the size of the fuller bust without
sacrificing firm support or comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Crossover _ Provides separation. An everyday bra for most sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Strapless _ Wear with strapless fashions or clothing with skinny
straps or extra-wide boat necks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: JC Penney
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
