<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-JUKEBOXES04 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing that tune with jukeboxes
 &HT;    By Amy Kincheloe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A large man in a yellow shirt stands in the middle
of Chapter 11 with a dollar bill in his hand and an intent look in
his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Like a moth to a flame, he is drawn toward the brightly lit
jukebox hanging on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay attention _ I could be a disc jockey,'' the anonymous man
shouted to the crowd gathered at the bar. He then proceeded to
point out, to anyone who would listen, his favorite bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Doors _ now this is my music,'' he said. ``Man, I love
AC/DC, ooh, and Bob Seger, too. And ZZ Top is always going to be
around.''
</P>
<P>
   As his music selections start to play, he settles in at the bar
and starts to groove.
</P>
<P>
   The man in the yellow shirt is not alone in his love for
jukeboxes, just ask around your local bars and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come in a place, you want to hear good music not
twiddle your thumbs,'' said Clark Williams, a customer at Charlie's
Corner. ``When you get off work, you want to have a few drinks,
listen to the jukebox and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charlie's Corner bartender Peggi Shepard admits that the
atmosphere can get downright playful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play something they don't like, they beat a trail to the
jukebox to play something else,'' Shepard said. ``We often have
jukebox wars. Someone will get up and play songs that they know
another person doesn't like, and then that person will get up and
play songs that they know the other person doesn't like. We have a
lot of fun going back and forth like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that favorite music can be from a local artist like
Texas singer-songwriter Pat Green, who grew up in Bosqueville and
Waco. His song ``George's Bar,'' which is about all the time he
spent at George's Restaurant in Waco, appears on a few of the
jukeboxes here in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not some mega star, so guys like me appreciate being put
on their jukebox,'' Green said. ``We're not the kind of guys who
get played on the radio all the time, so we have to depend on other
avenues for people to hear us. Jukeboxes are a good way. It's
satisfying to know there's several places in town where you can
listen to my music on jukeboxes.''
</P>
<P>
   George's owner Sammy Citrano said Green's music and songs by
other Texas artists are often the most played in his establishment.
In fact, he said, most of the customers know their selections by
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a free jukebox, and people pay to hear their
favorites. So we keep up with the Baylor kids and the older
people's requests,'' Citrano said. ``It's amazing that a lot of
people have their favorites memorized. You can often hear them call
out four numbers to a friend standing at the jukebox, and sure
enough that's the song they want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   However, what one person wants to hear on the jukebox is not
necessarily what everyone else in the place wants to hear. But
Green concedes that's part of a jukebox's charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the basic concept of being able to choose your own
music,'' Green said. ``With that dollar, you can dictate to
everyone in the bar what they're going to hear, and that's pretty
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ellis, co-owner of Ellis Music Co., has serviced
jukeboxes for more than 40 years. He has seen the requests for
certain artists come and go through the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always request certain records. It just depends on where
you're at,'' Ellis said. ``Some of it's The Dixie Chicks, some of
it's Ricky Martin and some of it's B.B. King. It just depends on
the location you're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
