<HEADER>
A8381 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALL-IDEAS04-COX     07-03 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-IDEAS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creativity drives Mall of America
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ What I loved about my first visit to the Mall of
America in Minneapolis this week wasn't that it has 500 stores and
22 sit-down restaurants. Or that there's no sales tax on clothing
in Minnesota, or even that it includes some of my favorite stores:
Nordstrom, Bloomingdale's and Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   What I loved is that the powers-that-be who created the giant
mall have allowed themselves to think creatively about what an
American mall might be rather than lock themselves into stereotypes
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   I've been thinking about that subject a lot because I'm worried
about the future of my neighborhood's mall. I keep asking myself
why a mall can't look at innovative ways to attract customers,
especially families.
</P>
<P>
   The Mall of America has done just that, and it seems to be
working. Since opening in 1992, the mall has become a destination
spot, attracting 43 million people a year, 40 percent of them
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   One of the mall owners is the Melvin Simon Group out of
Indianapolis, a company that also serves as mall managers. And the
indoor amusement park, Camp Snoopy, is run by Ohio's Cedar Point.
</P>
<P>
   I toured the mall with Maureen Cahill, associate director of
public relations. Here are a few examples of creative thinking and
programming that go way beyond the tons of shoe and clothing
stores.
</P>
<P>
   _ An alternative high school, the Metropolitan Learning
Alliance, is located in the mall. The off-site campus targets
students in five Minneapolis-area school districts. It gives
high-school and post-secondary technical college credits. The
school has seven classrooms and a technology computer lab and also
is used by the University of St. Thomas for courses in retail
management.
</P>
<P>
   _ National American University is the first college campus in a
mall. Cahill says it's especially valued by mall employees who want
to take accounting, marketing, computer and business courses. Day
and night classes are offered three days a week and on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   _ Couples can get married at the ``Chapel of Love.'' The unusual
wedding spot has attracted more than 2,000 couples from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Greek Bodyline Mediterranean Spa offers services ranging
from body wraps and massage to nonsurgical face lifts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daily guided walking tours.
</P>
<P>
   _ A youth liaison program was started in 1995 to develop
relationships, trust and respect with kids both inside the mall and
in their communities. Youth Liaisons are security officers who
focus on issues that are important to teens. They organize
youth-targeted events, visit schools and volunteer at community
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mighty Moms and Dedicated Dads is a team of real-life moms
and dads who work side-by-side with mall security officers on
Friday and Saturday evenings. They welcome kids, encourage them to
behave and follow the rules, and act as a first level of
intervention if the need arises. The program is part of the mall's
innovative approach to dealing with unsupervised youth and making
the mall safer for all guests.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kid's Quest, a day-care center where parents can leave
children while they shop.
</P>
<P>
   _ The SHAPE program offers classes in adult basic education and
English as a second language. The classes are free and the schedule
is flexible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Help phones are located throughout the mall to assist
shoppers. There's also a ``One Call for the Mall'' line that
answers questions about reaching any store, restaurant or
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   _ You've probably read about the more glitzy attractions such as
Camp Snoopy, the full-scale, indoor amusement park. When the
Minneapolis winter gets rough, kids can still have an
almost-outdoor amusement-park experience. There's a 500-seat
theater beside Camp Snoopy and a new climbing wall with three
levels of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   _ A more recent addition is UnderWater World, a full-scale, 1.2
million-gallon aquarium. Acrylic tunnels equipped with a moving
walkway lead visitors through the aquatic adventures.
</P>
<P>
   _ When I passed the four-story Lego Imagination Center, I saw
lots of families huddled around tables building Legos together.
There's no purchase required and they're welcome to stay as long as
they like.
</P>
<P>
   The mall, which has a lot of the stores you'd expect, also has
some unique shops, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ A magnet store.
</P>
<P>
   _ A NASCAR Silicon Motor Speedway store with simulated racing
machines.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Great Cars Great Trucks store, which showcases Chrysler's
latest models and concept cars. There are interactive Sega games, a
life-sized Jeep simulator and a theater.
</P>
<P>
   _ Postmark America is a one-of-a-kind postal retail store. You
can buy stamps as well as a complete line of post-office
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Basic Brown Bear Factory, kids can help make a teddy
bear. You select a bear and then assist in stuffing, sewing,
bathing and dressing the bear.
</P>
<P>
   _ Custom Foot uses a computer to take three-dimensional
measurements of a shopper's feet. Measurements are sent to Italy
and custom-made shoes arrive at your home within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oshman's Supersports USA lets you try before you buy. You can
sink a jump shot, lace up roller blades and skate, or drive a
three-wood deep into an in-store golf simulator.
</P>
<P>
   _ The LifePlace celebrates life even when an illness is
involved. The store offers items that make living with an illness
or disability easier. There's a collection of soft dolls that have
their own ``illness'' and can be used as teaching tools.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much this mall doesn't offer. Cahill says its
success is due to the fact that it provides something for everyone
and families can spend days there. The mall also includes bars open
till 1 a.m. You can learn more at www.mallofamerica.com on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   I left believing that there's no reason our area malls couldn't
come up with innovative uses for mall space and create complexes
that will attract those from neighboring cities as well. It's
certainly worth some thought.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
