<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RV-LUXURY-ART-1150(2T     07-03 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RV-LUXURY-ART-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUXURY HOMES ON ROAD GROW WITH PROSPERITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Minn.) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THORNTOWN, Ind. _ It is simple, Clarence and Maryann Cornell
said. Financially secure, they wanted to travel and they wanted to
do it in comfort and style, their two yelping dachshunds in tow.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the Cornells, owners of two stationary homes _ one in
Minnesota, the other in Florida _ explained their latest
acquisition: a $112,000 Fleetwood Southwind motor home they had
just eased into a spot at Old Mill Run Park, a 67-acre campground
with a stream and fishing ponds, amid corn and soybean fields here
in central Indiana, 35 miles northwest of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Over a long weekend, they will lounge on leather upholstery in a
plushly carpeted living room with expandable walls, cook in a
kitchen complete with four-door refrigerator-freezer and bathe in a
big tub in their bedroom suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the dogs,'' said Mrs. Cornell, who is 40, ``the only way
to do it is with a motor home.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornell, 69, outside lowering the motor home's built-in awning,
shrugged and agreed. ``That's the gist of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In these days of unparalleled affluence, the Cornells can
splurge more than most. He is a semiretired executive; their
children are grown. But in their taste for luxury on the road, they
are far from alone.
</P>
<P>
   Chariots like that of the Cornells _ and bigger ones, costing up
to $1 million, with washers, dryers, tile-walled baths,
surround-sound stereos and storage compartments beneath the wheels
known as basements _ pull into Old Mill Run Park every day. The one
thing that does not often pierce this middle-class campground's
horizon of metal boxes on wheels is the peak of a spartan camper's
tent, though there are sites for them.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a place in America that captures how the waning
century's longest stretch of prosperity has fogged over memories of
recessions, unemployment, inflation, gasoline rationing and sinking
stock markets, the American campground is as sure a contender as
the thriving marinas of Florida or the shoulder-to-shoulder big
houses of suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   While roughing it with bugs, Sterno stoves and sleeping bags in
the thick of the bush still lures many of the hardy and fit, the
old conventional campground now more often means trailers with
window screens, three-burner stoves, air-conditioning and
queen-sized beds.
</P>
<P>
   Motor homes, many of them 300- and 400-horsepower ``diesel
pushers,'' as they are called, pull the family car to the campsite,
or ``duallies,'' big muscular, $40,000 pickups with four wheels in
the rear, haul in the trailers.
</P>
<P>
   It all costs money, far more than the gains in income that most
Americans have realized over the last decade. But like the boats
and the extra-large houses, a deluxe home on the road is something
that many of them will stretch themselves thin to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are buying more now than they ever did in their life,''
said John Shufflebarger, who as a salesman at the Indy RV Center
near Indianapolis supplies some of the vehicles that come here. ``I
don't believe people in the United States are going to let money or
gas prices interfere with their entertainment. As long as the
economy is as good as it is now, they're going to go out and have a
good time.''
</P>
<P>
   For three years, Mary Kay Baker, 36, a cheery preschool teacher,
her husband, John, 39, a farmer and water-well driller, and their
children, Bradley, 11, and Kristen, 15, have been spending weekends
and summer vacations here. A year ago, Mrs. Baker's parents, Bill
and Ferne Ferrel, started coming, too, in a trailer of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The Bakers, who earn something under $60,000 a year, put 10
percent down from their savings to buy their $21,000, 35-foot
Innsbruck trailer. Unlike many Americans, the Bakers do save
something, about 10 percent of their income, but they save to
spend, not for the rainy days of unemployment or plunging stocks
and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember the recession,'' Mrs. Baker said, sitting at
the family picnic table.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Recreational Vehicle Industry Association says
the booming economy induced Americans to spend $8.4 billion for
nearly 300,000 recreational vehicles, from $3,000 pop-up camping
trailers to self-propelled motor-home behemoths, most of which cost
$50,000 to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s through last year, the association says, the
industry sold two million vehicles, almost half a million more than
in the 1980s. All together, the association says 9.3 million are in
service and that one in 10 households has one.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, after many years of camping with their children,
Ralph Christman, 47, a former farmer and automobile assembly line
worker, and his wife, Sandy, formerly the activities director at a
veterans' home, bought Old Mill Run Park.
</P>
<P>
   The park has 347 campsites, with 197 of them renting for $950
for the season that runs from April to October. All of these are
taken. Most of the other sites, renting for an average of $21 a
day, except for those for tents, are at least two-thirds full on
weekdays and tend to fill up on weekends. The vehicle sites have
small lawns and easy hook-ups to water and electricity and many to
cable television and telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   People come for the swimming, fishing, the five-hole golf course
and volleyball, bingo and horseshoe tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's carefree,'' Mrs. Christman said. Children come
into the campground store with $20 bills to buy candy and trinkets
and spend it all, she said, adding, ``Then they go back and get
some more.''
</P>
<P>
   As production of RVs has climbed, so have the features on which
consumers splurge. Many are equipped with one to three expandable
sides, known as slide-outs. These are sections of wall, floor and
ceiling that with the push of a button pop out from a vehicle's
aluminum hide to create more space inside.
</P>
<P>
   Driven or towed, the bigger vehicles require a gallon of
gasoline or diesel oil to travel 7 to 10 miles. But relatively
inexpensive fuel, $1 a gallon for gasoline or diesel oil at at a
station near this campground, has erased memories of the oil crisis
in the mid-1970s, when rationing and soaring prices put the
recreational vehicle business in mothballs.
</P>
<P>
   The lush economy has blessed Jack Andres, 65, who retired last
year as a utilities engineer at Purdue University in West
Lafayette, Ind., and his wife, Janet, 59, who was an administrative
secretary there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last working years, our salaries were higher, and our
investments made more money,'' Mrs. Andres said. ``It's allowed me
to retire before I was 62.''
</P>
<P>
   They sold their home last year and, with savings and profits,
have settled into a 28-foot, single-slide-out trailer that they
keep here. They also bought a camper that fits into the bed of
their pickup that they take on visits to 11 children from two
marriages and to Naples, Fla., the site of their modular home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be, camping was your cheap summer vacation,'' Mrs.
Andres said. ``Camping is a lifestyle for us now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With the growth of motorized camping, the age of the motorist
has dropped. Almost entirely retirees before the 1990s, the average
trailer and motor home owner today is 48, said Jeff Beddow, the
industry association's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   At the Old Mill Run Park, the Christmans' clientele is blue
collar and white collar. Postal workers and construction workers
reside lot to lot with doctors and executives. They seem
universally affluent, in outlook and attitude if not in all cases
in assets and income.
</P>
<P>
   Judee and David Duncan, both 58, parents of five children, have
a 38.5-foot Fleetwood Avion fifth-wheeler, a trailer that hitches
into bed of a pickup. It is the Duncans' only home.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan retired from the Navy, having risen to lieutenant
commander from seaman, and went to work for the Raytheon Co. Five
years ago, at 53, while working 70 hours a week managing a missile
assembly plant, he had a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to chuck it all,'' Duncan said. ``We sold our
3,000-square-foot home, bought a fifth-wheeler and have been on the
road since. I have owned everything a person could want. Boats.
Woodworking equipment. And I do not miss it a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The low-inflation economy, Duncan said, protects the buying
power of his $35,000 annual pension from the Navy that he and his
wife are living on. ``Sometimes I think of getting a part-time
job,'' Duncan said, ``but it doesn't last very long.''
</P>
<P>
   When the campground closes in the fall, he said he and Mrs.
Duncan would drive to the Outer Banks of North Carolina to fish and
then roll on to Florida for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   For some other campers here, mostly young, but older ones, too,
the decade's prosperity has inspired revisionist thinking about the
notions of spending, saving and borrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Rumery, 71, basks under his awning, wearing a T-shirt
that says, ``I'm a two-steppin' country western dancer.'' He and
his wife, Nancy, 68, used to share driving of a Mayflower moving
van, and then he became the company's supervisor of driver
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the Depression,'' Rumery said. ``I was born in 1927.
I grew up dirt poor.'' Gesturing from his patio, he said, ``We just
bought that '99 Chrysler this year,'' with 10 percent down. ``We
had a '96 Mercury. But it was gray and she wanted red, so we just
bought it.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Rumery is his 1999, 36-foot, $22,000 Nomad trailer with
two slide-outs. ``We just bought it, too,'' he said, again with 10
percent down. ``I don't believe in paying cash. Why should I take
it out of the market where it's working for me and put it in
something that's going to start depreciating the day I buy it?''
</P>
<P>
   With pensions, Social Security, Medicare, consulting fees, and a
lively stock market, Rumery said, ``We believe we've got the
ability to do what we want to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
