u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ILLEGAL-BARBECUES-     07-03 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ILLEGAL-BARBECUES-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBECUE SUBCULTURE FLOURISHES OUTSIDE THE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Phyllis Norton-Towers, a real estate broker in
Brooklyn Heights, enjoys a charmed urban life. She lives in a
brownstone apartment with a garden where turtles swim in a
makeshift pond and plump roses climb a wooden trellis. Her dinner
guests relish the cloth-covered garden furniture, the sauvignon
blanc and especially the cuisine made possible by the barbecue: a
Weber grill fueled by a 20-pound propane tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where it all takes place,'' said Ms. Norton-Towers
contentedly as she described the stuffed chicken and even the peach
cobbler she had grilled one recent evening. ``My dream was: I want
to be able to cook outside.''
</P>
<P>
   With her headband, her gold bracelets and a drink in hand, Ms.
Norton-Towers hardly fits the image of a law breaker. Yet she is
among an entire class of New Yorkers engaged in an illicit
activity: barbecuing with compressed gas.
</P>
<P>
   Two single-spaced pages of municipal regulations make it almost
impossible for most city dwellers to grill within the law.
Barbecues on residential property, using either propane or
charcoal, cannot be operated within 10 feet of any combustible
material, like Ms. Norton-Towers' wooden trellis and her
cloth-covered furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Propane, the most highly regulated fuel, cannot be transported
into the city via tunnels or the lower levels of bridges, and tanks
cannot be refilled anywhere in the city. Also, it is illegal to
carry more than a pound of propane through a house or apartment.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, to comply with the regulations and maneuver a
20-pound tank onto a terrace? ``You'd have to bring it in by
helicopter,'' said Brian Dickson, a spokesman for the Fire
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Although the department regards propane as a serious potential
fire hazard and has confiscated illegally stored propane used for
commercial purposes, officials acknowledge that any crackdown on
residential barbecuing has been minimal. The city does not keep
lists of offenders, and it has no record of having caught one. The
penalties on the books range from a citation to a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   As they fire up their grills this holiday weekend, many New
Yorkers have only a hazy sense of the prohibitions. Some, like Ms.
Norton-Towers, believe they are following the laws. Others, like
Brad Grossman, a chiropractor who recently grilled filet mignon for
guests on the silvery rooftop of his Christopher Street building in
Greenwich Village, know the regulations but choose to ignore them,
the hunger for barbecued meat being more powerful than the fear of
discovery.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of one die-hard barbecuer, a television producer
who lives in a brownstone on the Upper West Side, ``Some laws are
meant to be broken.'' And broken they are with impunity, on the
city's terraces, patios, fire escapes and sidewalks and in its
gardens and alleys, as New Yorkers grill everything from sliced
cauliflower to marinated bratwurst.
</P>
<P>
   The rare law-abiding barbecue lover, like Debra Duchin, a
private investigator who lives on the Upper East Side, so feared
the possibility of a fine that she turned her propane grill into a
planter and packed it with petunias.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Wing, a former executive food editor of Country Living
magazine who grills year-round at her West 71st Street brownstone,
says she uses charcoal instead of propane to comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of a confrontation with neighbors she described as
``cantankerous,'' who doused her with water as she grilled in her
garden, she moved her equipment to the roof. But there she is
courting trouble, too, because the grill sits on a potentially
combustible plastic mat.
</P>
<P>
   Each summer, the boards of many of the city's large co-op
apartment buildings send out stern letters telling tenants to put
down their tongs. But as Bob Plant, president of the board of his
co-op on East 24th Street, acknowledged, grilling continues. ``It's
a very abused regulation,'' he said. ``I can remember spotting a
dozen propane barbecues myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, many New Yorkers regard the laws as little more than a
nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   One recent Friday night, as Grossman presided over his
propane-fueled grill, flipping stalks of asparagus and chicken
breasts for a score of dinner guests, he offered a typically
caustic assessment of the city's barbecue regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really ruining the quality of life up here in New York
City,'' he said, snorting derisively, when asked about those who
ignore the rules. ``We are menaces to society.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His guests, equally uninterested in the regulations, were all
too willing to discuss their own barbecuing habits, like driving
tanks of propane through tunnels and carting them through French
windows leading to apartment terraces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, we have a good fire department around the corner,''
said Gerard O'Brien, an actor who uses a propane barbecue on his
wooden roof deck in TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman chimed in: ``We can see 10 other roofs from here, and
people are barbecuing all the time. My neighbors don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cavalier attitude of many New Yorkers, propane can
pose a real threat. A Fire Department official said that the
average tank of propane used for a grill has the force of four
sticks of dynamite, and that even an empty canister has enough
residual gas to blow up a house.
</P>
<P>
   A number of accidents related to propane barbecuing have
occurred on Long Island. In 1991, a propane blaze at Caumsett State
Park in Suffolk County left a child in critical condition. In 1994,
two teen-agers in Coram flicked a cigarette lighter near a propane
barbecue, causing an explosion. The boys survived, but only barely.
</P>
<P>
   Even legal activity connected with city barbecuing has a furtive
quality to it, as was evident one recent Saturday at T.W. Smith
Welding Supply Corp. on West 59th Street near the West Side
Highway.
</P>
<P>
   This desolate spot, adorned with signs reading ``Danger:
Compressed Gas,'' is one of two stores in Manhattan that exchange
empty propane tanks for full ones. Especially on summer weekends,
the store is thronged with New Yorkers unloading empty tanks from
the trunks of taxis, willing to abide by the law but annoyed at
having to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Others drive out to New Jersey to refill their tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a place somewhere on one of those anonymous routes,''
said one city barbecuer, who had borrowed a car in order to make
the trip. ``They told me they were out of propane. I said, `How can
you do that? I rearranged my whole life.'''
</P>
<P>
   The company finally rustled up enough gas to make possible a few
hamburger dinners. Then the New Yorker drove home through the
Lincoln Tunnel and walked the tank through his front door.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Wilson, a creative consultant to Donna Karan, once
dispatched a friend to New Jersey to refill her propane tank before
a dinner party in her Upper West Side garden. But the friend, who
had secured the tank in her car with a seat belt, became stuck in
traffic, and as an hour ticked by and she failed to telephone as
promised, Ms. Wilson began to regret having made the request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought, all for a barbecue,'' she said. ``A little
bump from another car and, like, she could blow up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
