<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FIVE YEARS LATER: ROLE REVERSAL AMONG NATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see SOC-BRAZIL-STAR, SOC-CHINA-NORWAY) 
 (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ There it is, in my T-shirt drawer, one of my
favorite gamers. Some artist did a fine job reproducing both the
Stars and Stripes and the Brazilian flag with that other-worldly
white globe, and a soccer ball floating in between.
</P>
<P>
   In bright red capital letters it says: ``STANFORD WORLD
SOCCER,'' and the date is July 4th _ 1994, that is.
</P>
<P>
   I bought the T-shirt at a stand operated by one of the Stanford
clubs or teams. I wear it only for quality outdoor workouts in good
weather; it's much too beautiful to waste under a sweatshirt.
</P>
<P>
   That was the day Tab Ramos' eye socket was bashed in by an ugly
elbow from Leonardo, an otherwise reputable Brazilian regular. That
was the day the United States could not mount an offense even after
Leonardo was banished with a red card, and was beaten, 1-0, in the
men's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that fledgling capitalists at Stanford will be
vending more T-shirts Sunday just like my precious souvenir. All
they would have to do is change the year to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Stanford will be jumping, and the T-shirts will
commemorate the semifinal of the Women's World Cup, an event
gathering momentum every hour, now that Americans are getting a
glimpse of the four semifinalists, their skill, their charisma.
</P>
<P>
   There is one major difference between 1994 and 1999, however:
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Americans are Brazil, and the Brazilians are
America.
</P>
<P>
   By that I mean the American women are the core of their sport _
the first World Cup champions in 1991, the gold medalists at the
1996 Summer Games, and now the magnet for the 600,000-plus tickets
the organizers have hawked.
</P>
<P>
   They are the center of the universe, at least until kickoff
against the Brazilian women, who are being plucked from the
hillside slums, who are learning the national game, who are the
face of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have been at this sport seriously for only a
decade, but they now have the backlog of instinct and technique
just like the Brazilian men. The way it is with dynasties, they
kill you with their depth.
</P>
<P>
   The early Brazilian men's champions were slightly more dependent
on Pele than this American women's team is carried by Mia Hamm, but
soccer is a total team game, with superb players controlling their
own sector, making the stars look good.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of gigantic corporate marketing hype, Ronaldo was
set up to be the star of the 1998 World Cup, but the most
indispensable player on that runner &UR; - &LR; up Brazil team was Roberto
Carlos, the chunky dynamo with his powerful kicks from offensive
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   This American women's team is as deep, as subtle, as those good
Brazilian men's teams. Hamm was badgered by an excellent German
defender Thursday night; that is part of her job description. For
all the soap opera of the goal scorers, we have not yet mentioned a
player who helped turn around Thursday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Just as grim, flat-topped Dunga was the glue to the 1994
Brazilian men, so Michelle Akers, she of the lion's mane and
similar nature, is the ferocious core of the American women.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows about Akers' injuries and her continuing
struggle with chronic fatigue syndrome. She has been moved back, a
logical move for a weary 33-year-old, but on Thursday, when the
Yanks fell behind early, she insinuated her tall, reconstructed
body in the scrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to bang some heads _ get more physical and take
control of the game _ so I took it upon myself to make some
statements in hopes of firing up the team,'' Akers said Friday,
feeling refreshed.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15th minute, Akers took a header that sailed high, a
warning that the old lady was up front. A minute later, her hard
shot was deflected by a defender, the ball squirting to Tiffeny
Milbrett (who really grows on you, game by game), who directed it
into the net. In the 30th minute, Akers was back on defense,
booting a dangerous ball into the sixth row, to buy some time. A
minute later, she headed the ball upfield. Akers was also whacked
around a few times, nothing new there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to have to take her out at halftime,''
coach Tony DiCicco said Friday, ``but it got a little cooler, and
she is an incredible competitor. I thought she was stronger in the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   That night he had said, ``If you want to see guts personified,
there's Michelle Akers.'' And he added, ``One word that comes to
mind every time I think of Michelle Akers, and it's `Champion.'''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Akers will be a literal champion
again. The Brazilian men do not win all the time, and besides,
either Norway or China will be in the women's final.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, it is Brazil against the United States, five years
later. All you vendors on the Stanford campus, I want to buy an XL
T-shirt, one with the Stars and Stripes and that Brazilian globe on
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
