<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     07-03 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SAMPRAS, WHO NEVER WENT AWAY, VS. AGASSI, WHO'S BACK
AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The pigeon appeared just about the time Tim
Henman was trying to prove he wasn't one himself. Pete Sampras,
down a set, on serve at 4-3 in the second, was beginning to find
the range. Naturally, the bird landed on Henman's side of the
scarred lawn, and scampered about, like a bouncing volley, from the
ball boy's clutches.
</P>
<P>
   The Center Court partisans thought this funny, failing to note
the ominous sign, that Henman was about to assume the role. He
barely held serve in the eighth game. He double-faulted on set
point in the 10th game. He lost his first service game in the third
set and Sampras was soon back in his accustomed position, the
Wimbledon final, where he will find Andre Agassi, that strangest of
tennis birds.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits have had to endure English pigeons for decades, which
is why the local sports pages have been overdosing on Henman, along
with the cricket results against New Zealand. Forget the Women's
World Cup _ unfortunately, it's only a rumor here.
</P>
<P>
   And as for the stunning news regarding Alexandra Stevenson and
her newly identified biological father, we might as well be talking
about Dr. Kevorkian. The tabloids prefer the local hook, and
Michael Douglas happens to be running around town with a British
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   The Stevenson angle died, anyway, when Lindsay Davenport crushed
the 18-year-old qualifier Saturday in straight sets, to set up a
women's final against the seven-time champion, Steffi Graf. That's
three Americans, including an all-Yank men's final, on the fourth
of July. ``An experience, a good scene,'' Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge for American tennis,'' Agassi said, in a serene, almost
dream-like state, after wearing out Pat Rafter from the baseline in
straight sets. ``It was starting to get discouraging not having the
American guys at the end of these events.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is going for a men's record sixth Wimbledon and a
record-tying 12th Grand Slam title against Agassi, the all-time
champion of reinvention. Until Agassi appeared in maybe the best
shape he's ever been in and won the French Open last month, people
had every right to believe he was done as a serious Grand Slam
threat. Now the baseline slugger with the happy feet, long known by
some colleagues as Andre Boy, seems, at 29, to have finally become
a man.
</P>
<P>
   His athletic bar mitzvah occurred two years ago on the
Challenger Circuit, or the tennis bush leagues. That's where Agassi
went to re-learn the art of competing, of caring, at the time his
career was a boulder on the edge of a cliff. The results are
present and accounted for in his media guide profile, right there
with his victories in each of the Slams: runner-up in Las Vegas, to
Christian Vinck. Winner in Burbank, over Sargis Sargsian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of great memories throughout my career and I have
to say playing the Challengers are some of them,'' Agassi said.
``It reflected a time in my career that I was making a statement,
not only to everyone, but to myself that it was something really
important to me, that I still wanted to play. In hindsight, I'm
proud I went through it, but I don't advise it to anybody. It's a
long way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing the role of the villainous gunslinger against Henman is
one thing. But it has to rankle Sampras how Agassi has been able to
drop in and out and back into contention, with people always so
doggone thrilled to have him back. Sampras, meanwhile, has kept his
nose to the grindstone, dropping Grand Slam victories into his
tennis bag as he would his racquets. He's finished the last six
years as No. 1 in the ranking, but it was as if Agassi turned the
light back on in American men's tennis by winning the French.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else to say outside I have a hard time
believing it still,'' Agassi said, playing right into the
myth-makers' hands.
</P>
<P>
   What Agassi's latest emergence suggests is that the computer
rankings _ Sampras starts Sunday as No. 1 but won't be after it's
over, win or lose _ should be junked. Before departing Wimbledon
for the rest of his life, Boris Becker said the one thing he would
most want changed is the indecipherable system that makes
globetrotting drones of players, more concerned with compiling
points than with entertaining fans.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that John McEnroe, Bjorn Borg and Mats
Wilander, among others, did most of their winning before 25. These
aren't team-sport athletes, who began serious play at 14 or 16.
Bouncing on and off the tour, the way Agassi has for years, makes
perfect sense for a man in his 20s whose life has been spent
``striking the ball with conviction,'' to borrow an Agassi-ism from
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, it turns out, wasn't wasting his talent as much as he
was unwittingly preserving it. Is it really seven years since he
won this tournament and fell face down in the grass, apparently on
his brother's cue? The Agassi who dismissed Rafter and takes aim at
Sampras' serve on Sunday is better than the one who outlasted Goran
Ivanisevic. Good as Sampras is on grass, there have been recent
signs of slippage, though he hasn't quite sunk to the level of his
first pro match against Agassi, a decade ago in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six-one, 6-1, he couldn't hit a ball in the court,'' Agassi
said. ``I thought he stunk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did,'' Sampras agreed. ``Believe me, I wasn't very good at
that point.''
</P>
<P>
   They've come a long way since then, on different paths, and here
they are. The Wimbledon final, on the fourth of July. No pigeons on
Center Court on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
