<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOURDEFRANCE-BOARDMAN     07-03 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-BOARDMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ENGLAND'S BOARDMAN, RAIN IS THE ENEMY AS TOUR BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LE PUY DU FOU, France _ The eight other riders in his Credit
Agricole team were out training on back roads all over the Vendee
region, but Chris Boardman was interested in only a small stretch
of pavement. It measures 6.8 kilometers, or about 4 miles, and he
pronounced it acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not as bad as I thought,'' Boardman, an English rider, said
Friday after he had returned from his reconnaissance of the course
for the prologue that opened the 86th Tour de France on Saturday.
``Apart from one climb, one hurdle to get over, it's perfect.
Beautiful surface, too, no real hard turns, nothing technical.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused. ``Unless, of course, it rains,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boardman is the king of the prologues, both in the Tour and
other races. The world record-holder in the one-hour race against
the clock (35 miles), he has the perfect aerodynamic position, the
focus and the power to dominate these solitary races _ unless it
rains.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he went all out in a rainy Tour prologue in Brittany,
skidded on a turn and crashed, fracturing his right leg and heel
and ending his season. The next year, when the race started in rain
again, this time in the Netherlands, he rode conservatively and was
happy with a top 10 placing.
</P>
<P>
   The weather forecast for the prologue is possible rain, which
would be welcome to everybody roasting in 90-degree heat except
Boardman. ``That crash left definite scars on my time-trialing
ability in the rain,'' he said. In dry conditions, he won the Tour
prologues, and the overall leader's yellow jersey at the start, in
1994, 1997 and 1998. ``On paper I'm the favorite,'' he said, not
immodestly. ``But I'm trying not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boardman has often been accused of overthinking a race. Last
year, at the start in Dublin, Ireland, he spoke despairingly of his
chances beforehand, then won easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I surprised everybody,'' he said, ``myself most.''
</P>
<P>
   The course here, in farm country just outside the medieval town
of Le Puy du Fou, was used in the prologue of the 1993 Tour, a race
Boardman missed because he had not yet turned professional. The
winner that time was Miguel Indurain, the Spaniard who won five
consecutive Tours from 1991 through 1995.
</P>
<P>
   On a dry course, Indurain, known then as Big Mig, stormed to a
clocking of 8 minutes 12 seconds 67 hundredths, or 49.8 kilometers
an hour (31 mph). He was 8 seconds faster than his runner-up, Alex
Zuelle, a Swiss then with the ONCE team in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Zuelle is a starter this year under new colors. He moved from
the Festina team and a seven-month suspension for doping to Banesto
in Spain, replacing as its leader Abraham Olano, who moved to ONCE.
(A hefty pay raise comes with each step in these musical chairs and
both men are now near the top salary of $2 million annually.)
</P>
<P>
   Olano and Zuelle are among the favorites in the overall Tour and
the prologue, too, since they perform in time trials almost as well
as Boardman and climb much better than he does. Others with good
chances in the prologue include Lance Armstrong and Bobby Julich,
two Americans who are also among the overall favorites in the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   That list does not include Boardman, whose weakness in the high
mountains is well documented. He has other goals. One is the time
trials, 56.5 kilometers (35 miles) in Metz on July 11 and 57
kilometers in Futuroscope on July 24, the day before the Tour ends
in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are flat,'' he said, ``and could suit me.'' Both are also
almost exactly the distance he covered in setting the world hour
record in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   First, he has to make the scene. Last year he crashed and
dropped out with injuries on the second daily stage in Ireland, and
he has not finished a Tour since 1996. ``That's one of my goals
this year,'' he said. ``Finishing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
