<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MENTALLY-ILL-NYT     07-03 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MENTALLY-ILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY DEBATES PLAN TO FORCE TREATMENT ON THE MENTALLY ILL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Spurred by a succession of violent attacks
committed by people with schizophrenia, lawmakers are moving closer
to an agreement on a plan that would give the courts new powers to
force the mentally ill into treatment against their will.
</P>
<P>
   The plan being considered by legislative leaders from both
parties would allow judges to hospitalize people temporarily if
they have a history of violence or have been hospitalized before
for mental illness and have refused to follow their prescribed
treatment, aides involved in the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 states have involuntary treatment statutes. The plan
being considered in Albany could affect as many as 4,000 people a
year, mostly those who are able to function well while being
treated in a hospital but who fail to take their medicine once they
are released.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has been attacked by some advocates for the mentally
ill, but negotiators for Gov. George Pataki and Democratic
legislative leaders say they have reached agreement on the general
outlines of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the officials say two main questions are still in
dispute. The first is whether the state would oversee and pay for
medicine, counseling and other treatment ordered by the courts. The
second is whether judges would have the power to fine or send to
prison a mental patient who refused to follow a court's orders for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions have been delayed by a protracted fight over the
state budget, which is now nearly 100 days late. Legislative
leaders have said there will be little movement on other issues
until a new budget is passed. ``A lot of progress has been made,''
said James McGuire, the counsel for Pataki. ``We're hopeful that
will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to enact an involuntary treatment law has been prompted
by years of concern among some mental health experts and ordinary
citizens about mentally ill people on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns have been heightened by several recent incidents,
particularly two instances of strangers being shoved in front of
New York City subway trains this year. In each case, the defendant
is a schizophrenic man who had not taken medication. In one case
the victim died, and in the other his legs were cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the legislative proposal say it does nothing to
address a more fundamental problem. They contend that the state has
failed to provide adequate finances for community-based programs,
such as supervised housing and intensive case management, which
they say would help the most seriously mentally ill and also
protect the public. The critics note that the defendant in the
fatal shoving incident, Andrew Goldstein, had tried to get help
before the attack occurred, only to be turned away repeatedly by
the state's mental health system.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the proposal contend that it is often the only way
to deal with mental patients who are so gravely ill that they
refuse to follow treatment orders. ``The solution we are seeking
keeps the streets safer and keeps the mentally ill safer,'' said
D.J. Jaffe, a board member of the Treatment Advocacy Center in
Manhattan, which supports the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Under current New York law, mentally ill people can be
involuntarily committed briefly in hospitals or longer in mental
institutions only if a judge deems they are a danger to themselves
or others. That standard has been applied in a variety of ways,
though; one person might be committed for neglecting his basic
needs, and another might be committed for a violent act.
</P>
<P>
   Under the outlines of the proposal, a limited list of people _
including a treatment provider, a family member or roommate of a
mentally ill person _ could ask a judge to order a patient to
comply with treatment or be hospitalized, aides involved in the
negotiations said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Negotiators generally agree on the criteria that must be met
before a court can compel mentally ill people to undergo treatment
or commit them to a hospital temporarily. The proposal would apply
to a mentally ill person who has been hospitalized twice in the
last 36 months or has a history of violence.
</P>
<P>
   It would also allow judges to hold patients who refuse to comply
with treatment orders in a hospital for up to 72 hours to determine
whether they need commitment in an institution. The duration of the
commitment would be the same as what current law provides.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are pressing for the legislation to make the state pay
for any court-ordered treatment, a concession to critics of the
bill who say the problem is not so much that mental patients refuse
treatment but that the state's mental-health system is inadequately
financed.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiators for the governor disagree, saying the point of
the legislation is not to provide additional services to mental
patients but to get them to follow the treatment that has already
been prescribed. The governor proposes to make local governments
responsible for overseeing the law.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators also disagree about whether a mental patient should
be held in contempt of court for failing to abide by a treatment
order issued by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's plan would allow a judge to fine or even imprison a
mental patient who refused to follow a treatment order. Democrats
say that approach essentially makes mental illness a crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1550EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
