<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-BRAZIL-STAR-NYT &LR;      07-03 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BRAZIL-STAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S SISSI WILL PUT U.S. ON DEFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see BRAZIL-SOCCER-REVIEW) 
 (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ It did not discourage Sisleide Lima do Amor
when the boys in the streets of Salvador, Brazil, did not want her
to play in their pickup games. Inevitably, she got her way. ``I
owned the ball,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She had learned to play soccer using rolled-up socks, oranges,
bottle caps, even the heads of dolls that her parents had bought
for her. Buy her a ball, her father told her mother. Maybe, then,
she will leave the dolls alone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 32, she is the leading scorer in the Women's World Cup,
a player of liquid grace and stirring precision on free kicks who
has put Brazil into the semifinals on Sunday against the United
States at Stanford Stadium. China will face Norway in the other
semifinal in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other Brazilian players, as her reputation has grown
her name has shrunk. She is known simply as Sissi, a wraithlike
figure who has shaved her head in emulation of her country's
dominant star, Ronaldo, and who wears the No. 10 of her other hero,
Romario.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen minutes into overtime of Thursday's quarterfinal, Sissi
was presented with a free kick 25 yards from the Nigerian goal.
Brazil had lost a 3-0 lead and all of its energy on a muggy night
in suburban Washington, while Nigeria played with a relentless
momentum, its confidence building with each of its three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's playmaker in midfield, Sissi had delivered two assists
in the first half, but she was nowhere to be found in the second.
This is her game, a rhythmic ebb and flow, moments of brilliance
followed by long silences, followed by breathtaking re-emergence.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with her left foot, Sissi stopped in a moment of stunning
accuracy what had seemed to be inevitable triumph for Nigeria. Her
free kick curved and dipped wickedly and nicked the upper inside of
the left post, landing in the one spot where the Nigerian
goalkeeper was vulnerable. Brazil had won, 4-3, and Sissi, her
spirit renewed, sprinted around Jack Kent Cooke Stadium, gesturing
for the cameras, pulling her jersey over her head in weary
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   It was her seventh goal of the World Cup _ ``The goal I will
remember most the rest of my life,'' Sissi said.
</P>
<P>
   A relieved Brazilian coach, Wilson Oliveira Rica, said: ``For
Brazil, Sissi is the best in the world. For us, Sissi is the queen
of soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sissi began the tournament with a hat trick in a 7-1 victory
over Mexico, then added two more goals in a 2-0 victory over Italy.
She even scored one of the goals with her less-reliable right foot,
refuting a coach who had told her ``the only thing my right foot is
good for is getting on the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   She contributed her sixth goal in a 3-3 draw with Germany, then
brought salvation for Brazil in the quarterfinals. In a country
where soccer is a secular religion, Sissi's game is built on a kind
of faith that she will be able to deliver what is needed. A
feathery pass, an inexorable goal. She controls the ball as nimbly
as a magician handles quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might not feel her for a while, but then she'll make a
dangerous pass or a free kick,'' said Lauren Gregg, an American
assistant coach. ``She doesn't have to be involved in every play.
She's got a great sense of what the game needs. Her free kick
ability is among the best in the world. She can win a game with one
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Chastain, an American defender, said: ``Sissi is doing
for this World Cup what every World Cup needs, providing great
skill and flair. It's something girls can look at and emulate. You
don't have to be an American for young girls to look at her and see
that she's a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Fourth of July semifinal comes five years to the day
after Brazil defeated the United States, 1-0, in the second round
of the 1994 men's World Cup at Stanford Stadium. This time,
however, it is the Americans who have the tradition and the favored
status, while emerging Brazil is the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am aware of the significance of this date,'' Sissi said.
``We are hoping we can achieve the same result as the men did.''
</P>
<P>
   As a girl, she said, she sometimes grew frustrated with the
resistance of the boys and took her ball and ran home. But soccer
remained her game, indoors and out. ``Just about anything in the
house, I was able to break it,'' Sissi said.
</P>
<P>
   By 14, she had moved away from home, living in the dormitory of
a professional club team. Since Sissi joined the national team in
1988, women's soccer has catapulted cultural barriers to social
acceptability. Brazil has a women's league, corporate support from
Nike and salaries of up to $8,000 a month for its top stars.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring one goal at the inaugural Women's World Cup in
1991, Brazil finished fourth at the 1996 Summer Olympics and is
considered the most improved team in the world. Still, the interest
in women's soccer does not approach the hysteria surrounding the
men's team.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Zagallo, the coach of the 1998 men's team that lost in the
World Cup final, was ``sitting on a missile,'' said Oliveira Rica,
coach of the women's team. ``I am sitting on a firecracker.''
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup is serving as a redemptive tournament for
Sissi, whose future was in doubt after ankle surgery and who was
dumped from her club team, Sao Paulo, after it finished only third
in the 1998 Brazilian championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this will shut a lot of people up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was surprised by the attention she has been
receiving in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When the Brazilian team walked past the White House while in
Washington for the quarterfinals, she said a Chinese man recognized
her and called out her name. It was beginning to rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me his umbrella,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
