<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      07-03 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS-AGASSI OFFERS A GLAMOUROUS WIMBLEDON FINAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Two men on a history-seeking mission
Saturday chose Wimbledon as the storybook stage to rekindle a
riveting rivalry that had been in remission.
</P>
<P>
   The five-time Wimbledon monarch Pete Sampras, one Grand Slam
title away from catching Roy Emerson's career record dozen, and his
perennial nemesis, Andre Agassi, who zoomed out of oblivion to
capture last month's French Open and Saturday seized Sampras' No. 1
ranking, successfully negotiated their semifinal hurdles Saturday.
They thus earned the privilege of crashing head-on in the final of
the most prestigious Grand Slam tournament in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's an experience I'll never forget, win or lose,''
Sampras said of his imminent clash with the charismatic but erratic
rival he credits with pushing him to become the player who can, if
he stays on track, break virtually every record in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the top-seeded Sampras, who has lost only one
Wimbledon match in seven years and is one victory away from passing
Bjorn Borg to become the only man in this century to collect six
Wimbledons, throttled Britain's Tim Henman, 3-6, 6-4, 6-3, 6-4.
After a stiff start, Sampras limbered up his forehand weapon, the
one Agassi irreverently praises as ``obnoxious,'' and took
advantage of a double fault from Henman at set point in the second
set. From then on, he was in control.
</P>
<P>
   In a rematch of last year's semifinal, Sampras again manhandled
his golfing and doubles partner and denied the host nation _ whose
Center Court fans seemed poised to rush the court and smother the
American ingrate with their Union Jacks as the fourth set faded
away _ its first homespun champion since Fred Perry, immortalized
by the statue that guards Center Court, ruled the roost in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the home country will have to settle for statuary while
the United States, which last monopolized Wimbledon's final in
1993, can thrill to the sight of Sampras and Agassi, who have not
squared off in a Grand Slam final since 1995, locking horns for the
first time in a Wimbledon final. And doing it at the respective
ages of 27 and 29, proof positive that at Wimbledon, it's not just
the pampered grass that's evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Sampras, with a raised fist and a meaningful glint
in his eye, put himself in position for the Wimbledon
``three-peat'' he so covets, particularly since his stock at the
three other slam venues has failed to keep pace with this one, than
Agassi continued to stampede through the draw like a raging bull
and used his vaunted return of serve like a vise to crunch
second-seeded Patrick Rafter in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rafter, the U.S. Open's two-time defending champion,
wore his signature white war paint and ponytail, it was Agassi, now
brandishing a 13-match unbeaten streak in majors, who did all the
menacing in their 7-5, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2 clash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was on for him today; he was very powerful with
everything he did,'' said Rafter, who not only failed in his bid
for a first Wimbledon final but also lost his chance to snag the
No. 1 spot. ``It's the best I've seen him serve, very strong from
the baseline, never really gave me a chance to control the points:
I felt like I was never in those points.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the entrepreneur, Agassi promised he and Sampras would
deliver their own special brand of Fourth of July fireworks when
Wimbledon plays host to its first all-American men's final since
Sampras defeated Jim Courier, then the reigning French Open
champion, to win the first of his five titles six years ago. The
way Agassi sees it, both he and Sampras, who leads their rivalry by
13-10, would probably have an extra fistful of major titles had
they not gotten in each other's way over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate each other; we caused a lot of grief for the other
one's career,'' said Agassi, joking, who is 1-2 against Sampras in
Grand Slam finals with a victory at the 1995 Australian Open and
losses at the 1990 and 1995 U. S. Opens. In their only previous
Wimbledon confrontation, Sampras dethroned Agassi, then this Grand
Slam's defending champion, in their 1993 quarterfinal, 6-2, 6-2,
3-6, 3-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who seems to have used the dissolution of his marriage
to Brooke Shields to light a flame under his competitive instincts,
was quick to enumerate the selling points of a Sunday
Sampras-Agassi match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you get the luxury of seeing a number of things,''
said Agassi, who thrives on his differences, on and off the court,
from Sampras. ``You get to see contrasts in play, contrasts in
personality, you get to see two guys who have basically grown up
together and have somehow managed to bring out the best in each
other's game. The stage is set: It's time to go out there and not
miss our cue.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Agassi missed being a part of occasions like this one,
he demoted himself to the Challenger Circuit in 1997 after falling
to Rafter in the fourth round of the U.S. Open. His ranking dipped
below 100, but his competitive mettle was restoked after he came in
second in a tiny event in his hometown, Las Vegas, and then took
home a title in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't advise it to anybody, dropping to 142 in the world,''
Agassi said. ``It's a long way back.''
</P>
<P>
   But leave it to Agassi, who is nothing if not mercurial, to
savor the climb. Last month at the French Open, Agassi's validation
effort became complete when he won his fourth career major at the
only Grand Slam he had never won before. The victory made him the
first man since Rod Laver, and the fifth man in history, to win all
four Grand Slams. Agassi also went into the record books as the
only man to win his slams on three separate surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hung over my head a lot more than just history,'' Agassi
said about his decade of disappointment at the French, where he was
twice a disgruntled runner-up in 1990 and 1991. Here at the All
England Club, where the top world ranking is already his, Agassi
has set his sights on a second Wimbledon title, a feat that would
make him the first man since Bjorn Borg in 1980 to negotiate the
treacherous transition from a championship on red clay to a title
on the most famous lawn in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi said, ``Tomorrow is a great day for many reasons, and I
guess I need to stop thinking about the history and start thinking
about what an obnoxious forehand that guy has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
