<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO FOOTBALL NOTEBOOK: HAPPY BIRTHDAY, AL; LAWRENCE PHILLIPS
RECONSIDERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Davis, the Oakland Raiders' managing general partner, turns
70 Sunday. And the NFL is thoughtful enough to have already given
him a birthday present: the league's toughest schedule in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders open at Green Bay and then play at Minnesota. Home
against Chicago. At Seattle. Home against Denver. At Buffalo. Home
vs. the Jets, Miami and San Diego. At Denver. Home against Kansas
City and Seattle. At Tennessee. Home against Tampa Bay. At San
Diego and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Playing four of your first six games on the road is bad enough.
But if the Oakland A's make the baseball playoffs _ unlikely, but
not an impossibility _ the first Broncos game might be played at
Denver and would require five of Oakland's first six games to be on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   And here is a nice gesture: Oakland's last two games, both on
the road, will be sandwiched around Christmas and New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's 1999 opponents had a .570 winning percentage last
season. The Jets and Tampa Bay face teams with the second-highest
average, .539. Denver, which won the Super Bowl, ranks fourth in
strength of schedule, with its opponents averaging .535. Atlanta,
which lost the Super Bowl, ranks 18th (.492 opponents' average).
</P>
<P>
   For Oakland, an 8-8 team a year ago, it's a very rough road.
</P>
<P>
   Happy birthday, Al.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips Isn't Through
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Phillips is back from Europe and on the minds of a few
NFL teams. Phillips, a running back, had his troubles with the Rams
and Dolphins and was cut before last season. His reputation as a
problem child persists in and out of football.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, though, played well in NFL Europe this spring and NFL
teams are considering whether to give him another shot to see if he
can be the productive, slashing, exhilarating runner he was in
college at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Among the candidates:
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay, whose new coach, Ray Rhodes, could scare Phillips
straight. Baltimore, whose offense under new coach Brian Billick
will be suited for Phillips. Kansas City, which is running-back
starved. Oakland, which has always cradled talented, controversial
players. New England (there is a need, but is there a will?).
Detroit (what if Barry Sanders never shows?) And Minnesota, whose
coach, Dennis Green, collects good players and gets them to produce
for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
