<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-FRANCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS MUST MAKE DO WITHOUT FRANCO
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By   JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has been so long since John Franco was seriously
injured that even his wife, Rose, didn't understand what he was
talking about late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I phoned her and said, `I got hurt tonight,' '' said Franco,
who was placed on the 15-day disabled list Saturday for the first
time since 1993. ``She thought I blew a save. I said, `No, I'm
really hurt.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Franco strained the flexor tendon in the middle finger of his
left hand while delivering a pitch in the ninth inning of a game in
which the Mets trailed the Atlanta Braves by 12-0. He was in the
game only because he had not pitched since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine replaced Franco with infielder Matt
Franco once the pitcher had to come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have had Matty start the ninth, as it turns out,''
Valentine said. ``I had the wrong Franco start the ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Franco did not second-guess the decision to use him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to pitch,'' he said. ``I pitched Monday in a 10-4
game. It could have happened in a 2-1 game, too. It's just bad
timing.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing is especially bad considering that the Mets were
facing two more games with the Braves, four games with the Expos
and then three with the Yankees next weekend leading into the
All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-throwing Armando Benitez will assume Franco's role as
closer. Dennis Cook, Turk Wendell and Greg McMichael will probably
share Benitez's setup role. And the left-handed Rigo Beltran was
called up from Class AAA Norfolk to take Franco's place on the
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who has 416 saves in his career _ second in major league
history _ had converted 19 of 20 save opportunities this season and
was tied for third in the league at the time of the injury. That
performance had given him the hope that he would be named to the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had an outside chance,'' said Franco, a four-time
selection, the last time in 1990. ``But I thought I had an outside
chance the last four or five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco will wear a splint on the finger for the next four or
five days. He will also undergo a magnetic resonance imaging test,
probably Tuesday, once the swelling goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Franco said the injury was similar to one Bret Saberhagen had
with the Mets in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like I cracked my knuckle,'' Franco said. ``It was a
pop like that. I can't bend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been worse,'' he said. ``It could have been my
arm or my elbow. But it's still part of pitching. It's still my
pitching hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of depressing,'' he said. ``It's frustrating. You
just scratch your head. The doctors said it will be seven to 10
days before I can pick up a ball again.''
</P>
<P>
   Or sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Franco said he had to turn down a number of fans' requests late
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `What about your other hand?' '' Franco said. ``I
said, `I'm left-handed.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So is Beltran, who arrived at Shea shortly before game time
Saturday _ with a shaved head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone will move up a little toward the end of the game,''
Valentine said, meaning his other relievers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
