<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CORYATT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORYATT RESURFACES AS A COWBOY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ind.)  (mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quentin Coryatt was the No. 2 overall pick in the 1992 National
Football League draft, by Indianapolis. Steve Emtman was that
draft's No. 1 pick, also by the Colts. Emtman and Coryatt, one-two
in '92. Emtman was a monstrous defensive lineman and Coryatt, a
linebacker from Texas A&AMP;M, was speedy and strong, and their blend
of athleticism and savvy was supposed to lift the Colts into
contention.
</P>
<P>
   The first three years with them, the Colts went 9-7, 4-12 and
8-8. Dark days. No playoffs. By 1995 Emtman was gone due to injury,
but Coryatt remained and the Colts saw some sunshine. They scooted
to a 9-7 record and a spree in the playoffs that put them in the
American Football Conference championship game. Indianapolis lost
to Pittsburgh, 20-16, a gnawing defeat one game away from the Super
Bowl. But finally, it seemed, Coryatt and the Colts seemed on the
verge of becoming contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the 1996 season, Coryatt tore 20 percent of the muscle
around his left pectoral. Later in the season he ripped his right
pectoral muscle off the bone. In 1997, he injured his left
shoulder, and before last season the Colts released him. Over these
three seasons, the Colts were 9-7 (losing by 42-14 in the playoffs
to Pittsburgh), 3-13 and 3-13.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt gained tryouts with Chicago and Dallas last year after
his release. No luck. The shoulder simply was not strong enough.
</P>
<P>
   So, Coryatt spent last season out of football. He underwent
reconstructive surgery on his shoulder on Sept. 30 and spent the
fall and off-season in rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt turns 29 on Aug. 1. He has played six NFL seasons. And
now, finally, he is ready for his seventh, in Dallas, where he has
already been anointed as the Cowboys' starter at strong-side
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has blessed me with fortitude,'' Coryatt said recently.
``I've had a rash of injuries and this should be my eighth year. It
will be my seventh if I'm blessed to stay healthy. I have a love
for the game. I've missed it. I was a winner in college and then we
didn't win much with the Colts. And now I'm with a franchise that
is used to playing in Super Bowls. I'm in a place with great
tradition. There is an energy and an attitude here that is
different from most places. I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey, Dallas' head coach, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we brought him in last year, he just couldn't do it,''
Gailey said. ``But then this year we liked what we saw and signed
him right before the draft and now he has been in two minicamps. He
has shown excellent quickness, good instincts to the ball and an
understanding of the game. He is giving us a pass rusher as well as
a nickel pass rusher. He gives us speed at linebacker and we've got
a fast group now that can shrink the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the sidelines don't move. The faster a guy you get, the
more he can overcome mistakes with his speed and get to the ball
carrier and get to loose balls. Quentin is showing all of that and
the intangibles of leadership. We expect him to be here
contributing this year and many years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt, 6 feet 4 inches and 250 pounds, said that the way
Dallas wants him to play linebacker allows him to ``get on my horse
and ride.'' At Indianapolis, he played more of an in-the-gap style
on defense. With the Cowboys, he and linebackers Dexter Coakley
(weak side) and Randall Godfrey (middle) will be more mobile,
either in a contain style (the ball carriers are forced to remain
inside the defense) or an underneath style (the linebackers pursue
quickly enough to force the ball carriers to run laterally).
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys report to training camp on July 25. Their first
preseason game is Aug. 9, a Monday night affair against the
Cleveland Browns in the Hall of Fame game at Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey sees questions. When will Deion Sanders, hampered by a
toe injury, be ready? What about Leon Lett: Does the indefinite
suspension he received for violating the league's substance-abuse
policy mean he will be out for the season? Will the offensive line
work now that it has been shuffled, with Larry Allen moving to left
guard and Flozell Adams in his place at left tackle? Will Raghib
Ismail, the free-agent receiver the Cowboys signed, hit the ground
in full stride?
</P>
<P>
   Also, can Coryatt produce another season like the one he had in
Indianapolis in 1995 when he made 163 tackles? And will his
shoulder hold up?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can get positive answers to those questions, I like our
team,'' Gailey said. ``If it all falls in place, this is really
going to be a good team with a fun offense to watch. I'm going to
take them that Monday morning before our first preseason game to
the Hall of Fame. I want them to see what has been done and what's
possible. Some of them already know. I'm anxious.''
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt is more anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone that stays away from the game for a year can't wait to
get back,'' he said. ``If you get the chance, especially for a
second time, to enjoy what you do, well, that's what life is all
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
