<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER'S BEST PITCH: FOR NOW, HIS BRAINBALL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until he joined the Mets this season, the lasting
memory of Orel Hershiser in Shea Stadium was seeing him warm up in
the Dodgers' bullpen as the fourth game of the 1988 National League
Championship Series stretched past midnight into extra innings.
With a record streak of 59 scoreless innings that season, he was
baseball's best pitcher, but the Mets had a 2-1 series lead,
winning both games that Hershiser had started.
</P>
<P>
   Most pitchers would have waited until their next start, but
there was Hershiser out there in the bullpen that Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay Howell had just been suspended,'' he said, referring to
the closer who had been ejected from the third game for having pine
tar on his fingers in a chilly rain. ``I told Tommy Lasorda, `If
you need me tonight, I'll be your Jay Howell.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers' manager told him, ``No, Bulldog,'' In the
dugout during the 10th inning of a 4-4 tie, Hershiser again
volunteered to go to the bullpen, but Lasorda again told him,
``No.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 11th, Hershiser went to the bullpen on his own, warmed up
and told Mark Cresse, the bullpen coach, to inform Lasorda that he
was ready, And in the 12th inning, with two out and the bases
loaded, he preserved a 5-4 victory that squared the series.
</P>
<P>
   When Hershiser blanked the Mets, 6-0, in the seventh game in Los
Angeles, the Dodgers went to the World Series, where his two
victories dominated the Oakland Athletics in five games.
</P>
<P>
   No pitcher has ever had a year quite like Hershiser did then _
23-8 with a 2.26 ERA and those 59 consecutive scoreless innings,
surpassing Don Drysdale's 1968 streak of 56 innings. He had eight
more consecutive scoreless innings in his 3-0 post-season record.
</P>
<P>
   What did he have then that batters couldn't hit?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a sinking fastball that they knew was coming, but they'd
swing and miss it, or hit it softly,'' he was saying now in the
Mets' clubhouse. ``I had a curveball that was very sharp and was an
above-average major league pitch by itself. I had a four-seam
fastball that didn't sink that I threw to low-ball hitters. And I
had a change-up.''
</P>
<P>
   He had so much faith in his sinking fastball that he threw it
nine out of 10 pitches for ground-ball outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one went through the hole for a single,'' he said, ``I knew
the next one would be for a double play.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night Hershiser, who was with the Indians and the
Giants the four previous seasons, will take his 8-5 record to the
mound at Shea Stadium in the finale of a three-game weekend series
with the Atlanta Braves. What does he have now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a brain,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   And his brainball is now his best pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all those old Dodger pitchers used to come to Vero Beach
for spring training _ Sandy Koufax, Don Drysdale, Johnny Podres,
Larry Sherry, Ron Perranoski _ I'd hear them say, `If I only knew
then what I know now, how good would I have been?' The more I heard
that, the more I wanted to be the youngest, smartest pitcher. I
knew I had to learn myself and learn the game. Some learn one, but
not the other. The combination is where success lies.''
</P>
<P>
   If a pitcher's art is painting the corners of the plate,
Hershiser spoke like an artist selecting colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a palette of pitches,'' he explained. ``From 65 miles
an hour to 100 miles an hour. Extreme movement to erratic movement.
Same speed to changes of speed. And you find winning and losing at
every level. But why do some guys win and some lose?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll hear pitchers say, `I had great stuff and got shelled,'
but you never hear them say, `I had great location and got
shelled.' So you've got to ask yourself, `Who am I today and how do
I use what's on the palette?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But location isn't the only thing,'' he continued. ``If your
pitches are straight with the same speed, you're going to get hit.
Movement and location are more important. I still have that
knowledge, and I still have the guts to evaluate myself honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   But how do his pitches as a Met compare with his 1988 pitches?
</P>
<P>
   ``My sinking fastball still exists,'' he said, ``but it's not as
dominant. They hit it softly on good days; they hit it hard on bad
days. My curveball is still there, but it's not as precise and
sharp. And now I throw a slider. I still throw the four-seam
fastball, but I need to throw it more to set up the sinker.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not the same pitcher, but at 40, he's a winning pitcher
who needs only two victories for 200 as a Hall of Fame candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giants, Cubs, Phillies and Marlins talked to me, and some
of them offered me way more than the Mets did,'' he said, alluding
to his $2 million salary with another $500,000 in incentives. ``But
the Mets were the best fit. And the Mets were a good club with a
chance to win, and with a good infield for my sinker.''
</P>
<P>
   And for his brainball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
