u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CHINA-NORWAY-NYT &LR;      07-03 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CHINA-NORWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA AND NORWAY RENEW SOCCER RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ The goalkeeping of China's Goa Hong and the
scoring prowess of Norway's Ann Kristin Aarones will be the key
factors in Sunday's semifinal between the two powerhouses in
women's soccer. The leaping ability of these two players, who were
both doubtful to be in the tournament because of illness and
injury, could very well determine the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the 10th game between the two teams in a series
that Norway leads by one victory. The game at Foxboro Stadium is
expected to feature China's speed and quickness against Norway's
physical strength and style of long crosses into China's penalty
area with the head of Aarones the target of the long floating
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Aarones had a viral infection that didn't clear up until May and
made the team at the last moment. Goa hurt her back in the 1996
Olympics, which threatened to put an end to her career; but she is
playing with help from a brace she wears around her waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubted whether I was going to be here,'' Aarones said. ``I
played only a couple games before the team was selected. I'm
extremely happy to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Aarones is the tallest player in the Women's
World Cup. At 6 feet, she has dominated action in the air, scoring
several goals on headers. The 31-year-old Goa has been the best
goalkeeper in the tournament, having allowed just two goals in four
games.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates and opponents said Goa's best attribute is her
quickness, but her coach had a lot more to say about Goa, who is
single and envious of her two younger sisters, who are married with
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is not just the quickest,'' Ma Yuanam, the coach of China,
said about Goa. ``Quickness is just one dimension. She is the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with her quickness and tremendous reflexes, Goa can jump
very high, a trait she cultivated as a youngster because she wanted
to be a point guard in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play basketball because I was not afraid of high
balls,'' Goa said after Friday's practice at nearby Babson College
for the clash against Norway. ``I wanted to be a point guard,'' she
said through an interpreter, ``but I ended up as a goalie in
soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the presence of the towering Aarones around her
goal area on set plays like corner kicks would be a distraction to
her, Goa laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can jump high, also,'' she said. ``It's not dangerous for
me,'' she said with a louder laugh before she got serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're physically a strong team,'' Goa said about Norway.
``But we have a defensive system from midfield to defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway has been the most productive team in the tournament with
16 goals in the four games. It is a very well balanced and
experienced team, having reached the semifinals in all three World
Cup tournaments. The Norwegians were also the silver medalists in
the 1966 Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Aarones has been the most productive of the Norwegians in this
tournament with four goals, with only Brazil's Sissi and China's
Sun Wen ahead of her with seven and five goals, respectively.
Aarones seems to get the big goal at the most crucial time for
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows the timing of Aarones' goals better than the
Americans. She scored the only goal in the 1995 World Cup semifinal
against the Americans, who failed to defend the title they won in
China four years earlier because of that goal by Aarones.
Naturally, the precious goal came on a header.
</P>
<P>
   It was Aarones who also scored the precious first goal in the
elimination of Sweden in the quarterfinals last Wednesday that sent
the Norwegians to their third semifinal in as many World Cup
tournaments. That goal by Aarones also came on a header.
</P>
<P>
   China's coach did not hesitate for a moment to answer the
question as to what makes Norway a dangerous team.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 6, and then No. 9 and No. 11,'' Ma said, referring to Hege
Riise, Aarones and Marianne Pettersen, who wear those numbers,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Aarones and Pettersen form a formidable duo of strikers in the
middle of the Norwegian attack. Each can hold the ball well and
wait for the other to make a move into space. Pettersen is right
behind Aarones in scoring with three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Norway has allowed three goals in the tournament, but this time
the Norwegian defense will have to deal with Sun Wen and Jin Yan,
who have combined for eight of China's 14 goals, with Sun scoring
five.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
