</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSHMONEY04-COX     07-03 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHMONEY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush pioneers his way to unprecedented fund raising
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Southern California crowd buzzed into the
Century Plaza ballroom for an evening of coq au vin, chocolate
ecstasy and a less-than-intimate 2,000-person encounter with a
Texan who had their money and wants their votes.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bo Derek and Pat Boone. It was many men with women who
might have been their wives but could have been their daughters. It
was a ballroom packed with people who probably could afford more
than the $1,000 price of admission if allowed by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said George W. Bush fund-raising guru Jack Oliver as
the crowd filed in, ``is going to be wild.''
</P>
<P>
   And a fitting end to a wild four months of fund raising that put
Bush, Oliver and campaign finance chairman Donald Evans in the
record books. No candidate has ever come close to raising this kind
of money _ at least $36.25 million since March 7 _ so quickly, so
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   What's the secret, governor?
</P>
<P>
   ``A wonderful personality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was joking, but there's no doubt that his charisma and
skill as a campaigner have helped the dollars flow. Even though he
hasn't articulated positions on many issues, many Republicans are
so desperate for a winner after eight years of Bill Clinton and Al
Gore that they are willing to open their checkbooks for a candidate
who is likable, attractive, and good on the stump.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, other factors. Bush not only inherited his
father's famous name _ no small asset in the fund-raising game _
but his donor lists, as well. That valuable information has helped
him build a fund-raising infrastructure that is sucking up so much
cash that he may skip federal matching money and the spending
limits that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   But some are troubled by the governor's vast sum of money, the
way it was raised, and the possibility that he won't be bound by
spending limits designed to limit the influence of money in
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has raised so much more than everybody else that we face
the specter of the real decision on who the nominee will be is
being made by funders, not by voters. We've never seen that
before,'' said Larry Makinson of the Washington-based Center for
Responsive Politics, which tracks contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is speaking so loud, so early, that it may speak
louder than voters. This thing may be decided long before Iowa and
New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fund-raising juggernaut is fueled in large part by the
``pioneers,'' supporters who have committed to raising at least
$100,000 apiece, no mean feat considering the $1,000 per person
contribution cap. The Bush campaign won't say how many pioneers
there are, but it has said that 2,500 people promised to raise
$10,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush isn't the first to use a pioneerlike system _ the
members of his father's ``Team 100'' each raised $100,000 for the
Republican Party in 1988 _ he has employed it more effectively than
any presidential candidate before him. Democratic front-runner Al
Gore is using a system similar to the pioneers, but his
fund-raisers are aiming to collect $50,000 each, Gore campaign
spokesman Roger Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush folks, wary of having their fund-raising champion
portrayed as the candidate of big money, downplay the importance of
the pioneers. They note that contributions have come from 75,000
people in all 50 states, and that the average donation was $480,
less than half of the $1,000 limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't dollars,'' Evans said of the contributions.
``These are from the hearts of people who love this country and
care about this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is clear that the pioneers are raising vast
sums of money for Bush _ and government watchdog groups fear the
pioneers aren't all doing it to fulfill their patriotic duty.
Meredith McGehee of the Washington chapter of Common Cause said
many Washington lobbyists are eager to ``bundle'' for Bush so that
if he is elected they can call in their chips for special interest
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is you have powerful Washington insiders who
use their Rolodex and say, `George W. is going to be next
president, so you'd be wise to pony up,' '' McGehee said. She also
noted that the group of Americans that can realistically expect to
raise $100,000 from family and friends is an extremely exclusive
one.
</P>
<P>
   So what sort of person is a pioneer? People like Edison Electric
Institute President Thomas Kuhn, who represents the electric
utility industry in Washington. Kuhn, a classmate of Bush's at
Yale, has helped rally many Washington lobbyists behind the
governor. He said some of the lobbyists, and the CEOs of the
companies they represent, have become pioneers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhn dismissed the idea that the fund-raisers he has recruited
are expecting political influence or access in exchange for their
services. Kuhn said they are impressed with Bush's ``record of
success'' and the broad appeal he demonstrated in two gubernatorial
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a unifier. I think he's proven that he can work on
bipartisan basis,'' Kuhn said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Bush pioneers are oldtimers with long-standing
family ties. For the first three-month reporting period, the
largest single chunk of cash, more than $172,000, came from donors
with ties to the Houston-based law firm of Vinson &AMP; Elkins.
</P>
<P>
   The pioneer at work there is Thomas Marinis, a partner at the
firm and a longtime Bush friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been a friend of George Bush since we were little boys,
and a number of our partners here are close friends of his. We, on
our own, got together and raised a lot of money among our partners,
'' he said. ``It is not anything the firm did as a firm.''
</P>
<P>
   An Austin American-Statesman computer analysis of Bush's
contributions during the first three months of 1999 suggests that
longtime family friends are liking the family more and more. As
many as 750 people who gave money to Bush's father in 1992 have
donated money to the governor. But they're being more generous with
the son than they were the father: The elder Bush raised $815,000
from those donors during the entire 1992 campaign, while the
younger Bush was able to collect $712,000 in just three months.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the pioneers have Bush family ties. Gerald Issa of San
Diego, who makes his money making car alarms, is also a Bush
pioneer. An unsuccessful candidate for the GOP U.S. Senate
nomination in California last year, Issa is now dedicating much of
his time to raising money for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled a satisfied smile as the crowd filled the ballroom at
the Hyatt in La Jolla last Tuesday for a Bush breakfast. This, he
said, is easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are calling me up and saying, `How do I get involved.'
I've never had an easier job,'' he said, noting there were about 80
people in the crowd who were on his list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fairly lucky,'' said Issa. ``I have 300 members of a
Lincoln Club who are Republicans, Probably 200 of those have
given.''
</P>
<P>
   The people behind the Bush money also are folks who claim to be
making their first go-round in big-time politics. People like
Robert Herbold, who sees life from the lofty perch of executive
vice president and chief operating officer of Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush backers were finding their seats at a Silicon Valley
breakfast in Palo Alto last week, Herbold was not shy about talking
about pioneering above and beyond the call of duty.
</P>
<P>
   How much did he bring in for Bush?
</P>
<P>
   ``From the standpoint of what's been reported in the paper this
morning of $36 million, the answer is a fair amount at this
juncture,'' said Herbold, who tags himself as ``a champion in the
northwest part of the country as regards to fund raising'' for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Herbold is among the well-connected whose link to Bush began
before the governor was acknowledging he wanted to be president.
Herbold, who says he has never been politically active, was invited
to Austin by Bush last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an incredible thing to see the public jump so
quickly behind a candidate,'' Herbold said.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, high-techster Steve Papermaster is a pioneer for
Bush. He's been working his business community for nine months as
Bush moved toward a White House race.
</P>
<P>
   Papermaster said he has moved ``several hundred thousand
dollars'' Bush's way. It's a simple matter of networking, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system works by grass-roots spreading the word, talking to
people, calling people on the phone, sending e-mails,'' said
Papermaster, a host of the Palo Alto event. ``We use a lot of
e-mail. It's a great way to spread the word very, very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   And, so far, very successfully. More than 100 people at the Palo
Alto and San Francisco fund-raisers were there at Papermaster's
invitation. Many committed only to paying the $1,000 entry fee to
give Bush a listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over half of them walked away saying he's our guy,''
Papermaster said. ``He closed the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Papermaster is spending a good deal of his time on the Bush
campaign, an effort he said is contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel like if these other intensely busy executives in
the technology industry are willing to spend the time and energy
that they must feel pretty strongly about this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not multilevel marketing, but he said Bush backers tend to
beget more Bush backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Amway,'' said Papermaster. ``It's Bushway.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
