<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-NOTEBOOK-2TAK     07-03 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE AGENTS: WOOING BEGINS IN EARNEST 
JUST BUSINESS WITH THE CBA 
UP FOR A PROMOTION 
MEMORIES OF THE DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the next three weeks or so, Charles Oakley will be a
popular man. Maybe not in the vein of Anfernee Hardaway, Mitch
Richmond and Vin Baker _ All-Stars looking for their next
multimillion-dollar contract. But as one of 187 free agents who
cannot sign a deal until Aug. 1, Oakley is expected to be courted
by several franchises seeking that special, nasty disposition for
their playoff-bound team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning on taking as many trips as possible,'' said
Billy Diamond, the veteran forward's business manager. ``Charles is
looking at it like a high school senior being wooed by colleges.
The nice thing about the NBA is, there's no limit on the amount of
trips you can take. We figure 29 visits is about right. Or 28 _ if
you don't count the Knicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Oakley is not even counting the Knicks out. He would
not mind being a role player in Marcus Camby's shadow, although
that would require working out a sign-and-trade deal with Toronto
because of the Knicks' salary cap situation.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the next month will be hectic for people in
the league trying to build a better team. Teams were permitted to
begin negotiating with free agents as of last Thursday. Chicago,
Toronto and the Los Angeles Clippers are the only teams with
significant room under the salary cap to sign quality free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the league's sign-and-trade clause _ in which the player's
current team can re-sign the player to a lucrative contract with
the idea of moving him for another player or players with similar
salaries _ will most likely be employed often over the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Anfernee Hardaway, warts and all, is still the biggest catch.
Babied to no end in Orlando, he drove Magic officials mad with his
petulant ways the past few years. He and Baker are the most
prominent players to exercise escape clauses in their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   With the Magic giving up Horace Grant while acquiring one
quarter of Seattle's roster on draft night _ Duke's Corey Maggette,
whom the Sonics chose 13th, plus Dale Ellis, Billy Owens and Don
MacLean _ it appears Orlando is preparing for life after Penny.
</P>
<P>
   But the Magic insist Hardaway is still in its plans. Most
likely, he is in the franchise's sign-and-trade plans. Orlando does
not plan to lose Hardaway for nothing the way it did Shaquille
O'Neal to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn ``Doc'' Rivers has gone about building a relationship with
Hardaway after Rivers was named coach last month. The Magic
entertained deals before the draft from Phoenix (Danny Manning, Pat
Garrity) and Minnesota, which was thinking about parting with point
guard Terrell Brandon and its sixth pick.
</P>
<P>
   Portland has also reportedly separately offered Rasheed Wallace
and Isaiah Rider, but it's unclear what the Blazers wanted other
than Hardaway in return.
</P>
<P>
   As for Baker, the Sonics have said they want to re-sign him, but
he is expected to test his market value after a miserable season in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hornacek, John Stockton and Karl Malone are also free
agents, but they all appear locked up in Utah for however long they
want to play together. Same goes for Charles Barkley in Houston,
where the Rockets plan on rewarding Barkley generously in perhaps
his farewell season.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jaren Jackson and Malik Rose are role players for the
Spurs, it seems likely that San Antonio will pay whatever it must
to bring both players back to the championship team.
</P>
<P>
   After drafting Connecticut's Richard Hamilton seventh, the
Wizards will most likely let Calbert Cheaney go and may even move
Richmond in a sign-and-trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   Diamonds in the rough: Shandon Anderson, Michael Curry, Derek
Fisher, Gary Trent and Hersey Hawkins. Hawkins is getting to be
ancient, but he can still fill it up from the perimeter. And as his
former teammate Dale Ellis has proved for a while now, old shooters
don't retire; they just keep on chucking.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see if the Heat keeps Dan Majerle and
Terry Porter, two reliable veterans who could not keep up with the
Knicks' guards in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   As for Oakley, it does not appear he is headed back to Toronto _
especially after the Raptors acquired Antonio Davis from Indiana.
Beyond Chicago or the Clippers, the most obvious places where he
would end up would be the Lakers, Seattle, Miami or Atlanta, all
teams with title aspirations in need of another solid veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not ruling out the Nets, either,'' said Diamond, who
noted that Oakley was not heavily recruited while in high school.
``Hey, Charles is just sitting back and enjoying the attention. The
usual process is they send the company jet out, you tour the
facilities, the arena and the city. Before he went to Virginia
Union, he didn't get a whole lot of interest. This kind of makes up
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just Business With the CBA
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, Isiah Thomas was busy in his Detroit
offices trying to close a deal that would give him outright
ownership of the Continental Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it's merely a former player and current
broadcaster making a huge investment. But beyond the business
ramifications, Thomas' purchase could also be viewed as the first
major step toward the NB A forming a partnership with the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership would not only include using the CBA as an
NBA-sponsored developmental league for potential NBA players, but
it would also help the league implement an age requirement for
players entering the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern and the deputy commissioner, Russ
Granik, have expressed a desire to address the proliferation of
teen-age players entering the league, and Stern has mentioned 20
years old as a possible age limit for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   In addressing their concerns, though, they also indicated the
league was contemplating some sort of minor league system for
players who chose not to attend college, a system that would not
only include basketball opportunities but also nurture young
players about to embark on a pro career.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Thomas, the NBC analyst and former Pistons All-Star who
has spoken to Stern about using the CBA as an exclusive farm system
for NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see the CBA become the NBA's official
developmental league and mirror baseball,'' Thomas said. ``It's a
place where you can develop players, referees, coaches and
experiment with rule changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine-team CBA season runs from November through March. While
it bills itself as the official development league of the NBA,
there is no business connection between the two. Last season, 137
former CBA players appeared on NBA rosters in training camp and the
regular season. Sixty-three players were called up during the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't comment on whether the NBA will go along with it, but
I'd like to present options for them that make the CBA a viable
business opportunity,'' Thomas said. ``I would like to see that
relationship more cemented, so the NBA becomes more of a partner
and we combine all our resources to make basketball better.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Stern's desire to create some sort of league-sponsored
alternative to the NBA before he continues the process of
implementing an age requirement, a joint announcement between both
leagues in the next few weeks would not be a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Up for a Promotion
</P>
<P>
   After handling draft-day duties and being the front man for the
Knicks organization the past week, it would almost be a slight not
to promote Ed Tapscott to the vacant general manager position.
</P>
<P>
   Tapscott, who is the assistant general manager, worked under
Ernie Grunfeld before Grunfeld was relieved of his duties in April.
He knows the college game better than anyone in the organization
and has dealt with many of the league's other general managers the
past few years. Everything points to Tapscott's getting the job.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if the Madison Square Garden president, Dave Checketts,
were to go another direction, the organization could easily
splinter again.
</P>
<P>
   Memories of the Draft
</P>
<P>
   Wally Szczerbiak had his family in attendance for draft night
Wednesday at the MCI Center when he was selected sixth by the
Minnesota Timberwolves. The contingent included his father, Walter,
who once starred for Real Madrid in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Walter's last night at the NBA draft? He attended the 1984 event
as a guest of a friend who worked for the Portland Trail Blazers,
the night the Blazers selected Sam Bowie second and passed on the
greatest player in history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
