<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-COL-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RUMBLING OF REVOLUTION IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Interest in local history is not only alive
and kicking here, it's yelling, calling names and bringing
lawsuits, just in time for Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of this fight is a band of insurgents who are trying
to wrest control of the 98-year-old Stamford Historical Society
from leaders they liken to King George III _ old, hidebound,
autocratic and dismissive of new ideas. Without a revolution, they
say, the society will go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like dropping tea into Boston Harbor,'' said Patricia
Kane, 56, a lawyer and the leader of the insurgents, who has been
on the society's board for a year, ``because if you push people too
hard, they start to push back. And if we don't start pushing, we
won't have a historical society.''
</P>
<P>
   Humbug! the society's leadership says. ``This is really nothing
but an effort by a group to take control because they think that
this board of, well, fairly senior-citizen leadership is old and
will be a pushover,'' said Ishier Jacobson, 77, a retired
utility-company chairman and a member of the society's powerful
executive committee. ``I think we have shown that we are not
pushovers.''
</P>
<P>
   George Washington may or may not have slept here but, according
to the society, he did have breakfast at Webb's Tavern, on what is
now Bank Street, in 1789. And although Stamford patriots never
threw tea in Stamford's shallow harbor, they did protest the Stamp
Act by burning a consignment of bohea tea in Atlantic Square.
</P>
<P>
   If the two sides in the historical-society fight agree on
anything, it is that history from the Revolution on is a big deal
to New Englanders, and that control of its repository is worth
fighting for, especially in an old city that is rapidly changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a community of new people, new people coming every
day,'' Jacobson said, ``and the one thing we can do as a society is
give children a feeling of roots, whether they came from Nevada or
Honduras or wherever. If you do enough of that, then you help give
people the feeling that they are part of this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kane owns the third-oldest house in Stamford, an immaculate
colonial from 1721 on High Ridge Road, and she has no argument with
the society's mission, only with its management. The $1.2 million
the society had in its general fund six years ago has shrunk to
$640,000, she notes. If the trend continues, she says, the society
will go broke, but Jacobson maintains that new contributions will
keep the balance up.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement broke out into open catcalls and chaos on June
14, when Ms. Kane and several dozen allies took over the annual
nominating meetings and, by offering nominations from the floor and
voting on them, added 18 new members to the board of directors,
doubling its size. Or so they say.
</P>
<P>
   Walter H. Wheeler III, 76, the president of the society,
maintained that floor nominations were illegal, and that most of
the rebels, having joined only recently with cut-rate, $10
six-month memberships, were ineligible to vote anyway. He adjourned
the meeting, but the rebels maintain they are the new board, or
part of the old one, or something in between.
</P>
<P>
   Now the city of Stamford has frozen a $10,000 donation to the
society until some sort of peace is made, and Pitney Bowes, an
office-equipment company founded in Stamford by Wheeler's ancestors
that is a longtime supporter of the society, is also critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bylaws or no bylaws, I have a general distrust of any
organization that isn't willing to consider nominations from the
floor,'' Polly O'Brien, the company's director of community
affairs, wrote to Wheeler last week.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler, a yachtsman, was said to be teaching sailing in the
Adirondacks and could not comment, but Jacobson did. ``She doesn't
know what she's talking about,'' he said. Now the old board has
brought a lawsuit against the new board to force it to stop calling
itself a board, and the whole thing has gone personal. ``Ms. Kane
is ambitious, but she's not very successful as a lawyer,'' Jacobson
said. ``I think this is just something she does.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kane said, ``I can leave the historical society tomorrow and
I'll still have a life, but a lot of people there, it's the single
thing they have, and they're trying to hold onto their niche.''
</P>
</TEXT>
