<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-NEWARK-STADIUM-960     07-03 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-NEWARK-STADIUM-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWARK HAILS BASEBALL'S RETURN, BUT HIGH COST IS RAISING DOUBTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (rk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK _ Groundskeepers painstakingly leveled the clay-orange
dirt around home plate this week, and masons grouted between the
earth-hued blocks at the entrance to the new Riverfront Park
stadium, which is bringing minor league baseball to New Jersey's
largest city for the first time in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here proudly predict that the soldout opening game on
July 16, between the Newark Bears and the Lehigh Valley Black
Diamonds, will be the first of many sellouts that will draw
thousands to the city and enliven its downtown.
</P>
<P>
   They say the park will accelerate Newark's renaissance, which
began in 1997 with the opening of the New Jersey Performing Arts
Center nearby and will continue with a proposed new stadium for the
Nets and the Devils, New Jersey's pro basketball and hockey teams.
</P>
<P>
   What could be wrong this picture?
</P>
<P>
   For one, the 6,000-seat stadium cost $34 million, about 50
percent more than planned. People familiar with the economics of
minor league baseball say it is by far the most expensive minor
league park in the country, built when minor leagues and their
teams are coming and going at a rapid pace. A potential baseball
glut, some industry experts say, makes Newark's expensive ballpark
far from a sure economic bet.
</P>
<P>
   With opening day just two weeks away, city and Essex County
officials are discounting warnings of traffic nightmares as they
work to pin down contracts to provide several thousand parking
spaces, at rates of $3 to $4, near the stadium. Without such
agreements, parking rates within four blocks of the stadium could
easily surpass the $6 to $7 charged during business hours. That
would leave officials hard-pressed to keep their promise of an
affordable trip to the ballpark, where seats cost $6 to $8.
</P>
<P>
   But officials from Mayor Sharpe James to County Executive James
W. Treffinger dismiss the gloomy predictions, saying that the
parking will be in place and the streets equal to the traffic flow.
</P>
<P>
   They said the cost overruns were largely the fault of local
opponents who forced the city to move the stadium from its original
site, a landmark park, to a combination of city-owned and private
parcels at the northern edge of downtown Newark, off McCarter
Highway. This plunged city and county planners into tough
negotiations with the owners of the once-depressed and neglected
properties, who extracted $7 million for the land.
</P>
<P>
   One million dollars was added to the ballpark's cost because
about 15 underground oil storage tanks at the new site had to be
cleaned up. And the regional boom in construction has made labor
more expensive, adding $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost overruns have been overblown and misinterpreted,''
said James, a Democrat, ``and they haven't hurt this investment in
affordable, family entertainment that will change the image of
Newark forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger, a Republican, said he believed that the investment
in the stadium would increase the value of more than 2 million
square feet in nearby office space. If the value of those buildings
rises by a mere 20 percent, county studies have shown, tax revenues
would increase by $1.2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city and county, under a 10-year contract with
the Bears, will get 25 percent of the income from advertising and
concessions, 75 percent of the price of luxury box seats and $1
from every ticket sold.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly run Essex County Improvement Authority, which
financed the stadium, will also get all the proceeds from the sale
of the right to name it. The authority will get 5 percent of the
gross revenues after the team's first $4.75 million, and could get
as much as 20 percent depending on how much more the team makes.
</P>
<P>
   For Treffinger, the stadium also solves a political problem. As
part of the arrangement to move the stadium to the downtown site,
the city allowed construction of a much-needed county jail within
city limits. This not only spared Treffinger the onerous task of
putting the jail elsewhere in the county, but it also eliminated
the imminent threat of a $300 million fine and penalties from a
federal court ruling requiring a plan to relieve overcrowding at
the current jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``These benefits alone make it worth it to build the stadium for
the Bears,'' Treffinger said. ``But beyond that, when we talked
with the New Jersey Nets about their moving from the Meadowlands
and building an arena here, the minor league stadium was a crucial
part of the attraction for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium's cost overruns and the additional burden it places
on taxpayers have drawn fire from the editorial pages of the The
Star-Ledger, which once supported it. Some elected officials who
once backed the stadium have turned critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't do a project like this anywhere in the country
without recognizing the possibility of additional costs, but not 50
percent additional,'' said state Sen. Ronald L. Rice, a former city
councilman who unsuccessfully challenged James' re-election effort
last year.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bears' owner, former New York Yankees catcher Rick
Cerone, such complaints are background noise as he climbs into the
unfinished skyboxes of the stadium. On clear days he can see the
World Trade Center just over the center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 17 years as a player, this was a way to stay in the
game,'' said Cerone, 45, who grew up in Newark and remembers his
late father, Aldo, telling him stories about the Newark Bears and
the Newark Eagles of the old Negro Leagues, which shared Newark's
25,000-seat, Ruppert Stadium until 1950. ``My father saw me start
on this effort before he died three years ago,'' Cerone said, ``and
while they say don't go into business where it is personal, this is
personal.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cerone said that the early tense days and their uncertainties
have given way to fretting about getting the seats installed in
time and whether the shimmering Kentucky bluegrass sod will root
deeply enough before opening day. He said he was less worried now
about the marketing of the team and the stadium, which will draw on
5.4 million people within a 15-mile radius, because he has a
waiting list of corporate customers for advertising signs,
promotional nights and sky boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Riverfront Park has incorporated some of the city's baseball
lore into the design. For example, a bleacher section that
Hallmark, a real estate company, has subsidized as seating for
youth groups from around the city has been called the ``Knothole
Gang'' after the children who used to peer through the holes
drilled in the wooden fence that lined the left field of Ruppert
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the nostalgia the stadium may evoke, there is no
guarantee that it will be an economic home run. Andrew Zimbalist,
an economist at Smith College in Northampton, Mass., who
specializes in the sports business, said public investments in
stadiums, even in well-heeled major league sites, often falter.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he said, a stadium winds up taking entertainment
dollars that had been going to locally owned bowling alleys,
restaurants and movie theaters. Zimbalist said stadiums also
involve maintenance, sanitation and security costs that, along with
the debt service, can mean ``a negative bottom line year after
year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the real risk is the independent minor league, where more
of the teams fail than succeed,'' he said. ``Plus there are six
other independent minor league teams in New Jersey, some from
different leagues, pulling on their market share.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears are part of a boomlet in minor league baseball. They
belong to the independent, six-team Atlantic League, one of the
current crop of five independent minor leagues nationwide with a
total of 48 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Wolf, founder and commissioner of the Northern League, and
president of the company that publishes the minor league baseball
trade magazine Baseball America, said that major league baseball
enjoyed a resurgence in the 1980s with the construction of new
stadiums as economic development vehicles for many cities,
including Baltimore and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The desire for new-stadium buzz filtered down to the 160 cities
that were homes to the minor league farm teams that are affiliated
with major league teams. As a result, he said, in the last decade
80 new minor league stadiums had been built around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Wolf said that there are more cities interested in minor
league baseball than there are major league-affiliated farm teams.
Since 1993, he said, 14 leagues have been started with a total of
66 teams. But Wolf noted that those numbers have been winnowed by
mergers and the tough economics of baseball in small cities.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said that he hoped Newark's team would not suffer because
of the cost of the stadium. ``This is far and away the most
expensive minor league stadium, major league-affiliated or
unaffiliated,'' he said. ``It is too expensive and certainly sets a
new standard for a 6,000-seat stadium that shouldn't be more than
$19 million, not counting land.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the stadium's backers say its prospects look good. A
smiling Cerone on a recent day was visited by people seeking
autographs and business people seeking to discuss deals. Among them
were a group from NorCrown Bank, which has just six branches in
Livingston and South Orange. The bank is trying to decide whether
the stadium will be the site of its first stand-alone ATM.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think a lot of people from Essex County will come this way
and from an advertising point of view, a corporate presence here
for us will be significant and good advertising,'' said Monte
Ehrenkranz, vice president and branch coordinator. ``We just have
to decide whether it's worth the investment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
