<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8485 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-SERB-CHURCH-     07-03 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-SERB-CHURCH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH OF MILOSEVIC'S RISE NOW SENDS MIXED MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating to note that the name Father Sava, who is quoted toward
the end of the story, is CQ at this time.)   
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN with CARLOTTA GALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A handful of black-robed, full-bearded
Serb Orthodox priests bobbed on the edges of a noisy crowd that
assembled last week in the Serb town of Cacak to demand that
President Slobodan Milosevic resign.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, the Rev. Stojan Stokic, a village priest who had
driven more than 150 miles for the rally, showed off the same pious
fury, the same political passion that characterized many Roman
Catholic priests in Poland who more than a decade ago helped the
Solidarity movement topple communism.
</P>
<P>
   To see and hear Stokic was to believe that something fundamental
is changing in the soul of the Serbian Orthodox Church, which
grabbed international attention last month by coming out ahead of
Serb opposition parties and calling on Milosevic to step down.
</P>
<P>
   But Stokic, who said he would preach his anti-Milosevic politics
in his parish on Sunday morning, is still an exception.
</P>
<P>
   The Orthodox Church is both bound by and responsible for the
notion that wherever Serbs live and bury their dead should be part
of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   This is the church that 10 years ago welcomed Milosevic's
violent nationalist land grab in the collapsing Yugoslavia and
whose most senior bishops traveled in the war zones of Croatia and
Bosnia, blessing Serb forces shelling towns like Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Even though its head, Patriarch Pavle, said last week in Kosovo
that the Serb leader's policies are criminal, the church continues
to send mixed signals about what its priests should do in toppling
a president who is indicted as a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Stokic said the war in Kosovo, where Serbs committed atrocities
against Albanians before losing control of territory his church
regards as sacred to Serbs, had changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so ashamed and I am feeling guilty,'' he said.
``Milosevic never mentions that Albanians were killed. He is only
president of the police. It isn't the job of the Orthodox Church to
speak about politics. But now in this terrible time, we must speak
out against this man.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bishop Atanasije, vicar of the patriarchy in Belgrade, the
Yugoslav capital, and a cleric who often speaks for Pavle, said in
an interview: ``The church is not a political body. If the church
has called for Slobodan Milosevic to resign, it is not because the
church is involved in politics, it is out of her own pastoral care
for the people of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking pains to deny news stories that parish priests around
Serbia have been instructed to use Sunday's services as the
beginning of a campaign to teach Serbs about atrocities committed
in their name in Kosovo, the bishop said, ``Those reports have
nothing to do with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It is enough that the church hierarchy has spoken publicly, he
said, adding that in local parishes, priests should stick to the
Gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need for the priests to speak out,'' said
Atanasije, drawing a clear distinction between what the Serbian
Orthodox Church is willing to do here and what the Catholic Church
did in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Roman Catholic Church is allowed to use any means in order
to achieve a good goal,'' the bishop said. ``The Orthodox Church
must always use evangelical means. We cannot say to the people rise
up and throw off your government. We cannot use evil means to
overcome evil. We can say obey the statutes of the law. That's
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decade during which Milosevic has been fomenting ethnic
war in Yugoslavia, the Serbian Orthodox Church has frequently
criticized him and called for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, shortly after the start of the Croatian war, Pavle
accused Milosevic of making Serbs ``victims of communist tyranny''
and called for the creation of a government of national salvation.
The patriarch in 1997 led a procession of more than 100,000 people
into central Belgrade and lent his support to months of
demonstrations during which opposition parties demanded that the
president step down.
</P>
<P>
   But until the patriarch began speaking recently of the ``evil''
he has seen in Kosovo, the focus of church criticism has not been
that Milosevic's government committed atrocities in trying to
create a new Serb empire, but that it has been unsuccessful in
building that larger state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We blame Milosevic not for trying to defend the nation, but
for failing,'' said Atanasije.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its recent statements about Kosovo, Atanasije said the
church is not rethinking the support that many of its senior
priests, including the patriarch himself, gave in blessing Bosnian
Serb forces whose leaders have now been indicted for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   One priest, the Rev. Filaret Micovic, photographed in Bosnia
atop a tank while brandishing a Kalashnikov rifle, was recently
promoted to bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything strange about the presence of a priest
among his troops,'' Atanasije said.
</P>
<P>
   This continuing stream of conflicting messages _ the embrace of
nationalist aspirations but the rejection of Milosevic's savage
means of realizing them _ grows out of the pivotal role that the
church has played for nearly seven centuries in gestating and
defending the idea of what it means to be a Serb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a Serb and being Orthodox mean the same thing,'' said
Mirko Djordjevic, a retired literature professor and the author of
a new book about the church and its ties to Milosevic. ``Our church
itself has generated nationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Under centuries of Ottoman occupation, when the state of Serbia
ceased to exist, it was the church and its myth-making senior
clerics who kept the fires of Serb nationalism burning, and made
honored saints of Serb warriors. Prince Lazar, who led Serb forces
against the Turks in the glorious lost battle of Kosovo in 1389,
was reputed by the same church that made him a saint to have said:
``It is better to die in battle than to live in shame.''
</P>
<P>
   The hold on many Serbs of what the church has always described
as a glorious national past has encouraged Serbs to hope for
another Great Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In realizing the church's long-held dream that all Serbs should
live in the same state, the rise of Milosevic in the late 1980s was
the best news the Serbian Orthodox Church had heard for decades,
Djordjevic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church believed Milosevic was the messiah who had come to
smile on all Serbs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in Bosnia, the bishops openly supported Radovan Karadzic,
blessing his war to lop off part of that former Yugoslav republic
and fuse it to Serbia. Karadzic, leader of the Bosnian Serbs during
the 1992-1995 war, has been indicted for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of Tito's communism, during which the church was
repressed and controlled by the government and some of its vast
properties were confiscated, Milosevic allowed the church to
reclaim its role in Serb society. Priests appeared on
state-controlled television. He pledged to allow religious
education in schools and to return church property, promises later
broken.
</P>
<P>
   But Christian holidays have again become public celebrations in
Serbia and the church in 1989 was allowed to elect a patriarch,
Pavle, who is from Kosovo, without government interference. As
Yugoslavia unraveled and wars began in the early 1990s, Serb
paramilitary leaders _ many of them responsible for atrocities and
wholesale campaigns of theft in Croatia and Bosnia _ invoked the
church as their inspiration for defending Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The warlord Zeljko Raznjatovic, who is known as Arkan and has
been indicted as a war criminal, said publicly that his ``supreme
commander'' was Pavle. Before Arkan's indictment by the war crimes
tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, but after worldwide publicity
about the brutality and greed of his paramilitary fighters,
Orthodox priests officiated at his lavish and very public wedding
in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Djordjevic, regarded as a leading expert on the Serbian church,
says Pavle has been ``shocked'' by the evidence of atrocities that
he has seen in Kosovo since the 11-week war with NATO ended in
early June.
</P>
<P>
   That shock has resulted in what Djordjevic describes as a new
direction for the church, with the patriarch and Bishop Artemije,
the most senior representative of the church in Kosovo, speaking
openly of ``evil'' done by Serbs against Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Artemije took part Friday in a U.N.-sponsored meeting with the
leader of the Kosovo Liberation Army, Hashim Thaci, and other
Albanian leaders. They signed a joint statement condemning war
crimes and crimes against humanity committed against Albanians in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Artemije has long opposed Milosevic but has not often been heard
inside Yugoslavia. Shortly after the NATO bombing began, he made a
proclamation to be read in every church in Kosovo, criticizing what
he called ``pogroms'' against the Albanians. It condemned the
burning of houses and attacking of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read it in our church,'' said Father Sava, an assistant to
Artemije and one of the most outspoken liberal priests in the
church. He admitted that many priests may have chosen not to follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was brave, because of the secret police,'' the priest said.
``And you know we have no free media. Artemije was then attacked by
Serb state media and called a madman.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orthodox Church is not a monolith, he explained, and priests
do not have to obey the patriarch, as members of the Roman Catholic
Church have to obey the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not unified,'' Father Sava said. ``People can have
their own political understanding. There are a lot of deluded
people in the church as well.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade on Friday, Atanasije insisted on steering an
interview away from the matter of the church's new openness about
atrocities committed by Serbs and toward what he described as
foreigners' refusal to give equal time to the abuse of Serbs by
other ethnic groups across Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Westerners tend to close their eyes when the suffering of
Serbs is concerned,'' the bishop said, emphasizing an abiding
tradition in the Orthodox church that sees Serbs as victims of
foreign manipulation. ``What was done in Kosovo, of course, was
evil. But the next question that has to be asked is who committed
evil. The Serbs were not the only actors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
