   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-VALLEY _ NEW MARKET, Va. _ Another evening of baseball
bliss is settling over the Shenandoah Valley. The smell of frying
onions drifts out from the concession stand as the Eagles sing
``Take It Easy'' over the PA system. With Massanutten Mountain
looming behind the outfield fence, college players from across
America warm up on the dusty diamond that has become their field of
dreams. ``This is a once in a lifetime experience _ every kid's
dream,'' said J.C. Bunch, a catcher from Austin, Texas, and Trinity
College. ``The league provides an opportunity to be seen by
scouts.'' But the Shenandoah Valley League offers more than it's
advertised ``Gateway to the Majors.'' Living with families in the
valley's tiny towns, the players get a glimpse of a life they
didn't know existed. ``It's kinda like Mayberry here,'' said
Charlie Wentzky, a pitcher from Anderson, S.C., and the College of
Charleston. ``It's amazing that there are people like this left in
the world.'' (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Localized versions featuring players from Georgia, Austin
and West Palm Beach MOVED Monday, June 22 in (l) lifestyle, (s)
sports and (t) travel categories.
</P>
