<P>
   EYEWITNESS-FREEDOMTRAIN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``The country
was ready to come together,'' recalls Ruth Dukkony, who helped
organize one of the biggest Bicentennial celebrations of all, the
Freedom Train. Crowds everywhere packed platforms and sidings to
catch a glimpse of the rolling exhibition that mixed history,
popular culture and odd bits of Americana. Inside were 510 works of
art, historical artifacts or other exhibits from 35 states (plus
Puerto Rico and Washington, D.C.). It had been Dukkony's job to
persuade the owners to turn them over.(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CEMENTPLANT _ BRANFORD, Fla. _ It's one of those simple,
Deep-South pleasures that country folk take for granted and city
folk may drive hours to enjoy: floating down an ice-cold,
spring-fed river in the heat of summer on a fat rubber tire tube.
Thousands flock each summer to North Florida's Ichetucknee Springs
State Park to do just that, drinking in the unspoiled natural
splendor of a crystal-clear river. But a proposal to build a large
cement plant a few miles away from the river has triggered a
controversy, splitting the small communities that dot the rural
countryside near the Ichetucknee. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN PAROLE PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   The Austin American-Statesman has prepared a package that looks
into the secret workings of the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles.
All files MOVED TUESDAY:
</P>
<P>
   TX-PAROLE-MAIN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He was 21 when, in a flash of
anger, he slammed his 9-month-old niece to the floor because she
was crying. A cracked skull silenced her forever. Involuntary
manslaughter, the jury called it, and gave the man 18 years in
prison for his crime. He has done 10 and, because of ``good time''
laws that speed up the clock on sentences for good behavior, he is
scheduled to walk out of prison in just a few months.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday, three members of the state Board of Pardons
and Paroles sat inside a cluttered conference room in Northwest
Austin, deciding under what conditions the convicted baby-killer
will get his freedom. Same for a rapist with a preference for
14-year-old girls, a trigger-happy gangster who almost killed two
people, a longtime burglar who beat his girlfriend, a schizophrenic
arsonist and more than 100 other imprisoned criminals with
penchants for violence or sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 1: Protect the public
</P>
<P>
   But the public is nowhere to be found. The deliberations take
place behind closed doors in an increasingly controversial process
by which Texas decides which criminals should be freed early from
prison, under what rules those convicts must live, even whether
execution-bound convicts should receive clemency.
</P>
<P>
   It is also Texas' biggest state secret. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TX-PAROLE-FILES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Not only are the meetings
secret where Texas paroles are decided, but so are the case files
that guide those decisions. Listing of information that would be
available. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TX-PAROLE-MEMBERS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Board of Pardons
and Paroles has 18 members, including the chairman. Annual salary
for the full-time job is $62,500; $65,000 for the chairman. All are
gubernatorial appointees who serve six-year terms. List of the
board members. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TX-PAROLE-COMPUTERS _ HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ It's just a laptop
computer, parole board member Rissie Owens says, ``and I haven't
really even learned how to use it yet.'' But officials hope it will
soon take Texas' archaic record-keeping system for parole and
clemency cases into the modern era.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has been repeatedly criticized for its antiquated
and, at times, sloppy record keeping and is poised to go online
within two years.
</P>
<P>
   TX-PAROLE-FIGURES _ Stats on numbers of prisoners released.
(Ward, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TX-PAROLE-CASES _ Thanks to the lock of secrecy on Texas' parole
files, law-abiding Texans normally can't see what parole board
members consider in deciding which criminals to free early from
prison _ and which ones to keep in. In an exclusive glimpse behind
those closed doors, parole officials recently allowed the
American-Statesman to review several case files _ with names
deleted so as not to violate state law. We culled through the files
and listed the information parole board members said was pertinent
to their decision. Read the facts. Cast your vote and then see how
the real board members decided each one. Your options are to
parole, deny parole, make convict serve all time remaining, or
review the case again in several month. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
