<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WHAT IS THIS, THE TAMMY WYNETTE STRATEGY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I made the major pitch, but Mrs. Clinton chimed in.'' _ Sen.
Charles Schumer on Hillary Clinton's role in a White House meeting
about aid to New York hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton is making a pilgrimage to Oneonta, N.Y., this
week to ``visit'' with Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the man she hopes
to replace in the Senate. If establishing an exploratory committee,
renting office space and hiring staff are not enough proof that
Mrs. Clinton is a serious candidate, this trip ought to do it.
Nobody travels to Oneonta without a really, really good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, last week there were signs that Mrs. Clinton has
not quite made the mental shift to candidate mode. She is stuck in
political limbo, with one foot on the campaign trail and the other
in the safe-house world of first-ladydom.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schumer, who will be the senior senator from New York
when Moynihan retires, set up a White House meeting last Thursday
on the effect of the president's Medicare plan on teaching
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   New York has a number of these facilities, which spend a lot of
money caring for poor people and training new doctors. In the old
days, the teaching hospitals paid for these worthy but not
particularly remunerative activities by overcharging the patients
who were able to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the health-care system has allegedly become efficient,
the hospitals are in danger of losing their shirts. Naturally,
Schumer is concerned. So is Dennis Rivera, the head of the hospital
workers union and a major player in New York Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   This was an excellent opportunity for Mrs. Clinton to
demonstrate that she is a politician separate and distinct from her
husband. The issue at hand, after all, is a pricey but technical
detail in a general policy that Schumer, and virtually every other
Democrat, endorses.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton's aides wanted everybody to know that she came
to the meeting at Schumer's invitation, and that her interest in
teaching hospitals was longstanding and not at all restricted to
the ones in New York. They described, in a word, the attitude of a
first lady, not a Senate candidate steeped in the parochial
interests of the state where she may someday buy a home and
register to vote.
</P>
<P>
   And what did Mrs. Clinton do during the meeting itself? She
chimed in. Chiming is not as degrading as pouring tea or baking
cookies, but it does not exactly convey the impression of
forcefulness you want to give as a potential U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   The White House meeting had several purposes, including a
perfectly natural desire to pander to the powerful Rivera. The
participants may also have wanted to exchange information on the
problems of the teaching hospitals, although to tell the truth
everybody in the room was already pretty well grounded.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing it did not need to do was to make Schumer look
good. The man is not up for re-election for more than five years.
In the six months he has been in office, he has been on the evening
news about as often as Tom Brokaw, thanks to his position as a
leading advocate of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, he tills his political truck garden so diligently
that Democrats in the remotest corners of upstate New York see him
more regularly than they see their dentists. ``Tell him enough
already,'' one of them pleaded recently.
</P>
<P>
   Why then, was Schumer describing himself as the star of the
meeting and putting Mrs. Clinton in a subsidiary role as yes-woman?
Granted, anybody who knows Schumer knows that it is frequently
difficult to get a word in edgewise. But if Mrs. Clinton had wanted
to be depicted as the chief champion of New York's interests, he
and the other participants would have said as much, even if she had
actually done nothing more than nod her head and order sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first lady went because she's concerned and she conveyed
those concerns in the meeting,'' said Howard Wolfson, press
secretary for the exploratory committee. Asked whether Mrs. Clinton
was participating in the meeting as first lady or Senate candidate,
he added, ``She's always the first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's White House spokeswoman, agreed
that her employer attended the meeting in first lady mode, but
noted that she would trek up to Oneonta as a potential candidate.
As for the teaching hospitals, Ms. Berry said, ``she was glad to
come and hear what she knew to be grave concerns on these
institutions' part.'' You will note that Mrs. Clinton has now been
assigned a purely auditory role in the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Deconstructing descriptions of a routine White House meeting
would be picky indeed if Mrs. Clinton's whole history was not one
of confusion over where her identity of wife ends and her own
political persona begins.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of women who originally liked the idea of first lady as a
policy-driven political partner were chagrined when Mrs. Clinton
turned out to be most popular and successful when she played the
role of supportive wife. No doubt Hillary Clinton felt pretty much
the same, and she may be frightened of letting go of that
restrictive but comfortable identity.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the political big time we are talking about, and if
Mrs. Clinton wants to run for office, she had better let go and
strike out on her own. Senators are not supposed to chime in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
