<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-STRIPERS-NYT     07-03 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-STRIPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS COLUMN: A THOUSAND-MILE SEARCH FOR STRIPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER KAMINSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In angling there are few second chances _ for the angler or the
fish. The striped bass, the supreme flyrod gamefish of the shallow
waters of the Northeast, is a happy exception.
</P>
<P>
   Like most marine resources, stripers were, until recently,
treated as if they were a harvest-at-will species that would
naturally replenish itself. Under the right circumstances that is
true, but only if female stripers are allowed to reach sexual
maturity at the age of 8 years.
</P>
<P>
   When low size limits and unlimited bag limits led to a depletion
of these crucial Year 8 stripers, the Chesapeake Bay fishery, by
far the region's largest, nearly disappeared. In response, strict
controls designed to insure that the Chesapeake females were able
to reproduce sparked a dramatic comeback.
</P>
<P>
   This policy had a halo effect on Hudson River fish because they
experience their greatest mortality when they descend to the ocean
in late spring (the same protected waters that the Chesapeake fish
migrate to in the warmer months). According to Kathy Hattala, a New
York state fisheries biologist, the striper population boomed.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the cleaning up of New York Harbor waters and with
it, the removal of the pollution block that kept young stripers
from moving to nurseries in Jamaica and Raritan Bays, as well as
the western Long Island Sound, and you have the current bumper
crop.
</P>
<P>
   I saw living, breathing, breeding proof of this in a
thousand-mile striper pilgrimage that I made this season. It began
in early May when my brother Don and I drove down to the tidal
flats where the Susquehanna River empties into Chesapeake Bay and
ended last week on Long Island's Great South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   That first trip, on a windy, cast-defeating day on the
Chesapeake, we joined the flyrod guide Joe Evans for an
experimental one-week window during the spawning season. Lured by a
friend's report of a 30-pounder sighted, hooked and landed in
shallow water, we had no such luck although we did catch and
release a dozen smaller stripers along the rocky shores of the bay.
But for the most part, the stripers were more interested in
spawning than eating.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop was a wadeable flat 300 miles north, just upriver from
the Kingston-Rhinecliff Bridge in New York state. The Catskills
flyrod guide Ray Ottulich had spent a good part of the off-season
researching the striper possibilities in the river.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm late May day we tramped through woods full of new
leaves and flowering dogwood. The Adirondacks guide Tom Akstens
joined us, and we waded out into the river and began casting
Clouser Minnows. We spent about five hours fishing the end of the
swing in the tide without a hit. I was losing faith.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Hattala showed up leading a two-boat expedition of
scientists and volunteers. Would we mind, she asked, if her team
set out their haul seine where we were fishing? We offered to help
and within 10 minutes we had pulled stripers up to 25 pounds from
the same water we had fished. One big female had bloody sides as a
result of insistent males rubbing up against her _ a sure sign of
spawning activity.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was time to head for the ocean, I figured. Surely, the
Chesapeake fish had begun to make their move to their summer range
along the mid-Atlantic coast. And on a hot, early June day, I drove
to Staten Island and joined Franck Crescitelli and Dino Torinos on
their flyfishing boat out of Great Kills Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Brigades of screaming gulls slashing and diving along a tidal
rip opposite Coney Island caught our attention. We eased into the
feathery mayhem and were soon fast to bluefish. We backed off from
the school and put on sinking lines. Stripers, especially big ones,
are often found on the periphery of schools of blues. It's nice
when angling logic and reality move in tandem. Within an hour we
had caught a half-dozen stripers _ the largest a 29-incher.
</P>
<P>
   I knew it wouldn't be long before I heard reports of big
stripers showing up on the white sandy flats of Long Island, my
favorite place for striper flyrodding. Last week Barry Kanavy
called from his bay house in the Great South Bay to confirm my
intuition. I invited Alan Harding, a Carroll Gardens chef, to come
along and to bring his spices.
</P>
<P>
   I had hoped for a sunny day that would allow for sight fishing.
Of course, heavy overcast and fog enveloped us. Still, we were
there and so were the fish. A bayman _ his buckets full of clams _
gestured that there were fish farther down the channel between two
grassy islands. We quickly caught two bluefish, assuring dinner.
</P>
<P>
   I tied on a popping bug as Kanavy poled us along a productive
flat. A striper lunged at my fly, looking like a large linebacker
about to engulf a small quarterback. When I missed, Kanavy
chastised me for lifting the rod rather than striking with my line
hand first.
</P>
<P>
   I double-hauled hard and put the fly back in the same spot and
gave it a few loud pops. The striper came for it again. I drove the
hook home and he was on. That's what I mean by stripers being a
second-chance fish. Once you interest them, you can tease them back
for a another look if they haven't felt the point of the hook.
Then, Harding, who hadn't been fishing since he was a boy, hooked a
beautiful 30-inch striper on spinning tackle. We kept that one for
the chef.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the bay house we opened a cold chablis, Kanavy put Van
Morrison on the boom box and we set about making a meal. Harding
took the helm at the stove, while Kanavy's brother-in-law Phil
Potak, a playwright, filled two buckets with salt water so the
clams could purge themselves of mud. As an appetizer, Harding
dusted the bluefish with crushed peanuts and wrapped the cooked
meat in rice crepes filled with fresh savoy cabbage, lemongrass
pickle and cellophane noodles. It was to my knowledge the world's
first South Vietnamese-style summer rolls made with bluefish.
</P>
<P>
   We dunked them in a mix of fermented fish sauce, chili paste and
sugar cane juice that could wake the dead. More wine followed, then
the striper, which was simply pan-fried. After dinner, Phil read
from his plays and I dozed off to sleep which, I realized the next
morning, was the first time that I had fallen asleep to the sound
of a man reading stories since I was 5 years old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
