poor women for a post-welfare life, Lashanda Washington, 20,
prepares for the changes that will come after she stops receiving
welfare. Ms. Washington, 20, like countless other young
central-city women, has found her efforts to build a new life
complicated by family bonds more powerful than many policy-makers
understand. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MILWAUKEE -- July 3, 1999 -- WELFARE-FAMILIES-3, 7-3 --
Lashanda Washington, 20, has been caught in conflicting roles as
she tries to leave welfare, while caring for her son, Jermaine, 2,
and an often abusive mother. Loving a troubled relative to death, a
struggle often forgotten in policy forums, is one of the most
common situations poor women face when leaving the welfare rolls.
``My mama is like everything to me,'' says the younger Ms.
Washington. ``I love my mama to death.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York
