<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8501 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      07-03 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Sunday,
July 4. If you have any questions, please call Patricia Hardin on
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4753.
</P>
<P>
   MOLD-ILLNESSES-2TAKES (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ Stachybotrys atra is
a greenish-black, slimy mold that thrives on water and construction
materials such as wallboard that contain cellulose. Evidence is
mounting that the mold might be a health threat responsible for a
host of hard-to-diagnose medical problems. Researchers have
identified the mold as the likely cause of potentially fatal lung
bleeding in infants. They've linked it to asthma and other
respiratory problems. And they've named it a suspect in
sick-building and chronic-fatigue syndromes. By ALAN BAVLEY. Story
will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-CLASSES (Undated) _ Kansas and Missouri together will
receive $30 million from the U.S. Department of Education to hire
more than 700 teachers in a new federal effort to reduce the size
of first-, second- and third-grade classes. The Class Size
Reduction Program is mainly aimed at districts with high levels of
poverty, although suburban and rural districts will receive a cut,
too. By JIM SULLINGER. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   FISHER COLUMN (MEXICO, Mo.) _ Last weekend this community
saluted its angel _ grayish-white muck that turns into a
semi-gelatinous goop when damp, much to the delight of children and
the fuming of back-road motorists. Mexico honored clay. Clay is
common as dirt, maybe more so since it's usually what's under dirt.
Except in Mexico a particular type of clay is king, a substance
that's brought wealth to this part of the state; provided jobs for
generations of residents; helped hurl men into space; and, on a
more down-to-earth note, meant youngsters here have all the clay
they want to play with. By JIM FISHER. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
