<HEADLINE>
IN MEXICO, THEY TAKE QUIET PRIDE IN THEIR FIREBRICK CLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO, Mo. _ Name a product _ sorghum, pumpkins, outhouses _ or
a person _ Mark Twain, Jesse James, Harry S. Truman _ and likely as
not somewhere in Missouri it or they are marked by a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend this community saluted its angel _ grayish-white
muck that turns into a semi-gelatinous goop when damp, much to the
delight of children and the fuming of back-road motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico honored clay.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, that may sound nuts. Clay is common as dirt,
maybe more so since it's usually what's under dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Except in Mexico a particular type of clay is king, a substance
that's brought wealth to this part of the state; provided jobs for
generations of residents; helped hurl men into space; and, on a
more down-to-earth note, meant youngsters here have all the clay
they want to play with.
</P>
<P>
   An even closer look might suggest clay _ the kind that formed in
this part of Missouri 300 million years ago _ could be honored by
more than just residents of this small town. Without it, modern
life would be vastly different _ the mass production of steel,
aluminum, cement, glass and a host of other goods would be nearly
impossible or far more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, what received recognition here were the huge beds
of fire clay that underlie Mexico and a good part of the
surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Mined from open pits, then molded, formed, cast, even sprayed
pneumatically, the fire clay is transformed at plants here into the
refractories that direct and control the tremendous heat needed by
the ```furnaces of industry'' _ from blast furnaces to ships'
boilers, cement kilns to aluminum smelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take away fire clay, and society as we know it goes poof,''
said Charles R. Stribling III, chairman of the board of the
Missouri Military Academy at Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely basic. But most people have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Stribling was walking across the lawn of Presser Hall southeast
of downtown, where the third annual Clay Days U.S.A. was in full
swing.
</P>
<P>
   Tents were on the grounds, and inside them were pottery artists'
creations. There was a demonstration where people could use several
pottery wheels to make bowls and jars and plates on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The only local potter of about a dozen on hand was John
Tsikalas, a native of Greece who taught high school English here
for almost three decades. ``Mr. T.,'' as he is known locally, said
on retirement he jumped into pottery with both feet. His creations
have a Grecian style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, this is great,'' Mr. T. said. ``All these people. And
clay. Clay is our heritage here in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   On the northeast corner of the lawn a group of young people were
building a demonstration kiln out of bricks contributed by Harbison
Walker, formerly A.P. Green Industries, which along with Mexico
Refractories, now National Refractories, made Mexico into the
``Firebrick Capital of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The potters were the best attractions organizers could think
of to tout the observance,'' said Sue Caine, executive vice
president of the Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, fire clay isn't exactly sexy. It's just clay.
And most ordinary people aren't out in their back yards
constructing kilns out of firebrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted was clay to be the centerpiece. And who else
does clay? Potters. So this is about as close as we could get.''
</P>
<P>
   Which apparently was close enough. About 2,000 people showed up
over two days, wandered among the booths and bought some of the
pots, statuary and other wares _ plus souvenirs _ and had a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   Especially the youngsters who were elbow-deep in a huge box of
the fire clay sent over by Harbison Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not as good as what you'd buy at a hobby shop,''
said Becky Erdel, an art teacher at Mexico High School. ``Not for
molding. It's just different. See, there are little grains of rock
in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But kids don't care. Clay is clay to a kid. Just look.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is Erdel's contention that more clay makes happier
kids. Name a better way, she said, to get children absolutely
involved than when they're kneading, pummeling, molding and forming
something out of clay. Clay busies idle hands, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stack, the geologist for Harbison Walker, says the clay
in Audrain and surrounding counties is of an unusual purity that,
once turned into firebrick and its cousins, can sustain extreme
heat and reactive chemical compounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the veins are almost on the surface, some of it is
several feet down,'' said Stack. ``What we take is usually within
20 feet of the surface. Deeper than that and the cost goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, clay has been our oil or gold,'' said Leta Hodge, a
local historian who recently wrote a history of Audrain County.
</P>
<P>
   Fire clay was discovered here in the 1870s, but the industry of
refining and processing it into a salable product began fitfully.
It did not reach its stride until A.P. Green _ who incidentally was
the grandfather of Sen. Kit Bond of Missouri _ bought out an
existing firebrick plant in Mexico. The industry soon copied his
methods of mechanization, use of electricity and new manufacturing
processes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, J.B. Arthur, one of Green's lieutenants, broke away and
started Mexico Refractories Co. Competition between the two
companies was fierce. For years there was an informal rule against
Mexico Refractories employees dating, let alone marrying, an A.P.
Green worker, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Hodge said the long haul from mined clay to finished fire bricks
in naval ship boilers, on the Saturn rockets' launch pads or any of
a thousand other uses seemed to cultivate a conservative streak in
folks here.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here don't flaunt things,'' Hodge said. ``I think in
the last 20 years people have started to look and see what's been
important to their town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always known about the fire clay. We've always
appreciated it. But it's not something broadcast or played up. It
was just here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
