<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8508 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-CLASSES-KAN &LR;      07-03 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-CLASSES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOALS OF FEDERAL EDUCATION DOLLARS ARE MORE TEACHERS, SMALLER
CLASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When school starts in a couple of months, little Johnny's
teacher might be in the classroom on Uncle Sam's dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas and Missouri together will receive $30 million from the
U.S. Department of Education to hire more than 700 teachers in a
new federal effort to reduce the size of first-, second- and
third-grade classes.
</P>
<P>
   The Class Size Reduction Program is mainly aimed at districts
with high levels of poverty, although suburban and rural districts
will receive a cut, too.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say smaller classes result in more individual
attention for students and improved reading skills _ a foundation
for future learning. The goal is an average national classroom size
of 18 students in those early grades.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas education officials said the $9.5 million they expect
should put between 200 and 250 additional teachers into
primary-grade classrooms. Educators in Missouri said the $20.5
million slated for that state should produce about 500 new
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Moe, director of communications for the Missouri State
Teachers Association, said that number wasn't much when you
consider that 60,000 teachers currently work in Missouri public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spread out over 12 grades, the numbers are not that
significant,'' he said. ``But apply those teachers to the early
grades and the impact looks more significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by President Clinton, the Republican-led Congress
approved a spending bill last year that included $1.2 billion for
30,000 new teachers nationwide. Clinton eventually wants 100,000
new teachers at a cost of $11 billion over six years.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies cited by the Department of Education have shown
that a pupil-teacher ratio of 18-to-1 or less improves a student's
ability to learn in the early grades. Those studies are presented
in more detail at the department's Web site, www.ed.gov.
</P>
<P>
   The money appropriated last year began flowing to state
treasuries Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the metropolitan area, schools in Jackson, Clay, Platte and
Cass counties will be eligible for almost $3.5 million, or 17
percent of Missouri's total. The biggest share of area money _ $1.6
million _ will go to the Kansas City, Mo., School District.
</P>
<P>
   Alsia Cunningham, interim director of consolidated federal
programs for the Kansas City, Mo., district, said one new
third-grade teacher would be added in each of 24 schools this fall.
She said efforts to find and hire those teachers began in April.
</P>
<P>
   She said that would reduce the pupil-teacher ratio to 18-to-1 in
those classes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a national teacher shortage, Cunningham said she was
optimistic the new teachers could be found.
</P>
<P>
   The district plans to set aside 15 percent of the money for
staff development and extensive training, because many of these
teachers will be new to the profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to throw them into a situation and leave them
there,'' Cunningham said. ``We want to prepare teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the district wouldn't get to use all of the $1.6
million. She said about $300,000 to $400,000 would have to be set
aside for new teachers in charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   On the Kansas side, the Kansas City, Kan., School District will
receive $929,000 of the $1.86 million scheduled to go to schools in
Johnson, Wyandotte and Leavenworth counties.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Murray, assistant superintendent of personnel in Kansas
City, Kan., said the district planned to add 28 teachers with the
money _ 26 at the elementary level and two in middle school.
</P>
<P>
   She said class sizes in the early grades there currently
averaged about 20 pupils. She said the new teachers should reduce
that number to about 18.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Dennis, assistant education commissioner in Kansas, said
putting a teacher in a classroom took an annual average of $37,000
in salary and benefits. Missouri educators said that was close to
the average cost there.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis said that average cost dropped when applied only to
elementary teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In the Shawnee Mission School District in Kansas, officials
estimate they will add eight to 12 teachers using their $353,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shawnee Mission has 2,100 teachers. The pupil-teacher ratio in
elementary grades there is 17.7 students for each teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Bartkowski, a district spokeswoman, said the goal was to
reduce that ratio to 17-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help us reach that goal,'' she said. ``Every little
bit helps.''
</P>
<P>
   A little bit is the amount many rural districts will be getting.
</P>
<P>
   East Lynne School District in rural Cass County, for example,
has one school building, about 200 children and a principal, Dan
Doerhoff, who doubles as the district superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   The district is scheduled to receive $3,760, which won't even
come close to adding a teacher. The school's largest class is
kindergarten, with 20 students projected for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if there was enough money for another teacher, would I
divide the 20 by two and end up with two classes of 10?'' Doerhoff
asked.
</P>
<P>
   He said the money for East Lynne would be used for staff
development and training.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis said that Kansas lawmakers had talked about using state
money to reduce class sizes but that no measure had passed the
Kansas House or Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians and educators worry that the federal money will
flow for a few years and then stop _ leaving state and local
taxpayers with the responsibility of paying for the federal
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the intent of providing more teachers is on target,
there are challenges facing many schools,'' Missouri Education
Commissioner Robert Bartman said. ``School people are reluctant to
commit to this as their budget item, for example, by hiring a new
staff member during the first year, without some level of comfort
that the money will also be there next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for those school districts scrapped for space, it's also
more difficult to hire teachers anyway. Where are you going to put
them?''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Snowbarger, an Olathe, Kan., Republican, was a member of
Congress last year when the appropriation was approved. Snowbarger
said he voted for the bill, which included many other spending
measures but opposed the money for class-size reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of Kansas City, Kan., which benefits from any federal
program based on a socioeconomic criteria, the rest of the (3rd
Congressional District in Kansas) wasn't likely to gain that much
from it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The current congressman from Kansas' 3rd District, Democrat
Dennis Moore, said he supported the president's efforts to put more
teachers in the classroom and expected a move this year in Congress
to appropriate money for even more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be difficult to predict, however, whether the
U.S. government would continue funding these teachers in future
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's required to take this money,'' he said. ``They have
the option of picking it up or letting it lapse. It's not like an
unfunded mandate. If it proves effective, then I'd be hopeful the
school boards would do everything they could to continue it in the
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
