<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood mystifies New York
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was two years ago this month that Kevin Millwood
found himself on a plane to Atlanta, a minor-league pitcher of
uncertain pedigree wondering if baseball really had a place for
him. As the Braves' season reached the midway point Saturday
afternoon, the same young man was utterly unrecognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood became the Braves' first 10-game winner with a two-hit,
eight-inning performance that compares with anything this staff has
produced this year as the Braves shut out the Mets for the third
consecutive game, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   New York attempts to avert the sweep tonight against John Smoltz
but the second-place Mets have lost four of five to the Braves this
year and stand 4-13 against them the past two seasons. The Braves
lead the division by five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said when we started playing these guys that we wanted to
try and keep them down,'' said Millwood, who has lost just once in
his past 10 starts. ``We don't want to give them any games or let
them get some wind in their sails.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Millwood guy,'' opposing starter Al Leiter said, ``is
definitely nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan made the difference with a two-out, two-run home
run in the fifth, his 16th of the season and 100th of his career.
Eddie Perez added an insurance RBI in the sixth. John Rocker
replaced Millwood after a leadoff walk in the ninth and recorded
his 17th save, stranding two men.
</P>
<P>
   The loss marked the first time in Mets' history they have been
shut out by the same team in three consecutive games. Since New
York's 10-2 win last Friday at Turner Field, the Braves have held
them at a .125 average while outscoring them 27-5.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood (10-4) struck out six while winning his fourth in four
starts. Of his past 40 innings, opponents have gone hitless in 26.
He leads the club in strikeouts with 86.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the best pitching performances I've seen
anywhere this year,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``Anywhere. Against
us, for us, on TV, American League. Anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
