<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker's chances diminished
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Rocker figures he needed one, perhaps two more
saves and drop his ERA a couple of points. The word from San Diego
is it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Though he readily admits his five-run implosion in Montreal on
Tuesday night cost him a chance at making the National League
All-Star team, Rocker has not given up hope. Nor has his manager,
Bobby Cox, who has spoken in his behalf several times in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   However, San Diego's Bruce Bochy, who will manage the NL team,
has intimated John Smoltz is the only Braves pitcher he has under
consideration. That holds even if Smoltz is selected and opts not
to go to save wear on his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before (the Montreal loss), I thought my chances were pretty
good,'' said Rocker, who picked up his 17th save in Saturday's 3-0
victory against the Mets. ``I usually set goals and if I give up a
run, it'll fire me up to try and pitch 10 scoreless innings. And I
think I was on eight scoreless innings until Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been able to throw two more scoreless and get two
more saves, I think that would have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have. But with his ERA up from 1.77 to 2.89 this week,
Rocker admits his candidacy has faltered behind the league's
foremost closers. San Francisco's Robb Nen has four blown saves to
Rocker's three but still leads the league with 21 saves. Houston's
Billy Wagner entered Saturday with 19 saves and a 1.87 ERA. Trevor
Hoffman (20 saves) is a snap choice for his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're up against veterans, you've got to have numbers
that are at least equal if not better,'' Rocker said. ``More often
than not, they're going to go with the veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   The education of Simon
</P>
<P>
   With New York left-hander Al Leiter working, rookie first
baseman Randall Simon was out of the lineup after 15 consecutive
starts that changed his season. During that span, he hit .478 and
is 9-for-15 (.600) on the trip. His average down to .232 on June
13, he enters tonight's game hitting .333.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is new patience at the plate. While the club
will not discourage Simon from customarily swinging at the first
pitch, he has become more selective. After drawing just five walks
in his first 32 games, he has walked seven times in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Where the league was successful at pitching to Simon up and away
out of the strike zone, pitchers are now reconsidering his weak
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pitching me all sorts of ways,'' Simon said.
``Sometime you can see them talking to each other. They're throwing
balls to try and make me chase. I'm just trying to do better. I'm a
good hitter. ... At first, I was swinging at everything. But
playing more makes you adjust to all kinds of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm just looking in one zone and looking for my pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Home run king Hank Aaron was honored before the game as part of
Major League Baseball's 35-year celebration of homer No. 715. The
Mets presented him with a $15,000 check for his Chasing The Dream
Foundation. ... Tough weekend for Andruw Jones. A Brian Hunter foul
ball almost picked him off in the dugout in the fourth inning
Saturday. Friday night, he struck out against emergency reliever
Matt Franco. ``I only take pitchers deep,'' Jones said. ``I don't
take third basemen deep.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
