u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-JULY4GAME04-COX     07-03 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-JULY4GAME04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. defense in good hands with Scurry
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ There have been games where Briana Scurry
looks about as busy as the Maytag repairman, as the U.S. women's
soccer team rolls up lopsided results generally with ease. But when
the American defense breaks down, as it has done frequently during
the Women's World Cup, she comes quickly under siege.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting to such sweeping circumstances is the norm for any
goalkeeper, but Scurry has become adept at handling the escalating
expectations of a U.S. team that lately has shown some signs of
crumbling literally right before her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed Scurry, who earned more attention for running naked
through the streets of Athens after the U.S. won the 1996 Olympic
gold medal than the considerable feats she performed in uniform,
may be at the top of her game.
</P>
<P>
   High-flying Brazil, which meets the U.S. in today's World Cup
semifinal at Stanford Stadium, (4:30 p.m., ESPN) should give Scurry
and her defense perhaps its biggest challenge of the World Cup,
although the Americans will have a huge Independence Day home crowd
of nearly 69,000 solidly in their corner.
</P>
<P>
   They may not notice Scurry until Brazil surges toward her with
its typical fury, but as she has shown before in the World Cup,
there's a wealth of confidence in the U.S. camp that the last line
of defense has never been in better hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Briana is the best goalkeeper here,'' said U.S. coach
Tony DiCicco, himself a former goalkeeper who works with Scurry and
her two backups during every practice. ``I've seen her play
incredible games for us many times before. But she's added so many
more dimensions to her game. She's dominating the penalty area
more, she's more confident in her kicking game, she's reading the
game better. She could be having her best tournament ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's touted scoring trio of Sissi, Pretinha and Katia has
been lethal, and their teammates form perhaps the speediest
starting unit in the World Cup. That has raised more questions
about a U.S. defense that has given up only three goals, but has
been vulnerable early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to respect their speed,'' said defender Joy Fawcett,
who scored the game-winning goal against Germany in the second
half. ``The important thing for us will be to put pressure on them
individually. We can't get caught stepping back.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what happened on Thursday against Germany in the
quarterfinals. Scurry called off defender Brandi Chastain in the
first five minutes when Germany was applying pressure, but perhaps
a moment too late. Chastain made a back pass just as Scurry slid
out to the edge of the penalty box, and the ball passed her as it
rolled into the net for a 1-0 U.S. deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't ever want to have a start like that, no matter who
you're playing,'' Scurry said. ``But I think it might be more
detrimental to be behind to a team like Germany because their
defense is so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry didn't complete the thought, but Brazil's defense
revealed gaping holes in a 4-3 overtime win over Nigeria. After
going up 3-0 early in the second half, Brazil gave up three goals
in the last 27 minutes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Sissi, who leads the World Cup with seven goals,
scored the winner against Nigeria on a well-taken free kick, one of
four she has scored on set pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sissi's difficult to stop,'' DiCicco said. In 94 games, Scurry
has given up 53 goals for a solid 0.60 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. leads Brazil 8-1-1 all time, including a 3-0 win
earlier this spring in Orlando, Fla. ``They're a good team and
they're riding high, but there are weaknesses we feel we can
exploit,'' Scurry said. ``Brazil is a quick-strike team, but we are
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
