<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crowd may aid, hinder the U.S.
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif._ Parades, barbecue, fireworks and World Cup
soccer. Which of these doesn't fit as a July 4 tradition? None of
them, if you're a U.S. team playing Brazil in the World Cup and in
Stanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It has been five years to the day since the Americans played
Brazil tough before losing 1-0 in the second round of the 1994
World Cup, probably still the high-water mark of U.S. men's soccer.
After the game, goalkeeper Tony Meola and teammates ran around the
track, hoisting the American flag and thanking the home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women realize that today's game should generate extra
attention because of the holiday and the stakes involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're incredibly excited to be playing on the Fourth of
July,'' coach Tony DiCicco said. ``The crowds have been great all
along, but we know this one could be the 12th player for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Players agree the pro-American crowd may be even more
enthusiastic, but acknowledge that it could also be a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's any indication of what it's been in the past games,
it's going to be crazy,'' midfielder Michelle Akers said. ``You
want to be in the moment, but on the other hand, you can't get too
carried away with it. It's a very big game, and we've got to
concentrate really hard and stay focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Approaching a sellout
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday morning, more than 67,000 tickets had been sold
for today's doubleheader. After the World Cup match, the San Jose
Clash and D.C. United play in a Major League Soccer regular-season
contest. Stanford Stadium capacity is listed at 69,686 for soccer,
although it holds around 80,000 for football. Women's World Cup
officials said they probably would not open up additional seating.
</P>
<P>
   The other World Cup semifinal also is part of a doubleheader
with the MLS. Before Norway plays China in Foxboro, Mass., tonight,
the New England Revolution plays host to the New York/New Jersey
MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   Move it or lose it
</P>
<P>
   For some unexplained reason, FIFA personnel didn't allow media
more than 10 to 15 minutes of access to the Brazilian players after
a Saturday morning workout at Stanford Stadium, and virtually none
to sign autographs with fans sitting in end-zone bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   When star forward Pretinha was signing autographs for
youngsters, a FIFA attendant grabbed her arm, imploring her to walk
to the team bus. She responded by giving him a backhand that
momentarily kept him at bay before she scribbled out her name a few
more times.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. locker room was open for nearly half an hour after its
late-morning training session, but players were escorted away from
autograph seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Pele won't choose sides
</P>
<P>
   The biggest game ever for Brazil's women's team has made Pele a
proud fan of his countrywomen, but the rousing following of the
U.S. team has him torn about who he will root for today.
</P>
<P>
   The former Brazilian star and soccer's goodwill ambassador,
heartened by the popularity of the sport among American girls, said
he won't reveal his rooting interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is with Brazil, but I'm very happy the U.S. team has
done so well,'' he said. ``I only wish it was the final.''
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
