A8515 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BONDS-LADN     07-03 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BONDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' CONFIDENCE MAN IS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It wasn't his defense the San Francisco Giants
missed most, even though he's won seven gold gloves.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't his production at the plate either, even though he's a
three-time MVP.
</P>
<P>
   It took seven weeks, but the Giants finally figured it out. What
they missed most about Barry Bonds was the simplest of things.
</P>
<P>
   His confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can just feel it when he's on the field,'' outfielder
Ellis Burks said. ``We had to find it for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants did just that, posting a 25-22 record while Bonds
rehabilitated from surgery to repair a torn ligament in his left
elbow. In the process, they remained close to the top of the
National League West standings and proved their own resiliency to
themeselves.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds returned on June 9, weeks earlier than the doctors
predicted, though pain in his elbow persists. Jeff Kent is seeing
fastballs in the cleanup spot again. The team speed has improved.
The lineup is cohesive.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have their confidence man back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude was we'd be in first place when Barry got back,''
Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``We weren't, but we were close.''
</P>
<P>
   They gutted it out without their franchise player. They stayed
afloat. They survived.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds must be beaming with pride, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said. ``I don't have to be proud of them.
They have to be out for their own success. They don't have to
please me. The fans and the city are the ones they need to make
proud. Not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride has always been an issue with Bonds. Humility is not one
of his stronger virtues, and he makes no apologies for it.
</P>
<P>
   He says his confidence is often misconstrued by reporters, who
fire softball questions his way and get heaters thrown back at
them.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Bonds almost anything. The response you get is never the one
you expect.
</P>
<P>
   His contentious relationship with the press is well documented,
though he insists he isn't trying to be a jerk when he answers a
question with a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't tolerate ignorance,'' Bonds said. ``I don't like to be
called names, either. It's like that kid at school with glasses who
gets called names in the playground. You never appreciate that
stuff, no matter who you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't no better than you and you ain't no better than me.
It's not an ego thing. I don't like being treated like a god. It's
just that my profession happens to be playing baseball. Because of
that, people expect things from me that they shouldn't expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what?''
</P>
<P>
   It's his candor and his frankness that often get interpreted as
cockiness. And it's his confidence _ that stabilizing force the
Giants missed so dearly _ that gets most criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was Muhammad Ali confident?'' Bonds said. ``Was Michael Jordan
confident? Was Joe Montana confident? Kareem Abdul-Jabbar? Is Shaq
confident?
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes my confidence different from Ken Griffey Jr.'s?
From anybody else's? Why does my confidence have to be construed as
something else?''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds said sitting and watching for seven weeks didn't change
his mentality. He's not any more mellow than he was last season or
the year before. But it's apparent to some on the team that Bonds
is more content this year, that he's more appreciative of the game,
that he is a happier person.
</P>
<P>
   The finalization of his divorce with ex-wife Sun might have
something to do with it. And maybe missing those 47 games did
something, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He realized he's human,'' Baker said. ``When you've played as
long as Barry has and you've never had a major injury, never had to
miss so many games, that can get lost on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The most common shot taken at Bonds is that he isn't a clutch
performer, particularly in his limited postseason experience. In
three NLCS series defeats with the Pirates from 1990-92, Bonds
batted .191.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes to hear what they can't do or where they
failed,'' Baker said. ``Especially when you've had a career like
Barry's.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Bonds burning to get the Giants to the postseason? Is he
determined to bust out in the playoffs to take away his critics'
ammunition?
</P>
<P>
   What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go to the playoffs to prove anything to anybody,''
Bonds said. ``I go to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
