<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOW `MO' THE MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When given the choice, you always choose paper over plastic.
</P>
<P>
   You are a Clipper fan; you need something to wear.
</P>
<P>
   You've remained loyal and steadfast through thin and thinner,
for badder or worse.
</P>
<P>
   But there is lightning at the end of the tunnel. Four nights ago
and five seconds before you sprayed beer up your nostrils, the
Clippers drafted Lamar Odom. Suddenly, Susan Lucci has been blown
out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Now you are a Clipper fan due for hip-replacement surgery after
four days of swagger practice.
</P>
<P>
   Time out, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   You are a Clipper fan, so you know who Maurice Taylor is. Right,
he's ``Mo,'' one of two Clippers (rookie free agent Tyrone Nesby is
the other) who would think nothing of ripping out the heart of a
defender and ramming it through the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   You already knows that Mo plus Odom equals Modom. You know they
should be baud to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   And the rest of the NBA knows who Mo is, because Mo is among the
three most-productive lads from the NBA Draft of 1997. After two
seasons, only two players from that class - Tim Duncan and Keith
Van Horn - have more points and rebounds than Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1, Duncan and Van Horn also will be signing six-year
contract extensions for about 70 million scoots. It's the league
maximum; it's what NBA teams do when slouching into the realization
that they possess a franchise player entering the final year of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   You are a Clipper fan. You do the math, you do the history. You
know there may be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   You know the potential problem is named Donald T. Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   You know he's the owner of the Clippers and a threat to the
welfare of his own team, because every sports columnist within
spitting distance of the Sports Arena has given Sterling the
raspberry in print. You know the historical residue of his
decisions has made several hard-working, intelligent Clipper
employees look lazy and stupid.
</P>
<P>
   You also know Sterling is no dummy, because we are telling you
so, unleashing deductive logic to assume anyone who's amassed that
kind of bank must have some high-caliber synapses.
</P>
<P>
   You also know Sterling realizes that making money often requires
spending money first. But you're not sure if Sterling, in terms of
NBA business, knows when to say spend.
</P>
<P>
   Around the water cooler, it has been suggested Sterling may want
to show Mo the money, all $70 million, but not until after
</P>
<P>
   the coming season. The people he pays to assess these basketball
possibilities want to give Taylor the extension now. Sterling wants
more evidence.
</P>
<P>
   You are a Clipper fan, and you are booing.
</P>
<P>
   You also know, because we're telling you, Mo probably will
politely request to be traded to another NBA franchise if he's not
offered the max before training camp.
</P>
<P>
   If he's traded, it will be the worst thing to clout this
franchise since Marques Johnson's head rammed Benoit Benjamin's
tummy, or Norm Nixon (Mo's agent) ripped his Achilles tendon, or
Derek Smith ripped his knee, or Ron Harper ripped his knee, or
Danny Manning ripped his knee or Sean Elliott ripped his knee a few
years before inspiring the Clippers to draft Danny Ferry instead of
him, then trade Ferry for Harper, who (you may recall) ripped his
knee.
</P>
<P>
   If Taylor's not traded, the first Clipper season at Staples
Center will feature a cloud of doom treading air in front of
Sterling's luxury suite, blocking his view of the action.
</P>
<P>
   Then Taylor's contract will expire and he will sign with another
team.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a far worse hit to the Clippers than Sterling's
decision to snuff a trade that would have brought Glen Rice and
Willie Burton for Manning.
</P>
<P>
   You know where to cut the holes in the paper bag.
</P>
<P>
   You are a Clipper fan.
</P>
<P>
   (No. You are not Billy Crystal.)
</P>
<P>
   While the checkbook's open
</P>
<P>
   To Sterling's credit, he did not laugh himself to sleep when
Clipper basketball operations crew members asked if it would be OK
to romance Orlando's free-agent guard Anfernee ``Penny'' Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Penny's six-year tab would be about $68 million.
</P>
<P>
   Penny's agents didn't laugh at the Clippers, either, possibly
because Hardaway may, in theory, accept the challenge of battling
Shaquille O'Neal for Staples supremacy. With Taylor, Odom and
Michael Olowokandi on his side, it almost sounds plausible.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more likely Penny and his pals define Clipper interest
as another offer to use as leverage for a sign-and-trade deal
involving the Magic that can bring Penny more than $80 million for
six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But matching salaries could make sign-and-trades more difficult
than the media members who propose them realize.
</P>
<P>
   So despite preliminary chats between the parties, Penny as a
Clipper remains a Hail Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reach in Wednesday's draft was Cleveland grabbing
Duke's Trajan Langdon at No. 11. Yeah, Langdon was the best shooter
available, but he's a 6-1{ off-guard who figures to be a career
backup. ... If Larry Bird was disillusioned with life as an NBA
coach before the draft, he must be miles beyond peeved now. First,
his Pacers are to deal his toughest player, power forward Antonio
Davis, to Toronto for the fifth pick. As part of the deal, the
Raptors selected 6-11 high schooler Jonathan Bender and will
surrender the kid to Indiana. But, according to reports from
Indianapolis, Bird would have preferred Miami of Ohio forward Wally
Szczerbiak. ... Look for free agent Clipper forward Rodney Rogers
to be playing for the Nuggets again next season. ... Another
possible free-agent target for the Clippers is Orlando's Bo Outlaw,
an ex-Clipper who would bring serious juice to their second team.
... In drafting power forwards Elton Brand, Michael Ruffin and Lari
Ketner to go with husky small forward Ron Artest, the Bulls now
have a better pass rush than the Bears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
