<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES BEAT METS, 3-0  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fred Wilpon, one of the Mets' co-owners, said his
general manager, Steve Phillips, gave him a briefing Saturday on
the Mets' attempts to upgrade their starting rotation before the
July 31 trading deadline. But the Mets have had a more pressing
need than a front-line starter against the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some runs,'' a downcast Wilpon said after the first-place
Braves had blanked the Mets, 3-0, at Shea Stadium to pull five
games ahead of them in the National League East. ``You can't win if
you don't score.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have now gone 28 consecutive innings without a run
against Atlanta, with shutouts in the first two games of this
three-game series and another last Sunday in Atlanta. The Braves
are the first team to shut out the Mets in three consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood (10-4) was the culprit Saturday, allowing two
hits in eight-plus innings while outpitching Al Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Leiter provided a blueprint for defeating the Braves
_ one the Mets have not been able to follow. ``To beat the Atlanta
Braves,'' he said, ``you've got to get superior starting pitching,
key hits and obviously scratch out a couple of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was the National League's pitcher of the month for June.
But June is over, and so is his five-game winning streak. Leiter
(7-6) allowed three runs in six innings Saturday, including a long
two-run home run to Brian Jordan in the fifth, before 43,256 fans
on a sweltering afternoon. The Mets did not advance a runner past
first base until the ninth inning as Millwood surrendered just two
singles. The Mets finished with three hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the best pitching performances I've seen
anywhere this year,'' Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox said. ``Anywhere.
Against us, for us, on TV, American League. Anywhere. He was just
tremendous on the hottest day.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood said: ``We said when we started playing these guys that
we wanted to try to keep them down. We don't want to give them any
games or let them get some wind in their sails. We wanted to try to
beat them as much as we could and not let them get too confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Their mission has been a success. The Braves are 4-1 against the
Mets this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' performance Saturday was not as glaringly dominant
as Friday's 16-0 rout, but it was convincing enough. The Braves
have taken the first two games of this series by a combined score
of 19-0, while the Mets have had just six hits _ all singles _ and
just four runners in scoring position, including one Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That was in the ninth. Brian McRae drew a full-count walk off
Millwood to open the inning, prompting Cox to call for John Rocker,
who uncorked a wild pitch to allow McRae to advance to second.
After the pinch-hitter Todd Pratt flared a single to right field,
the Mets had runners on first and third with nobody out and their
second, third and fourth hitters in the order coming up.
</P>
<P>
   But Edgardo Alfonzo popped to short center field. John Olerud
popped to left. And Mike Piazza, who is 16 for 77 (.208) with
runners in scoring position this season, struck out on three
pitches to complete a frustrating 0-for-4 day. The Mets were shut
out in consecutive games for the first time since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``A base hit by any of us three would have given us some
momentum,'' Piazza said. ``There seems to be this sort of trait. We
all kind of go cold simultaneously. It seems like we've been stuck
in neutral the last two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Through six and one-third innings, the Mets had one hit off
Millwood _ Robin Ventura's fifth-inning single. Leiter, meanwhile,
was in a jam in just about every inning. Then in the fifth, after
Chipper Jones lashed a changeup for a two-out double, Jordan
drilled a flat 2-0 slider into the bleachers in left field. The
home run was Jordan's 16th of the season and 100th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the straightest fastball I've ever seen Leiter
throw,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter said, ``Tell Brian it was a slider and I guess it backed
up and looked like a fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' closer, John Franco, who was placed on the 15-day
disabled list Saturday with a finger injury, said before the game
that this series and the one in Atlanta last weekend were a sort of
gauge ``to see where we're at with them.'' So far, not very close.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron threw out the ceremonial first pitch. ... Mets
Manager Bobby Valentine was asked about the Padres'
franchise-record 14-game winning streak, which ended Saturday.
``Everyone gets hot and everyone gets cold,'' he said. ``That's
something some people don't understand. That's why people get
fired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
