<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CHASTAIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASTAIN STRIKES A POSE FOR SOCCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Mia Hamm is considered the cover girl for U.S. women's
soccer, Brandi Chastain could be called the centerfold.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain, a skilled fullback, recently landed such off-field
status by donning little more than the stitching on a soccer ball
in a national magazine layout.
</P>
<P>
   Her risque display of flesh in the current issue of Gear
Magazine has supplied endless fodder for the American press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' said Steve Vanderpool, director of
public relations for Women's World Cup '99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows about Mia and many know about Michelle
Akers.... It's great that Brandi is putting another face out out
there for women's soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she's putting a tad more than just a face out there.
</P>
<P>
   The full-page, side-view shot of a squatting Chastain shows her
in the buff, wearing only a pair of Nike soccer boots while
clutching a ball in front of her.
</P>
<P>
   But a pair of goals _ including a heart-stopping own goal
credited for Germany _ in Thursday's Women's World Cup
quarterfinals redirected some of the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain's miscommunication with U.S. keeper Briana Scurry
almost proved costly, but her half-volley goal in the second half
sparked the team's rally for a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down to it, she still finds ways to grab the
headlines, doesn't she?'' teammate and Pasadena native Carla
Overbeck said wryly.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain, Overbeck, Hamm and the rest of the American cast
remain alive heading into today's semifinal against Brazil in San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   While Brazil can boast the flashy ``mono-names'' _ Pretinha,
Roseli and the electrifying Sissi, to name a few _ the Red, White
and Blue is gushing with talent and experience through and through.
</P>
<P>
   Few exemplify that as well as the 30-year-old Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-year national team veteran, she is among the pioneers
of the worldwide women's soccer movement, playing in all three
World Cups with exactly 100 caps to her credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of defenders, she's among the best there is,'' said
Akers, who has been with the national team since its inception in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see it in her pinpoint passing; she can thread the
needle and connect with where players are headed. She has the
smarts for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither her precision nor her intuition are a mere coincidence.
Chastain spent her early playing days honing lethal attacking
talents and she polishes her read on the game every fall as an
assistant to husband and head coach Jerry Smith at Santa Clara
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the welts to prove it,'' joked Chastain, who often
mixes up it with her current collegiate players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put me up front, in the back, at midfield... just don't waste
your time putting me in the stands. I'll find a way onto the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   That's perfectly fine with U.S. coach Tony DiCicco.
</P>
<P>
   ``She brings that coaching perspective to the field, knows when
to play conservatively but knows how to change it up when need
be,'' DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her physical skills are well refined, too. If we had 11 of her
on the field, with the skill level and the tactical approach, we'd
be totally unbeatable.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco was also quick to put Chastain's rare blunder against
Germany in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on that play,'' he deadpanned. ``I've seen
big-time professional players make a mistake like that and they
were out of the game. To Brandi's credit, she came back and scored
the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's semifinal also qualifies as a homecoming for Chastain.
She played for Archbishop Mitty High before starring for both UC
Berkeley and Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the chance to play against the World All-Stars, a few
exhibition matches and possibly the semifinal _ that's the best
part,'' said Chastain in February, on the eve of the U.S. vs. World
All-Stars match in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the chance to represent my country and maybe show off
for family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But can she show off any more than she did for the camera lens
recently?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's totally the way she is,'' said DiCicco, his naturally
reddish facial features flushing a few shades deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we have to keep an eye on her. She's the
free-spirited type.''
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, Chastain quickly corrals those spirits into
a laser-like focus for game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being a little crazy _ some would say strange _ off the
field, but it's all business between the lines,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt a little embarrassed because that magazine ended
up with half-naked girls shown all over the place. I was hoping my
shot would be a tongue-in-cheek boost of publicity for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges a major responsibility of a different sort
during the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make it a great show and showcase the opportunities
for future players,'' Chastain said. ``When I first started out,
there were no female role models to look up to. But the
opportunities have kept opening up since Title IX. The American
women's team's success is just another example of one of those
avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to keep creating exposure for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain has already done that _ in more ways than one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
