<HEADER>
A8525 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-MARCH-BOS &LR;      07-03 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-MARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION BUILDS OVER PROTESTANT MARCHING SEASON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ Frank Gibson's great uncle died at
the Battle of the Somme 83 years ago this week. Saturday, he
watched as British soldiers put the finishing touches on the barbed
wire and trenches meant to keep him and other Protestants from
marching through a Catholic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The scene, Gibson said, reminded him of the trenches in France
where his uncle and tens of thousands of Ulstermen died in service
to the king. Now it was the apparatus that he said was ``oppressing
the loyal Protestant people of Ulster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My great uncle's got to be turning in his grave,'' said
Gibson, 40, gazing over the fields at Drumcree Church. ``The army
he died for is doing this to his people.''
</P>
<P>
   Over on the Garvaghy Road, Catholic nationalist residents took
little comfort from the fact that Protestant unionists like Frank
Gibson feel abandoned. They fear the authorities will betray them
at the last minute and allow the Orange Order to march through
their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Chambers and Sue-Ellen Millar, both 18, sat on the stoop
of the Ashgrove Community Center, Millar gently rocking the
carriage that held her 7-months-old daughter Courtney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, the army might still let them down the road,'' said
Millar, voicing a cynicism that is common here, despite the hard
line the police and the army held against the Orangemen last year.
Dozens of police officers were injured, one was killed, and at
least 18 had to move their families in the face of loyalist
intimidation because of their stand at Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the standoff resumes.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, after he and his Irish counterpart had given
the political parties of Northern Ireland a plan to steer them
through the stalemate that has stalled the peace process, British
Prime Minister Tony Blair spoke of ``the most historic opportunity
for peace this land has known.''
</P>
<P>
   But here in Portadown, history is relative, and the politics
that Blair and Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern hold up as an
alternative to the violence of the last 30 years rings hollow to
people who are preoccupied with a 15-minute march that encapsulates
everything for them.
</P>
<P>
   For Protestants, who say they are being slowly overtaken by
Catholics, history means that a parade which has followed a
traditional route for nearly 200 years should be allowed to
continue, no matter how many people it offends. They say the peace
process is a conspiracy to strip them of their rights, and point to
the banning of Sunday's parade for the second consecutive year as
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics guffaw when they hear that Protestants feel
marginalized. To them, history is more recent. They talk about how
Bobby Hamill was kicked to death two years ago when he strayed off
the Catholic plantation to socialize in the town center at night.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as loyalists walked past St. John's Catholic church
on the way to the standoff at Drumcree, they jumped up and down,
aping Hamill's killers and shouting his name.
</P>
<P>
   Millar and Chambers are case studies of young Catholics here.
Neither has ever ventured into the town center at night. They said
the unofficial curfew is 6 p.m., summer or winter. If you stay
later, you risk the fate of Bobby Hamill, who died as a group of
police officers stood by a few hundred feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be the next Bobby Hamill,'' Chambers says.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of grievance held by Protestants is no less strong,
even though they still control the town and make up 60 percent of
the population. They say Catholics are determined to drive them
out.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics ``don't want us in the country anymore,'' said Stephen
McKinney, 34, who literally wore his colors on the sleeve of his
orange shirt. Two of McKinney's uncles were shot dead by the IRA,
and he is not in a forgiving mood.
</P>
<P>
   Neither are the people of the Garvaghy Road, who are quick to
point out that the annual siege over the parade is nothing compared
to the everyday pressure of being surrounded by hostile loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the fields of Drumcree Church have become a
flashpoint in July, an annual reminder that as the peace process
matures, there are still ancient, visceral hatreds that flourish on
this beautiful island.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the international news media descend here, clogging
the narrow roads, providing a windfall for those few fortunate
whose driveways offer enough space for satellite trucks or a
sweeping view of the fields where Orangemen converge loudly and
violently to demand the right to march through a neighborhood that
does not want them.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of international observers also descend on the place,
few if any bothering to talk to Protestants. International opinion
seems squarely behind the Catholic nationalists, yet another reason
why the Protestants of Portadown feel isolated and react with
anger.
</P>
<P>
   Some are bigots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholics are breeding like rabbits,'' Peggy Moore was saying
Saturday, standing in the shadow of the 15-foot metal barrier,
reinforced with concrete, that will prevent the Orangemen from
reaching the Garvaghy Road. Asked if what she was saying was
bigoted, the 65-year-old Moore replied, ``How can it be bigoted if
it's true?''
</P>
<P>
   Some are simply scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hate Catholics. I know a lot of good Catholics,'' said
Gary Robertson, 35, a deliveryman. ``But Tony Blair wants to let
the IRA into government, and I'm supposed to sit back and accept
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Orangemen will hold a service at Drumcree Church,
dedicated to men like Fred Gibson, Frank Gibson's great uncle, who
died in the squalor of the trenches of the Somme. Then they will
march a hundred yards or so down to the metal barrier topped with
razor wire. Harold Gracey, the local Orange Order leader, will
formally register his disgust that they are not being allowed to
walk the Queen's highway.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Orangemen will take to the fields. At night, young
loyalists will attack the police and soldiers across the stream
whose banks have been widened. Some will try to scale the barbed
wire and breach the trenches. They will be beaten back by the
police and soldiers, who will receive little thanks from the
Catholic nationalists they are protecting.
</P>
<P>
   On the Garvaghy Road, people are sealed in, army checkpoints at
the top and bottom of the road. They say they are being held
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Held hostage, too, is the peace process, which every year at
this time is simply pushed to the side and put on hold, to see how
bad it will be at Drumcree, a perennial reminder that peace, like
history, is relative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
