u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS &LR;      07-03 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS LEFT ON RUNWAY AS ALLIES BLOCK DEPARTURE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Hundreds of Russian peacekeeping troops bound for
Kosovo were left waiting on the runway Saturday after the United
States and its allies blocked their departure for the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The move reflects the mutual suspicion between Russia and the
West even after NATO halted the bombing of Moscow's ally,
Yugoslavia, after 11 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow had planned to send the first large contingent of its
expected force of 3,600 peacekeepers to join the several hundred
Russian troops guarding the airport in Kosovo's capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow and NATO have been unable to resolve differences over
Russia's role in the peacekeeping force for Kosovo. Clinton
administration officials said Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria,
acting on a NATO request, had refused to allow Russia to fly troop
transport planes over their territory.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Russian troops in Kosovo is sensitive because most
Albanians view the Russians with the same distaste as the Serbs who
had ruled the province. The vulnerability of the peacekeepers
themselves was underscored Saturday when British paratroopers shot
four Albanians, killing two, in an act that outraged Pristina
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration says the Kremlin has tried to
renegotiate an agreement signed in Helsinki last month to allow
Russian troops in Kosovo to report only to Russian commanders,
rather than remain under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials also say Russia, which had originally agreed
to scatter its troops in sectors under American, British, and
German commanders, now wants to station its forces throughout the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Russian leaders say they never agreed to put their troops under
NATO control in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our contingent in Kosovo will be under complete political and
military control of the Russian command,'' Colonel General Leonid
Ivashov, a senior military negotiator, said in Moscow last week.
``This is provided for in the documents signed by the Russian and
US defense ministers in Helsinki.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks at NATO headquarters in Belgium last week could not
resolve the difference of opinions. That caused the alliance to
block Russia's request last week to fly its troops over Hungary,
which became a NATO member in April, and Romania and Bulgaria,
which have asked to join.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is NATO's view that we work through all these agreements
before any more Russian forces are deployed,'' National Security
Council spokesman P.J. Crowley said Saturday. Talks between Russia
and NATO will resume this week.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman said Secretary of State Madeleine
K. Albright had telephoned Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov on
Friday to relay NATO complaints about continuing the deployment of
the several thousand Russian troops into Kosovo until a
satisfactory agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Russia surprised and upstaged the alliance when it sent 200
troops from its peacekeeping force in Bosnia across Serbia and into
Kosovo several hours before NATO troops entered the province.
</P>
<P>
   The dash was hailed as a victory in Moscow, where there is
growing resentment at what many Russians perceive as global
arrogance on the part of the United States and its allies. The
commander of the march, Viktor Zavarzin, became a hero and was
promoted to a three-star general. Perhaps no man better symbolizes
the chasm between Russia and the West than Zavarzin, who was
rejected by NATO as Russian liaison to the alliance on the grounds
that he might be a spy.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's newly assertive behavior, seen as a welcome development
in Moscow political and military circles, has put NATO on the
lookout for new surprises, especially after Russian strategic
bombers engaged in a Cold-War-stylemilitary exercise near Iceland
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The move to block Russian reinforcements in Kosovo could raise
the stakes in the Kremlin's confrontation with the West. But so
far, the Kremlin has been silent on NATO's move to halt its troop
shipments, which was first reported in The New York Times Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, paratroopers in Ivanovo, a city 200 miles northeast of
Moscow, spent the day loading equipment, only to learn that their
flight had been delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Another paratroop force of about 1,000 men was reported arriving
in the Black Sea port of Tuapse, where they would be transported to
Yugoslavia by sea with 40 military vehicles. Russia's Black Sea
fleet said it received permission from NATO member Turkey for four
transport ships to navigate the Bosporus straits that connect the
Black Sea to the Mediterranean on July 10 and 11; it was unclear if
the alliance expects to prevent the troops from departure.
</P>
<P>
   Russian media reported last week that Moscow had decided to send
the bulk of its 3,600 troops to Kosovo via sea to save cash.
</P>
<P>
   Filipov reported from Moscow; Farrell from Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
