u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     07-03 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT ORIOLES, 6-5  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In deciding on the pitching staff for the American
League All-Stars, Joe Torre has chosen democracy. He has polled his
fellow AL managers to name the top eight pitchers in the league. He
counted their votes, put them in order and, if all enter the
All-Star Game break uninjured and available, they will be his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, he confirmed, are his own Yankees David Cone and
Mariano Rivera. What about Orlando Hernandez? Well, Torre left a
ninth spot on the staff open. Call it his dictator pick. And El
Duque? ``He got some votes from other managers,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Saturday. Hernandez struggled with his command
most of the afternoon and was hurt by two pitches within seconds of
each other in the fourth inning. He appeared about to be collared
with a loss against the Baltimore Orioles before 42,859 at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But then something remarkable happened. In the bottom of the
ninth inning with two men on, Scott Brosius hit a 3-1 pitch from
Arthur Rhodes into the left-field bleachers for a 6-5 victory. It
was the Yankees' first game-winning home run in the bottom of the
ninth since July 28, 1996, when Darryl Strawberry did it against
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The heroic ninth began when Chili Davis singled off Rhodes to
open the inning and the Orioles left-hander then walked Jorge
Posada. Rhodes struck out Luis Sojo when the home plate umpire,
Larry Barnett, ruled he had not checked his swing.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Brosius blast gave the victory to Jason Grimsley,
who pitched two innings of shutout relief. But it also awarded
Hernandez, who had won of four of his previous five starts and
showed an All Star-caliber will that has helped him lower his
earned run average from 6.56 to 3.91 in his last eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the game after six and two-third innings, Hernandez
had given up five hits and the score was tied, 3-3. He gave the
left-handed reliever Mike Stanton the ball with two outs and men
and first and second. But the game got away from the Yankees, and
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, responsibility for a double by B.J. Surhoff that
chased Charles Johnson and Brady Anderson home with the winning
runs rested with Ricky Ledee. He got the start in left field after
Shane Spencer was hospitalized Saturday night at Columbia
Presbyterian Medical Center, where he is in stable condition and
being treated for an irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee didn't make the best of his opportunity. Stanton threw a
fastball that Surhoff drove into the left-center-field gap. Ledee
missed snagging it as it sailed past his back-handed stab. In the
next inning, he made matters worse by allowing Johnson, the
Orioles' catcher, to pick him off first base.
</P>
<P>
   It was a frustrating way for the Yankees to end a two-game
winning streak _ especially on an afternoon when Derek Jeter and
Bernie Williams extended hitting streaks to 13 and 14 games and
Hernandez battled gamely for an All-Star spot.
</P>
<P>
   His one bad inning was the lightning-strike fourth. Hernandez
had blanked the Orioles through three and two-thirds innings when
Albert Belle came to the plate. He worked the burly power hitter to
a 3-1 count, then grooved a fastball that Belle rocketed 406 feet
and over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Belle had barely touched all the bases after his 17th home run
of the season when Hernandez again mislocated his fastball. This
time designated hitter Harold Baines spanked him for his mistake,
yanking it over the fence near the left field foul pole for his
1,538th career run batted in, which moved him past Joe DiMaggio and
into 32nd place on the career r.b.i list. It was the sixth time
this season that the Orioles had hit back-to-back homers, and it
put the Yankees down, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees responded in the bottom of the inning. After
Williams walked and Tino Martinez singled to right, Chili Davis
came to the plate with two outs and sprayed a single to left field
that Surhoff scooped up, throwing to the plate. But Williams was
running as Davis swung and slid home well before the ball and the
Yankees were back in the game, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque, however, could not escape trouble in the fifth after
Cal Ripken rolled a double down the first base line to begin the
inning. He was sacrificed to third by Hairston. But after Hernandez
struck out Johnson, Brady Anderson poked a single to right field to
score Ripken for a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   This time Jeter responded for the Yankees. With two out and
Brosius on third, Jeter slammed a two-run homer to right -center to
tie the game. It was Jeter's 14th homer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees couldn't do any more damage to the Orioles
right-hander Sidney Ponson, who over seven innings held them to six
hits.
</P>
<P>
   So Hernandez's All-Star fate will remain in the hands of Torre
and his selection for the ninth spot on the AL roster. ``Some guys
can get hurt, though you don't wish that,'' Torre said. ``Or some
may have to pitch that previous Sunday and will be unavailable. A
lot can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Manto, who was claimed off waivers from the Indians, was
added to the roster after Shane Spencer was placed on the 15-day
disabled list with an irregular heartbeat. Manto, 34, has a .227
career average and mostly plays first or third base, but Manager
Joe Torre talked with him about being an emergency catcher and
filling in at shortstop or second as well. ``It's easy for me to
assume my role,'' Manto said. ``I'm the 24th or 25th guy and I'm
content with that.'' ... The Yankees signed the former Met
left-hander Allen Watson to a minor league contract, and he
reported to Class AAA Columbus. The Yankees only have one
left-hander in the bullpen, Mike Stanton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
