<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8528 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     07-03 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMORROW WON'T COME SOON ENOUGH IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The proof was in the purge, and the ugly white
caps from spring training were at the bottom of the pile burning
Saturday morning in the Dodgers bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   They had tried lineup changes, meetings, benchings. Raul Mondesi
shaved his head, Gary Sheffield grew back his goatee. A two-out hit
or a well-pitched game would have been better, but 34-44 teams
never quite get to that. So a pregame exorcism was all that was
left.
</P>
<P>
   Players getting together to burn the white hats worn during
interleague play was symbolic. It was one of many bad ideas last
winter that went into building this miserable team.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them belonged to new general manager Kevin Malone.
How much of this would be happening if Chan Ho Park, Carlos Perez
and Darren Dreifort didn't look as though they were working on a
new pitch in the instructional league?
</P>
<P>
   But Malone was brought here to set the tone and Saturday's 9-1
loss to the first-place Giants was just another example of his
tough rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the Fox-directed signing of Kevin Brown to a
seven-year, $105 million contract. That was the price a team with
four No. 3 starters had to pay to boost its starting rotation. But
it was absurd to think a guy who is aloof by nature and plays just
every fifth day could be a leader.
</P>
<P>
   Also thinking that Brown, a ground-ball pitcher, would turn
around a team so limited defensively probably wasn't good for the
investment. Leadoff hitter Eric Young is hobbled at second by a bad
Achilles and he and Eric Karros have no range on the right side.
More painful is Young's .349 on-base percentage. Young is 0 for 10
in his last three games, with many of the outs lazy fly balls to
the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the trade for Todd Hundley, whose reconstructed
right elbow made the move questionable. It was thinking the team
would be fine with career minor-leaguer Paul LoDuca as the backup
even though the team admitted Hundley would need at least 40 games
off this season.
</P>
<P>
   When LoDuca didn't work out, the Dodgers sent for Angel Pena,
their top prospect who was growing bored in the minors. When Raul
Mondesi began to yawn at Triple-A in 1992, the Dodgers busted him
down to Double-A. Pena, who should be a good one, was rewarded for
his indifference and the Dodgers were rewarded with his .188
average. And in their desperation for left-handed hitting, they
stayed with Todd Hollandsworth, who has more days on the disabled
list in his career than RBI. When the Dodgers look for someone off
the bench in the late innings, there is a good chance Hollandsworth
will be in the trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were hasty in giving the 2-9 Perez a three-year, $15
million contract even though during four years in Montreal he had
never pitched a meaningful game. Malone had him and liked him with
the Expos and his feelings were confirmed when Perez had four
consecutive, complete-game victories last September.
</P>
<P>
   It looked impressive, but the season already was over. Maybe not
in the standings, but definitely on the faces in the Dodgers
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's maneuverability was hampered by the $54 million he
inherited in guaranteed contracts. But he added to the burden by
taking on center fielder Devon White for three years at $12
million.
</P>
<P>
   White's 94 runs and 22 homers last year with expansion Arizona
looked pretty good. But his attitude was such a turnoff to
Diamondbacks officials, they didn't even talk to him when he became
a free agent last winter. This season, White has missed 21 starts
and hasn't been on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   When he won a June 9 game against the Angels with a grand slam,
it ended two months batting of around .200. But after that game,
White, 36, said he had ``nothing to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair to look longingly at Roger Cedeno, who could
make the National League All-Star team with the New York Mets after
several unfulfilling seasons with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno was crushed by expectation here and needed a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   But Mondesi, long removed from that minor-league demotion, is a
star, even if he has one home run in his last 111 at-bats. Instead
of being accountable for his part in the mess, he complains that
manager Davey Johnson is picking on him by moving him out of the
cleanup spot to everywhere from leadoff to sixth in the order.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up and the Dodgers are 10{ games back on the Fourth of
July. Last year, they were 12{ back on this day. But that is not
reason for optimism. It is a reason to start thinking about next
winter. &QL; 
Deputy Sports Editor Matt McHale covers baseball for the Daily
News. He can be reached at (800) 777-4953 or mch013aol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
