<SLUG> BC-R-ILL-DRIVEBY-SHOOTINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER COACH KILLED, ATTACKER MAY BE TIED TO STRING OF SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add map note)  (ART ADV:  Locator map  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A lone white gunman cruising the streets Friday
evening in a light blue car shot and killed a black former
Northwestern University basketball coach, wounded six Orthodox Jews
and fired upon a car carrying Asian-Americans in what the police
are investigating as possible hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In all, beginning about 8:30 p.m., the authorities said, the
gunman fired at more than a dozen people in six locations within
about 12 miles of one another, beginning in the northern Chicago
neighborhood of Rogers Park and ending in the suburbs of Skokie and
Northbrook.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman, described as between 25 and 30 and about six feet
tall, with short brown hair, had not been arrested by midday
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we're not jumping to the conclusion that it's a
hate crime,'' said Patrick T. Camden, a spokesman for the Chicago
Police Department. ``All of the elements appear to be there, but
until we get the offender we won't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The former coach, Ricky Byrdsong, 42, was fatally shot in the
town of Skokie, as he was walking near his home with two of his
children. As the family reached an intersection, a blue car drove
by and seven shots were fired. Byrdsong was hit once in the lower
back. His children were not hit.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks had begun south of there about 20 minutes earlier in
Rogers Park, at Chicago's border with Evanston, just west of Loyola
University, with three Orthodox Jews being shot as they left
Sabbath services.
</P>
<P>
   Then two blocks to the north, a fourth was shot.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a fifth victim was shot a few blocks south,
and finally a sixth was injured nearby. One of the wounded was a
15-year-old boy; the rest were adults.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the shootings were done by one man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all getting the same vehicle description,'' said Lt.
Barry Silverberg of the Skokie Police. He described the car as a
light blue Ford Taurus with a large scratch on the rear door on the
driver's side.
</P>
<P>
   Byrdsong died Saturday after surgery at Evanston Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other victims, the 15-year-old boy and a 40-year-old
man were hospitalized in serious condition. Two men, ages 31 and
34, were in fair condition. And the other two victims, both age 31,
were treated at a hospital and released. A bullet went through the
clothing of another man, who was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers Park is known for its eclectic mix of religions, ethnic
groups and races. It is home to Hispanics, Asians and
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   After many years of economic hardship, the economy there is on
an upswing, with a new shopping center and condo conversions in one
of the last affordable neighborhoods along the city's north
lakefront.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers Park has experienced anti-Semitic attacks before. On a
Friday night in 1994, a Jewish institute was burned and four
synagogues were vandalized.
</P>
<P>
   Byrdsong was fired in 1997 after four seasons with Northwestern,
where he had a record of 34-78, including 10-62 in the Big Ten
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Before Northwestern, Byrdsong was an assistant coach at Arizona,
Eastern Illinois, Western Michigan and Iowa State, where he played
college ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
