<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA NOT ENOUGH FOR CUBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NL MVP Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs is only two homers behind
his pace from last year, when he finished with 66. Sosa hit his
30th on Wednesday, giving him 13 for the month of June. He set a
record with 20 homers last June.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa also hit his 300th career homer during the month, which is
amazing since he hit his 200th less than two years ago. He went
from 200 to 300 in 1,045 at-bats over 261 games _ after needing
1,056 games and 3,877 at-bats to accumulate the first 200 homers.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising he would get hot in June, finishing the
month with seven homers in his last eight games, including at least
one in four straight. But as with last year, Sosa's numbers aren't
translating into victories for the Cubs. They were 10-17 in June
after going 12-15 last June. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More warning signs
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks have come back to the field in the West
and things have gotten so bad they used Nicaraguan right-hander
Vicente Padilla in a save situation in his major-league debut.
Padilla, who opened the season in the Single-A California League,
started the ninth Tuesday with a 4-2 lead vs. Cincinnati but gave
up four hits and three runs without retiring a batter in a 5-4
loss. The D'backs have blown 13 saves and dropped 15 games in an
opponent's last at-bat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Aaron
</P>
<P>
   With 15 homers and 64 RBI entering the weekend, Atlanta's
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan is on pace for the most productive season by a
Braves right fielder since Hank Aaron hit 44 homers and drove in
127 runs in 1966. While two other right fielders have hit 40 or
more homers _ David Justice, 40, 1993;
</P>
<P>
   Dale Murphy, 44, 1987; Aaron, 40, 1973; Aaron, 44, 1969 _ during
that stretch, no one has driven in more runs. With little more than
half the season remaining, Jordan could reach Aaron's 1963 total of
130 RBI and with a prolific second half, he might top Hugh Duffy 's
1894 franchise- record 145 RBI. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Team chemistry
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins beat the Mets on Wednesday with a dramatic
ninth-inning homer by Mark Kotsay , but Florida's only veteran
starter Alex Fernandez wasn't pleased. Fernandez, who is 2-5
despite a 3.17 ERA, left the game with a 3-2 lead and watched
Braden Looper give up the tying run in the seventh. It was the 10th
blown save in 20 chances for the young Marlins relievers this year
(the third by Looper), and it's happened to Fernandez four times.
``It gets old, it gets frustrating,'' said Fernandez, who broke a
$400 clubhouse TV the last time it happened. ``But I've got to have
some common sense and understand what I'm playing with and who I'm
playing with.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the rocks
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and Rockies were picked by many to finish 1-2 in the
West. Instead, they are battling for last place. Colorado took a
seven-game losing streak into the weekend and no game was worse
than Monday's vs. San Diego. The Rockies committed three errors in
the first inning alone and four in all, and catcher Henry Blanco ,
naturally a former Dodgers farmhand, allowed nine stolen bases,
including five by Damian Jackson. Two of those four errors were
made by Vinny Castilla, who had five in a six-game stretch and 14
overall _ more than all of last season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cable guy
</P>
<P>
   The $400 million deal to sell the Mets to Cablevision is likely
to take place this month, pending final negotiations over how much
day-to-day input former Mets owners Fred Wilpon and Nelson
Doubleday will have. They'll retain 20 percent of the club, and
while Doubleday is happy just to take the money and run, Wilpon
still wants to be near the action. This was the type of squabble
between cable chief Charles Dolan and George Steinbrenner that
killed the Cablevision-Yankees deal last winter. A sale would
strengthen the Mets' case for a new stadium, a planned 45,000-seat
Ebbets Field replica with a retractable roof, which they hope to
have by 2003. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
