<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8541 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-03 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DODGERS NEED IS A GUY LIKE DEMPSEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Davey Johnson has likened managing a baseball team
to running a restaurant. The analogy is good food for thought.
Because whether it's diners or dingers your livelihood depends on,
success is a matter of synergy.
</P>
<P>
   You can have efficient hostesses, nimble waiters and a
celebrated chef, but if the food preparers don't do their jobs, or
the busboys theirs, the final product will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, you can have one of the league's best pitchers, a
dependable closer, a Gold Glove outfielder and an All-Star hitter,
but if your infielders can't turn the double play and your pinch
hitters can't turn on a fastball, your rawhide is going to cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the Dodgers, baseball's version of the Border
Grill.
</P>
<P>
   Both the eatery on Melrose Ave. and the team in Chavez Ravine
were hotter than jalapenos in the '80s. They were the talk of a
town that loves to hear itself speak. The Grill's dishes were
divine and in 1981 and 1985 and especially in 1988, so were the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Grill since has left chic Melrose Ave. and the
Dodgers have disappeared from the National League's high-rent
district. They're both still around _ you can find the Grill in
Santa Monica and the Dodgers in the cellar of the NL West _ but the
buzz has left their buildings. People are talking now about
Dominick's and Reign and the San Diego Padres and the Cincinnati
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant doesn't go bad overnight and neither does a
ballclub. It just looks that way to people oblivious to the
day-to-day dynamics chipping away at the glitzy exterior. The truth
is, the Dodgers have been limping since just after Kirk Gibson's
gimpy home-run trot in Game 1 of the 1988 World Series against
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez. Charles Johnson. Tom Candiotti. Roger Cedeno.
Hideo Nomo. So many ex-Dodgers are thriving it suggests the front
office has been as error- prone as this team. Network sports sage
Bob Costas once spoke of the Dodgers being ``the worst team ever
put on the field.'' Amazingly, he was referring to the 1988 World
Series, not the California Civil-War Series that resumed Friday at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the 1988 squad had a much lower profile than the
team that dropped its sixth straight game Saturday. What that team
lacked in style points, though, it made up for in substance. From
top to bottom, the 1988 team had all the winning ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser. Rick Dempsey. Franklin Stubbs. Steve Sax.
Alfredo Griffin. Jeff Hamilton. Mickey Hatcher. John Shelby. Danny
Heep. It's not a lineup any rotisserie player would love, but it
won the World Series for the Dodgers 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with the 1999 Dodgers. They seem to have been
thrown together as if for a fantasy-baseball league where chemistry
isn't a concern. The 1999 Dodgers, who have a lot of chefs and not
nearly enough table setters, could learn a lot from picking the
brains of players on the 1988 team.
</P>
<P>
   Why not start with the bullpen coach, Dempsey? Dempsey was a
super sub on the 1988 team, one in a band of reserves that to a man
had more energy than ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible, how we played the game,'' Dempsey said.
``That year we played the game almost as perfect as you could play
it. We didn't beat ourselves too often. It was not a selfish
ballclub. Guys understood their roles. We all genuinely liked each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to gauge the affection this year's Dodgers have for
one another. Three hours before Friday's game, five players sat in
the home clubhouse. Three were chatting _ into their cellular
phones.
</P>
<P>
   After the 6-3 loss, the players hurried to beat the traffic,
rushing out of the clubhouse with sneakers unlaced and sandals
unfastened, fanning out toward homes all over greater L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Team chemistry can't be bought, as the Dodgers are finding out
$80 million after the fact. It is fueled by winning, of course, but
it starts with teammates taking the time to get to know one another
as people and not just players.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how far camaraderie can carry a team. Dempsey could
tell this year's Dodgers that and so much more.
</P>
<P>
   If only they'd ask.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, inexcusably, not one player has ripped open the
cellophane wrapping on this walking encyclopedia of winning
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   You can read whatever you want into that. Dempsey has his own
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impression I get from a lot of players is when they make
five, six, ten million dollars, they probably feel like they've
maxed out on knowledge,'' Dempsey said. ``There's nothing more they
think they need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Dodger Blue, from Dempsey on down, wants you to know
the Dodgers are not soulless. They swear the mistakes being made,
on the bases and behind the plate and on the mound and in the
field, are a product of caring too much, not too little.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone, so full of himself in
April, has come up empty in his search for answers. He proclaimed
himself ``humbled'' and believes he has plenty of company in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the players' frustration. I see their disappointment. I
see their pain,'' Malone said. ``The fans don't see it because we
don't show it. It's part of the society we live in. Men aren't
supposed to show compassion, emotion. Men are supposed to be
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are tough all right _ on toilets and walls and water
coolers. Those shows of emotion are not constructive.
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Gibson and Hershiser found other ways to fire up their
teammates. Today that responsibility has to fall squarely on the
shoulders of Kevin Brown and Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi and
Devon White and Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a bad group of guys here,'' Dempsey said. ``I
just think we do need a little better leadership. I haven't seen
that real fire yet. We need somebody to pick the ballclub up and
carry it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game, the Dodgers set caps and jerseys and
equipment ablaze in an exorcism exercise that was Brown's idea.
Something tells us that's not the fire Dempsey was looking for. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
