   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, July 4. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
SLEEPWALK (Phoenix) _ Scott Falater, whose ``sleepwalking'' defense
failed to prevent him from being convicted of murder for stabbing
his wife 44 times, still considers himself an innocent man, even
though he ``killed my wife with my hands,'' and realizes many
people will think he came up with ``this scam of a defense'' even
if he were to appeal and be acquitted. Falater talked about his
life in jail, his thoughts for the future, his trial and his
children in an exclusive jailhouse interview with The Republic. By
JERRY KAMMER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHAFF-WEATHER (undated) _ Hair-thin fibers released by military
jets to evade radar during aerial war games in southern Arizona may
be shorting out spectacular monsoon lightning over Phoenix.
Researchers say the fibers _ called chaff _ float above the state
for up to a day, forming massive clouds seen only by weather radar
and preventing the huge buildup of energy needed to produce
lightning. By THOMAS ROPP. Story will move in ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   PUZO-BONANNO _ Bill Bonanno of Tucson, whose family was the
model for The Godfather and whose own memoirs as a mafioso have
just been published, saluted Mario Puzo for having ``set the gold
standard'' for books and films depicting organized crime. By JON
KAMMAN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ In keeping with America's most
beloved Independence Day tradition, the United States departments
of Justice and Veterans Affairs have decided to hold an
old-fashioned barbecue. They've dug a long narrow pit in central
Phoenix, stoked it with plenty of hot coals, and built over it a
sturdy spit on which they hope to impale then slowly roast a
77-year-old war hero named Bob Deheer. By E.J. MONTINI. Story will
move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories.
</P>
