<HEADLINE>
HUSBAND CONVICTED IN `SLEEPWALK' KILLING: `I'M NOT MONSTER'
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Scott Falater, convicted of murder despite his defense
that he was sleepwalking when he stabbed his wife 44 times, wants
the world to know one thing:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not this monster that they're trying to paint me to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know who I am on the inside,'' Falater said in an interview
Friday in the Madison Street Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hasn't changed. That will never change, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first public comments since his June 25 conviction,
Falater, who is seeking a new trial, decried the ``lynch-mob blood
lust''in public reaction to his trial.
</P>
<P>
   The former Motorola engineer also said that even he remains
uncertain about his sleepwalking defense, which drew international
attention to his case, and that he realizes many people will always
consider it a ``scam.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater, 43, also sought to rebut critics ``who don't know me
from Adam but suddenly find they can spout off all sorts of
terrible things about me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they spent an hour with me, they wouldn't say those
things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in black-and-white jail house stripes, Falater appeared
re laxed and self-assured one week after he was found guilty of
first-de gree murder in the bloody, 1997 killing of his wife,
Yarmila.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 90 minutes, Falater poured out his remorse about
killing his wife, a brutal act that he acknowledges but for which
he claims complete amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about his feeling of failure as a father, the
forgiveness he says he's received from his mother-in-law, his anger
at what he considers foul play by the prosecu tor, his puzzlement
at the verdict and his determination to find mean ing in his life
even if he's sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming there will come a time, sometime maybe in this
life or maybe in the next life,'' he said, ``when I will see the
purpose and I will see that it was a good thing after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater continued to assert his innocence despite a jury that
took less than eight hours to agree that he committed premeditated
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say I am innocent,'' he said calmly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not _ maybe I killed my wife with my hands. I certainly
didn't plan it. I certainly never intended to do anything like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his monthlong trial in Mari copa County Superior Court, Fala
ter's attorneys argued that he had been sleepwalking when he
stabbed his wife, stashed his bloody clothes, dragged her into the
pool, held her head underwater, then walked back inside his house.
</P>
<P>
   But Falater detached himself from his own defense, declining to
say that he actually was sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember what hap pened,'' he said. ``That's all I can
say. How can I say I was sleepwal king when I don't remember?''
</P>
<P>
   Falater said he isn't scared by the death penalty, which
prosecutor Juan Martinez intends to seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to lay my chips with God anytime,'' Falater said.
``I know how I live my life, despite what's been said about me. I
know who I am, what kind of person I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater countered Martinez's claim that Falater tried to deceive
the jury with a ``Don Quixote fantasy'' about his home life, which
defense witnesses, including Falater's two children said was never
marred even by serious argu ment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was the fantasy _ what happened one night or the previous
20 years of my mar riage, the previous 41 years of my life?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reality. And so I tell you that's what I hope God
would judge me on.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater said he was ``appalled'' at what he called Martinez's
distortion of the facts, particularly the prose cutor's claim that
Falater had taken part in a suspicious conversation three weeks
before the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez claimed Falater had talked then about the case of
Canadian Ken Parks, who used a sleepwalking defense to win acquit
tal on a murder charge. But the prosecutor never produced testi
mony to support the claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never heard of Ken Parks before I was arrested,''
Falater said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Martinez had based his claim on a distorted version of a
conversation among Falater's col leagues that took place after they
learned about the sleepwalking de fense.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Lori Voepel, who partic ipated in the interview, noted
that Judge Ronald Reinstein had in structed the jury to ignore the
discussion of the Canadian issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's hard to remove that taint,'' said Voepel, who cited
the issue in her motion for a new trial, filed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Falater also claimed that Martinez deliberately distorted
information about Yarmila's contraction of a venereal disease,
human papilloma virus.
</P>
<P>
   With the jury out of the court room, Martinez said a nurse had
told Yarmila that the disease meant her husband had been ``messing
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinstein ruled that the episode was irrelevant to the trial,
and the jury heard nothing of it.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Falater fears the jury may have been exposed to
heavy press coverage of the issue, ``which sort of implied that
yes, I had been fooling around on my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I had never been unfaithful to my wife,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater said he never contracted the disease, that Yarmila's
case of HPV had never been a source of conflict in their marriage,
and that the virus is sometimes transmitted through non-sexual
contact.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has refused to comment on the defense claims.
</P>
<P>
   Falater, whose marriage to Yar mila was consecrated for eternity
in a Mormon temple ceremony, said he hopes to be reunited with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly hope she would be forgiving towards me and
would want me back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's calm demeanor broke down briefly as he discussed his
wife and his two children, 15-year-old Michael and Megan, this
year's valedictorian at North Canyon High School, who turned 18 the
week her father was convicted of murdering her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children have been dam aged in ways I don't even know, I'm
assuming,'' Falater said, adding that Megan had fallen into a
depression after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Falater disputed the post-trial observations of one juror about
his interview with a detective a few hours after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He accepted the fact that his wife was dead too easily,''
juror Theresa Beaubien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just pretty numb that night,'' said Falater, who added
that police had earlier shouted him down when he asked what had
happened to Yarmila.
</P>
<P>
   And Falater said his moth er-in-law has forgiven him for killing
Yarmila.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `You know, there's good and bad people in all of us,
and I know this was the bad person in you that would have done
this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected the criticism of those who compared his case
with O.J. Simpson's and called it a ``rich-man's defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a rich man,'' said Falater, claiming he has a negative
net worth after setting aside a fund for his children's education
and after making some payments to defense attorneys Voepel and Mike
Kimerer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike spent the last dollar of mine in October of last year,''
Falater said. He said Kimerer has been donating his time ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Falater also said his former lock-'em-up attitude toward
lawbreakers has undergone a major transforma tion in the 2{ years
he has spent in custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``These (inmates) are real people, real sorrows, real emotions,
every bit as good as anybody out there,'' he said. ``And many of
these guys have never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially, I feel terrible for a lot of the kids who I meet,
who . . . were raised in a neighborhood where they didn't know
anything but gangs. And they've never been given a fair shake, and
yet, they're being punished for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater said he has given religious instructions to fellow
inmates who have sought it. He said he would like to continue to
help them as he struggles with the possibility that he may never
again be a free man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working with the assump tion that there is still some
meaning and purpose to all of this, that the Heavenly Father knows
what he's doing,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
