<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERMOSILLO GIVES GALAXY A SPARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ The Galaxy is benefiting from the acquisition of
Carlos Hermosillo faster than coach Sigi Schmid had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hermosillo's arrival June 12, Schmid joked after another
loss that ``the cavalry was on its way,'' referring to the arrival
of Mexico's all-time leading scorer. Obviously, he was looking for
a positive spin on what was turning out to be a disastrous season.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, he was close to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, once 5-9, had gone its first 12 games without
scoring more than one goal. The team is 3-0 with Hermosillo and has
stretched its winning streak to four games. Hermosillo has also
scored a goal in each of his games.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the Galaxy hopes to continue its winning ways in front
of what should be a larger-than-usual crowd at the Rose Bowl when
it faces Miami (4-12, 8 points) at 7:30 p.m., with the traditional
Fourth of July fireworks show to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Schmid talked about how Hermosillo has
affected the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very upbeat person, a practical joker,'' Schmid said.
``There's always a smile on his face _ on the bus or on the field
in training. Based on his pedigree and on what he's accomplished,
that goes a long way when the young players see him enjoying his
work. It shows them the discipline and respect needed to succeed,
but that you can also have a good time doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   That off-field work ethic is what the Galaxy needed most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is. He's a man of tremendous character,'' Schmid said. ``He
has boosted our team morale and camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Women's World Cup taking center stage the past few
weeks, the Galaxy has quietly begun to make a move in the Western
Conference race. Los Angeles (9-6, 21 points) is tied for third
with Chicago and trails first-place Colorado (10-3, 26 points) by
only five points.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy is also no longer the worst scoring team in the
league. It has 10 goals in its past three games to bring its season
total to 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy we're finding the net on a more regular
basis,'' Schmid said. ``I'm glad we're helping the league's goal
average instead of bringing it down.''
</P>
<P>
   One concern Schmid has, however, is helping Cobi Jones find the
consistency that helped him score 19 goals and set up 13 others
last year. Jones was named the U.S. Player of the Year and had a
successful stint with the U.S. national team as well.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has only two goals and three assists this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, that's a priority for me, to help Cobi turn things
around,'' Schmid said. ``Jones was asked to carry a tremendous load
for us this season, and that took a tremendous amount of energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a lot of little nagging injuries and he's the
second-most fouled player in the league. He will find his game. Now
that our team seems to have found its game, it's our job to help
him find his.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not that far off; he's just mentally and physically
fatigued at this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
