</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK HANDS GIANTS A VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chan Ho Park walks to the mound on eggshells these
days, his arm never better, his confidence never worse.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday against the San Francisco Giants, he was a 9-1 loss
waiting to happen, a shattered pitcher on a shattered team that
dropped its sixth straight in front of a crowd of 41,770 at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Park now has four consecutive losses of his own since returning
from a suspension for kicking Angels pitcher Tim Belcher on June 3.
But unlike most of his teammates, who say their slump is a passing
thing, there is genuine concern about Park's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to know what he is thinking out there right now,''
pitching coach Claude Osteen said. ``It doesn't seem like his mind
is on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Park (4-7) hasn't won since May 26, but he has never been this
bad. Against the first-place Giants, he allowed nine runs and left
in the fifth inning without retiring a batter. He was coming off
last Sunday's 8-7 loss in San Francisco, where he gave up seven
runs (six earned) in 32/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot of pressure on me right now and it is impossible
to relax,'' said Park, whose ERA is 10.04 since June 1 and 6.19
overall. ``So many things are running through my head. I am not
strong mentally out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not strong enough to withstand several close calls by
home-plate umpire Randy Marsh. After loading the bases in the fifth
by allowing a single and two walks, Park thought he had J.T. Snow
struck out. He didn't get the call, walked Snow and was pulled
after hitting the next batter, Ellis Burks.
</P>
<P>
   Both later scored to make it 9-1 and make it easy on Giants
starter Mark Gardner (3-6), who left after five innings with a
strained hip muscle.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that reliever Onan Masaoka and Mike Maddux
followed Park with five innings of scoreless relief. The last-place
Dodgers are freefalling, dropping six games in the standings in the
last seven days.
</P>
<P>
   They are hoping to avoid their second consecutive sweep tonight
when Ismael Valdes, who has dropped five straight decisions, takes
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Carlos Perez, who ran into trouble Friday night after
getting the first two outs in four separate innings, Park got
knocked around early and often. His fastball was around 95, but he
was timid in tight spots.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Benard opened the game with a double and scored on Barry
Bonds' infield out. Bonds made it 4-1 in the third inning with a
two-run homer, his third of the series and ninth overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants blew it open in the fifth and Park had no explanation
more than an hour later. He went back to watch the inning on replay
and counted at least eight pitches he thought Marsh missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you're on, you get through that,'' Osteen said.
``It's obvious that his confidence isn't there. Neither is the
aggressiveness he has shown in the past. A big part of my job is
being a psychologist. We'll try to figure this out before his next
start.''
</P>
<P>
   That will come Thursday in Colorado against the Rockies, who
entered Saturday with nine consecutive losses before stopping San
Diego's winning streak at 14 with a 12-10 victory in the opening
game of a doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Park will do more thinking. Last year, he was
National League Pitcher of the Month in July after going 4-0 with a
1.05 ERA. To that point, he had also struggled with his confidence
after battling back trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the turning point was last season,'' said
Park, who finished with 15 victories. ``I'll try to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Park claims his problems do not stem from failed attempts last
month to get a multiyear contract from the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   His teammate Valdes went through a similar situation last year.
After winning 28 games in his first two full seasons, Valdes
appeared headed for a long and lucrative contract. Instead, he had
back-to-back subpar seasons and wound up signing a one-year deal
with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was criticized for not challenging hitters. Park now
faces the same scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel like I have to turn this thing around for
everyone,'' Park said. ``We need to get some wins and get this
thing going. But I'm not making it happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
