<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDESI ACCEPTS BLAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Raul Mondesi knows something about slumps. He has
one home run in his last 114 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that the Dodgers' listless stretch could
change if he has more games like Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi is still holding at 19 home runs, but he went 3 for 3 in
a 9-1 loss to the San Francisco Giants, including a sharp double in
the second inning that led to the Dodgers' only run.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Dodgers' (34-44) sixth consecutive loss, one short of
their longest slump since Aug. 7-13, 1993. They are 10 games under
.500 for the first time since 1992, when they finished last.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this is on me,'' said Mondesi, who is still on pace
to hit 40 homers this year. ``When I was hitting, we were okay.
Since I stopped, we've haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are 10-21 since May 28 when he hit a home run
against the Atlanta Braves. In an effort to get Mondesi rolling,
manager Davey Johnson has moved him out of the cleanup spot.
Mondesi has batted first, third and sixth. Saturday, he was in the
fifth spot.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi has told teammates he thinks Johnson is picking on him
in light of the team's failures. Saturday, he said it is no big
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worrying about that; it will take care of itself,''
Mondesi said. ``If I keep working hard, days like this will mean
wins later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna BP: Antonio Osuna, sidelined most the season with elbow
problems, made 35 pitches to hitters before the game and said he is
ready to return.
</P>
<P>
   The club will decide the next move for Osuna, who underwent
surgery May 20 to remove a bone spur from his right elbow. He could
throw to hitters again at Dodger Stadium or begin a minor-league
rehabilitation assignment at Single-A San Bernardino. Osuna is
expected back right after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Third baseman Adrian Beltre, who strained his groin
Friday night, did not play Saturday and said he might not return
until Monday in Colorado. ``It was still sore when I got to the
ballpark,'' said Beltre, who has missed just five of 78 games this
season. . . . Five scoreless innings by relievers Onan Masaoka and
Mike Maddux continued a solid stretch for the Dodgers bullpen. In
the last 35 games, they are 4-3 with a 2.52 ERA and nine saves.
Masaoka also got his first major-league at-bat and was credited
with a sacrifice. . . . Giants starter Mark Gardner (3-6) left
after five innings with a strained left hip flexor but recorded his
second victory over the Dodgers in the last seven days. The Dodgers
had just four hits off Gardner and three relievers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
