<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8764 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPT-TALK_RADIO-PHOENX     07-03 2108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-TALK_RADIO-PHOENX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS RADIO: HOW MUCH IS TOO MUCH?  
 3 PHOENIX STATIONS FIGHTING FOR LISTENERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There are those times, rare as they may be, when
sports talk radio rises above itself. It's relevant, topical and
informative.
</P>
<P>
   Other times, it becomes radio's slime pit. You want to jab at
the off button, or turn in frustration to hard rock to drown out
the drivel.
</P>
<P>
   As in most love-hate relationships, the day-to-day reality
usually falls between the two extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after the emergence of Phoenix as the nation's only
market with three full-time sports-talk stations, the rules have
changed. Two years after ``The Republic'' last examined this
sports-talk glut, hosts routinely deliver crude lines as if
auditioning for a nightclub act; many change stations, some are
canned, a few are run out of town; and collegiate and professional
teams keep landing in new flagships.
</P>
<P>
   The can-you-top-this-one attitude is prevalent. Who can
out-gross whom?
</P>
<P>
   ``What people are coming to expect in talk radio is talent,''
said Clancy Woods, the general manager of KGME and the Phoenix
market manager of Chancellor Media, which recently added KGME-AM
(550) to its stable of stations.
</P>
<P>
   Counters Tony Femino of KMVP-AM (860): ``A lot of guys come here
and get their first radio jobs after delivering milk a year ago. I
think you have to prove yourself. Any idiot can talk . . . it's how
you go about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports talk radio has had growth, but I don't know if it's
progressed.'' &QL; 
`More not better' &QL; 
So how have the three 24-hour sports stations, fraught with their
fragile egos, gone about it the last couple of years?
</P>
<P>
   For KGME-AM, it was moving down the dial, getting a stronger
signal and picking up Arizona State athletics in the process. Its
shock talk/guy talk format has propelled it to No. 1. KDUS-AM
(1060) has rights to the Cardinals and Coyotes, but only one local
program and minuscule, if any, ratings. KMVP scored a coup by
picking up Femino after he left KGME, and its ratings have
improved; along the way, however, it lost ASU sports. KMVP's sister
station, KTAR-AM (620), is a pseudo-sports station, carrying
Diamondbacks and Suns game and limited sports talk.
</P>
<P>
   Who's winning the war? That depends on whom you ask.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to someone who listens to all three stations, such as
attorney Tom Lukas of Scottsdale, and he's hard-pressed to find an
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think more stations make it better,'' he said. ``It
actually makes it worse. It seems that particularly KDUS is really
reaching to just fill time. They couldn't possibly be going after
ratings. I was here from 1984 to 1991, then moved to San Francisco
until 2{ years ago. When I came back, I was absolutely amazed at
what we had here.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to advertisers, and they point to ratings among the genre's
target group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients hire us to find the best way to reach their
audience,'' said Mike Horne of Results Media. ``In this case, it's
anyone (advertiser) who's interested in a male-driven audience.
Anyone who has a product for the young male audience, usually
25-44, this is a perfect spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost depends. At the three stations, the combined audience
for a week is only 200,000 listeners. What really drives how much a
station can charge are the ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   Horne, who works on a two-book average, said the latest numbers
show KGME at the top, with a 3.0 rating for the 6 a.m.-midnight
slot among the target audience (25-54 males). KMVP follows with
1.6, and KDUS was not a factor. In the winter book, KGME's morning
show (4.2) led KMVP (1.4), and its afternoon offering (3.1) also
was ahead of KMVP (2.9). KDUS' ratings, again, were barely blips.
</P>
<P>
   Preaching to the choir &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A major advertiser on sports talk radio is Fox Sports Net
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a major investment with KGME, who we view as the
leader in sports talk radio,'' said Kyle Eng, the director of
marking and communications for Fox. ``We view advertising on sports
talk radio as an effective way to reach our core audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Eng said the network knows that advertising on sports talk radio
is like preaching to the choir, and that's the reason advertisers
like to spread their message on different stations in the same
family.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to the hosts and their bosses, and they're not hesitant to
pat themselves on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest,'' said Bruce Jacobs, a morning co-host at
KGME. ``We never get scooped. We're the only sports radio station
in this town that ever breaks a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm tooting my own horn, that's fine. We are much more
aggressive. We've done a lot more breaking stories than any station
in this town. In fact, all of them combined.''
</P>
<P>
   While the myriad of sports talk show hosts may profess to have
all the answers, questions keep swirling.
</P>
<P>
   Sports talk shows around the country have changed dramatically
during the last decade. It has reached a point where you can be
shocked by what someone says but not the least bit surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Jude LaCava, a former host of the 620 Sports Line during the
days when KTAR was regarded as the major sports station in Arizona,
always was viewed as a ``safe'' bet. Even now, as the sports anchor
at Channel 10 (KSAZ-TV), he approaches his job in a light-hearted
manner, but he never strays into questionable territory.
</P>
<P>
   He believes nothing can stop the talk show pendulum until
advertisers go elsewhere and people turn a deaf ear. LaCava said if
he were doing a talk show today, his style would be similar to the
one he had a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never allow outside force to influence who I am,'' he
said. ``You've got to be yourself. You've got to change with the
times, you have to adjust, but creativity has no limits. I like to
think we had just as much entertainment value but in a different
style.''
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment could be Jacobs' middle name. That seems to be the
crux of his show, get down and dirty and if sports comes up, fine.
In fact, one self-promotional spot touted the fact the show only
had a 10 percent sports content.
</P>
<P>
   Should kids listen to this? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people who are entertained by the show, the happier
we are,'' said Jacobs, the one person many listeners, athletes and
team officials love to hate. ``In terms of the material we talk
about sometimes, do I think kids should listen to it? I don't think
it's as graphic as say, Howard Stern, but I'm not so sure little
kids should be listening, quite honestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But junior high kids, 14, 15, I don't see any problem with
them listening to our show. The stuff they hear in school is a lot
worse than they ever hear on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' show with Jim Traber, the station's afternoon duo of
John Gambadoro and Tim Liotta, and KMVP's Paul Calvisi and Ron
Wolfley are the ones who most frequently stray off the sports line.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who said sports talk radio is headed in the right
direction in Phoenix, apparently is working on a plan of putting
his hosts on a shorter leash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a balance to strike between individual
responsibilities and opinions, and responding to the needs of the
community,'' Woods said. ``It just may be a coincidence, but since
we've owned KGME, I think you're seeing less of that (guy talk)
than you did previously. There's much more of a focus on
credibility and access.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to the hosts, and what I've explained to people is
that being obnoxious and not having access to key sports figures in
the sports marketplace is not a position that is valuable to us.
Outspoken and credible, that is a position that we would like to
have. I hope we are the station that is the place somebody can
count on for us to state an opinion, to ask the hard questions, if
necessary, but more importantly be the place where you can get the
most information about sports in the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Liotta, who also serves as KGME's program director, said his
stations' future is bolstered by the fact Woods ``is such an avid
proponent'' of talk radio, ``and he has a vision that goes way
beyond what others see.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if some of his hosts go too far at times, Chris
Gallu, general manager at KTAR/KMVP said, ``Absolutely. I would
never tell you that my guys have never gone over the edge because
they have. It's my job to talk to them about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kennedy, the lone host at KDUS, thinks too much deviation
from sports isn't the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy talk rates and sports talk doesn't rate,'' Kennedy said.
``And I believe it's damaged the industry. I think it's forced
people to focus on the ridiculous. I think most of our listeners
would rather talk about sports, not the box scores, that's boring,
but interviews and talk about people who play the game, the arenas,
the business of sports, anything but (guy talk). I think a steady
diet of that is what's ruining sports talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've forgotten that sports are fun. I think that's
the problem now.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gambadoro, a co-host at KGME, cares little what his rivals
think _ and he said that he doesn't look at KDUS as competition,
anyway: ``They ventured in, went a year, and it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   When hosts like Gambadoro wan der off, they can always see the
logic.
</P>
<P>
   `Sex on radio isn't funny' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want everybody to love you,'' he said. ``You want
people to love you and hate you, but you want them to listen. Those
hosts that are out there to make everybody like them, that doesn't
work. You want people to hate you and disagree with you. That's
what makes talk radio great.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Cesmat of KTAR wonders how long the status quo can prevail,
asking, ``Do advertisers want to associate themselves with
pornography on the radio, in essence? Do teams want to be
associated with topless clubs, strip joints and jokes about sex? Do
teams want to be associated with that?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear some of this stuff that has gone out on the air,
to me it's like somebody isn't getting enough direction. It's not
funny. Sex on the radio is not funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the envelope to the edge, or even off the table, could
work, Femino said, if done creatively and in fairly good taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in talking about dates,'' he said. ``You can't
waste people's time. Here are the dynamics. Give the information,
be entertaining, do good interviews and then talk to the callers.
We'll put our interviews up against anyone, not just in the market
but in the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the creativity aspect that's important,'' continued
Femino, who refers to the University of Arizona as the University
of Geraldo and former Nebraska Coach Tom Osborne as the Pope on a
Tractor. ``How far can you go? That completely depends on the host.
If the host is good at doing something, you can go as far as he
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   True up to a point, says Mike Golic of ESPN Radio, a former host
at KGME.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line is definitely shorter nationally,'' Golic said. ``As
far as pushing the envelope, locally you can get away with more.''
</P>
<P>
   Accountability is one area that's extremely gray in talk radio.
Hosts frequently state opinion as fact, and when they're wrong,
they seldom recap their transgressions. They have the forum to
criticize unmercifully, to accuse and to convict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think there's accountability, in terms of what you say
about athletes or coaches,'' Jacobs said. ``There's no
accountability if you never show up in a locker room, which a lot
of people in this town and business don't. They just rip away, and
you never see them. That's not my style.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambadoro said accountability comes in ``if we say something
incorrect, wrong or stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, the lawyer listener from Scottsdale, said talk show hosts
are fairly well shielded from lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're talking about public figures, you would have to
prove it was malicious,'' he said. ``In most cases, they have a lot
of leeway.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems to puzzle most people is that Phoenix has so much
sports talk, a business that has a narrow base, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Can they all survive?
</P>
<P>
   When KDUS got the Cardinals rights two years ago, general
manager Chuck Artigue said if he ran the other sports stations in
town, he would change formats. It appears now that KDUS might be
the station on the bubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, yes, I think three stations are too
many,'' Kennedy said. ``I don't think there's room, long term, for
the survival of three sports stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought initially there was enough of the pie out there for
all of us to get a slice and survive, but I don't believe that any
more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
