u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-SPENCER-NYT     07-03 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-SPENCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSETTLING HEART AILMENT SENDS SPENCER TO SIDELINE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Instead of playing left field at Yankee Stadium
Saturday, Shane Spencer was lying at Columbia-Presbyterian Medical
Center being treated for an irregular heartbeat. It is never
enjoyable to be poked and prodded inside a hospital, and the
mysterious aspect of a 27-year-old who has never had previous heart
problems suddenly experiencing them added to the delicate nature of
Spencer's condition.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer told the Yankee trainers that he felt dizzy during
Friday night's game with the Orioles, and Joe Torre replaced
Spencer with Ricky Ledee in the seventh inning. Before the eighth
was over, Spencer, who was growing nervous because he was having
heart palpitations, was brought to the hospital, where he will
remain for an undetermined period.
</P>
<P>
   When General Manager Brian Cashman asked about visiting Spencer
Saturday morning, he was told not to bother because Spencer had to
undergo a battery of tests and could not see anyone. That was
unsettling enough to make some Yankees feel pensive. Chili Davis
stopped a humorous discourse about himself to mention how he felt
sorry for Spencer; Derek Jeter promised to call Spencer; and Ledee
whispered about the awkwardness of taking over left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not funny when a teammate gets hurt and you get the
chance to play,'' Ledee said. ``It doesn't feel right.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Scott Brosius' dramatic three-run home run off Arthur
Rhodes in the ninth inning gave the Yankees a 6-5 victory over the
Orioles Saturday, Torre discussed Spencer's travails as someone who
has more knowledge of heart ailments than he wants. Torre's brother
Rocco died of a heart attack three years ago, and another brother,
Frank, had a heart transplant a day before the Yankees nabbed the
1996 World Series title. But each Torre was twice as old as Spencer
is. Twenty-seven-year-old professional athletes are usually
concerned about what club to hang out in, not about atrial
fibrillation. Unfortunately, Spencer is being treated for atrial
fibrillation, something he most likely had not heard of before
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Coastal Cardiology of San Luis Obispo, Calif.,
atrial fibrillation is a disorder that is found in nearly two
million Americans, most of whom are older. The two upper chambers
of the heart, the atria, collect blood from the veins and pump it
to the ventricles. When atrial fibrillation is present, the atria
quiver instead of beating effectively. There are numerous risk
factors that can trigger the condition, including high blood
pressure, an overactive thyroid and excessive consumption of
alcohol. Dr. Stuart Hershon, the team's physician, was not certain
what caused Spencer's disorder, but he said that Spencer did not
have any blood clots, which is considered extremely important for
his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say he was in danger,'' Hershon said. ``But when
someone has an irregular heartbeat at 27, you want to find out
what's wrong. I don't think he was ever in danger, but he had to be
treated appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Hershon gave Cashman the results of the unspecified tests,
and the Yankees determined that Spencer would need at least several
days to recuperate, they placed him on the 15-day disabled list.
Torre had not spoken with Spencer, but said: ``When things like
that happen, especially when you're young, it scares you. I'm sure
he was a little frightened, and might still be.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is Spencer's heart or Darryl Strawberry's colon
cancer, medical questions eventually give way to baseball
questions. That happened Saturday. While Spencer's health is the
major issue, the timing of his problem is disappointing from a
baseball perspective since Spencer had finally claimed ownership of
left field with 12 hits in his last 36 at-bats, including four
homers. Now the job is open again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure makes you think there's something more to left field
than playing it,'' Torre said. ``It's strange.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees presumably had too many left fielders, but no one
from the group of Spencer, Ledee, Chad Curtis and Tony Tarasco
seized the position until Spencer started 17 of the last 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   If Spencer returns in two weeks, he should play like someone who
has seen a ghost. It took him nine years to make it to the major
leagues, and he was an improbable hero last year. Still, Spencer
should realize more than ever that there are no guarantees. Savor
each game. Get enough rest. Eat properly. Avoid carousing. He will
not be 27 forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is temporary, and we'll get him back,'' Cashman
said. ``From everything I'm hearing, we're not going to lose him
for the entire season. It's frustrating for him. But we still
believe in him and Ricky Ledee, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee has been in this odd situation before. He was omitted from
the 1998 post-season roster until Strawberry learned during the
division series that he had cancer. It was an uncomfortable way to
be welcomed back, but Ledee wound up thriving in the World Series
with six hits in 10 at-bats. Ledee has not been as polished since,
including Saturday when he took a questionable angle on a fly ball
to enable two runs to score, went 0 for 2 and was picked off first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't fun when anybody goes down,'' Ledee said. ``But
somebody has to do something. I guess I got a chance to play.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
