<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  LONG WINDINGROADLEADSRANGERS'   07-03 1669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ZIMMERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
LONG, WINDING ROAD LEADS RANGERS' ZIMMERMAN TO ROOKIE STARDOM 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Zimmerman, accidental tourist and quasi-amateur pitcher,
had a great time in the summer of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He visited the famed Louvre museum in Paris and checked out the
Eiffel Tower and the Arc de Triomphe. He sailed down the Grand
Canal in Venice and stood in admiration of the grandeur of the
Swiss Alps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had taken my skis with me,'' Zimmerman said. ``But I
had no money anyway. I was trying to see Europe as cheaply as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He was getting paid $1,000 Canadian a month, plus an apartment
to pitch for the Montpellier Barracudas in France's National
Baseball League. The money was under the table because he had hopes
of pitching for the Canadian National team in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The major leagues were the furthest thing from his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was 10,000 miles away,'' Zimmerman said. ``The closest
thing we had to major-league baseball is we would get a tape of
week-old Atlanta Braves games in the mail. We'd all go to a pub,
put the tape in the VCR and watch the game, even though we already
knew the final score. It was a huge social event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys just wanted to see Tom Glavine and John Smoltz pitch on
the big screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz and Glavine are All-Star pitchers. Sitting in a French
pub and playing in a country where many people don't know baseball
exists, Zimmerman had no hope of ever pitching in an All-Star Game
himself.
</P>
<P>
   But now, that might become a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman's tortuous climb to the major leagues could be
rewarded on Wednesday if New York Yankees manager Joe Torre selects
him to the American League All-Star team for the July 13 game in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' said Greg Hamilton, Zimmerman's coach in
France and with the Canadian National team. ``It couldn't have
happened to a better individual. His approach and dedication to the
game are second to none. With Jeff, one of the big keys was just
staying with it and refusing to give up on a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   His All-Star credentials are impeccable. He was 7-0 with an 0.94
earned-run average before last night's game, and opponents were
hitting barely over .100 against him. But Zimmerman insists on
downplaying the anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great, but I don't even want to think about it,''
Zimmerman said. ``That's still a couple of weeks away. We still
have some big games in our division before that. If it happens,
great. But I don't want to even get caught up in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look to the present. I worry about what I have to do today.
That's what got me here so far.'' Like a movie script Zimmerman,
who grew up in the small town of Carseland, Alberta, learned to
play baseball in the western wilderness of a country known more for
hockey and lacrosse. He went to two junior colleges and TCU, a
school not known for turning out major-leaguers. He pitched in
France, two years with the Canadian National team and one year in
the independent Northern League.
</P>
<P>
   He got his first job in America on the strength of a fax.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left is to decide whether Matt Damon or Woody
Harrelson will play him in the movie. Kevin Costner would be
perfect, except he's too old. Maybe in the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmerman refuses to see himself as an inspiration to
underdogs everywhere who harbor a dream of overcoming
insurmountable odds to reach the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The story of what got him here, however, is much better than
that, especially when considering that his father, Bill, has spent
the past year fighting cancer, including spending 4 1/2 months in a
coma. During that time, on several occasions, the doctors urged the
family to pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my inspiration,'' Zimmerman said. ``He's helped me
appreciate where I am right now. Before, if I had a bad outing, I'd
be down for a couple of days. I'd overanalyze everything, stew over
it. I wouldn't be able to sleep at night because I was so
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, my dad is fighting for his life against a disease that is
devastating his body and I'm thinking, `You're agonizing over a
home run. Let's put things in perspective and not take the game too
seriously.' It's not life or death. What my dad is going through
is. If he's mentally strong, I have to be, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Zimmerman more than inspired his sons. He and the boys'
mother, Sharon, devoted maximum time, energy and money to ensuring
Jeff and his younger brother Jordan, now a relief pitcher for the
Seattle Mariners, would fulfill their dreams of playing
major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where they found the money or the energy to do
everything they did,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Carseland is a town of about 300 people, 30 miles outside
Calgary. Bill and Sharon Zimmerman, before they were divorced in
1994, owned two small hotels in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Zimmerman said running them is a 24-hour-a-day job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff and Jordan were crazy about sports, so their parents
did everything they could to make sure they had a chance to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a population of 300, we never had more than nine kids on
a team,'' Sharon said. ``Most of the time we were running around
trying to find that ninth kid. The boys were also three years
apart, so they were never on the same team. Bill was always running
one way and I was running the other. Then on weekends, there would
be a tournament, so we'd all pack up and go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff was always dedicated. He didn't have to be told what to
do. Every day he would do his exercises, or run a mile. You'd see
him walking from the kitchen to the living room, going through his
pitching motion.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jeff was 16, the family moved to Calgary so he could play
against a higher level of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it snows in Canada six months out of the year,'' Jeff
Zimmerman said. ``So, my dad rented an old indoor airplane hangar
from World War II and renovated it into a baseball facility with a
batting cage and AstroTurf. They lost a lot of money doing it, but
it allowed my brother and I to play baseball all we wanted to in
Calgary.'' Mobile family After high school, Jeff Zimmerman went to
college in the United States. He attended two junior colleges _
Treasure Valley in Oregon and Indian Hills in Iowa _ before getting
a partial scholarship at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   The family took a bigger step with Jordan. When he was 14, a
Kansas City Royals scout strongly suggested he needed to play in
the United States. The Zimmermans made the ultimate sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called around and heard about Brenham, that their high
school had a good program,'' Sharon said. ``So, we called the high
school coach there, Earl Hathaway, and he said, `You're going to do
what?' But Bill and Jordan took an apartment in Brenham.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan eventually went to Blinn College, a two-year college in
Brenham, and was drafted by the Mariners. Jeff's nomadic existence
was only getting started. He wasn't drafted out of TCU even though
scouts told him he had potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to be drafted in the top 10 rounds,''
Zimmerman said. ``But I figured with 80 or 100 rounds in the draft,
somebody would take a chance on me. I was disenchanted with
professional baseball, so I started to look into playing in the
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who coached him on the Canadian Junior team, took
Zimmerman with him to France. Few people realize the French play
baseball, but it proved the right spot for Zimmerman. With
Montpellier, he developed the slider that is now devastating
American League hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say I dominated, but I didn't have to worry
about losing a ballgame,'' Zimmerman said. ``So, I was able to
experiment with the slider. I could throw it in different counts,
different situations. You can't do that in college ball in the
states.''
</P>
<P>
   The next two years were spent with the Canadian National team
while earning his master's degree at Simon Fraser University in
Vancouver, British Columbia. The goal was to play in the Olympics
in Atlanta. Instead, the Canadians lost to Nicaragua in the finals
of the qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right, Nicaragua,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball should have ended there. But Zimmerman, growing
stronger and gaining more confidence in his slider, had one last
card to play. He wanted to try out with the Winnipeg Goldeyes (it's
a fish) of the Northern League, with the idea of catching
somebody's eye in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He asked his parents and fiance Andrea Whiffen if they would
continue to support him, morally and _ more important _
financially.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said `Yes, go,' '' Sharon said. ``Pack up your bags and go.
There was no hesitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The tryout was a spectacle, which is normal for an independent
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was there,'' Zimmerman said. ``Guys from every
softball league and beer league. I was even pitching against
motorcycle gang members.''
</P>
<P>
   They were also using wood bats, a first for Zimmerman. It made a
big difference over the aluminum bats of amateur competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first four guys didn't hit the ball out of the cage,''
Zimmerman said. ``I was able to pitch inside and didn't have to
worry about being taken out of the ballpark. Throwing to wooden
bats was a lot easier. That gave me a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The confidence Zimmerman has to blow away American
League hitters came from throwing to Canada's version of the Hell's
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   He was 9-2 with a league-leading 2.82 ERA with Winnipeg and
making $700 a month, a pay cut from his lucrative venture in
France. He then sent a fax to 30 major-league teams, asking for
job.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were the only one to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching that game,'' Sharon said. ``I kept thinking:
`Amazing, how did he ever get there?' I knew he had potential, but
I was just hoping he would make it to Double A or Triple A.''
</P>
<P>
   He has done more than that. He might be an American League
All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
