<HEADER>
A8778 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-FUTURE-TEX     07-03 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FUTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS READY TO PROMOTE YOUNG MINOR-LEAGUERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Next season, the Stars will be a team with some
new faces _ and possibly some young faces _ general manager Bob
Gainey said last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have players who we have put into position to be NHL
players, and it's time for some of them to step up and be given
that chance,'' Gainey said. ``We expect to go into training camp
with the intent of allowing some players the ability to prove
themselves at the NHL level.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision makes perfect sense for the Stars, who will be able
to get more speed, younger legs and cheaper legs into the lineup.
But making the transition could prove tricky. How many young
players can step up at one time? Will the Stars lose the very
experience that helped them win the Stanley Cup if they clear out
unrestricted free agents Dave Reid, Pat Verbeek and Craig Ludwig?
And if owner Tom Hicks indeed has money to spend, should the Stars
at least be making inquiries about free agents such as Valeri
Kamensky?
</P>
<P>
   Gainey looked at all the questions last week after free-agent
shopping opened July 1 and decided the best thing to do was wait.
He set free all of the players who had contract options except for
defenseman Sergei Zubov. Zubov has been signed for one more year
and then could become a restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But players such as Reid, Verbeek, Ludwig, Tony Hrkac, Brent
Severyn, Benoit Hogue and Guy Carbonneau all are free to go to any
team that gives them an offer sheet. The Stars are gambling that
the free-agent market won't be lucrative this season and that
they'll be able to pick up players like Carbonneau, Ludwig, Hogue
and Hrkac at reduced prices. But Gainey said the Stars also need
time to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just came off a very emotional ride and I think it takes
time for things to settle down,'' Gainey said. ``I don't know what
our contract offers will be to certain players, but it's best for
them and for us if we allow ourselves the ability to step back
before we make important decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey and his right-hand contract man, Doug Armstrong, the
Stars assistant GM, will be in contact with player agents
throughout July. And once a few of the other unrestricted free
agents around the league start signing, the Stars will have a
better idea of what the going rate is for a player like Carbonneau
or Hogue. They might even look at signing Verbeek, if his asking
price drops greatly from the $3.2 million he earned last season.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Gainey said he feels confident that the young
players the Stars have been grooming to step up are ready to do
just that. Dead solid locks for next year's roster are Juha Lind,
25, and Blake Sloan, 23. The two wingers are expected to be
bookends on a fourth line that should have speed, toughness and
some ability to score. Also expected to be on the roster is
defenseman Brad Lukowich, 22 _ a Richard Matvichuk clone who could
be ready to step over Shawn Chambers and into the fifth defenseman
spot.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those three players, the Stars are expected to
let youngsters Manny Fernandez, 24, and Marty Turco, 23, battle for
the backup goaltender position. The Stars, who traded Roman Turek
to the St. Louis Blues, could go after a veteran free agent like
Ken Wregget as a backup, but Gainey said that would defeat the
purpose of drafting and working young talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players have been in the system and have worked to get
this opportunity,'' Gainey said. ``Now, it's time to give it to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Turco (24-17-10, 2.61 goals against average) was rookie of the
year in the International Hockey League with the Michigan K-Wings,
while Fernandez led the Houston Aeros to the IHL championship.
</P>
<P>
   Other young players expected to get the chance to make the
Stars' 24-man roster are: winger Jon Sim, 21; winger Jason
Botterill, 23; winger Jamie Wright, 23; defenseman Alan Latang, 23;
and recently acquired winger Warren Luhning, 24.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Stars have restricted free agents like Derek
Plante and Aaron Gavey who can play either at the NHL level or with
the K-Wings, the Stars' IHL affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   If the young players perform well, that would free up money for
the Stars to either grant raises to Mike Modano, Brett Hull and
Derian Hatcher or to try to negotiate long-term deals with Joe
Nieuwendyk, Ed Belfour and Zubov _ each of whom is heading into the
final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Stars say they are prepared to shake up their
winning chemistry if need be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the greatest mistake anyone could make, even if we
bring the entire team intact, is assuming the chemistry will be the
same,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Every team develops its
own chemistry and it takes time throughout the season to do that.
Next year, some of the players we had on this team will at
different stages in their contracts, different stages in their
lives, and that will affect our chemistry. We have to be prepared
to start over every single year no matter who's in camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have some time to put together the roster, but not too
much time. Training camp starts Sept. 4 in Vail, Colo. _ exactly
two months away.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
