<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIAS BY STATE POLICE PROTESTED IN ATLANTIC CITY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ Forty to fifty demonstrators were arrested
Saturday when the Rev. Al Sharpton took his civil disobedience
campaign to Atlantic City to protest racial profiling by the New
Jersey State Police.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration, in which protesters blocked one of the main
thoroughfares to the boardwalk and casino resort area, came the day
after Gov. Christie Whitman released a report acknowledging that
the state police tolerated a culture of racial discrimination and
sexual harassment. An earlier report acknowledged that state
troopers systematically discriminated against black and Hispanic
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters before the demonstration, Sharpton called
the latest report ``too little, too late.'' He said the state
needed to identify police officials who had engaged in racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's face-off between the police and protesters seemed
rehearsed by both sides. At 4 p.m., about 100 people moved into the
intersection of Arkansas Road and Baltic Avenue, where the Atlantic
City Expressway descends into Atlantic City, and sat down.
</P>
<P>
   Facing them were a row of Atlantic City police officers, who
ordered those who had volunteered to be arrested to stay where they
were and to raise their hands. Those who did not want to be
arrested were asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   No state troopers were involved because the demonstration took
place within city limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come to this city on this weekend to make a statement
that people are coming here to seek fun and sun and not facing the
realities of this society,'' Sharpton told reporters. He said the
point of the demonstration had been to divert traffic and send the
demonstrators' message to senior New Jersey officials, particularly
Governor Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Michael A. Hardy, said the site had been selected
because it is ``one of New Jersey's leading financial centers.''
</P>
<P>
   The police tried to insure that the protest would create a
minimum of disruption. Even before the demonstrators entered the
intersection, more than an hour behind schedule, the police had
cordoned off the avenue on both sides, diverting traffic to two
other main streets connecting Atlantic City to the Garden State
Parkway. Police continued to divert traffic during the protest,
which blocked Arkansas Road for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested _ the men in plastic handcuffs, the women
uncuffed _ were taken to the Atlantic City Convention Center, where
they were issued bench warrants and released. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-99 2350EDT &QL; 
