<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-AUSTRALIA-PBR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH BROKEN LEFT ARM, DUNN RIDES BULL TO AUSSIE VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACKAY, Australia _ Mounting two snorting bulls despite a broken
left forearm, Troy Dunn finished first in Ride the Rage, a bull
riding show staged last night in the world champion's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   When the title was at stake before an overflow crowd of more
than 10,000 at a dog racing track, Dunn posted a final-ride score
of 86 and earned $7,601 in Australian money (approximately $5,100
U.S.).
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time for Dunn to compete in Mackay, a
northeastern Australian coastal city near the Great Barrier Reef.
Dunn is the 1998 Professional Bull Riders Bud Light Cup Series
champion, and he lives in Stephenville when he competes in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, there was a lot of pressure to ride here at
home,'' said Dunn, who suffered a broken left arm during a North
American bull riding accident last month. ``But on the other hand,
I was pumped up by the big crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn punched up scores of 89 and 86 en route to winning the
title with a two-ride score of 175. After the last bull had bucked,
Dunn edged Australian Kelly Daley by a point.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's three-hour show in Mackay capped a series of three
Professional Bull Riders-sanctioned shows in Australia over the
past two weekends. The other two were in Townsville.
</P>
<P>
   Prize money will count toward qualifying for the PBR's Oct.
28-31 finals in Las Vegas. Unlike the PBR's cup series in North
America that features an invitational roster of 45 riders, the
three Australian events were classified as PBR Touring Pro Division
shows. That means that every PBR member was eligible to enter.
</P>
<P>
   The series, dubbed as the Troy Dunn International Challenge,
also was sanctioned by Championship Bull Riders, an Australian bull
riding organization.
</P>
<P>
   The three shows drew North American competitors who regularly
excel on the PBR's cup series. Terry Don West, who finished third
last year on the tour, won the June 24 opening show in Townsville.
J.W. Hart, a five-time PBR finals qualifier who lives near
Gainesville, finished third in the June 25 show in Townsville.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn stole last night's show in Mackay by pacing the field. In
the final, a bull named Sudden Impact had Dunn out of position
several times. But the stubborn Aussie hung on for eight agonizing
seconds to hear one of the sweetest horns of his life.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
