<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990703.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8809 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WOMEN-LADN     07-03 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLAST FROM THE PAST FOR U.S., BRAZIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO _ It's Sissy instead of Romario, Mia instead of Cobi.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it's Brazil and the United States today, just as it
was five years ago when a heavily favored Brazilian men's team
eliminated the Americans 1-0 in the second round of the 1994 World
Cup. At Stanford Stadium. On the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for the sequel, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   With a championship berth at stake next Saturday in the Rose
Bowl, the heavily favored American women hope to finish what the
men couldn't against a feisty and dangerous Brazilian side in the
Women's World Cup semifinals. The winner faces either Norway or
China, who meet today in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to play better against Brazil than we did against
Germany,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said. ``We'll have to be very
good to get into the final. Brazil is not an easy team. It will be
a hard game, with hard tackles, but it will be a game of skill and
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brazilians are very resilient as they showed against
Nigeria. We are stepping up to a higher level now.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the date didn't escape Brazilian coach
Wilson de Oliveira.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game is a different story, sometimes the same story
repeats,'' de Oliveira said. ``We hope this story repeats. We have
a dream. If we can emulate what happened in this stadium five years
ago, our dream will come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, DiCicco all but guaranteed that wouldn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of game that promotes soccer and women's
soccer,'' said DiCicco. ``Having the Brazilian fans and the Samba
only enhances the event and passion. But having said that, do I
think it's going to be the same result as '94? No I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The theatrics couldn't get much better than they were Thursday
in Washington D.C., where the U.S. rallied on two occasions from a
goal down to pull out a 3-2 quarterfinal victory over Germany, with
President Bill Clinton and his family looking on.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Brazil recorded a thrilling victory of its
own. It blew a 3-0 halftime lead, then rallied to earn a 4-3
victory in overtime thanks to a perfectly placed Golden Goal from
Sissi off a free kick.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, DiCicco learned a few things about his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Brazil unraveled a bit under pressure,'' said
DiCicco. ``We felt they lost some focus and had trouble stringing
passes together. Brazil felt the game was in hand and what we saw
was a team we hadn't seen earlier in the World Cup. They were
starting to show their nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   For the American women, it was the first time they had to face
true adversity in the tournament. Down 2-1 in the second half, not
only were their tournament hopes on the line, but a couple more
German goals could have kept them out of the 2000 Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A few encouraging words from DiCicco and veteran Carla Overbeck
at halftime helped calm them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carla said that everything we've done in this lifetime comes
down to these 45 minutes,'' said midfielder Julie Foudy. ``We had
45 minutes to make a difference. That's it and we had to leave
everything on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said Shannon MacMillan, who has a goal and three assists
in the last two matches, could start in place of forward Cindy
Parlow as he looks for a quicker team this time. He also has the
option of playing four midfielders and having MacMillan and
Kristine Lilly patrol the flanks.
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said he also may insert defensive midfielder Tiffany
Roberts during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her nickname is `The Little Animal,' '' he said. ``She's like
a puppy chasing you that you can't get rid of. She's one of our
hardest players in terms of committing to win a ball _ and she's
probably one of the smallest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
